EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong low pressure moved over the Cape Cod Canal and coupled with a strong low level jet to produce a burst of heavy snow over much of Southern New England during the morning commute.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was downed in Pelham by heavy snow and winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system in the Great Lakes redeveloped south of New England, spreading snow across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Seven inches of snow fell in eastern Hillsborough County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system moved through southern New England from the southwest spreading snow across the area. This was followed by strong warm advection resulting in a precipitation change to freezing rain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Nearly six inches of snow fell across eastern Hillsborough County.  A brief change to freezing rain resulted in a glaze of ice on top of the snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system moved across the Ohio Valley and into southern New England. This low developed a secondary low off the coast of New Jersey. These two low pressure systems resulted in precipitation overspreading the area while warm air moved in aloft. This made precipitation type a challenge with snow, freezing rain, and sleet occurring across southern New England.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An eighth of an inch of ice and 2.6 inches of snow fell in eastern Hillsborough County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system moved across the Ohio Valley off the shore of New Jersey and south of Southern New England, spreading snow across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Eight inches of snow fell in eastern Hillsborough County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A coastal low pressure system moved southeast of Nantucket, spreading snow across Southern New England. Snowfall amounts ranged from three inches on Cape Cod to almost twelve inches in southern New Hampshire. This late season storm affected most of the east coast and resulted in hundreds of flight cancellations at Boston's Logan Airport and many car accidents.  In New Hampshire, snowfall amounts ranged from seven to nearly twelve inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ten to eleven inches of snow fell across eastern Hillsborough County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front moving through Southern New England coupled with a 50 mph low level jet produced strong gradient winds across much of the area.  Winds remained below advisory criteria (31 mph sustained or 46 mph gusts) but with some trees still partially to fully leafed, these winds did produce some minor damage.||In Pelham, New Hampshire, this minor damage had unfortunate consequences when a strong gust of wind toppled a weakened birch tree onto a 10 year old trick or treater, killing him.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 10 year old boy was killed when a birch tree was blown over by a strong gust of wind.  Photos of the tree shown on local news outlets as well as reports in local newspapers indicated that the tree was at least partially rotted.  ||The closest observations are available eight to nine miles away at either Lawrence Municipal Airport (KLWM), MA and Nashua, Boire Field (KASH), NH.  Observations on the hour either side of the accident recorded wind gusts to 43 mph at KLWM and 21 mph at KASH.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong winter storm event struck the northwest quarter of Minnesota during the Christmas holiday, dropping heavy amounts of snow over an extended period of time. One to two feet of snow fell over portions of the northwest quarter of Minnesota, with the most snow falling over the central Red River Valley. The system was well forecast, which gave people ample time to adjust their Christmas plans. The actual track of the surface low was a bit of hybrid, tracking from Arkansas northward into Iowa, where it stayed nearly stationary for over a day. Conditions finally improved on the morning of the 26th, but it took a long time to dig out from all the snow.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind chills down to 34 below zero were reported in Essex.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold Canadian system converged with a warm Pacific weather system to produced accumulating snow accross western Montana.  Snow amounts ranged from eight to eighteen inches of new snow.  In addition, as the strong cold front pushed through northwest Montana, northeast winds caused blowing and drifting snow and low visibilities.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter 3 miles east of Lolo reported 8 inches of snow.  A trained spotter in Miller Creek reported 8 inches of snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Prolonged snowfall produced heavy accumulations over southeast South Dakota, ranging up to over 20 inches in several areas. The snowfall took place from two days before to the day after Christmas. The snowfall was accompanied by increasing north to northwest winds which caused widespread blizzard conditions on Christmas day and the start of the next day. The blizzard added to the very heavy snowfall made almost all travel impossible, and shut down commerce.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow combined with increasing winds to produce widespread blizzard conditions. The snowfall over 3 days varied from 10 to 18 inches. North to northwest winds reached sustained speeds over 30 mph and there were gusts over 40 mph. These winds combined with the heavy snowfall to produce widespread visibilities below a quarter mile from Christmas day to the start of the next day. Most roads were blocked and travel was brought to a standstill, as was the limited holiday commerce.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A complex and slow-moving system brought an extended period of snow to central Illinois from December 25th through December 27th.  The first wave of significant snow occurred during the night of December 25th through midday on the 26th.  Due to favorable temperature and moisture conditions aloft, very large snow flakes were produced, resulting in impressive snowfall rates.  By the time the wave departed the area by the late afternoon of December 26th, a wide swath of 3 to 6 inch snow accumulations had occurred along and west of the Illinois River. A weaker wave brought another period of light snow during the morning of December 27th.  By the time the precipitation ended, all of central Illinois had picked up between 3 and 5 inches of snow, with 7 to 9 inch amounts common along and west of the Illinois River.  Due to the prolonged period of snow, numerous traffic accidents occurred around the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous traffic accidents were reported across Douglas County due to snow-covered roadways.

CZ_NAME: S & E JACKSON / LARIMER / N & NE GRAND / NW BOULDER COUNTIES ABOVE 9000 FEET
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A winter storm produced areas of moderate to heavy snowfall in the North-Central Mountains.  Storm totals included:  11 inches at Roach SNOTEL, 10.5 inches at Cabin Creek, 10 inches at St. Mary's Glacier, 9 inches at Fremont Pass, Deadman Hill and Lake Irene; 7 inches at Summit Ranch and 6 inches at Columbine SNOTEL.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm totals included:  11 inches at Roach SNOTEL, and 9 inches at Fremont Pass, Deadman Hill and Lake Irene.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A complex and slow-moving system brought an extended period of snow to central Illinois from December 25th through December 27th.  The first wave of significant snow occurred during the night of December 25th through midday on the 26th.  Due to favorable temperature and moisture conditions aloft, very large snow flakes were produced, resulting in impressive snowfall rates.  By the time the wave departed the area by the late afternoon of December 26th, a wide swath of 3 to 6 inch snow accumulations had occurred along and west of the Illinois River. A weaker wave brought another period of light snow during the morning of December 27th.  By the time the precipitation ended, all of central Illinois had picked up between 3 and 5 inches of snow, with 7 to 9 inch amounts common along and west of the Illinois River.  Due to the prolonged period of snow, numerous traffic accidents occurred around the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous traffic accidents were reported across Morgan County due to snow-covered roadways.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure moved into Kansas and deepened during the afternoon of the 9th and moved east across northern Missouri during the night and morning hours of the 10th.  A very strong temperature contrast became established along a frontal boundary extending through the low.  Polar air was in place over northern Iowa and areas north with temperatures in the teens.  In contrast, temperatures were in the low 50s over southern Iowa and in the 50s and 60s to the south of Iowa. Moisture streamed north into the system during the late afternoon and evening hours with surface dew point values reaching the 40s to low 50s south of the low.  The airmass was dry initially, but was overcome by the evening hours.  Very warm air did stream in aloft with 850 mb temperatures above +10 C. over southern Iowa during the early afternoon.  This set the stage for a band of ice pellets and some freezing rain during the initial stages of the snow event.  With the dry atmosphere, temperatures aloft cooled quickly and changed the ice pellets to snow fairly quickly.  Other than the initial onset of the precipitation, most of the precipitation fell as snow.  A band of moderate snow set up across central into east central Iowa as a strong deformation zone set up to the north of the low pressure track.  A band of 6 to 8 inch snowfall occurred in a band about two counties wide between the Interstate 80 and U.S. Highway 30 corridors from just west of Interstate 35 east.  Some of the heavier snowfall totals included 8.1 inches just southwest of Newton in Jasper County, 7.6 inches in Boone County in Boone, 7.5 inches in Marshall County at Marshalltown, 7.4 inches in Tama County at Garwin, 7.2 inches in Jasper County at Kellogg, and 7 inches just northeast of Des Moines in Polk County.  Roadways became quite slippery, however the snow was generally of light consistency with little wind during the event.  As a result, the heavy snowfall was more of an inconvenience rather than a life threatening event.

Moisture streamed north into the system during the late afternoon and evening hours with surface dew point values reaching the 40s to low 50s south of the low.  The airmass was dry initially, but was overcome by the evening hours.  Very warm air did stream in aloft with 850 mb temperatures above +10 C. over southern Iowa during the early afternoon.  This set the stage for a band of ice pellets and some freezing rain during the initial stages of the snow event.  With the dry atmosphere, temperatures aloft cooled quickly and changed the ice pellets to snow fairly quickly.  Other than the initial onset of the precipitation, most of the precipitation fell as snow.  A band of moderate snow set up across central into east central Iowa as a strong deformation zone set up to the north of the low pressure track.  A band of 6 to 8 inch snowfall occurred in a band about two counties wide between the Interstate 80 and U.S. Highway 30 corridors from just west of Interstate 35 east.  Some of the heavier snowfall totals included 8.1 inches just southwest of Newton in Jasper County, 7.6 inches in Boone County in Boone, 7.5 inches in Marshall County at Marshalltown, 7.4 inches in Tama County at Garwin, 7.2 inches in Jasper County at Kellogg, and 7 inches just northeast of Des Moines in Polk County.  Roadways became quite slippery, however the snow was generally of light consistency with little wind during the event.  As a result, the heavy snowfall was more of an inconvenience rather than a life threatening event.

A deep trough of mid level low pressure, extending from the Upper Midwest southwest into Texas brought a period of cold rain and snow to South Texas on the 4th.  When the clouds cleared at the end of an unusually cold afternoon on the 4th, Canadian high pressure overspread the region overnight on the 4th and into the 5th, bringing the coldest surface temperatures in nearly 5 years to all of Deep South Texas. ||Morning lows on the 5th dropped to the mid 20s to around 30 in all counties, with freezing or lower temperatures lasting up to 6 hours in typically colder pockets.  The freeze was frosty for many critical agricultural areas of the Rio Grande Valley; temperatures hovering just below 32 combined with calm winds limited notable damage to protected crops and plants.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Clearing skies and a chilly air mass (temperatures in the upper 40s) during the afternoon on December 4th set the stage for a widespread freeze overnight on the 4th into the morning of the 5th as winds calmed, allowing temperatures to fall steadily from the 30s into the 20s in Starr County.  By daybreak on the 5th, lows fell to the mid or upper 20s, including 24 at Falcon Lake near the Zapata County line, and 26 at the Rio Grande City Cooperative Observer location.  Estimated and measured duration of 32 degree or lower temperatures was 7 to 10 hours.||The freeze was accompanied by several hours of frost, which combined with calm winds minimized notable damage to temperature sensitive crops.  Unprotected plants at individual residences may have received some damage, but costs were unknown.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Prolonged snowfall produced heavy accumulations over southeast South Dakota, ranging up to over 20 inches in several areas. The snowfall took place from two days before to the day after Christmas. The snowfall was accompanied by increasing north to northwest winds which caused widespread blizzard conditions on Christmas day and the start of the next day. The blizzard added to the very heavy snowfall made almost all travel impossible, and shut down commerce.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow combined with increasing winds to produce widespread blizzard conditions. The snowfall over 3 days varied from 12 to 18 inches. North to northwest winds reached sustained speeds over 30 mph and there were gusts over 40 mph. These winds combined with the heavy snowfall to produce widespread visibilities below a quarter mile from Christmas day to the start of the next day. Most roads were blocked and travel was brought to a standstill, as was the limited holiday commerce.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong low pressure tracked from Texas through Iowa from December 24-25 bringing precipitation which began as freezing rain in many areas due to trapped cold air at the surface. The cold air persisted long enough to allow significant icing of 1/4 to 1/2 inch in many areas, despite very strong east to southeasterly flow of milder air just off the surface. By midday most stations had risen above freezing and liquid rain was falling.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy icing and substantial tree damage was reported near Meadows of Dan with up to 3/4 inch on trees and power lines. There were scattered power outages.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A fast-moving upper-level disturbance tracked through central Illinois on December 19, 2009, bringing a period of light snow to the area.  Total snowfall was generally around 1 inch...with higher amounts northwest of the Illinois River.  Due to the light accumulation of snow, many area roads became slick and hazardous.  As a result, a few traffic accidents were reported.  The most serious accident involved a car on I-55 in Springfield that skidded off the road and hit a light post, killing the driver.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Due to icy road conditions, a car skidded off I-55 in Springfield near the Sangamon Avenue exit at 6:10 AM.  The car struck a light post, killing the driver.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold Canadian system converged with a warm Pacific weather system to produced accumulating snow accross western Montana. Snow amounts ranged from eight to eighteen inches of new snow. In addition, as the strong cold front pushed through northwest Montana, northeast winds caused blowing and drifting snow and low visibilities.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter in Elk City reported 14 inches of snow.  The Idaho DOT reported 12 to 16 inches of new snow along Highway 12 between Lowell and Powell.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous upper level disturbance crossing from Southwest Texas into the Big Bend Region helped intensify a Gulf Low, or Texas Nor'easter, just south of the mouth of the Rio Grande River late on December 15th and 16th.  Moderate to heavy rain developed across the region overnight on the 15th, and continued through the day and evening of the 16th as the system gradually tracked northward along the coast.||Event total rainfall in Hidalgo, Cameron, Willacy, and southern Kenedy County ranged from 3 to 4 1/2 inches, with peak values occurring in the more populated portions of the area including Pharr and McAllen in Hidalgo County, and Brownsville through Harlingen in Cameron County in particular.||The steady rains, falling on increasingly saturated soils, eventually produced pockets of nuisance flooding in typically poor drainage locations across the Lower and Middle Rio Grande Valley from mid morning through early evening on the 16th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rain, heavy at times between the pre dawn hours and mid afternoon on the 16th, accumulated to more than 2 1/2 inches between midnight and noon at McAllen's Miller Airport and likely across nearby areas including Pharr and Edinburg.  The rainfall caused widespread, nuisance (minor) flooding of poor drainage roadways especially in Pharr and Edinburg during the daylight hours of the 16th, slowing traffic.  Event totals in Hidalgo County were among the highest in the Rio Grande Valley, including 4.22 inches at La Joya, 4.40 inches a little north of Pharr, and 3.66 inches at the McAllen/Miller Airport.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deep trough of mid level low pressure, extending from the Upper Midwest southwest into Texas brought a period of cold rain and snow to South Texas on the 4th. The freeze was frosty for many critical agricultural areas of the Rio Grande Valley; temperatures hovering just below 32 combined with calm winds limited notable damage to protected crops and plants.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A drizzly, chilly afternoon on December 4th featured temperatures falling into the upper 30s to around 40 before nightfall.  Clearing skies and calming winds right after dark set the stage for temperatures to steadily fall to or below freezing overnight.  By daybreak on the 5th, readings ranged from the upper 20s to around 30 area wide.  A daily record low was tied in Harlingen (31 degrees) and broken at the Valley International Airport (29 degrees).  ||Duration of freezing or lower temperatures varied by location.  Rural locations in southwestern and northwestern Cameron County likely had 8 hours or more of freezing temperatures; Valley International Airport, just east of populated Harlingen, had more than 6 hours of freezing temperatures.  Farther south and east, Brownsville International Airport had an hour of freezing temperatures; Los Fresnos had only two hours of freezing temperatures.||The freeze was accompanied by several hours of frost, and, with calm winds, there were no reports of notable crop damage in Cameron County.  Residential damage to temperature-sensitive plants likely occurred, but the extent was unknown.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 6 to 10 inches over extreme northeast Nebraska was accompanied by north to northwest winds sustained at 30 to 40 mph, with some gusts over 50 mph. The combination of snow and strong winds created widespread blizzard conditions with visibilities near zero. The blizzard closed schools and businesses and halted travel. The snowfall began on the morning of December 8th. The winds increased during the evening of the 8th, and became strong enough to cause the blizzard after midnight on December 9th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: New snowfall of 7 to 10 inches was accompanied by north to northwest winds sustained at 30 to 40 mph, with gusts up to 50 mph. These strong winds produced widespread blizzard conditions beginning a little after midnight on December 9th. Schools and many businesses were closed on December 9th, as the snowfall and near zero visibilities made travel impossible that morning. Blizzard conditions abated that afternoon as winds steadily decreased, although hazardous wind chills which began during the blizzard continued that night and into the early morning of December 10th. Actual new snowfall reports included 9 inches several miles southwest of Hubbard.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rain, heavy at times during the daylight hours of the 16th, accumulated between 1 1/2 and 2 1/2 inches between 6 AM and 6 PM in a pocket of central Cameron County along and near Highway 77, between Brownsville and Harlingen. The rainfall caused areas of nuisance (minor) flooding of poor drainage roadways in the area during the daylight hours of the 16th, slowing traffic.  Event totals in Cameron County included 4.52 inches in Rancho Viejo, 3.82 inches near Brownsville, and 3.79 inches just west of Harlingen.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A thunderstorm briefly became severe during the early afternoon hours of the 5th. Marginally severe hail was reported north of Sulphur in Murray County. No damage was reported.
A coastal storm brought high winds and rain to much of Southern New England.  These winds resulted in tree damage across much of Massachusetts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Automated Surface Observing System at Fitchburg Municipal Airport (KFIT) recorded wind speeds of 36 mph and gusts to 52 mph.  In addition, trees were downed on Pleasant Street in Leominster and large branches were downed on Clarendon Street in Fitchburg.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large and intense area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and eventually up the east coast on December 18th and 19th. The initial precipitation began as a heavy wet snow on Friday afternoon December 18th. Accumulations around eastern Kentucky ranged between 1 and 4 inches. Ridgetop locations along the Virginia and west Virginia borders saw as much as 6 inches, with 13 inches reported on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County. This initial round of snow fell generally between 2 and 6 pm on the 18th. ||After several hours of nothing but rain, another round of widespread and intense snowfall began at around 10 pm. The Jackson weather office picked up 2.6 inches of snow between 10 pm and midnight on the 18th and there were 11 inches on the ground by early Saturday morning. By 7 am on Saturday December 19th 5 to 7 inches of snow blanketed the ground across much of southeast Kentucky. The highest snowfall totals for this event were 16 inches on Black Mountain, 13 inches on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County, and 11 inches at the Jackson weather office. Numerous trees and power lines were downed by the heavy wet snow with widespread and long lasting power outages reported across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Pike county emergency management reported a power line that had been downed by heavy wet snow was on fire in some trees along River Road in Mouthcard.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A severe thunderstorm drifted northeast from the Atlantic waters to central Marathon, producing strong downburst winds out of the northeast across the east end of Boot Key Harbor and areas around the Sombrero Country Club.  While originally reported as a landfalling waterspout and tornado, wind damage was consistent with that of strong straight-line winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Significant damage to trees was noted along the back nine of the Sombrero Country Club, with lose objects and lawn furniture tossed from under stilted homes into Boot Key Harbor.  No damage was observed to roofing materials, doors or windows.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stationary front stretched from Hartford, Connecticut across northern Rhode Island to southeast Massachusetts combined with an upper level disturbance to produce showers and thunderstorms across southern New England. Plenty of moisture was in place across these areas, increasing the chance for heavy rain and flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The weatherflow station at Fogland recorded a wind gust of 44 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stationary front moved northward as a warm front during the daytime on December 8th, 2009. As the front moved north, an area of low pressure developed along the front. The low pressure brought several periods of heavy rain to West Tennessee. Flash flooding occurred as a result of the heavy rain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain produced flash flooding just west of Mason. Highway 70 was closed as a result.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front approached the Mid-South on December 24th, 2009. Heavy rain ahead of the front produced flash flooding across Eastern Arkansas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Total rainfall from Wheatley was 6.20 inches. The heavy rain produced large areas of standing water.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure tracking just south of the Gulf of Maine brought heavy snow to portions of Downeast Maine. The snow began during the evening of the 5th and continued into the morning of the 6th. Storm total snow accumulations generally ranged from 5 to 9 inches...with the heaviest snow along the coast.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm total snow accumulations ranged from 5 to 7 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A persistent trof focused an extended interval of heavy snow across northern and portions of eastern Maine. Snow began during the afternoon of the 22nd and continued into the evening of the 23rd. The heaviest snow fell across northern and northwestern portions of Aroostook county where storm total snow accumulations of 10 to 15 inches were common...with 16 to 20 inches across the Saint John Valley where isolated totals exceeded 20 inches. A sharp gradient of diminishing snow totals occurred south of the trof.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm total snow accumulations ranged from 10 to 15 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A rare nighttime waterspout was observed near Key West as showers developed along cloud lines near the Lower Florida Keys.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A commercial fisherman reported an unsually nighttime waterspout about one mile south of Key West.  The waterspout dissipated in less than ten minutes while slowly drifting north.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Convergence cloud lines extending off the south Florida mainland became the focus for a waterspout just east of Big Pine Key.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A waterspout was observed as a condensation funnel cloud halfway between the cloud base and water surface about two miles east of No Name Key.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As a strong cold front approached the Florida Keys from the northwest, several waterspouts developed in association with showers and thunderstorms developing in advance of the front.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A waterspout was observed one to one and a half miles south of Key Colony Beach.  The waterspout became mature with a full spray ring visible by 0846 AM EST and drifted towards the east.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure area moved from the Central Rockies across the Central High Plains, producing an area of heavy snow over portions of northwest Kansas and southwest Nebraska.  Snowfall up to 11 inches was reported.  Gusty north winds resulted in some blowing and drifting of snow.  Maximum snow totals in Nebraska included: Six inches in Hitchcock and Red Willow counties.  In Kansas, six inches fell in Rawlins, Sherman and Wallace counties, seven inches in Thomas and Logan counties, eight inches in Sheridan county, ten inches in Decatur, Norton and Gove counties and eleven inches in Graham county.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Up to six inches of snow was reported in Wallace county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful low pressure system moved across Lower Michigan on the 9th.  Snow surged northward ahead of the low, with intense snowfall rates on the morning of the 9th.  By evening, snowfall totals of 6 to 12 inches were common across all of Northern Michigan.  Glennie, Rogers City, and Central Lake all had a foot of snow during the day, while Curtis picked up 16 inches.  The snow transitioned to lake effect snow that night, and lasted into the 11th in some of the snowbelts.  Localized 4 to 8 inch accumulations were common in a given 12 hour period.  There was a considerable amount of wind, and thus blowing and drifting snow, especially on the 9th.  Gaylord had its 2nd largest three-day snowfall since 1950, with 21.8 inches.  Almost all school districts were closed on the 9th, and some schools called off classes for three consecutive days.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A swell from a strong low far northwest of the Aloha State caused surf of 10 to 16 feet along the north-facing shores of Niihau, Kauai, Oahu, Molokai, and Maui; and 6 to 12 feet along the west-facing shores of Niihau and Kauai.  No serious property damage or injuries were reported.

Swells from powerful lows far northwest of the islands caused surf of 20 to 45 feet on north-facing shores of Niihau, Kauai, Oahu, Molokai, and Maui; 10 to 25 feet along the west-facing shores of Niihau, Kauai, Oahu, and Molokai; and 8 to 14 feet along the west-facing shores of the Big Island of Hawaii. The wrap-around effect was also in evidence as surf rose to 6 to 10 feet along the east-facing shores of Kauai, Oahu, and the Big Island. A professional surfer was injured at Waimea Beach Park on Oahu on December 7th because of the conditions. There were no reports of serious property damage, though the surf did deposit sand and other debris on coastal roads and property near the shore in several locales.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The strong pressure gradient associated with a deep area of low pressure that moved across the Great Lakes on December 9th, brought strong and gusty winds to eastern Kentucky. Widespread moderate to sometimes intense rain showers led to some flooding problems around the area as well. Numerous reports of downed trees and power lines were received, inspite of the fact that the winds came up just short of warning criteria. A combination of wet ground and steep terrain allowed the sub warning criteria winds to bring down trees and power lines at many locations around eastern Kentucky.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were blown down in the Barnes Mountain area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Under an unstable air mass, strong convective storms moved over the Portland metro area, dropping healthy amounts of rain.  Given the time of year, with plenty of newly fallen leaves in gutters and street drains, urban flooding was reported around the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A spotter reported flooding of low lying portions of SE Division Street between 140th and 164th Avenues.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Minor road flooding was reported along Science Park Drive near the Hope Depot, with about 4 feet of water covering the road for about 1/10 of a mile.  The road had been blocked off to traffic.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system tracked through Northern Lower Michigan, dragging a cold front through southeast Michigan. Wind gusts to 60 mph occurred south of M-59, which lead to downed tree branches along with a few trees and power lines. About 40,000 customers lost power, most concentrated in Wayne County.

An upper level disturbance brought a general two to four inch snowfall to the entire region. As the storm departed, lake effect snow developed off Lakes Erie and Ontario in the colder, westerly flow. The event was a short lived onemainly in a twelve- hour period from Monday (28th) morning through the pre-dawn hours of Tuesday.  The snows were very disruptive in the Buffalo area during the afternoon commute as whiteout conditions prevailed as 4 to 10 inches of snow falling in just a few hours.  Off Lake Erie, specific snowfall amounts included: Alden 11 inches; Glenwood 10 inches; West Seneca 9 inches; Orchard Park and Elma 8 inches; Dunkirk and Warsaw 7 inches; and Buffalo 3 to 9 inches (from north to south). Off Lake Ontario, specific snowfall amounts included: Copenhagen 14 inches; Beaver Falls 11 inches; Watertown and Lacona 10 inches; Black River 8 inches; and Scriba, Carthage and Palermo 7 inches.

A pre-frontal squall line extended across southwest Georgia into the Florida panhandle as a strong short wave trough traversed the local area in the evening. These features enhanced scattered storms that developed across the local area over an unstable airmass.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Power lines were blown down near Hoboken.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms erupted during the late night and early morning hours across north Alabama in advance of a strong storm system moving from the southern Plains into the middle Mississippi Valley.  The storms evolved into a small quasi-linear convective system (QLCS) as they moved into northeast Alabama.  A meso-cyclone developed along this line producing a short-lived EF0 tornado in eastern Marshall County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown down by thunderstorm winds at the intersection of 4th Street NE and 7th Avenue NE. The tree landed on a car which was luckily unoccupied.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level storm moving across the Mississipi Valley brought a dry line and cold front into north Alabama during the afternoon and early evening hours.  Several classic supercell thunderstorms developed by early afternoon in northwest Alabama, sweeping across the remainder of north Alabama during mid to late afternoon hours.  Many of the storms produced very large hail, up to baseball and softball sized, producing significant damage, especially from Decatur through Madison and northwest Huntsville.   One of the supercells produced a long track tornado producing damage of up to EF-3 intensity which struck northeastern Marshall County, crossed Lake Guntersville, and moved into southern DeKalb County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail was reported by UAH storm spotters at the intersection of County Line Road and Palmer Road.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Unusually high tides produced flooding on portions of Front Street and Orange Street. Six inches of water entered a few establishments.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong area of low pressure moved from the gulf coast to offshore the Carolinas and up the east coast from the 18th to the 19th. This storm produced heavy snow across Garrett county Maryland, portions of northern West Virginia, and portions of Fayette and Westmorland counties in Pennsylvania. Total storm accumulations were from one to 2 feet in Preston and Tucker counties in West Virginia with over a foot in Garrett county Maryland. Storm totals were 6 to 12 inches elsewhere.

A strong area of low pressure moved from the gulf coast to offshore the Carolinas and up the east coast from the 18th to the 19th. This storm produced heavy snow across Garrett county Maryland, portions of northern West Virginia, and portions of Fayette and Westmorland counties in Pennsylvania. Total storm accumulations were from one to 2 feet in Preston and Tucker counties in West Virginia with over a foot in Garrett county Maryland. Storm totals were 6 to 12 inches elsewhere.

An upper atmospheric area of low pressure and weak surface low moved across Vermont on the morning of December 28th. Periods of light snow occurred from daybreak through the late afternoon hours on December 28th which resulted in 2 to 4 inches of snow accumulation with localized higher amounts.||An arctic cold front and upper atmospheric disturbance moved across Vermont during the morning commute of December 29th with snow showers and localized snow squalls. Widespread snowfall accumulations of 1 to 3 inches occurred with localized amounts up to 4 inches.||Two-day storm totals were 4 to 12 inches across much of Vermont. Some specific higher snowfall totals included; 12 inches in Killington (Rutland county), 11 inches in Westfield (Orleans county) and North Underhill (Chittenden county), 10 inches in Lincoln (Addison county), 9 inches in Jay (Orleans county) and Richmond (Chittenden county), 7 inches in Sutton (Caledonia county), South Burlington (Chittenden county), Eden (Lamoille county), Rutland (Rutland county), Northfield (Washington county) and Sheldon Springs (Franklin county) with 6 inches in Stowe (Lamoille county), Newport (Orleans county), Waterbury (Washington county) and Bethel (Windsor county).||Rapidly falling temperatures to the single digits above zero degrees along with falling and blowing snow during the morning commute of December 29th accounted for roads to flash freeze that resulted in numerous vehicle accidents, especially along Interstate 89 between Montpelier and St. Albans.

Overall, drought conditions continued to ease across most of South Texas during the month of December, as almost all of South Texas experienced above normal rainfall during the month. Strengthening El Nino conditions, in part, helped to produce the beneficial rainfall. ||Along and southwest of Interstate 37 many locations received more than 200% normal precipitation for the month of December.  The Corpus Christi International Airport received 3.96 of rainfall for the month, roughly 225% of normal rainfall for December.  Along and northeast of Interstate 37 most locations received between 100-200% of normal precipitation.  The Victoria Regional Airport received 3.74 of rainfall for the month, roughly 150% of normal for December.||By the end of the first week in December, Victoria, Goliad, Bee, Refugio and Calhoun counties were no longer considered to be in drought, and by the middle of the month Aransas county was no longer in drought.  By the end of December, only Jim Wells and Duval counties were considered to be in extreme drought.  Severe drought conditions were observed across southern San Patricio, Nueces, Kleberg, and southeastern Webb counties.  Moderate drought conditions were observed across northern San Patricio, southern Live Oak, and southern McMullen counties. (per the U.S. Drought Monitor: http://www.drought.unl.edu/dm/monitor.html) ||Near to slightly above normal soil moisture was observed across all of South Texas by the end of December.  Supplemental feeding of hay for livestock continued to decline.  Pecan harvesting was actually slowed due to the rain.  Most cattle remained in good condition.  Wheat and oats progressed from fair to good condition because of the light rains and cool temperatures.  Cool season grasses looked good and the fire |danger remained low during the month. ||Reservoir levels for the Corpus Christi and Victoria water supply either rose or remained nearly steady during the month.  Choke Canyon Reservoir was near 68% capacity and Lake Corpus Christi near 33% capacity by the end of the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: High winds developed along the Rocky Mountain Front due to a strong surface gradient. Wind gusts in excess of 60 mph were reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust to 65 mph was reported at East Glacier 8SE (site known as Deep Creek).

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Severe Thunderstorms including supercells and organized multicell storms developed across parts of Kansas during the evening of June 7.  The storms produced numerous reports of large hail and a few reports of wind damage also occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Nickel and penny size hail along with quarter size hail was reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Severe Thunderstorms including supercells and organized multicell storms developed across parts of Kansas during the evening of June 7.  The storms produced numerous reports of large hail and a few reports of wind damage also occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Nickel size hail was reported by a trained spotter.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Severe Thunderstorms including supercells and organized multicell storms developed across parts of Kansas during the evening of June 7.  The storms produced numerous reports of large hail and a few reports of wind damage also occurred.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Light freezing rain developed late on Christmas Eve and continued throughout the overnight before becoming heavier shortly before sunrise. Light ice accretion occurred, mainly on elevated surfaces during this time. Quite a few slick spots also developed, mainly on bridges and overpasses. Freezing rain continued through the morning hours along the eastern escarpment of the Blue Ridge, and became heavy at times by mid-morning. By the time the precipitation tapered off, ice accretion ranged from .25 to .5 inch across much of the area. The combination of ice and wind gusts up to 60 mph (with gusts up to 80 mph in the higher elevations) caused numerous trees and power lines to fall. The resultant widespread power outages exacerbated the problems for areas that had yet to recover from the December 18th snowstorm.

A strong weather system remained stalled over the region with several rounds of heavy rainfall.  This caused widespread flash flooding and flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Up to three inches of rain fell in a short amount of time on saturated soils causing flash flooding.  Numerous roads were flooded including Highway BB southeast of Tipton. Also, a car was washed off of Highway BB just south of U.S. 50.  No one was injured due to the incident.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong weather system remained stalled over the region with several rounds of heavy rainfall.  This caused widespread flash flooding and flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Between 3 and 4 inches of rain fell in a short amount of time on saturated soils causing flash flooding.  Numerous roads were flooded including Highway C at the intersection with Silvers Road and Highway N east of the intersection with Highway K.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Substantial low level moisture combined with an upper level disturbance to produce showers and thunderstorms across Southern New England.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees near the Route 1 auto mile were downed by thunderstorm winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Substantial low level moisture combined with an upper level disturbance to produce showers and thunderstorms across Southern New England.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were downed by thunderstorm winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A fast-moving storm brought widespread strong winds to northeast and eastern California on November 20. The storm also produced a modest snowfall from around Lake Tahoe northward.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A spotter two miles west of Loyalton reported winds sustained at 55 mph with gusts to 65 mph at 1133PST.  Additional high wind gusts include: 67 mph at Bull Flat RAWS at 1059PST and 69 mph at Doyle RAWS at 1211PST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A fast-moving storm brought widespread strong winds to northeast and eastern California on November 20. The storm also produced a modest snowfall from around Lake Tahoe northward.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Winds were sustained between 40-50 mph on Lake Tahoe.  Truckee AWOS recorded a gust to 64 mph at 1255PST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large and intense area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and eventually up the east coast on December 18th and 19th. The initial precipitation began as a heavy wet snow on Friday afternoon December 18th. Accumulations around eastern Kentucky ranged between 1 and 4 inches. Ridgetop locations along the Virginia and west Virginia borders saw as much as 6 inches, with 13 inches reported on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County. This initial round of snow fell generally between 2 and 6 pm on the 18th. ||After several hours of nothing but rain, another round of widespread and intense snowfall began at around 10 pm. The Jackson weather office picked up 2.6 inches of snow between 10 pm and midnight on the 18th and there were 11 inches on the ground by early Saturday morning. By 7 am on Saturday December 19th 5 to 7 inches of snow blanketed the ground across much of southeast Kentucky. The highest snowfall totals for this event were 16 inches on Black Mountain, 13 inches on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County, and 11 inches at the Jackson weather office. Numerous trees and power lines were downed by the heavy wet snow with widespread and long lasting power outages reported across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two inches of snow was reported on the ground by the Middlesboro rescue squad.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper atmospheric area of low pressure and weak surface low moved across Vermont on the morning of December 28th. Periods of light snow occurred from daybreak through the late afternoon hours on December 28th which resulted in 2 to 4 inches of snow accumulation with localized higher amounts.||An arctic cold front and upper atmospheric disturbance moved across Vermont during the morning commute of December 29th with snow showers and localized snow squalls. Widespread snowfall accumulations of 1 to 3 inches occurred with localized amounts up to 4 inches.||Two-day storm totals were 4 to 12 inches across much of Vermont. Some specific higher snowfall totals included; 12 inches in Killington (Rutland county), 11 inches in Westfield (Orleans county) and North Underhill (Chittenden county), 10 inches in Lincoln (Addison county), 9 inches in Jay (Orleans county) and Richmond (Chittenden county), 7 inches in Sutton (Caledonia county), South Burlington (Chittenden county), Eden (Lamoille county), Rutland (Rutland county), Northfield (Washington county) and Sheldon Springs (Franklin county) with 6 inches in Stowe (Lamoille county), Newport (Orleans county), Waterbury (Washington county) and Bethel (Windsor county).||Rapidly falling temperatures to the single digits above zero degrees along with falling and blowing snow during the morning commute of December 29th accounted for roads to flash freeze that resulted in numerous vehicle accidents, especially along Interstate 89 between Montpelier and St. Albans.

A surface low developed along a northward moving front and positioned across central Florida. Strong isentropic life and high moisture coincided along the front over Flagler county where heavy rainfall occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: County emergency management relayed storm total rainfall amounts of 1 to 2 inches across Palm Coast, with the highest amount of 3.5 inches measured in west-central Palm Coast. Elsewhere across the county, storm total amounts ranged from 3 inches in Bunnell to 4.30 inches in Haw Creek.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A major Bering sea storm and the associated front that extended to the Gulf of Alaska produced high winds across the Aleutians and blizzard conditions from the Pribilof Islands to the Bering Sea coast and high wind heavy snow and blizzard conditions across south central Alaska and Prince William Sound.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Cordova Boat Harbor weather system observed an 81 KT gust.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A major Bering sea storm and the associated front that extended to the Gulf of Alaska produced high winds across the Aleutians and blizzard conditions from the Pribilof Islands to the Bering Sea coast and high wind heavy snow and blizzard conditions across south central Alaska and Prince William Sound.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Spotters in the Susitna Valley reported snow fall totals as high as 37 inches for this storm.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An intense north Pacific storm moved into the central Bering Sea overnight December 3rd. This storm produced high wind across the Aleutians and Alaska Peninsula to the Pribilof Islands as well as snow and blizzard conditions in the Pribilof Islands.

A strong cold front swept across the mountains of North Carolina during the morning of November 27th. Northwest winds increased substantially, gusting to 60 mph and downing a couple of trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two trees were blown down in West Jefferson.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The remnants of Hurricane Ida soaked the region during November 12th. Winds gusting up to 35 mph and the wet ground made it easier for smaller trees to fall. One tree fell on a car, killing the driver in Rockingham county.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree fell onto a car, resulting in one fatality. This occurred 3 miles south of Bethany, on Witty Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Winds gusting to 30 to 40 mph combined with torrential rains, and wet soil, made it easier for trees to fall in the area November 11th, as the remnants of Tropical Storm Ida affected the region. Although no damage to structures were reported, one downed tree was run into by a vehicle, resulting in the driver being injured.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A four foot diameter tree fell onto Highway 60. A vehicle crashed into it resulting in one person being injured. The extent of the injury was unknown.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front embedded with a weak short wave of low pressure aloft moved into northeast Texas and southwest Arkansas.  Storms developed along this boundary and shear was excessive enough such that a weak tornado developed along the boundary.  In addition, heavy rainfall occurred across the region producing some flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A mother and her infant were trapped by flood waters at State Line Road and 40th Street.  The were rescued with no injuries reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front embedded with a weak short wave of low pressure aloft moved into northeast Texas and southwest Arkansas. Storms developed along this boundary and shear was excessive enough such that a weak tornado developed along the boundary. In addition, heavy rainfall occurred across the region producing some flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An EF1 tornado briefly touched down in New Boston, Texas along Pearly Street.  A mobile home was destroyed and 4 other homes sustained moderate to major damage.  Several trees were uprooted.  The tornado crossed Interstate 30 and quickly dissipated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dry weather persisted over parts of Molokai, Maui, and the Big Island of Hawaii.  Water restrictions remained in effect.
Dry weather persisted over parts of Molokai, Maui, and the Big Island of Hawaii.  Water restrictions remained in effect.

An area of low pressure moving up the east coast on December 5th brought subfreezing air and widespread light snowfall to eastern Kentucky. Most area received between 1 and 3 inches of the white stuff by Saturday afternoon, with locally higher amounts in the mountains along the Virginia and West Virginia borders.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two and a half inches of snow fell 1 mile west of Van Lear.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: An inch of snow fell 3 miles southwest of Clay City.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong wind gust downed a tree in Breathitt County on Christmas day.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown down across Highway 30 at Noctor.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak disturbance brought isolated light snow showers to portions of eastern Kentucky on December 31st.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An inch of snow fell at the Jackson weather office between 7 pm on December 30th and 1 am on December 31st.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered showers and thunderstorms developed as the result of an upper level disturbance moving through southern New England.  Unusually cold air in the upper levels aided in the development of large hail within these storms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A two and a half foot diameter tree on Cameron Avenue was downed by thunderstorm winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Isolated severe thunderstorms developed across the Trans Pecos region as an upper level trough remained across the Great Basin area. Modest low level moisture, instability and shear all combined to produce a few severe storms. Several large hail reports occurred during this event.

Isolated severe thunderstorms developed across the Trans Pecos region as an upper level trough remained across the Great Basin area. Modest low level moisture, instability and shear all combined to produce a few severe storms. Several large hail reports occurred during this event.

A dryline moved across West Texas on this day, resulting in thunderstorm development across the region.  In addition to the dryline, a cold front also approached the area from the north providing an additional focus for thunderstorms.

On this day, a surface trough located near southeast New Mexico was the focus for some thunderstorm development.  The deep layer shear and surface based instability resulted in a couple of severe thunderstorms.

On this day, a surface trough located near southeast New Mexico was the focus for some thunderstorm development.  The deep layer shear and surface based instability resulted in a couple of severe thunderstorms.
Intense heating along a dryline and upper level support from a speed max resulted in a couple of severe thunderstorms across portions of the Trans Pecos and Permian Basin of southwest Texas.

Considerable mid level moisture across portions of southwest Texas and lift associated with a shortwave trough resulted in thunderstorm development this day.  Although coverage remained isolated to widely scattered, multiple severe reports were received due to the instability across the region.

The strong pressure gradient associated with a deep area of low pressure that moved across the Great Lakes on December 9th, brought strong and gusty winds to eastern Kentucky. Widespread moderate to sometimes intense rain showers led to some flooding problems around the area as well. Numerous reports of downed trees and power lines were received, inspite of the fact that the winds came up just short of warning criteria. A combination of wet ground and steep terrain allowed the sub warning criteria winds to bring down trees and power lines at many locations around eastern Kentucky.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were blown down on Tap Lane 5 miles southeast of Mount Sterling.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were blown down on Highway 30 about 5 miles west of Booneville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A long wave trough was over the eastern U.S. with a swath of moisture confined over central Florida and points southward. Subsidence and dry air was noted over Southeast Georgia and portions of Northeast Florida. A shortwave trough move across the area over an environment that consisted of 1.5 PWAT and modified CAPES of 4200 J/kg and a lifted index of -8.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were blown down on St. Simons Island.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were blown down county-wide. Most damage was south of U.S. Highway 82 and east of U.S. Highway 301.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A long wave trough was over the eastern U.S. with a swath of moisture confined over central Florida and points southward. Subsidence and dry air was noted over Southeast Georgia and portions of Northeast Florida. A shortwave trough move across the area over an environment that consisted of 1.5 PWAT and modified CAPES of 4200 J/kg and a lifted index of -8.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Large metal signs and construction barrels were blown over across Interstate 95 from thunderstorm winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level disturbance brought a general two to four inch snowfall to the entire region. As the storm departed, lake effect snow developed off Lakes Erie and Ontario in the colder, westerly flow. The event was a short lived onemainly in a twelve- hour period from Monday (28th) morning through the pre-dawn hours of Tuesday.  The snows were very disruptive in the Buffalo area during the afternoon commute as whiteout conditions prevailed as 4 to 10 inches of snow falling in just a few hours.  Off Lake Erie, specific snowfall amounts included: Alden 11 inches; Glenwood 10 inches; West Seneca 9 inches; Orchard Park and Elma 8 inches; Dunkirk and Warsaw 7 inches; and Buffalo 3 to 9 inches (from north to south). Off Lake Ontario, specific snowfall amounts included: Copenhagen 14 inches; Beaver Falls 11 inches; Watertown and Lacona 10 inches; Black River 8 inches; and Scriba, Carthage and Palermo 7 inches.

On Friday December 4th, and for the second year in a row, an early December snow storm struck southern portions of the ArkLaMiss. This occurred as a strong upper level disturbance helped to induce a low pressure system over the northwest Gulf of Mexico. As was the case with last year's December snow storm, very little if any snow fell in extreme Southeast Arkansas and North Central Mississippi.  Light snow fell along the Interstate 20 corridor with up to an inch falling from Jackson to Meridian in Central Mississippi.  The heaviest snow fell along the Highway 84 corridor, where amounts ranged from two to five inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Measurable snow was reported across Adams County, with 3 inches reported in and around Natchez.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level storm moving across the Mississipi Valley brought a dry line and cold front into north Alabama during the afternoon and early evening hours.  Several classic supercell thunderstorms developed by early afternoon in northwest Alabama, sweeping across the remainder of north Alabama during mid to late afternoon hours.  Many of the storms produced very large hail, up to baseball and softball sized, producing significant damage, especially from Decatur through Madison and northwest Huntsville.   One of the supercells produced a long track tornado producing damage of up to EF-3 intensity which struck northeastern Marshall County, crossed Lake Guntersville, and moved into southern DeKalb County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Golf ball size hail was reported in the Wilhites community.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Light freezing rain developed late on Christmas Eve and continued throughout the overnight before becoming heavier shortly before sunrise. Light ice accretion occurred, mainly on elevated surfaces during this time. Quite a few slick spots also developed, mainly on bridges and overpasses. Freezing rain continued through the morning hours along the eastern escarpment of the Blue Ridge, and became heavy at times by mid-morning. By the time the precipitation tapered off, ice accretion ranged from .25 to .5 inch across much of the area. The combination of ice and wind gusts up to 60 mph (with gusts up to 80 mph in the higher elevations) caused numerous trees and power lines to fall. The resultant widespread power outages exacerbated the problems for areas that had yet to recover from the December 18th snowstorm.

A large and intense area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and eventually up the east coast on December 18th and 19th. The initial precipitation began as a heavy wet snow on Friday afternoon December 18th. Accumulations around eastern Kentucky ranged between 1 and 4 inches. Ridgetop locations along the Virginia and west Virginia borders saw as much as 6 inches, with 13 inches reported on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County. This initial round of snow fell generally between 2 and 6 pm on the 18th. ||After several hours of nothing but rain, another round of widespread and intense snowfall began at around 10 pm. The Jackson weather office picked up 2.6 inches of snow between 10 pm and midnight on the 18th and there were 11 inches on the ground by early Saturday morning. By 7 am on Saturday December 19th 5 to 7 inches of snow blanketed the ground across much of southeast Kentucky. The highest snowfall totals for this event were 16 inches on Black Mountain, 13 inches on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County, and 11 inches at the Jackson weather office. Numerous trees and power lines were downed by the heavy wet snow with widespread and long lasting power outages reported across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An inch of new snowfall was measured in Elkhorn City. The snowflakes were the size of half dollars and fell in a one hour period with snow covering the roads.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Extreme (D3) drought conditions prevailed across portions of northwest Wisconsin in early November, mainly across Sawyer and Washburn counties.  This area was downgraded slightly to severe (D2) drought status by the middle and end of the month.  Severe drought conditions also covered much of Price, as well as southern Iron, Ashland, and Bayfield counties, and eastern Burnett county through the month of November.

An upper level trough of low pressure with associated surface low and cold front moved across Eastern Tennessee late in the afternoon with extension into the early evening hours. This allowed for the formation of scattered convection in the moderately unstable atmospheric conditions just ahead of the front.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: One tree was reported down on Gamble Gap Road two miles northwest of Tellico Plains.

October of 2009 had been a very wet month.  Flooding that began in late October continued into early November.  The flooding was limited in nature, only affecting a few locations along the Skunk and Cedar River systems.  Damage was minimal.

Light snow accumulations in combination with a busy traffic period contributed to seven traffic accidents between Colfax and Uniontown on Highway 195.  A trained spotter in Pullman measured 1.3 inches of snow.

A combination of raised water levels from a persistent northeast wind, and high surf from swell generated by distant Hurricane Ida, led to moderate coastal flooding and beach erosion. This occurred around the time of high tide during the evenings of November 9th and November 10th.

Winds gusted to 40 to 50 mph in the area during the morning, with an isolated higher gust downing a tree in western Tazewell County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A relatively warm system moved in from the Pacific ocean at this time...but cold air was still trapped in some western Oregon valleys.  Rain falling into these valleys froze on contact.  The resulting layer of ice was very thin, but driving and walking conditions were treacherous.   Over 125 accidents were reported in Jackson County alone.  Most of the freezing precipitation reports came from Josephine County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous reports of freezing rain were received from spotters.  Traffic accidents were also reported by the newpapers.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Excessive heavy rainfall during the month of October resulted in a record breaking crest on the Bayou Bodcau Reservoir in the month of November.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Bayou Bodcau Reservoir near Bellview, Louisiana crested at its highest pool stage of record during November 5th at 200.27 feet.  The old pool stage of record was 197.40 feet set during March 18th of 2001.  With this kind of flooding, numerous trees will no doubt drown and considerable timber losses can be expected.  By mid November, the Corps of Engineers reopened the lake park to visitors but camps and recreational areas and trails behind the dam remained flooded through the end of the month.

Widespread moderate to sometimes intense rain showers led to some flooding problems around the area as well. Numerous reports of downed trees and power lines were received, inspite of the fact that the winds came up just short of warning criteria. A combination of wet ground and steep terrain allowed the sub warning criteria winds to bring down trees and power lines at many locations around eastern Kentucky.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On Friday December 4th, and for the second year in a row, an early December snow storm struck southern portions of the ArkLaMiss. This occurred as a strong upper level disturbance helped to induce a low pressure system over the northwest Gulf of Mexico. As was the case with last year's December snow storm, very little if any snow fell in extreme Southeast Arkansas and North Central Mississippi.  Light snow fell along the Interstate 20 corridor with up to an inch falling from Jackson to Meridian in Central Mississippi.  The heaviest snow fell along the Highway 84 corridor, where amounts ranged from two to five inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Over an inch of snow occurred across Smith County, with 2 inches reported in and around Smith County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As warm air headed north ahead of low pressure moving into the Ohio Valley freezing rain quickly developed across much of eastern Ohio, western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia, and Garrett county Maryland. Untreated roadways quickly accumulated up to one tenth of an inch of ice making travel nearly impossible between 6 AM and 10 AM. Major interstates in and around Pittsburgh, including the Pennsylvania Turnpike were closed for more than 2 hours until roads could be treated and surface temperatures warmed above freezing. 911 centers across the area received thousands of call due to minor accidents. 2 more serious accidents resulted in 2 deaths, one in Beaver county, PA and one in Westmoreland county, PA.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two trees were blown down, with one large tree across Highway 573.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper atmospheric area of low pressure and weak surface low moved across Vermont on the morning of December 28th. Periods of light snow occurred from daybreak through the late afternoon hours on December 28th which resulted in 2 to 4 inches of snow accumulation with localized higher amounts.||An arctic cold front and upper atmospheric disturbance moved across Vermont during the morning commute of December 29th with snow showers and localized snow squalls. Widespread snowfall accumulations of 1 to 3 inches occurred with localized amounts up to 4 inches.||Two-day storm totals were 4 to 12 inches across much of Vermont. Some specific higher snowfall totals included; 12 inches in Killington (Rutland county), 11 inches in Westfield (Orleans county) and North Underhill (Chittenden county), 10 inches in Lincoln (Addison county), 9 inches in Jay (Orleans county) and Richmond (Chittenden county), 7 inches in Sutton (Caledonia county), South Burlington (Chittenden county), Eden (Lamoille county), Rutland (Rutland county), Northfield (Washington county) and Sheldon Springs (Franklin county) with 6 inches in Stowe (Lamoille county), Newport (Orleans county), Waterbury (Washington county) and Bethel (Windsor county).||Rapidly falling temperatures to the single digits above zero degrees along with falling and blowing snow during the morning commute of December 29th accounted for roads to flash freeze that resulted in numerous vehicle accidents, especially along Interstate 89 between Montpelier and St. Albans.

Pacific moisture and post-frontal cold arctic air combibed to produce winter weather over a broad portion of North central Montana. Snow accumulations in excess of 8 inches were common. In addition to the snow, very cold wind chill readings were also reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 12 inches over 24 hours at 1W Marysville. Elevation 5750 feet.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Freezing rain developed over portions of North Central Montana. Ice accumulations of one-quarter inch were reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Law Enforcement officials report about .25 of inch of ice on roadways at Geyser.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A system moving west to east between 35 and 40 north latitude brought a heavy, wet snow to western Nevada.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: This storm produced a average of 1 to 2 feet of snowfall. Here are some reports: Mount Rose Ski Area with 26 inches, Incline Village with 19.5 inches, Dagget Pass with 15 inches, and Glenbrook with 12 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A system moving west to east between 35 and 40 north latitude brought a heavy, wet snow to western Nevada.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A solid 4 to 8 inches of snow fell with this system, especially in the foothills and north of highway 50. Here are some specific snowfall totals: 10 inches in NW Reno and Cold Springs Valley (Far NW Reno), 8 inches at the WFO Reno, 6 inches in Virginia City, and 4 inches at the Reno-Tahoe International airport.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An arctic airmass came through all of central and south central Texas before an upper level disturbance and strong jet stream moved overhead during the overnight hours on January 27 and the early morning of January 28.  Freezing rain was reported across much of the hill country and the interstate 35 corridor from New Braunfels up through Georgetown and Williamson County.  Many traffic accidents were reported with ice buildup from one tenth of an inch up to one quarter of an inch.  Heaviest ice was up through Williamson County where major impacts on roads and bridges were observed.  Elsewhere, bridges were iced and dangerous with ice accumulation on outside surfaces.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy ice accumulation was observed on guide wires around Rock Springs.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Light freezing rain developed during the evening across the mountains of extreme northeast Georgia. Ice accretion was mainly limited to elevated surfaces.

Freezing rain developed in some of the high valleys of the northern mountains during the evening. Ice accumulation was mainly confined to elevated surfaces. The freezing rain changed to rain soon after midnight.
A strong weather system remained stalled over the region with several rounds of heavy rainfall.  This caused widespread flash flooding and flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Up to three inches of rain fell in a short amount of time on saturated soils causing flash flooding.  Numerous roads were flooded including Highway Y due to water flowing out of Bear Creek.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large and intense area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and eventually up the east coast on December 18th and 19th. The initial precipitation began as a heavy wet snow on Friday afternoon December 18th. Accumulations around eastern Kentucky ranged between 1 and 4 inches. Ridgetop locations along the Virginia and west Virginia borders saw as much as 6 inches, with 13 inches reported on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County. This initial round of snow fell generally between 2 and 6 pm on the 18th. ||After several hours of nothing but rain, another round of widespread and intense snowfall began at around 10 pm. The Jackson weather office picked up 2.6 inches of snow between 10 pm and midnight on the 18th and there were 11 inches on the ground by early Saturday morning. By 7 am on Saturday December 19th 5 to 7 inches of snow blanketed the ground across much of southeast Kentucky. The highest snowfall totals for this event were 16 inches on Black Mountain, 13 inches on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County, and 11 inches at the Jackson weather office. Numerous trees and power lines were downed by the heavy wet snow with widespread and long lasting power outages reported across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two and a half inches of snow was reported on the ground in Pineville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level trough of low pressure with associated surface low and cold front moved across Eastern Tennessee late in the afternoon with extension into the early evening hours. This allowed for the formation of scattered convection in the moderately unstable atmospheric conditions just ahead of the front.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 100 year old elm tree fell onto a home which resulted in damage to the home's deck, back room, and the roof over the kitchen.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Widely scattered convection formed mainly north of Interstate 40 across Northeast Tennessee.  Storm formation was initiated by an upper level trough of low pressure crossing the Southern Appalachians in a weakly to moderately unstable air mass in place across the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees were reported down in Kingsport.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The remnants from Hurricane Ida which made landfall along the Florida panhandle combined with a powerful upper level storm system along the Carolina coast. The result was a powerful low pressure system which developed near Cape Fear and tracked to Cape Hatteras. Between 3 to 6 inches of rain fell across central North Carolina over a 3 day period. Gusty winds to 35 to 45 mph combined with saturated soil resulted in power outages and some property damage from falling trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts of 40 to 45 mph along with heavy rain resulted in numerous trees falling and knocking down power lines.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure tracking across the Pacific Northwest brought moisture into Montana from the south while cold air was moving into the state from Canada. The result was winter storm conditions, mainly confined to elevations above 5000 feet. Snow amounts in excess of 6 inches were reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Fifteen inches of snow fell at Lima 23SW (the Beagle Springs SNOTEL site - elevation 8850 feet).

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A combination of raised water levels from a persistent northeast wind, and high surf from swell generated by distant Hurricane Ida, led to moderate coastal flooding and beach erosion. This occurred around the time of high tide during the evenings of November 9th and November 10th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Water on Blue Water Highway on November 8th and 9th, enough to close the road evening of November 9th. Several roads closed San Luis Pass and Treasure Island subdivisions. Considerable debris pushed up on roadway in Surfside due to high surf and elevated water levels during evening of November 9th.

A strengthening area of low pressure moved out of the Gulf of Mexico, across southern Georgia, and then up the southeast coast. As the low passed south of the region, light snow became heavier across the mountains of extreme northern Greenville County. The heavy snow continued throughout the afternoon. Snowfall rates of 1-2 inches per hour became common across the area during the afternoon. The heavy, wet snow combined with gusty winds to cause numerous trees and power lines to fall across the area during the afternoon. Power outages resulted, and some customers were without power for as much as a week. The snow quickly ended on the evening of the 18th. Total accumulations ranged from 6-10 inches.||Many traffic accidents were reported during the storm, and continued for several days thereafter, as continuous melting and refreezing of ice and snow resulted in treacherous road conditions during the late night and morning hours.

In the wake of a cold front, temperatures across the region plummeted. The high at Fresno on November 12th was only 54 degrees, 10 degrees cooler than the previous days high and only 2 degrees above the record low maximum for the date, set in 1916. The morning of November 14th saw lows at the Wasco ALERT station and N.A.S. Lemoore of 29 degrees. A dry cold front moved through central California during the afternoon of the 14th, bringing another push of cold air into the region. Winds behind the front caused the development of upslope clouds along the foothills of the Southern Sierra Nevada. The next morning saw the first widespread hard freeze hit the Kern County deserts (the Western Mojave Desert), with lows in the coldest locations falling into the middle 20s.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong thunderstorm moved over the coastal waters on during the evening, which spawned a waterspout that moved ashore as a tornado.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The tornado caused widespread damage to a neighborhood in the Roads End area of Lincoln City, damaging 11 homes, 3 automobiles, and uprooting a couple trees and snapping another.  The uprooted trees were about 20-24 inches in diameter, and one was carried 20 yards downwind.  One home had major roof damage, with 40-50% of the roof collapsed.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Under an unstable air mass, a couple funnel clouds were spawned but never touched down.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A funnel cloud was reportedly spotted over McNary Feild in Salem, but stayed aloft and never touched down.  NWS WSR-88D Doppler radar indicated many convective showers around the area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level disturbance brought a general two to four inch snowfall to the entire region. As the storm departed, lake effect snow developed off Lakes Erie and Ontario in the colder, westerly flow. The event was a short lived onemainly in a twelve- hour period from Monday (28th) morning through the pre-dawn hours of Tuesday.  The snows were very disruptive in the Buffalo area during the afternoon commute as whiteout conditions prevailed as 4 to 10 inches of snow falling in just a few hours.  Off Lake Erie, specific snowfall amounts included: Alden 11 inches; Glenwood 10 inches; West Seneca 9 inches; Orchard Park and Elma 8 inches; Dunkirk and Warsaw 7 inches; and Buffalo 3 to 9 inches (from north to south). Off Lake Ontario, specific snowfall amounts included: Copenhagen 14 inches; Beaver Falls 11 inches; Watertown and Lacona 10 inches; Black River 8 inches; and Scriba, Carthage and Palermo 7 inches.

A strong upper level storm moving across the Mississipi Valley brought a dry line and cold front into north Alabama during the afternoon and early evening hours.  Several classic supercell thunderstorms developed by early afternoon in northwest Alabama, sweeping across the remainder of north Alabama during mid to late afternoon hours.  Many of the storms produced very large hail, up to baseball and softball sized, producing significant damage, especially from Decatur through Madison and northwest Huntsville.   One of the supercells produced a long track tornado producing damage of up to EF-3 intensity which struck northeastern Marshall County, crossed Lake Guntersville, and moved into southern DeKalb County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Penny size hail was reported 2.5 miles north of Priceville on Old Bethel Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level storm moving across the Mississipi Valley brought a dry line and cold front into north Alabama during the afternoon and early evening hours.  Several classic supercell thunderstorms developed by early afternoon in northwest Alabama, sweeping across the remainder of north Alabama during mid to late afternoon hours.  Many of the storms produced very large hail, up to baseball and softball sized, producing significant damage, especially from Decatur through Madison and northwest Huntsville.   One of the supercells produced a long track tornado producing damage of up to EF-3 intensity which struck northeastern Marshall County, crossed Lake Guntersville, and moved into southern DeKalb County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail up to 0.875 inches fell east of Sheffield.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As warm air headed north ahead of low pressure moving into the Ohio Valley freezing rain quickly developed across much of eastern Ohio, western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia, and Garrett county Maryland. Untreated roadways quickly accumulated up to one tenth of an inch of ice making travel nearly impossible between 6 AM and 10 AM. Major interstates in and around Pittsburgh, including the Pennsylvania Turnpike were closed for more than 2 hours until roads could be treated and surface temperatures warmed above freezing. 911 centers across the area received thousands of call due to minor accidents. 2 more serious accidents resulted in 2 deaths, one in Beaver county, PA and one in Westmoreland county, PA.

A strong area of low pressure moved from the gulf coast to offshore the Carolinas and up the east coast from the 18th to the 19th. This storm produced heavy snow across Garrett county Maryland, portions of northern West Virginia, and portions of Fayette and Westmorland counties in Pennsylvania. Total storm accumulations were from one to 2 feet in Preston and Tucker counties in West Virginia with over a foot in Garrett county Maryland. Storm totals were 6 to 12 inches elsewhere.
