EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper atmospheric area of low pressure and weak surface low moved across Vermont on the morning of December 28th. Periods of light snow occurred from daybreak through the late afternoon hours on December 28th which resulted in 2 to 4 inches of snow accumulation with localized higher amounts.||An arctic cold front and upper atmospheric disturbance moved across Vermont during the morning commute of December 29th with snow showers and localized snow squalls. Widespread snowfall accumulations of 1 to 3 inches occurred with localized amounts up to 4 inches.||Two-day storm totals were 4 to 12 inches across much of Vermont. Some specific higher snowfall totals included; 12 inches in Killington (Rutland county), 11 inches in Westfield (Orleans county) and North Underhill (Chittenden county), 10 inches in Lincoln (Addison county), 9 inches in Jay (Orleans county) and Richmond (Chittenden county), 7 inches in Sutton (Caledonia county), South Burlington (Chittenden county), Eden (Lamoille county), Rutland (Rutland county), Northfield (Washington county) and Sheldon Springs (Franklin county) with 6 inches in Stowe (Lamoille county), Newport (Orleans county), Waterbury (Washington county) and Bethel (Windsor county).||Rapidly falling temperatures to the single digits above zero degrees along with falling and blowing snow during the morning commute of December 29th accounted for roads to flash freeze that resulted in numerous vehicle accidents, especially along Interstate 89 between Montpelier and St. Albans.

Overall, drought conditions continued to ease across most of South Texas during the month of December, as almost all of South Texas experienced above normal rainfall during the month. Strengthening El Nino conditions, in part, helped to produce the beneficial rainfall. ||Along and southwest of Interstate 37 many locations received more than 200% normal precipitation for the month of December.  The Corpus Christi International Airport received 3.96 of rainfall for the month, roughly 225% of normal rainfall for December.  Along and northeast of Interstate 37 most locations received between 100-200% of normal precipitation.  The Victoria Regional Airport received 3.74 of rainfall for the month, roughly 150% of normal for December.||By the end of the first week in December, Victoria, Goliad, Bee, Refugio and Calhoun counties were no longer considered to be in drought, and by the middle of the month Aransas county was no longer in drought. Severe drought conditions were observed across southern San Patricio, Nueces, Kleberg, and southeastern Webb counties.  Moderate drought conditions were observed across northern San Patricio, southern Live Oak, and southern McMullen counties. (per the U.S. Drought Monitor: http://www.drought.unl.edu/dm/monitor.html) ||Near to slightly above normal soil moisture was observed across all of South Texas by the end of December. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm front was stalled over the area with several rounds of heavy rainfall from October 8th through 10th.  Since the rain fell over the region for an extended period of time...it caused flash flooding and areal flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Four to five inches of rain fell in a short amount of time causing flash flooding.  Numerous roads were flooded including Highways 161 and 19 in and around the Montgomery City area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Freezing rain developed in some of the high valleys of the northern mountains during the evening. Ice accumulation was mainly confined to elevated surfaces. The freezing rain changed to rain soon after midnight.

Light freezing rain developed late on Christmas Eve and continued throughout the overnight before becoming heavier shortly before sunrise. Light ice accretion occurred, mainly on elevated surfaces during this time. Quite a few slick spots also developed, mainly on bridges and overpasses. Freezing rain continued through the morning hours along the eastern escarpment of the Blue Ridge, and became heavy at times by mid-morning. By the time the precipitation tapered off, ice accretion ranged from .25 to .5 inch across much of the area. The combination of ice and wind gusts up to 60 mph (with gusts up to 80 mph in the higher elevations) caused numerous trees and power lines to fall. The resultant widespread power outages exacerbated the problems for areas that had yet to recover from the December 18th snowstorm.

Light freezing rain developed during the early morning hours across the foothills and southern mountains of North Carolina, producing light ice accretion on elevated surfaces. A few slick spots developed on bridges and overpasses before temperatures warmed above freezing later in the morning. The ice accretion did cause some isolated damage to trees and power lines.

The strong pressure gradient associated with a deep area of low pressure that moved across the Great Lakes on December 9th, brought strong and gusty winds to eastern Kentucky. Widespread moderate to sometimes intense rain showers led to some flooding problems around the area as well. Numerous reports of downed trees and power lines were received, inspite of the fact that the winds came up just short of warning criteria. A combination of wet ground and steep terrain allowed the sub warning criteria winds to bring down trees and power lines at many locations around eastern Kentucky.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 52 mph wind gust blew shingles off a garage near Coon.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Law enforcement reported that the roads were impassible at the intersection of 42nd and Dixie due to high water.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong mid to upper level winds, associated with an approaching trough moving across the Rocky Mountains, mixed down to the higher terrain of the Guadalupe Mountains during the late afternoon hours.

Strong mid-level winds in the base of a trough mixed down to the higher terrain of the Guadalupe Mountains of Texas during the late afternoon peak heating hours of the day.

A large and intense area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and eventually up the east coast on December 18th and 19th. The initial precipitation began as a heavy wet snow on Friday afternoon December 18th. Accumulations around eastern Kentucky ranged between 1 and 4 inches. Ridgetop locations along the Virginia and west Virginia borders saw as much as 6 inches, with 13 inches reported on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County. This initial round of snow fell generally between 2 and 6 pm on the 18th. ||After several hours of nothing but rain, another round of widespread and intense snowfall began at around 10 pm. The Jackson weather office picked up 2.6 inches of snow between 10 pm and midnight on the 18th and there were 11 inches on the ground by early Saturday morning. By 7 am on Saturday December 19th 5 to 7 inches of snow blanketed the ground across much of southeast Kentucky. The highest snowfall totals for this event were 16 inches on Black Mountain, 13 inches on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County, and 11 inches at the Jackson weather office. Numerous trees and power lines were downed by the heavy wet snow with widespread and long lasting power outages reported across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Five and four tenths of an inch of snow had fallen since 10 pm Friday night near Talbert.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure tracking across the Pacific Northwest brought moisture into Montana from the south while cold air was moving into the state from Canada. The result was winter storm conditions, mainly confined to elevations above 5000 feet. Snow amounts in excess of 6 inches were reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Nine inches of snow fell at Helena 10S.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front passed through the Tidal Potomac and Chesapeake Bay on the 24th of October. Despite limited instability, strong winds aloft were able to mix down to the surface in heavier showers. The gusty showers occurred during the afternoon and evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust in excess of 30 knots was reported at Quantico.

CZ_NAME: EAST SLOPES OF THE SANGRE DE CRISTO MOUNTAINS
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level low pressure system tracked from the Four Corners area east-southeast across New Mexico during the weekend of the 14th and 15th.   As it exited the area, a strong back door cold front surged south across the eastern plains.  Heaviest snow amounts were generally above 8000 feet across north central and northwest New Mexico.  However, modest accumulations were also noted across the northeast behind the front.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Over a foot of snow fell at the highest elevations, including at the Angel Fire Ski Resort.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level system brought snow to much of New Mexico over a four day period.  Snow began over the northern mountains on the 28th and lingered through the morning hours of the 30th.  Amounts were typically light - on the order of 4 inches or less.   Then, as the system crossed northern old Mexico, significant snows developed over the south central mountains and adjacent plains to the east on the 30th through December 1st.  More than one foot of snow was reported across several of these locations.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Around 4 inches of snow was reported in and north of Tres Piedras.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Significant snow accumulations blanketed eastern Lincoln County.  The heaviest amounts were across southeast Lincoln County where up to 9 inches of snow was reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A long wave trough was over the eastern U.S. with a swath of moisture confined over central Florida and points southward. Subsidence and dry air was noted over Southeast Georgia and portions of Northeast Florida. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level disturbance brought a general two to four inch snowfall to the entire region. As the storm departed, lake effect snow developed off Lakes Erie and Ontario in the colder, westerly flow. The event was a short lived onemainly in a twelve- hour period from Monday (28th) morning through the pre-dawn hours of Tuesday.  The snows were very disruptive in the Buffalo area during the afternoon commute as whiteout conditions prevailed as 4 to 10 inches of snow falling in just a few hours.  Off Lake Erie, specific snowfall amounts included: Alden 11 inches; Glenwood 10 inches; West Seneca 9 inches; Orchard Park and Elma 8 inches; Dunkirk and Warsaw 7 inches; and Buffalo 3 to 9 inches (from north to south). Off Lake Ontario, specific snowfall amounts included: Copenhagen 14 inches; Beaver Falls 11 inches; Watertown and Lacona 10 inches; Black River 8 inches; and Scriba, Carthage and Palermo 7 inches.

A powerful low pressure system moved across Lower Michigan on the 9th.  Snow surged northward ahead of the low, with intense snowfall rates on the morning of the 9th.  By evening, snowfall totals of 6 to 12 inches were common across all of Northern Michigan.  Glennie, Rogers City, and Central Lake all had a foot of snow during the day, while Curtis picked up 16 inches.  The snow transitioned to lake effect snow that night, and lasted into the 11th in some of the snowbelts.  Localized 4 to 8 inch accumulations were common in a given 12 hour period.  There was a considerable amount of wind, and thus blowing and drifting snow, especially on the 9th.  Gaylord had its 2nd largest three-day snowfall since 1950, with 21.8 inches.  Almost all school districts were closed on the 9th, and some schools called off classes for three consecutive days.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An arctic airmass came through all of central and south central Texas before an upper level disturbance and strong jet stream moved overhead during the overnight hours on January 27 and the early morning of January 28.  Freezing rain was reported across much of the hill country and the interstate 35 corridor from New Braunfels up through Georgetown and Williamson County.  Many traffic accidents were reported with ice buildup from one tenth of an inch up to one quarter of an inch.  Heaviest ice was up through Williamson County where major impacts on roads and bridges were observed.  Elsewhere, bridges were iced and dangerous with ice accumulation on outside surfaces.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Spotters and law enforcement reported iced up bridges in the county causing traffic accidents.  The reports indicated between 1/8 and 1/4 inch of ice.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large and intense area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and eventually up the east coast on December 18th and 19th. The initial precipitation began as a heavy wet snow on Friday afternoon December 18th. Accumulations around eastern Kentucky ranged between 1 and 4 inches. Ridgetop locations along the Virginia and west Virginia borders saw as much as 6 inches, with 13 inches reported on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County. This initial round of snow fell generally between 2 and 6 pm on the 18th. ||After several hours of nothing but rain, another round of widespread and intense snowfall began at around 10 pm. The Jackson weather office picked up 2.6 inches of snow between 10 pm and midnight on the 18th and there were 11 inches on the ground by early Saturday morning. By 7 am on Saturday December 19th 5 to 7 inches of snow blanketed the ground across much of southeast Kentucky. The highest snowfall totals for this event were 16 inches on Black Mountain, 13 inches on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County, and 11 inches at the Jackson weather office. Numerous trees and power lines were downed by the heavy wet snow with widespread and long lasting power outages reported across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ten inches of snow was on the ground. The total snowfall from 10 pm Friday night through early Saturday morning was 11 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level trough across the Great Basin resulted in southwest flow aloft across West Texas and Southeast New Mexico. The combination of disturbances moving northeast across the area, strong daytime heating and good low level moisture ahead of the dryline resulted in severe weather across the area. The main threat during this episode was large hail and strong damaging winds.

An upper level trough across the Great Basin resulted in southwest flow aloft across West Texas and Southeast New Mexico. The combination of disturbances moving northeast across the area, strong daytime heating and good low level moisture ahead of the dryline resulted in severe weather across the area. The main threat during this episode was large hail and strong damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: There were numerous damage reports associated with this severe thunderstorm.  The damage path has been estimated according to these reports.  At 1945 MST, a trained spotter reported that a small camper was blown over onto a pickup truck near the intersection of Kincaid Rd and Highway 385.  Significant damage was done to the camper.  About five minutes later, 30' long by 20' wide metal sheds were destroyed about 5 miles south of Artesia and an Atoka, NM resident had his porch awning blown off his house.  Around 1955 MST, thunderstorm wind gusts snapped a power pole in half near the junction of 4 Dinkus Rd and Highway 285.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A mid level trough axis extended down the Appalachian spine and into the lower Mississippi River Valley which provided a west to southwest steering flow over the local area. Precipitable water amounts were near 2 inches with 500 mb temperatures ranging from -8 degrees C to -10 degrees C. Scattered severe storms developed during the afternoon and evening along the sea breeze fronts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were blown down and blocked a road near Interstate 95. The time of the event was based on radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Several hours of widespread moderate to heavy rain caused flooding and flash flooding across parts of western North Carolina, especially across the mountains. Rainfall amounts of 3 to 4 inches were common across the mountains, with 2 to 3 inch amounts over much of the western piedmont.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several roads were closed in the Brevard area, apparently due to flooding along creeks and streams that backed up due to a combination of heavy rain and flooding along the French Broad River. Closed roads included Green Rd to the southwest of Brevard, and Cascade Lake Rd  and Wilson Rd on the southeast side of town.

A strong upper level low pressure system tracked from the Four Corners area east-southeast across New Mexico during the weekend of the 14th and 15th.   As it exited the area, a strong back door cold front surged south across the eastern plains.  Heaviest snow amounts were generally above 8000 feet across north central and northwest New Mexico.  However, modest accumulations were also noted across the northeast behind the front.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts of 2 to 4 inches were common across the northwest highlands. The greatest snow totals were found just southwest of Cuba.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong center of low pressure tracked out of the plains states to the Great Lakes region. Ahead of this low in the Ohio Valley, southwest winds of 30 to 40 mph with gusts to 50 and 60 mph were common throughout the day. These strong winds peaked in the early afternoon with the passage of a cold front, and diminished later in the evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several large limbs were blown down onto power lines in the Richwood area.

Primary low pressure traveled from the Great Lakes across the Vermont/Canadian border on January 7th. Meanwhile, a coastal low slowly developed south of New England during the late afternoon of the 7th and eventually intensified as it moved into the Gulf of Maine during the night.||Snow overspread Vermont during the early morning hours of the 7th, but changed to a prolonged period of sleet and freezing rain as milder air aloft dominated due to the slow development of the coastal low. Precipitation changed back to light snow and snow showers before ending during the early morning hours of the 8th.||Total snowfall accumulations were 6 to 10 inches in northern Vermont with no ice accretion and 4 to 7 inches in central and southern Vermont with up to 1/4 an inch of ice accumulation. These wintry conditions led to numerous motor vehicle accidents as the storm occurred both during the morning and evening commutes.
A pacific storm brought strong winds to the coastline.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong winds were recorded at Garibaldi.  Strong winds were also reported at Cape Meares, with a peak wind gust of 58 kt, and at Clatsop Spit, with sustained winds up to 47 kt.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Lake effect snows developed off Lakes Erie and Ontario in a well-aligned, cold, unstable west to southwest flow.  Strong winds not along allowed the snow bands to extend well inland, but produced significantly reduced visibilities in blowing and drifting snow. The Lake Erie snows produced significant accumulations well into the Rochester metro area. Off Lake Erie, the event began in a southwest across northern Erie and southern Niagara counties, and then settled south into southern Erie and Wyoming counties by mid morning Thursday (10th) after dropping 2 to 4 inches. A short wave then approached and lifted the band northward for several hours during the day across the metro Buffalo area and across Genesee and Monroe counties, then settled slowly south and stalled out for many hours during the evening 10th with very intense snowfall rates across the Buffalo south towns and Wyoming county. This band also dropped down across the lakeshore areas of Chautauqua county with intense rates with major implications on the NYS Thruway. The NYS thruway was closed between Dunkirk and the PA line with hundreds of motorists stranded. The activity dropped further south and set up across the southern tier counties for much of Friday (11th) before drier air advected in during the evening. The activity weakened and ended by midnight. Specific snowfall amounts included: Springville 27 inches; Perrysburg 24 inches; Colden and Arcade 23 inches; Warsaw 22 inches; East Aurora and Batavia 17 inches; West Seneca 13 inches; and Buffalo and Rochester 3 to 9 inches (from north to south).|Off Lake Ontario, a similar scenario ensued, several hours later. The band initially set up in the Watertown area Thursday morning and slowly settled south later Thursday into early Friday (11th) with intense rates across southern Jefferson and central Lewis counties. The band then settled further into southern Lewis and Oswego counties later Friday as winds veered a bit further before weakening Saturday morning as the drier air advected in. Specific snowfall amounts included: Highmarket 40 inches; Port Leyden 37 inches; Lowville 30 inches; Redfield 28 inches; Copenhagen 21 inches; Carthage 15 inches; and Watertown 11 inches.

A long wave trough was over the eastern U.S. with a swath of moisture confined over central Florida and points southward. Subsidence and dry air was noted over Southeast Georgia and portions of Northeast Florida. A shortwave trough move across the area over an environment that consisted of 1.5 PWAT and modified CAPES of 4200 J/kg and a lifted index of -8.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A power line was blown down.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level storm moving across the Mississipi Valley brought a dry line and cold front into north Alabama during the afternoon and early evening hours.  Several classic supercell thunderstorms developed by early afternoon in northwest Alabama, sweeping across the remainder of north Alabama during mid to late afternoon hours.  Many of the storms produced very large hail, up to baseball and softball sized, producing significant damage, especially from Decatur through Madison and northwest Huntsville.   One of the supercells produced a long track tornado producing damage of up to EF-3 intensity which struck northeastern Marshall County, crossed Lake Guntersville, and moved into southern DeKalb County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorm winds knocked down trees in Meridianville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On Friday December 4th, and for the second year in a row, an early December snow storm struck southern portions of the ArkLaMiss. This occurred as a strong upper level disturbance helped to induce a low pressure system over the northwest Gulf of Mexico. As was the case with last year's December snow storm, very little if any snow fell in extreme Southeast Arkansas and North Central Mississippi.  Light snow fell along the Interstate 20 corridor with up to an inch falling from Jackson to Meridian in Central Mississippi.  The heaviest snow fell along the Highway 84 corridor, where amounts ranged from two to five inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Over an inch of snow fell across Jefferson County, with 2.5 inches reported in and around Fayette.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As warm air headed north ahead of low pressure moving into the Ohio Valley freezing rain quickly developed across much of eastern Ohio, western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia, and Garrett county Maryland. Untreated roadways quickly accumulated up to one tenth of an inch of ice making travel nearly impossible between 6 AM and 10 AM. Major interstates in and around Pittsburgh, including the Pennsylvania Turnpike were closed for more than 2 hours until roads could be treated and surface temperatures warmed above freezing. 911 centers across the area received thousands of call due to minor accidents. 2 more serious accidents resulted in 2 deaths, one in Beaver county, PA and one in Westmoreland county, PA.

Periods of light snow occurred from daybreak through the late afternoon hours on December 28th which resulted in 2 to 4 inches of snow accumulation with localized higher amounts.||An arctic cold front and upper atmospheric disturbance moved across Vermont during the morning commute of December 29th with snow showers and localized snow squalls. Some specific higher snowfall totals included; 12 inches in Killington (Rutland county), 11 inches in Westfield (Orleans county) and North Underhill (Chittenden county), 10 inches in Lincoln (Addison county), 9 inches in Jay (Orleans county) and Richmond (Chittenden county), 7 inches in Sutton (Caledonia county), South Burlington (Chittenden county), Eden (Lamoille county), Rutland (Rutland county), Northfield (Washington county) and Sheldon Springs (Franklin county) with 6 inches in Stowe (Lamoille county), Newport (Orleans county), Waterbury (Washington county) and Bethel (Windsor county).||Rapidly falling temperatures to the single digits above zero degrees along with falling and blowing snow during the morning commute of December 29th accounted for roads to flash freeze that resulted in numerous vehicle accidents, especially along Interstate 89 between Montpelier and St. Albans.

Overall, drought conditions continued to ease across most of South Texas during the month of December, as almost all of South Texas experienced above normal rainfall during the month. Strengthening El Nino conditions, in part, helped to produce the beneficial rainfall. ||Along and southwest of Interstate 37 many locations received more than 200% normal precipitation for the month of December.  The Corpus Christi International Airport received 3.96 of rainfall for the month, roughly 225% of normal rainfall for December.  Along and northeast of Interstate 37 most locations received between 100-200% of normal precipitation.  The Victoria Regional Airport received 3.74 of rainfall for the month, roughly 150% of normal for December.||By the end of the first week in December, Victoria, Goliad, Bee, Refugio and Calhoun counties were no longer considered to be in drought, and by the middle of the month Aransas county was no longer in drought.  By the end of December, only Jim Wells and Duval counties were considered to be in extreme drought.  Severe drought conditions were observed across southern San Patricio, Nueces, Kleberg, and southeastern Webb counties.  Moderate drought conditions were observed across northern San Patricio, southern Live Oak, and southern McMullen counties. (per the U.S. Drought Monitor: http://www.drought.unl.edu/dm/monitor.html) ||Near to slightly above normal soil moisture was observed across all of South Texas by the end of December.  Supplemental feeding of hay for livestock continued to decline.  Pecan harvesting was actually slowed due to the rain.  Most cattle remained in good condition.  Wheat and oats progressed from fair to good condition because of the light rains and cool temperatures.  Cool season grasses looked good and the fire |danger remained low during the month. ||Reservoir levels for the Corpus Christi and Victoria water supply either rose or remained nearly steady during the month.  Choke Canyon Reservoir was near 68% capacity and Lake Corpus Christi near 33% capacity by the end of the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An arctic airmass came through all of central and south central Texas before an upper level disturbance and strong jet stream moved overhead during the overnight hours on January 27 and the early morning of January 28.  Freezing rain was reported across much of the hill country and the interstate 35 corridor from New Braunfels up through Georgetown and Williamson County.  Many traffic accidents were reported with ice buildup from one tenth of an inch up to one quarter of an inch.  Heaviest ice was up through Williamson County where major impacts on roads and bridges were observed.  Elsewhere, bridges were iced and dangerous with ice accumulation on outside surfaces.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Highway 41 near the intersection of 83 was heavily iced over.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ice was reported on some roads and bridges.  Fatality accident occurred on Highway 281 on the Cibolo Creek bridge.  Most of the ice occurred in the western half of the county well west of Interstate 35.  Additional ice buildup was reported out by Canyon Lake and Spring Branch.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A mix of rain, sleet, and snow developed across the Georgia mountains around sunrise. Light accumulations of sleet occurred. Although the precipitation changed to mainly rain during the afternoon, temperatures that hovered right around freezing allowed for some light ice accretion to occur on elevated surfaces.

The strong pressure gradient associated with a deep area of low pressure that moved across the Great Lakes on December 9th, brought strong and gusty winds to eastern Kentucky. Widespread moderate to sometimes intense rain showers led to some flooding problems around the area as well. Numerous reports of downed trees and power lines were received, inspite of the fact that the winds came up just short of warning criteria. A combination of wet ground and steep terrain allowed the sub warning criteria winds to bring down trees and power lines at many locations around eastern Kentucky.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: One tree was blown down on Highway 1274 near Frenchburg.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak cold front moved through Southern New England, coupling with a warm, tropical airmass to produce showers and thunderstorms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees on the west side of Manchester, downtown Manchester, and on Middle Street were downed by thunderstorm winds.  A tree was downed onto a house in Manchester.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Severe weather developed on this day across portions of southwest Texas as abundant moisture resided over the region and a mid-level shortwave trough moved overhead.  This feature arrived during the peak heating hours of the day resulting in numerous storms developing.

A large and intense area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and eventually up the east coast on December 18th and 19th. The initial precipitation began as a heavy wet snow on Friday afternoon December 18th. Accumulations around eastern Kentucky ranged between 1 and 4 inches. Ridgetop locations along the Virginia and west Virginia borders saw as much as 6 inches, with 13 inches reported on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County. This initial round of snow fell generally between 2 and 6 pm on the 18th. ||After several hours of nothing but rain, another round of widespread and intense snowfall began at around 10 pm. The Jackson weather office picked up 2.6 inches of snow between 10 pm and midnight on the 18th and there were 11 inches on the ground by early Saturday morning. By 7 am on Saturday December 19th 5 to 7 inches of snow blanketed the ground across much of southeast Kentucky. The highest snowfall totals for this event were 16 inches on Black Mountain, 13 inches on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County, and 11 inches at the Jackson weather office. Numerous trees and power lines were downed by the heavy wet snow with widespread and long lasting power outages reported across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Five inches of snow had accumulated along Route 205 on the ridge along the Morgan and Wolfe county line.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An intense upper level low pressure area dropped southeast across the High Plains during the day, tightening the surface pressure gradient as it passed.  Northwest winds increased to 45-60 mph by mid-morning over much of northwest Kansas and southwest Nebraska.

Abnormally dry conditions persisted across much of southwestern Colorado, with extreme southwest portions of the state experiencing moderate drought conditions. The area of moderate drought expanded further north and eastward throughout the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Abnormally dry conditions persisted across the area through the month.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A mid level trough axis extended down the Appalachian spine and into the lower Mississippi River Valley which provided a west to southwest steering flow over the local area. Precipitable water amounts were near 2 inches with 500 mb temperatures ranging from -8 degrees C to -10 degrees C. Scattered severe storms developed during the afternoon and evening along the sea breeze fronts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts were estimated to be 55 to 60 mph in west Palm Coast.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An eastern U.S. trough axis edged eastward and increased southwesterly flow over the forecast area. Cool 500 mb temperatures ranged from -8 to -10 degrees Celcius. Scattered severe storms developed across the area in the afternoon and evening along the sea breezes and outflows.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Pea to penny size hail was reported with gusty winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A quasi-linear convective system (QLCS) composed of a few mini-supercell thunderstorms tracked eastward through southern middle Tennessee.  One such storm produced a brief tornado just south of Fayetteville.  The tornado uprooted numerous large trees and produced minor damage at a residence.  One person sustained a minor injury at their home.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown down near the Lynchburg Highway.

Ice accumulated from 1/4 to 1/2 inch across the region the night of December 8th into the morning of December 9th before the precipitation changed to all rain.

Ice accumulations ranged from one quarter to one half inch.

A severe thunderstorm associated with a long-lived cell exhibiting rotation on radar produced damage to several trees and small structures on the Forever Florida Eco Ranch near Kenansville in rural Osceola County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A NWS Storm Survey revealed several large oak trees toppled or split on the Forever Florida Eco Ranch on Highway 441 in rural Osceola County near Kenansville. Very minor wind damage occurred to a barn and a roof vent on the visitor center building. Several fences were damaged and two portable out buildings were blown onto their sides. Straight line winds were estimated at 50-60 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thick fog developed across a large part of east central Florida during the early morning hours and lasted until shortly after sunrise. The fog becomes especially dense near and west of the Interstate 4 corridor, resulting in a serious vehicle accident. The accident also produced significant structural damage to a bridge, resulting in the closure of multiple lanes of the Florida turnpike for several days.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Dense early morning fog contributed to a vehicle accident in Montverde within Lake County about 622 EST, according to Florida Highway Patrol officials. A man in a pickup truck drove through a stop sign and collided with a tractor-trailer. The tractor-trailer caught on fire, jackknifed, and struck a bridge below the Florida Turnpike, causing substantial structural damage to the bridge. Both drivers were injured. In addition, a fire truck crashed on its way to the accident scene, resulting in two additional injuries. Damage to the bridge caused both northbound lanes of the Florida Turnpike to be closed. One of the two northbound lanes was reopened two days later.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: During the afternoon and evening hours, shower and thunderstorm activity produced 2 to 4 inches of rainfall across Lincoln and Moore counties.  This flooding closed six roads in Lincoln county and many roads across Moore county.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flooding was reported at the intersection of state road 110 and Scott Orchard road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: During the afternoon and evening hours, shower and thunderstorm activity produced 2 to 4 inches of rainfall across Lincoln and Moore counties.  This flooding closed six roads in Lincoln county and many roads across Moore county.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Stoneboro road in Belleville was reported flooded.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Primary low pressure traveled from the Great Lakes across the New York/Canadian border on January 7th. Meanwhile, a coastal low slowly developed south of New England during the late afternoon of the 7th and eventually intensified as it moved into the Gulf of Maine during the night.||Snow overspread northern New York during the early morning hours of the 7th and continued until midnight on the 8th. Total snowfall accumulations were generally 4 to 6 inches with a brief period of sleet mixing with the snow at times.

A small but strong Pacific frontal system brought brief high winds to parts of the Oregon Coast.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong wind gusts were reported at Cape Foulweather.  Other wind reports from this storm include: 42 kt sustained with gusts to 52 kt in Florence; peak gusts to 55 kt on Hwy. 101 in Newport; sustained winds to 42 kt at the Newport Jetty; and peak gusts to 56 kt in Lincoln City.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A Pacific system brought heavy snow to the south Washington Cascades.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Swift Creek SNOTEL site measured 12 inches of new snow between 16:00 PST on December 14th and 04:00 PST on December 15th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong center of low pressure tracked out of the plains states to the Great Lakes region. Ahead of this low in the Ohio Valley, southwest winds of 30 to 40 mph with gusts to 50 and 60 mph were common throughout the day. These strong winds peaked in the early afternoon with the passage of a cold front, and diminished later in the evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A barn was blown down in Harlan Township. Several reports of trees and power poles and power lines were also reported across the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Deep low pressure strengthened as it moved from near Chicago to Quebec. As the system passed to the north, winds shifted to southwest and increased to storm force. The combination of the wind shift, rapid strengthening of the wind speed and the long fetch up the length of Lake Erie produced a seiche on the lake. Water levels rose over six feet in just a few hours.  The Lake Erie water level crested at Buffalo at 7.78 feet. Flooding was reported along the lake shore from Angola to Buffaloespecially along Route 5. The Buffalo Coast Guard was forced to seek safe harbor for its fleet, including using the Black Rock Lock to shelter vessels.

Lake effect snows developed off Lakes Erie and Ontario in a well-aligned, cold, unstable west to southwest flow.  Strong winds not along allowed the snow bands to extend well inland, but produced significantly reduced visibilities in blowing and drifting snow. The Lake Erie snows produced significant accumulations well into the Rochester metro area. Off Lake Erie, the event began in a southwest across northern Erie and southern Niagara counties, and then settled south into southern Erie and Wyoming counties by mid morning Thursday (10th) after dropping 2 to 4 inches. A short wave then approached and lifted the band northward for several hours during the day across the metro Buffalo area and across Genesee and Monroe counties, then settled slowly south and stalled out for many hours during the evening 10th with very intense snowfall rates across the Buffalo south towns and Wyoming county. This band also dropped down across the lakeshore areas of Chautauqua county with intense rates with major implications on the NYS Thruway. The NYS thruway was closed between Dunkirk and the PA line with hundreds of motorists stranded. The activity dropped further south and set up across the southern tier counties for much of Friday (11th) before drier air advected in during the evening. The activity weakened and ended by midnight. Specific snowfall amounts included: Springville 27 inches; Perrysburg 24 inches; Colden and Arcade 23 inches; Warsaw 22 inches; East Aurora and Batavia 17 inches; West Seneca 13 inches; and Buffalo and Rochester 3 to 9 inches (from north to south).|Off Lake Ontario, a similar scenario ensued, several hours later. The band initially set up in the Watertown area Thursday morning and slowly settled south later Thursday into early Friday (11th) with intense rates across southern Jefferson and central Lewis counties. The band then settled further into southern Lewis and Oswego counties later Friday as winds veered a bit further before weakening Saturday morning as the drier air advected in. Specific snowfall amounts included: Highmarket 40 inches; Port Leyden 37 inches; Lowville 30 inches; Redfield 28 inches; Copenhagen 21 inches; Carthage 15 inches; and Watertown 11 inches.

A major winter storm plowed through parts of Southwest Idaho and Southeast Oregon leaving many locations with heavy snow for the new year.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Cooperative observers at Garden City and Centerville reported 12 to 17 inches of snow while spotters from Pine, Lowman and north of Boise reported from 8 to 14 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A major winter storm plowed through parts of Southwest Idaho and Southeast Oregon leaving many locations with heavy snow for the new year.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A variety of sources including the Oregon Department of Transportation, spotters and cooperative observers reported 4 to 6 inches of snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The combination of subzero temperatures and a brisk north to northwest wind produced wind chill readings colder than 40 below zero.

A strong upper level storm moving across the Mississipi Valley brought a dry line and cold front into north Alabama during the afternoon and early evening hours.  Several classic supercell thunderstorms developed by early afternoon in northwest Alabama, sweeping across the remainder of north Alabama during mid to late afternoon hours.  Many of the storms produced very large hail, up to baseball and softball sized, producing significant damage, especially from Decatur through Madison and northwest Huntsville.   One of the supercells produced a long track tornado producing damage of up to EF-3 intensity which struck northeastern Marshall County, crossed Lake Guntersville, and moved into southern DeKalb County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Penny size hail fell in Anderson.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The winter lake effect season's second storm was a marginal one and restricted mainly to snows off Lake Ontario. It began following a cold front as a westerly flow set off a band of fairly heavy lake snows by midday Wednesday (16th) across portions of northern Oswego and southern Lewis counties. The flow veered to northwest Wednesday evening and snow bands shifted south across Oswego county. A good streamer off Georgian Bay reached western Lake Ontario and was enhanced as it crossed the lake right across the Rochester metro area which received several inches of snow during the evening. Another lake snow band developed over eastern Lake Ontario and dropped several inches as it crossed western Oswego county on a north-northwest flow.   This event was relatively minor with few affects. It did drop several inches on greater Rochester but it was during the mid and late evening with minimal traffic impact. Heavier snows were restricted to a small area in western Oswego county. Specific snowfall amounts included: Scriba 15 inches; Minetto 13 inches; Palermo 10 inches; and Martville 8 inches. The Rochester metro are received between four and seven inches.

An upper level disturbance brought a general two to four inch snowfall to the entire region. As the storm departed, lake effect snow developed off Lakes Erie and Ontario in the colder, westerly flow. The event was a short lived onemainly in a twelve- hour period from Monday (28th) morning through the pre-dawn hours of Tuesday.  The snows were very disruptive in the Buffalo area during the afternoon commute as whiteout conditions prevailed as 4 to 10 inches of snow falling in just a few hours.  Off Lake Erie, specific snowfall amounts included: Alden 11 inches; Glenwood 10 inches; West Seneca 9 inches; Orchard Park and Elma 8 inches; Dunkirk and Warsaw 7 inches; and Buffalo 3 to 9 inches (from north to south). Off Lake Ontario, specific snowfall amounts included: Copenhagen 14 inches; Beaver Falls 11 inches; Watertown and Lacona 10 inches; Black River 8 inches; and Scriba, Carthage and Palermo 7 inches.

Several hours of widespread moderate to heavy rain caused flooding and flash flooding across parts of western North Carolina, especially across the mountains. Rainfall amounts of 3 to 4 inches were common across the mountains, with 2 to 3 inch amounts over much of the western piedmont.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several streams flooded across Henderson County, and severe urban flooding developed in the Hendersonville area. Mud Creek flooded portions of highway 25 and highway 176. Roads that were closed in the county included Dana Rd, Fruitland Rd and Tracy Grove Rd in Hendersonville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Widely scattered thunderstorms produced some wind damage in the central and eastern midlands taking down some trees and powerlines.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: DOT reported a couple of trees down on Old Charleston Hwy (SC32-625) near the Lexington County Airport.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As warm air headed north ahead of low pressure moving into the Ohio Valley freezing rain quickly developed across much of eastern Ohio, western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia, and Garrett county Maryland. Untreated roadways quickly accumulated up to one tenth of an inch of ice making travel nearly impossible between 6 AM and 10 AM. Major interstates in and around Pittsburgh, including the Pennsylvania Turnpike were closed for more than 2 hours until roads could be treated and surface temperatures warmed above freezing. 911 centers across the area received thousands of call due to minor accidents. 2 more serious accidents resulted in 2 deaths, one in Beaver county, PA and one in Westmoreland county, PA.
A strong low pressure system tracked from the Gulf of Alaska to the Desert Southwest, bringing high winds to the Mojave Desert.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: This gust occurred 34 miles ENE of Beatty.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system tracked from the Gulf of Alaska to the Desert Southwest, bringing high winds to the Mojave Desert.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: This gust occurred 33 miles E of Beatty.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system tracked from the Gulf of Alaska to the Desert Southwest, bringing high winds to the Mojave Desert.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: This gust occurred at McCarran Airport (KLAS).

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A Pacific storm system and associated cold front brought locally heavy snow and high winds to the Mojave Desert and southern Great Basin.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The observer in Colorado City measured nine inches of snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Pacific moisture and post-frontal cold arctic air combibed to produce winter weather over a broad portion of North central Montana. Snow accumulations in excess of 8 inches were common. In addition to the snow, very cold wind chill readings were also reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ten inches of snow fell at Browning.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Pacific moisture and post-frontal cold arctic air combibed to produce winter weather over a broad portion of North central Montana. Snow accumulations in excess of 8 inches were common. In addition to the snow, very cold wind chill readings were also reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Six inches of snow fell at the Del Bonita Port-of-Entry.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Widespread rain changed to wet snow over much of southeast south Dakota. Snow accumulations of 1 to 3 inches were reported in an area north of Interstate 90 from Plankinton to De Smet to Brookings during the morning and early afternoon. Several vehicles slid off roads into roadside ditches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rain changed to wet snow, with the snow accumulating 1 to 3 inches. Several vehicles slid into roadside ditches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Rain changed to wet snow in part of southwest Minnesota. Snow accumulations of 1 to 3 inches were reported in Lincoln County Minnesota, including the Hendricks area, during the morning and early afternoon. A few vehicles slid off roads into roadside ditches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rain changed to wet snow, with the snow accumulating 1 to 3 inches. A few vehicles were reported to have slid into roadside ditches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The strong pressure gradient associated with a deep area of low pressure that moved across the Great Lakes on December 9th, brought strong and gusty winds to eastern Kentucky. Widespread moderate to sometimes intense rain showers led to some flooding problems around the area as well. Numerous reports of downed trees and power lines were received, inspite of the fact that the winds came up just short of warning criteria. A combination of wet ground and steep terrain allowed the sub warning criteria winds to bring down trees and power lines at many locations around eastern Kentucky.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were blown down acros Highway 92 East between mile markers 20 and 25 near Whitley City.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Severe weather developed on this day across portions of southwest Texas as abundant moisture resided over the region and a mid-level shortwave trough moved overhead.  This feature arrived during the peak heating hours of the day resulting in numerous storms developing.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Significant moisture just east of a dryline across the Big Bend region of Texas allowed for isolated convection to develop during the early evening hours.
Significant moisture just east of a dryline across the Big Bend region of Texas allowed for isolated convection to develop during the early evening hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several large rocks up to the size of basketballs were removed from SH 118 due to the flash flooding across the highway.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system tracked through Northern Lower Michigan, dragging a cold front through southeast Michigan. Wind gusts to 60 mph occurred south of M-59, which lead to downed tree branches along with a few trees and power lines. About 40,000 customers lost power, most concentrated in Wayne County.

The strong pressure gradient associated with a deep area of low pressure that moved across the Great Lakes on December 9th, brought strong and gusty winds to eastern Kentucky. Widespread moderate to sometimes intense rain showers led to some flooding problems around the area as well. Numerous reports of downed trees and power lines were received, inspite of the fact that the winds came up just short of warning criteria. A combination of wet ground and steep terrain allowed the sub warning criteria winds to bring down trees and power lines at many locations around eastern Kentucky.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous large trees were blown down throughout the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A surface trough extended from the Eastern Carolinas through the coastal plains of South Carolina and Georgia and across the Suwannee Valley and into the Panhandle.  A line of convection was enhanced by a passing upper level short wave trough, and storm produced impressive wind gusts across the area.

A powerful storm system brought heavy snow, ice and even blizzard conditions to a large portion of the central plains on December 7-9, 2009.  The greatest impact occurred across north central and northeast Kansas, southeast Nebraska, northwest and north central Missouri, and both southern and eastern Iowa, where strong winds gusting up to 45 mph produced blizzard conditions. The heaviest snowfall observed across extreme eastern Kansas was 8 inches in Atchison.||A review of the snow storm archives found this storm unusual in that it was the first snow storm that blizzard conditions were reported - wind speeds of 35 mph greater and wind-driven snow reducing visibilities to 1/4 mile or less sustained for three hours or more - to affect the forecast domain of the National Weather Service in Pleasant Hill, Missouri since the office opened in the 1992.  Though observed snowfall in the 10 to 14 inch range is uncommon, there have been several instances that snow amounts of these magnitudes have been observed in the past 15 years.  What is unusual is the combination of heavy snow and wind speeds exceeding 35 mph.  Since record keeping began, only five other instances have been recorded in which blizzard or near-blizzard conditions have impacted the forecast area for which the National Weather Service in Pleasant Hill has responsibility: February 5, 1924,  December 31, 1978-January 1, 1979,  December 1-2, 1985, January 18, 1996 and January 27, 1996.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Seven to eight inches of snow was observed across northern portions of the county.|Drifts of up to 4 feet were reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Several hours of widespread moderate to heavy rain caused flooding and flash flooding across parts of western North Carolina, especially across the mountains. EVENT_NARRATIVE: A stream gauge reported that Back Creek briefly went above flood stage in the southwest part of the county. Rocky River Rd was closed near Pharr Mill Rd due to flooding along the Rocky River.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Widespread heavy rain resulted in some flooding and more rapid onset flash flooding over parts of the Upstate.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Mount Lebanon Rd was closed due to flooding along the Middle Tyger River.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Although heavy rain began to taper off during the morning, flooding persisted along a few smaller streams into the late morning in response to 4 to 6 inches of storm total rainfall. In addition, minor flooding developed briefly in spots along the French Broad River.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold area of high pressure and clear skies allowed temperatures to drop into the mid to upper 20s, causing widespread freezing conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A cold area of high pressure and clear skies allowed temperatures to drop to around 30 degrees across Lincoln county.  The temperature was 32 degrees or lower for at least 3 hours.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold area of high pressure and clear skies allowed temperatures to drop into the mid to upper 20s, causing widespread freezing conditions.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A cold area of high pressure and clear skies allowed temperatures to fall into the upper 20s and lower 30s across Moore county. The temperature was 32 degrees or lower for at least 3 hours.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: After a wet month of September where 6 to 12 inches of rain fell across much of Dekalb county. Runoff from heavy rainfall across northern Alabama, which fell on the 12th, caused Big Will's Creek to backup and flood an area near the 201 mile marker of CR 39.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Runoff from heavy rainfall on the 12th caused Big Will's Creek to backup and flood CR 39 at mile marker 201. This road was closed for the entire day to traffic due to severity of flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: High astronomical tides and an onshore wind produced minor coastal flooding at Kure and Carolina Beaches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High tides produced flooding on Canal Street at Carolina Beach, and there was some coastal flooding beyond the turn to the landing at the Fort Fisher-Southport Ferry near Kure Beach.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Lightning struck a well outside a home in North Yarmouth and is believed to have followed underground wiring to the home where it ignited a fire in the basement.  The fire then completely destroyed the home.  Six people were at the home at the time and all got out safely, but one of the family's dogs perished in the blaze.

The remnants from Hurricane Ida which made landfall along the Florida panhandle combined with a powerful upper level storm system along the Carolina coast. The result was a powerful low pressure system which developed near Cape Fear and tracked to Cape Hatteras. Between 3 to 6 inches of rain fell across central North Carolina over a 3 day period. Gusty winds to 35 to 45 mph combined with saturated soil resulted in power outages and some property damage from falling trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts of 40 to 45 mph along with heavy rain resulted in numerous trees falling and knocking down power lines.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure moving from the central Plains toward the lower Great Lakes produced a wintry mix of precipitation on February 26. A combination of snow, sleet, freezing rain and rain occurred, along with isolated thunderstorms. Highest snowfall totals of 4 to 6 inches occurred through the Highway 10 corridor and points northward. Up to a half of an inch of sleet was reported across parts of the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Sleet accumulation totaled 0.50 inch.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A layer of snow and ice led to numerous accidents across southwest Wisconsin.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow and ice covered roads led to several accidents across Grant County.  One young man lost control of his truck and trailer snapping a power pole in half. About a half hour later a collision on Highway 18 led to several heads of cattle being killed in a trailer.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The wildfire started about 1105 CST off of County Road 5 and just north of Charlie Road in northwest Armstrong County or approximately two miles southeast of Washburn. The wildfire consumed an estimated three hundred acres. A total of three fire departments responded to the wildfire. No structural damage and no injuries were reported. The wildfire was determined to have been caused by welding equipment use and was contained by 1300 CST.

Lake effect snows developed off Lakes Erie and Ontario in a well-aligned, cold, unstable west to southwest flow.  Strong winds not along allowed the snow bands to extend well inland, but produced significantly reduced visibilities in blowing and drifting snow. The Lake Erie snows produced significant accumulations well into the Rochester metro area. Off Lake Erie, the event began in a southwest across northern Erie and southern Niagara counties, and then settled south into southern Erie and Wyoming counties by mid morning Thursday (10th) after dropping 2 to 4 inches. A short wave then approached and lifted the band northward for several hours during the day across the metro Buffalo area and across Genesee and Monroe counties, then settled slowly south and stalled out for many hours during the evening 10th with very intense snowfall rates across the Buffalo south towns and Wyoming county. This band also dropped down across the lakeshore areas of Chautauqua county with intense rates with major implications on the NYS Thruway. The NYS thruway was closed between Dunkirk and the PA line with hundreds of motorists stranded. The activity dropped further south and set up across the southern tier counties for much of Friday (11th) before drier air advected in during the evening. The activity weakened and ended by midnight. Specific snowfall amounts included: Springville 27 inches; Perrysburg 24 inches; Colden and Arcade 23 inches; Warsaw 22 inches; East Aurora and Batavia 17 inches; West Seneca 13 inches; and Buffalo and Rochester 3 to 9 inches (from north to south).|Off Lake Ontario, a similar scenario ensued, several hours later. The band initially set up in the Watertown area Thursday morning and slowly settled south later Thursday into early Friday (11th) with intense rates across southern Jefferson and central Lewis counties. The band then settled further into southern Lewis and Oswego counties later Friday as winds veered a bit further before weakening Saturday morning as the drier air advected in. Specific snowfall amounts included: Highmarket 40 inches; Port Leyden 37 inches; Lowville 30 inches; Redfield 28 inches; Copenhagen 21 inches; Carthage 15 inches; and Watertown 11 inches.

A powerful low pressure system moved across Lower Michigan on the 9th.  Snow surged northward ahead of the low, with intense snowfall rates on the morning of the 9th.  By evening, snowfall totals of 6 to 12 inches were common across all of Northern Michigan.  Glennie, Rogers City, and Central Lake all had a foot of snow during the day, while Curtis picked up 16 inches.  The snow transitioned to lake effect snow that night, and lasted into the 11th in some of the snowbelts.  Localized 4 to 8 inch accumulations were common in a given 12 hour period.  There was a considerable amount of wind, and thus blowing and drifting snow, especially on the 9th.  Gaylord had its 2nd largest three-day snowfall since 1950, with 21.8 inches.  Almost all school districts were closed on the 9th, and some schools called off classes for three consecutive days.

A strong upper level storm moving across the Mississipi Valley brought a dry line and cold front into north Alabama during the afternoon and early evening hours.  Several classic supercell thunderstorms developed by early afternoon in northwest Alabama, sweeping across the remainder of north Alabama during mid to late afternoon hours.  Many of the storms produced very large hail, up to baseball and softball sized, producing significant damage, especially from Decatur through Madison and northwest Huntsville.   One of the supercells produced a long track tornado producing damage of up to EF-3 intensity which struck northeastern Marshall County, crossed Lake Guntersville, and moved into southern DeKalb County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Golfball size hail was reported in the Cairo community.

An arctic airmass came through all of central and south central Texas before an upper level disturbance and strong jet stream moved overhead during the overnight hours on January 27 and the early morning of January 28.  Freezing rain was reported across much of the hill country and the interstate 35 corridor from New Braunfels up through Georgetown and Williamson County.  Many traffic accidents were reported with ice buildup from one tenth of an inch up to one quarter of an inch.  Heaviest ice was up through Williamson County where major impacts on roads and bridges were observed.  Elsewhere, bridges were iced and dangerous with ice accumulation on outside surfaces.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Austin Emergency Management reported icing across many roads in Austin.  Traffic accidents were reported across the city.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm front was stalled over the area with several rounds of heavy rainfall from October 8th through 10th.  Since the rain fell over the region for an extended period of time...it caused flash flooding and areal flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Very heavy rain fell over central Missouri in a short amount of time causing flash flooding.  In Boone county between 4 and 5 inches of rain fell.  Numerous roads were flooded, including Highways E, DD and Y.  Also, several water rescues had to be performed.  There were no injuries or deaths due to the flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level disturbance moved across southern New England bringing cold air in at the upper levels and producing showers and thunderstorms. The cold air at the upper levels created conditions conducive to the production of large hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A police officer was trying to open a garage bay door at the police station when lightning struck nearby, traveled through the ground and the building and shocked him.  He was treated and released from a local hospital.

A large and intense area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and eventually up the east coast on December 18th and 19th. The initial precipitation began as a heavy wet snow on Friday afternoon December 18th. Accumulations around eastern Kentucky ranged between 1 and 4 inches. Ridgetop locations along the Virginia and west Virginia borders saw as much as 6 inches, with 13 inches reported on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County. This initial round of snow fell generally between 2 and 6 pm on the 18th. ||After several hours of nothing but rain, another round of widespread and intense snowfall began at around 10 pm. The Jackson weather office picked up 2.6 inches of snow between 10 pm and midnight on the 18th and there were 11 inches on the ground by early Saturday morning. By 7 am on Saturday December 19th 5 to 7 inches of snow blanketed the ground across much of southeast Kentucky. The highest snowfall totals for this event were 16 inches on Black Mountain, 13 inches on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County, and 11 inches at the Jackson weather office. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level storm moving across the Mississipi Valley brought a dry line and cold front into north Alabama during the afternoon and early evening hours.  Several classic supercell thunderstorms developed by early afternoon in northwest Alabama, sweeping across the remainder of north Alabama during mid to late afternoon hours.  Many of the storms produced very large hail, up to baseball and softball sized, producing significant damage, especially from Decatur through Madison and northwest Huntsville.   One of the supercells produced a long track tornado producing damage of up to EF-3 intensity which struck northeastern Marshall County, crossed Lake Guntersville, and moved into southern DeKalb County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ham operator reported 1.5 inch diameter hail at a Gigaparts store in Huntsville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The remnants from Hurricane Ida which made landfall along the Florida panhandle combined with a powerful upper level storm system along the Carolina coast. The result was a powerful low pressure system which developed near Cape Fear and tracked to Cape Hatteras. Between 3 to 6 inches of rain fell across central North Carolina over a 3 day period. Gusty winds to 35 to 45 mph combined with saturated soil resulted in power outages and some property damage from falling trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts of 40 to 45 mph along with heavy rain resulted in numerous trees falling and knocking down power lines. A couple of trees fell on homes causing minor damage.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful low pressure system moved across Lower Michigan on the 9th.  Snow surged northward ahead of the low, with intense snowfall rates on the morning of the 9th.  By evening, snowfall totals of 6 to 12 inches were common across all of Northern Michigan.  Glennie, Rogers City, and Central Lake all had a foot of snow during the day, while Curtis picked up 16 inches.  The snow transitioned to lake effect snow that night, and lasted into the 11th in some of the snowbelts.  Localized 4 to 8 inch accumulations were common in a given 12 hour period.  There was a considerable amount of wind, and thus blowing and drifting snow, especially on the 9th.  Gaylord had its 2nd largest three-day snowfall since 1950, with 21.8 inches.  Almost all school districts were closed on the 9th, and some schools called off classes for three consecutive days.

As warm air headed north ahead of low pressure moving into the Ohio Valley freezing rain quickly developed across much of eastern Ohio, western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia, and Garrett county Maryland. Untreated roadways quickly accumulated up to one tenth of an inch of ice making travel nearly impossible between 6 AM and 10 AM. Major interstates in and around Pittsburgh, including the Pennsylvania Turnpike were closed for more than 2 hours until roads could be treated and surface temperatures warmed above freezing. 911 centers across the area received thousands of call due to minor accidents. 2 more serious accidents resulted in 2 deaths, one in Beaver county, PA and one in Westmoreland county, PA.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An arctic airmass came through all of central and south central Texas before an upper level disturbance and strong jet stream moved overhead during the overnight hours on January 27 and the early morning of January 28.  Freezing rain was reported across much of the hill country and the interstate 35 corridor from New Braunfels up through Georgetown and Williamson County.  Many traffic accidents were reported with ice buildup from one tenth of an inch up to one quarter of an inch.  Heaviest ice was up through Williamson County where major impacts on roads and bridges were observed.  Elsewhere, bridges were iced and dangerous with ice accumulation on outside surfaces.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Icing was reported on roads and overpasses in Marble Falls.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful storm system brought heavy snow, ice and even blizzard conditions to a large portion of the central plains on December 7-9, 2009.  The greatest impact occurred across north central and northeast Kansas, southeast Nebraska, northwest and north central Missouri, and both southern and eastern Iowa, where strong winds gusting up to 45 mph produced blizzard conditions. The heaviest snowfall observed across extreme eastern Kansas was 8 inches in Atchison.||A review of the snow storm archives found this storm unusual in that it was the first snow storm that blizzard conditions were reported - wind speeds of 35 mph greater and wind-driven snow reducing visibilities to 1/4 mile or less sustained for three hours or more - to affect the forecast domain of the National Weather Service in Pleasant Hill, Missouri since the office opened in the 1992.  Though observed snowfall in the 10 to 14 inch range is uncommon, there have been several instances that snow amounts of these magnitudes have been observed in the past 15 years.  What is unusual is the combination of heavy snow and wind speeds exceeding 35 mph.  Since record keeping began, only five other instances have been recorded in which blizzard or near-blizzard conditions have impacted the forecast area for which the National Weather Service in Pleasant Hill has responsibility: February 5, 1924,  December 31, 1978-January 1, 1979,  December 1-2, 1985, January 18, 1996 and January 27, 1996.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Six to eight inches of snow was reported across the county. Strong northwest winds reduced visibilities to less than a quarter of a mile at times.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A wave of damaging winds produced widespread and signficant damage to portions of north central and northeast Alabama during the late evening hours of the 12th into the early morning hours of the 13th.  These winds have been attributed to wake low / gravity wave combination on the northwest edges of a decaying mesoscale convective system (MCS) across central Alabama into northern and central Georgia.  Sustained wind speeds of 40 to 50 mph were common over a period of one to two hours, especially across Morgan, Cullman, Marshall and Jackson Counties.  Damages were most severe in the communities of Guntersville and Scottsboro where widespread damage was reported, and power was knocked out as numerous large trees were knoccked down.  Schools were closed in both communities for up to three days.  Many roads became impassible on the morning of the 13th due to the tree damage.  Trees were knocked down onto homes, vehicles and trailers, entrapping one individual in a camper in Scottsboro.  In Scottsboro, power was out for no less than three days in some cases.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High winds of 45 to 55 mph with higher gusts to around 65 mph downed numerous trees and powerlines across the county.  Particularly hard hit were the northern portions of the county. A gust to 47 mph was recorded at the Fort Payne Airport AWOS.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Light freezing rain developed late on Christmas Eve and continued throughout the overnight before becoming heavier shortly before sunrise. Light ice accretion occurred, mainly on elevated surfaces during this time. Quite a few slick spots also developed, mainly on bridges and overpasses. Freezing rain continued through the morning hours along the eastern escarpment of the Blue Ridge, and became heavy at times by mid-morning. By the time the precipitation tapered off, ice accretion ranged from .25 to .5 inch across much of the area. The combination of ice and wind gusts up to 60 mph (with gusts up to 80 mph in the higher elevations) caused numerous trees and power lines to fall. The resultant widespread power outages exacerbated the problems for areas that had yet to recover from the December 18th snowstorm.

A large and intense area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and eventually up the east coast on December 18th and 19th. The initial precipitation began as a heavy wet snow on Friday afternoon December 18th. Accumulations around eastern Kentucky ranged between 1 and 4 inches. Ridgetop locations along the Virginia and west Virginia borders saw as much as 6 inches, with 13 inches reported on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County. This initial round of snow fell generally between 2 and 6 pm on the 18th. ||After several hours of nothing but rain, another round of widespread and intense snowfall began at around 10 pm. The Jackson weather office picked up 2.6 inches of snow between 10 pm and midnight on the 18th and there were 11 inches on the ground by early Saturday morning. By 7 am on Saturday December 19th 5 to 7 inches of snow blanketed the ground across much of southeast Kentucky. The highest snowfall totals for this event were 16 inches on Black Mountain, 13 inches on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County, and 11 inches at the Jackson weather office. Numerous trees and power lines were downed by the heavy wet snow with widespread and long lasting power outages reported across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A snow depth of 4.5 inches was measured near Ned.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As warm air headed north ahead of low pressure moving into the Ohio Valley freezing rain quickly developed across much of eastern Ohio, western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia, and Garrett county Maryland. Untreated roadways quickly accumulated up to one tenth of an inch of ice making travel nearly impossible between 6 AM and 10 AM. Major interstates in and around Pittsburgh, including the Pennsylvania Turnpike were closed for more than 2 hours until roads could be treated and surface temperatures warmed above freezing. 911 centers across the area received thousands of call due to minor accidents. 2 more serious accidents resulted in 2 deaths, one in Beaver county, PA and one in Westmoreland county, PA.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper atmospheric area of low pressure and weak surface low moved across Vermont on the morning of December 28th. Periods of light snow occurred from daybreak through the late afternoon hours on December 28th which resulted in 2 to 4 inches of snow accumulation with localized higher amounts.||An arctic cold front and upper atmospheric disturbance moved across Vermont during the morning commute of December 29th with snow showers and localized snow squalls. Overall, drought conditions continued to ease across most of South Texas during the month of December, as almost all of South Texas experienced above normal rainfall during the month. Strengthening El Nino conditions, in part, helped to produce the beneficial rainfall. ||Along and southwest of Interstate 37 many locations received more than 200% normal precipitation for the month of December.  The Corpus Christi International Airport received 3.96 of rainfall for the month, roughly 225% of normal rainfall for December.  Along and northeast of Interstate 37 most locations received between 100-200% of normal precipitation.  The Victoria Regional Airport received 3.74 of rainfall for the month, roughly 150% of normal for December.||By the end of the first week in December, Victoria, Goliad, Bee, Refugio and Calhoun counties were no longer considered to be in drought, and by the middle of the month Aransas county was no longer in drought. Severe drought conditions were observed across southern San Patricio, Nueces, Kleberg, and southeastern Webb counties. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A moist and unstable atmosphere interacting with a potent cold front led to the formation of numerous strong to severe thunderstorms on Friday October 10th. Widespread wind damage was reported in several counties across eastern Kentucky. One tornado was also confirmed by an NWS assessment team in Estill County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Brief EF1 Tornado Touchdown confirmed by NWS Storm Survey Team about 5 miles south of Irvine on Murphys Ford Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Widespread rain changed to wet snow over much of southeast south Dakota. Snow accumulations of 1 to 3 inches were reported in an area north of Interstate 90 from Plankinton to De Smet to Brookings during the morning and early afternoon. Several vehicles slid off roads into roadside ditches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The strong pressure gradient associated with a deep area of low pressure that moved across the Great Lakes on December 9th, brought strong and gusty winds to eastern Kentucky. Widespread moderate to sometimes intense rain showers led to some flooding problems around the area as well. Numerous reports of downed trees and power lines were received, inspite of the fact that the winds came up just short of warning criteria. A combination of wet ground and steep terrain allowed the sub warning criteria winds to bring down trees and power lines at many locations around eastern Kentucky.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Portions of Highway 2012 or Balkan Road were flooded in Callaway.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large and intense area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and eventually up the east coast on December 18th and 19th. The initial precipitation began as a heavy wet snow on Friday afternoon December 18th. Accumulations around eastern Kentucky ranged between 1 and 4 inches. Ridgetop locations along the Virginia and west Virginia borders saw as much as 6 inches, with 13 inches reported on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County. This initial round of snow fell generally between 2 and 6 pm on the 18th. ||After several hours of nothing but rain, another round of widespread and intense snowfall began at around 10 pm. The Jackson weather office picked up 2.6 inches of snow between 10 pm and midnight on the 18th and there were 11 inches on the ground by early Saturday morning. By 7 am on Saturday December 19th 5 to 7 inches of snow blanketed the ground across much of southeast Kentucky. The highest snowfall totals for this event were 16 inches on Black Mountain, 13 inches on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County, and 11 inches at the Jackson weather office. Numerous trees and power lines were downed by the heavy wet snow with widespread and long lasting power outages reported across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: One to 2 inches of snow were on the ground in Monticello.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A dryline was located across the region on this day and this combined with weak mid to upper level disturbances moving over the area during the peak heating hours of the day, resulted in thunderstorm development.

An active severe weather pattern set up over portions of southeast New Mexico on this day, with an upper level trough crossing the Rocky Mountains.  The large scale lift associated with this trough combined with the moisture available resulted in thunderstorm development across portions of Lea County New Mexico.
Under an unstable air mass, a couple funnel clouds were spawned but never touched down.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A funnel cloud was reportedly spotted over the Riverbend Landfill near McMinneville, but stayed aloft and never touched down.  Small hail was reported to accompany this storm. NWS WSR-88D Doppler radar indicated many convective showers around the area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Under an unstable air mass, strong convective storms moved over the Portland metro area, dropping healthy amounts of rain.  Given the time of year, with plenty of newly fallen leaves in gutters and street drains, urban flooding was reported around the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An observer reported receiving 0.98 inches in two and a half hours.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Active southwest flow tracked storms inland from the Gulf of Mexico in the morning, then a passing short wave trough further de-stabilized the atmosphere in the afternoon to produce widespread strong to severe storms. Low level winds of 30-35 knots yielded strong wind gusts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A Gainesville television station reported 10 large trees were blown down across a field. The time of the event was based on radar.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The county road department reported numerous trees were blown down along Chester River Road. The time of the event was based on radar.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A passing upper level short wave trough moved across a moist and unstable airmass as a surface front sagged southward through the region. These ingredients produced scattered severe storms across the area in the afternoon and evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Penny to nickel size hail occurred west of Woodbine.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A passing upper level short wave trough moved across a moist and unstable airmass as a surface front sagged southward through the region. These ingredients produced scattered severe storms across the area in the afternoon and evening.
