EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A pre-frontal squall line extended across southwest Georgia into the Florida panhandle as a strong short wave trough traversed the local area in the evening. These features enhanced scattered storms that developed across the local area over an unstable airmass.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: On Friday December 4th, and for the second year in a row, an early December snow storm struck southern portions of the ArkLaMiss. This occurred as a strong upper level disturbance helped to induce a low pressure system over the northwest Gulf of Mexico. As was the case with last year's December snow storm, very little if any snow fell in extreme Southeast Arkansas and North Central Mississippi.  Light snow fell along the Interstate 20 corridor with up to an inch falling from Jackson to Meridian in Central Mississippi.  The heaviest snow fell along the Highway 84 corridor, where amounts ranged from two to five inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two inches of snow was reported in and around Columbia.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The remnants from Hurricane Ida which made landfall along the Florida panhandle combined with a powerful upper level storm system along the Carolina coast. The result was a powerful low pressure system which developed near Cape Fear and tracked to Cape Hatteras. Between 3 to 6 inches of rain fell across central North Carolina over a 3 day period. Gusty winds to 35 to 45 mph combined with saturated soil resulted in power outages and some property damage from falling trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts of 40 to 45 mph along with heavy rain resulted in numerous trees falling and knocking down power lines. A building in Mebane experienced roof damage.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful low pressure system moved across Lower Michigan on the 9th.  Snow surged northward ahead of the low, with intense snowfall rates on the morning of the 9th.  By evening, snowfall totals of 6 to 12 inches were common across all of Northern Michigan.  Glennie, Rogers City, and Central Lake all had a foot of snow during the day, while Curtis picked up 16 inches.  The snow transitioned to lake effect snow that night, and lasted into the 11th in some of the snowbelts.  Localized 4 to 8 inch accumulations were common in a given 12 hour period.  There was a considerable amount of wind, and thus blowing and drifting snow, especially on the 9th.  Gaylord had its 2nd largest three-day snowfall since 1950, with 21.8 inches.  Almost all school districts were closed on the 9th, and some schools called off classes for three consecutive days.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong center of low pressure tracked out of the plains states to the Great Lakes region. Ahead of this low in the Ohio Valley, southwest winds of 30 to 40 mph with gusts to 50 and 60 mph were common throughout the day. These strong winds peaked in the early afternoon with the passage of a cold front, and diminished later in the evening.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper trough moving over the islands from the northwest spawned heavy rain and flash flooding conditions.  A married couple from Hana, Maui, were apparently swept away by swollen stream waters on Thanksgiving night as they tried to make their way back to their home.  The couple's vehicle was found downstream the next day, but the individuals themselves were not located.  No serious property damage was reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Hanalei Bridge was closed because flood waters inundated the structure and Kuhio Highway in that part of north Kauai.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain caused the Honomaele Stream to rise above its normal level.  A married couple from Hana, Maui, apparently tried to cross the stream when it was flowing rapidly with the heavy rain waters.  Their vehicle was located the next day downstream, but the man and wife were not found.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Swells from powerful lows far northwest of the islands caused surf of 20 to 45 feet on north-facing shores of Niihau, Kauai, Oahu, Molokai, and Maui; 10 to 25 feet along the west-facing shores of Niihau, Kauai, Oahu, and Molokai; and 8 to 14 feet along the west-facing shores of the Big Island of Hawaii. The wrap-around effect was also in evidence as surf rose to 6 to 10 feet along the east-facing shores of Kauai, Oahu, and the Big Island. A professional surfer was injured at Waimea Beach Park on Oahu on December 7th because of the conditions. There were no reports of serious property damage, though the surf did deposit sand and other debris on coastal roads and property near the shore in several locales.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper atmospheric area of low pressure and weak surface low moved across Vermont on the morning of December 28th. Periods of light snow occurred from daybreak through the late afternoon hours on December 28th which resulted in 2 to 4 inches of snow accumulation with localized higher amounts.||An arctic cold front and upper atmospheric disturbance moved across Vermont during the morning commute of December 29th with snow showers and localized snow squalls. Widespread snowfall accumulations of 1 to 3 inches occurred with localized amounts up to 4 inches.||Two-day storm totals were 4 to 12 inches across much of Vermont. Some specific higher snowfall totals included; 12 inches in Killington (Rutland county), 11 inches in Westfield (Orleans county) and North Underhill (Chittenden county), 10 inches in Lincoln (Addison county), 9 inches in Jay (Orleans county) and Richmond (Chittenden county), 7 inches in Sutton (Caledonia county), South Burlington (Chittenden county), Eden (Lamoille county), Rutland (Rutland county), Northfield (Washington county) and Sheldon Springs (Franklin county) with 6 inches in Stowe (Lamoille county), Newport (Orleans county), Waterbury (Washington county) and Bethel (Windsor county).||Rapidly falling temperatures to the single digits above zero degrees along with falling and blowing snow during the morning commute of December 29th accounted for roads to flash freeze that resulted in numerous vehicle accidents, especially along Interstate 89 between Montpelier and St. Albans.

A low pressure center and the associated weather front over the Yukon Territory of Canada produced a local setup for heavy snow over the Upper Koyukuk Valley as moisture overran the cold air in place. The FAA Weather Observers at Bettles recorded 10.2 inches of snow from the 17th to the 18th, with 9 inches falling from the mid  afternoon of the 17th through the mid afternoon of the 18th.
An upper level storm system came across Texas and helped trigger a small cluster of strong to severe thunderstorms.

A powerful low pressure system moved across Lower Michigan on the 9th.  Snow surged northward ahead of the low, with intense snowfall rates on the morning of the 9th.  By evening, snowfall totals of 6 to 12 inches were common across all of Northern Michigan.  Glennie, Rogers City, and Central Lake all had a foot of snow during the day, while Curtis picked up 16 inches.  The snow transitioned to lake effect snow that night, and lasted into the 11th in some of the snowbelts.  Localized 4 to 8 inch accumulations were common in a given 12 hour period.  There was a considerable amount of wind, and thus blowing and drifting snow, especially on the 9th.  Gaylord had its 2nd largest three-day snowfall since 1950, with 21.8 inches.  Almost all school districts were closed on the 9th, and some schools called off classes for three consecutive days.

As warm air headed north ahead of low pressure moving into the Ohio Valley freezing rain quickly developed across much of eastern Ohio, western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia, and Garrett county Maryland. Untreated roadways quickly accumulated up to one tenth of an inch of ice making travel nearly impossible between 6 AM and 10 AM. Major interstates in and around Pittsburgh, including the Pennsylvania Turnpike were closed for more than 2 hours until roads could be treated and surface temperatures warmed above freezing. 911 centers across the area received thousands of call due to minor accidents. 2 more serious accidents resulted in 2 deaths, one in Beaver county, PA and one in Westmoreland county, PA.

A strong winter storm event struck the northwest quarter of Minnesota during the Christmas holiday, dropping heavy amounts of snow over an extended period of time. One to two feet of snow fell over portions of the northwest quarter of Minnesota, with the most snow falling over the central Red River Valley. The system was well forecast, which gave people ample time to adjust their Christmas plans. The actual track of the surface low was a bit of hybrid, tracking from Arkansas northward into Iowa, where it stayed nearly stationary for over a day. Conditions finally improved on the morning of the 26th, but it took a long time to dig out from all the snow.

A winter weather event produced 1 to 4 inches of snow across the upper Midlands and Pee Dee region of South Carolina.  There were few problems as surface temperatures were in the 40s and most of the snow melted when it came down on the highways, but remained on grassy surfaces for about a day.

The remnants from Hurricane Ida which made landfall along the Florida panhandle combined with a powerful upper level storm system along the Carolina coast. The result was a powerful low pressure system which developed near Cape Fear and tracked to Cape Hatteras. Between 3 to 6 inches of rain fell across central North Carolina over a 3 day period. Gusty winds to 35 to 45 mph combined with saturated soil resulted in power outages and some property damage from falling trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wendover and Battleground Avenues were closed due to flood waters from North Buffalo Creek.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered showers brought light amounts of rain on the 6th and 12th. The first real rain of the season occurred on the 28th and 29th. Several mountain locations received over an inch of rain, and higher elevations received six to twelve inches of snow. Rainfall amounts in the valley ranged anywhere from one-tenth of an inch to over one inch.||The State of Emergency for the State of California, as well as the Secretarial Disaster Declaration, remained in place. Some mandatory and voluntary water restrictions remained in place as well. Beginning November 1st, San Diego residents have been restricted to running sprinklers for only seven minutes a day before 10 am and after 4 pm. The Weekly U.S. Drought Monitor had all areas except for the deserts classified as D2 (severe drought), while the deserts remained at D1 (moderate drought).

A strong pressure gradient behind a cold front produced damaging winds across all of western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia, eastern Ohio, and Garrett county Maryland. Sustained winds were from 30 to 40 MPH with gusts over 60 MPH. The strongest reported wind gusts were 68 MPH in Franklin, PA and 66 MPH in Eighty Four, PA. Trees and power lines were reported down across the region, with more than 50,000 homes without power late afternoon on the 9th at the peak of the winds.

The couple's vehicle was found downstream the next day, but the individuals themselves were not located.  No serious property damage was reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A persistent trof focused an extended interval of heavy snow across northern and portions of eastern Maine. Snow began during the afternoon of the 22nd and continued into the evening of the 23rd. The heaviest snow fell across northern and northwestern portions of Aroostook county where storm total snow accumulations of 10 to 15 inches were common...with 16 to 20 inches across the Saint John Valley where isolated totals exceeded 20 inches. A sharp gradient of diminishing snow totals occurred south of the trof.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm total snow accumulations generally ranged from 14 to 20 inches...with locally up to 22 inches reported in the vicinity of Fort Kent.

A strong upper level storm moving across the Mississipi Valley brought a dry line and cold front into north Alabama during the afternoon and early evening hours.  Several classic supercell thunderstorms developed by early afternoon in northwest Alabama, sweeping across the remainder of north Alabama during mid to late afternoon hours.  Many of the storms produced very large hail, up to baseball and softball sized, producing significant damage, especially from Decatur through Madison and northwest Huntsville.   One of the supercells produced a long track tornado producing damage of up to EF-3 intensity which struck northeastern Marshall County, crossed Lake Guntersville, and moved into southern DeKalb County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail was reported by the Central Heights Volunteer Fire Department.

Primary low pressure traveled from the Great Lakes across the New York/Canadian border on January 7th. Meanwhile, a coastal low slowly developed south of New England during the late afternoon of the 7th and eventually intensified as it moved into the Gulf of Maine during the night. ||Snow overspread northern New York during the early morning hours of the 7th and continued until midnight on the 8th. Total snowfall accumulations were generally 6 to 9 inches with a brief period of sleet mixing with the snow at times.

A low pressure area moved from the Central Rockies across the Central High Plains, producing an area of heavy snow over portions of northwest Kansas and southwest Nebraska.  Snowfall up to 11 inches was reported.  Gusty north winds resulted in some blowing and drifting of snow.  Maximum snow totals in Nebraska included: Six inches in Hitchcock and Red Willow counties.  In Kansas, six inches fell in Rawlins, Sherman and Wallace counties, seven inches in Thomas and Logan counties, eight inches in Sheridan county, ten inches in Decatur, Norton and Gove counties and eleven inches in Graham county.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Five to six inches of snow was reported in Hitchcock County.

A large and intense area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and eventually up the east coast on December 18th and 19th. The initial precipitation began as a heavy wet snow on Friday afternoon December 18th. Accumulations around eastern Kentucky ranged between 1 and 4 inches. Ridgetop locations along the Virginia and west Virginia borders saw as much as 6 inches, with 13 inches reported on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County. This initial round of snow fell generally between 2 and 6 pm on the 18th. ||After several hours of nothing but rain, another round of widespread and intense snowfall began at around 10 pm. The Jackson weather office picked up 2.6 inches of snow between 10 pm and midnight on the 18th and there were 11 inches on the ground by early Saturday morning. By 7 am on Saturday December 19th 5 to 7 inches of snow blanketed the ground across much of southeast Kentucky. The highest snowfall totals for this event were 16 inches on Black Mountain, 13 inches on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County, and 11 inches at the Jackson weather office. Numerous trees and power lines were downed by the heavy wet snow with widespread and long lasting power outages reported across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter measured three quarters of an inch of snow 4 miles west of Paintsville.

This initial round of snow fell generally between 2 and 6 pm on the 18th. ||After several hours of nothing but rain, another round of widespread and intense snowfall began at around 10 pm. The Jackson weather office picked up 2.6 inches of snow between 10 pm and midnight on the 18th and there were 11 inches on the ground by early Saturday morning. The highest snowfall totals for this event were 16 inches on Black Mountain, 13 inches on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County, and 11 inches at the Jackson weather office. Numerous trees and power lines were downed by the heavy wet snow with widespread and long lasting power outages reported across the area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered showers brought light amounts of rain on the 6th and 12th. The first real rain of the season occurred on the 28th and 29th. Several mountain locations received over an inch of rain, and higher elevations received six to twelve inches of snow. Rainfall amounts in the valley ranged anywhere from one-tenth of an inch to over one inch.||The State of Emergency for the State of California, as well as the Secretarial Disaster Declaration, remained in place. Some mandatory and voluntary water restrictions remained in place as well. Beginning November 1st, San Diego residents have been restricted to running sprinklers for only seven minutes a day before 10 am and after 4 pm. The Weekly U.S. Drought Monitor had all areas except for the deserts classified as D2 (severe drought), while the deserts remained at D1 (moderate drought).

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong pressure gradient behind a cold front produced damaging winds across all of western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia, eastern Ohio, and Garrett county Maryland. Sustained winds were from 30 to 40 MPH with gusts over 60 MPH. The strongest reported wind gusts were 68 MPH in Franklin, PA and 66 MPH in Eighty Four, PA. Trees and power lines were reported down across the region, with more than 50,000 homes without power late afternoon on the 9th at the peak of the winds.
Fifteen inches of snow fell at the Black Bear SNOTEL site.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Fifteen inches of snow fell at the Black Bear SNOTEL site.   8 inches fell at White Elephant and 7 inches fell at Island Park.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: One foot of snow fell on the south side of Galena Summit.   Six to eight inches of snow fell in Hailey and Ketchum.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stationary front moved northward as a warm front during the daytime on December 8th, 2009. As the front moved north, an area of low pressure developed along the front. The low pressure brought several periods of heavy rain to West Tennessee. Flash flooding occurred as a result of the heavy rain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain produced flash flooding in and around Henderson. Numerous streets and roads were flooded as a result.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stationary front moved northward as a warm front during the daytime on December 8th, 2009. As the front moved north, an area of low pressure developed along the front. The low pressure brought several periods of heavy rain to North Mississippi. Flash flooding occurred as a result of the heavy rain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain produced flash flooding around Hernando. Pine Tree Loop was closed due to flood waters as a result.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large upper level low pressure system over the northern plains combined with an unusually cold air mass that spilled south out of Canada and brought an early season snow to eastern Nebraska and west central Iowa.  Even though temperatures with the snow fell into the 20s, warm ground temperatures caused most of it to melt on roads with most accumulations limited to grassy surfaces, vehicles, driveways and sidewalks.  Even then the snow on paved surfaces quickly melted that morning as temperatures climbed above freezing.  The heaviest snowfall set up along a 30 to 40 mile wide east-west band from Albion and Columbus east through the Omaha metro and into west central Iowa.  Heavier amounts included 7.6 inches in Bennington, 6 inches at Ft. Calhoun, 5.5 inches at the NWS office in Valley and in Schuyler, and 3.5 to 4 inches at Omaha Eppley, near Weston, at Fremont and in Underwood Iowa.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An early season storm dropped 2 to 4 inches of snow across much of the county, including around 4 inches in Underwood.  Due to warm ground temperatures, much of the snow melted on roads as it fell, but the roads did become slushy for a while toward the end of the event until melting completely late that morning or early in the afternoon.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong southeast winds occurring at high astronomical tide resulted in coastal flooding on Dauphin Island as well as other areas in southern Mobile County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Water covering Beinville Boulevard west of St. Stephens Street on the west end of Dauphin Island.  The Fort Gaines pier on the east end of Dauphin Island was under water.  Coden Belt Road in Coden, Warner Street in Bayou La Batre and Shell Belt Road were closed due to above normal tides.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong thunderstorms formed over Mobile Bay during the early morning hours of October 23rd, moving to the north at 20 knots.  Some of these storms produced wind gusts in excess of gale force.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Gale force wind gust measured by the USS Alabama battleship mesonet site.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The temperature fell to 29 degrees in Belle Mina.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A winter weather event produced 1 to 4 inches of snow across the upper Midlands and Pee Dee region of South Carolina.  There were few problems as surface temperatures were in the 40s and most of the snow melted when it came down on the highways, but remained on grassy surfaces for about a day.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Sheriff reported 3 to 4 inches of snow fell across Chesterfield county closing schools and some businesses.  A few secondary dirt roads were slushy and slippery at times.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure area moved from the Central Rockies across the Central High Plains, producing an area of heavy snow over portions of northwest Kansas and southwest Nebraska.  Snowfall up to 11 inches was reported.  Gusty north winds resulted in some blowing and drifting of snow.  Maximum snow totals in Nebraska included: Six inches in Hitchcock and Red Willow counties.  In Kansas, six inches fell in Rawlins, Sherman and Wallace counties, seven inches in Thomas and Logan counties, eight inches in Sheridan county, ten inches in Decatur, Norton and Gove counties and eleven inches in Graham county.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Six inches of snow was reported in Rawlins county.

The combination of very windy conditions and wet ground resulted in numerous fallen trees, which brought down power lines and damaged homes and cars.

A persistent trof focused an extended interval of heavy snow across northern and portions of eastern Maine. Snow began during the afternoon of the 22nd and continued into the evening of the 23rd. The heaviest snow fell across northern and northwestern portions of Aroostook county where storm total snow accumulations of 10 to 15 inches were common...with 16 to 20 inches across the Saint John Valley where isolated totals exceeded 20 inches. A sharp gradient of diminishing snow totals occurred south of the trof.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm total snow accumulations ranged from 10 to 15 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong winds developed across eastern portions of Washington county in the wake of intensifying low pressure exiting through the maritimes and a strong cold front which had crossed the region. Wind gusts of around 60 mph were reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts of up to around 60 mph were reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Swells from powerful lows far northwest of the islands caused surf of 20 to 45 feet on north-facing shores of Niihau, Kauai, Oahu, Molokai, and Maui; 10 to 25 feet along the west-facing shores of Niihau, Kauai, Oahu, and Molokai; and 8 to 14 feet along the west-facing shores of the Big Island of Hawaii. The wrap-around effect was also in evidence as surf rose to 6 to 10 feet along the east-facing shores of Kauai, Oahu, and the Big Island. A professional surfer was injured at Waimea Beach Park on Oahu on December 7th because of the conditions. There were no reports of serious property damage, though the surf did deposit sand and other debris on coastal roads and property near the shore in several locales.

A strong upper level storm moving across the Mississipi Valley brought a dry line and cold front into north Alabama during the afternoon and early evening hours.  Several classic supercell thunderstorms developed by early afternoon in northwest Alabama, sweeping across the remainder of north Alabama during mid to late afternoon hours.  Many of the storms produced very large hail, up to baseball and softball sized, producing significant damage, especially from Decatur through Madison and northwest Huntsville.   One of the supercells produced a long track tornado producing damage of up to EF-3 intensity which struck northeastern Marshall County, crossed Lake Guntersville, and moved into southern DeKalb County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Nickel size hail was reported along highway 101 in Lexington.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As a strong cold front approached the Florida Keys from the northwest, several waterspouts developed in association with showers and thunderstorms developing in advance of the front.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A large waterspout was observed about 5 miles south of Boca Chica Key by the Key West Naval Air Station weather observer.  The waterspout moved towards the east.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As a strong cold front approached the Florida Keys from the northwest, several waterspouts developed in association with showers and thunderstorms developing in advance of the front.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trained weather spotters reported a mature waterspout about one mile north of Marathon.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust of 42 knots (48 mph) was measured at the Sand Key Light C-MAN station.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A waterspout was observed in association with a cumulus cloud line north of Marathon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A waterspout was observed by a pilot about 5 nautical miles north of Marathon Airport.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A closed low pressure system tracking across the Great Basin brought heavy snow to portions of north central Idaho.  Lemhi County was most affected by this storm with seven to twelve inches of snow reported above 6000 feet.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Bannock Pass SNOTEL reported twelve inches of snow. Williams Creek SNOTEL reported ten inches of snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Fog and light freezing drizzle produced a thin layer of ice on area roads, including Interstate 70.  Accidents were reported in both Sherman and Thomas counties resulting in three fatalities and three injuries.  Dozens of other non-injury accidents were reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Light freezing drizzle and fog produced slick roads and numerous slide offs on Interstate 70.  One accident resulted in a fatality when the driver lost control of the vehicle and was ejected as it rolled over.  Property damage listed is only from the fatality accident.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: During the late afternoon, a funnel cloud formed over extreme southwest Melbourne, west of Interstate 95. A heavy shower was evident just south of the funnel and the rain area eventually built north to the location of the funnel.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A citizen observed a funnel cloud develop over extreme southeast Melbourne, south of Highway 192 and west of Interstate 95. Photographs of the funnel were taken.

CZ_NAME: VOLUSIA-BREVARD COUNTY LINE TO SEBASTIAN INLET 0-20NM
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An isolated strong storm moved from northern Brevard County, across Cape Canaveral and the adjacent intracoastal waters and into the near shore coastal waters. Wind gusts above 34 knots were recorded at Cape Canaveral.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust to 41 knots was recorded on Cape Canaveral at USAF tower 110.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A teenage boy drowned after being caught in a rip current along a portion of the Volusia County beach without life guards. Volusia County Beach Patrol reported the presence of very strong rip currents on this day.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 16 year old boy from New Smyrna Beach was caught in a rip current and drowned. |The boy entered the surf over a half mile away from the nearest life guard station. Volusia County Beach patrol reported that the boys mother stated that he could not swim well. Also, an elderly man was rescued from a rip current on another portion of the Volusia County beach and was taken to a local hospital and listed in stable condition.|Numerous other rip current rescues occurred along the County beaches during the day.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong center of low pressure tracked out of the plains states to the Great Lakes region. Ahead of this low in the Ohio Valley, southwest winds of 30 to 40 mph with gusts to 50 and 60 mph were common throughout the day. These strong winds peaked in the early afternoon with the passage of a cold front, and diminished later in the evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees were blown down across the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A severe thunderstorm drifted northeast from the Atlantic waters to central Marathon, producing strong downburst winds out of the northeast across the east end of Boot Key Harbor and areas around the Sombrero Country Club.  While originally reported as a landfalling waterspout and tornado, wind damage was consistent with that of strong straight-line winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Severe wind gusts out of the north northeast spread out of the east end of Boot Key Harbor.  Three small vessels, including one trimaran, were overturned.  A vessel docked at Dockside Marina measured a wind gust in excess of 100 mph at mast level.  An outdoor canopy secured by heavy tube steel framing was destroyed at a restaurant.  A tent was also carried into power lines, causing a power outage to most of the Sombrero Country Club and Sombrero Beach area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stationary front stretched from Hartford, Connecticut across northern Rhode Island to southeast Massachusetts combined with an upper level disturbance to produce showers and thunderstorms across southern New England. Plenty of moisture was in place across these areas, increasing the chance for heavy rain and flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The weatherflow station at Rose Island recorded a wind gust of 43 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A swell from a storm low far northwest of Hawaii generated surf of 15 to 25 feet along the north-facing shores of Niihau, Kauai, Oahu, Molokai, and Maui; and 8 to 15 feet along the west-facing shores of Niihau, Kauai, Oahu, and Molokai.  No serious property damage or injuries were reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The combination of increasing wind aloft and a tightening surface pressure gradient generated strong wind around and west of Clark, and along the U.S. Highway 287 corridor from near Muddy Gap to Beaver Rim. Peak wind gusts of 77 to 88 mph were recorded in and near the mouth of the Clark's Fork River Canyon. Nearby, estimated peak wind gusts of 60 mph occurred just west of Clark. Sustained southwest wind of 40 to 45 mph was recorded around 0700MST by an automated sensor on Beaver Rim. Strong wind gusts increased again during the late evening at Jeffrey City, where a peak gust to 59 mph was measured at 2105MST.

A low pressure area moved from the Central Rockies across the Central High Plains, producing an area of heavy snow over portions of northwest Kansas and southwest Nebraska.  Snowfall up to 11 inches was reported.  Gusty north winds resulted in some blowing and drifting of snow.  Maximum snow totals in Nebraska included: Six inches in Hitchcock and Red Willow counties.  In Kansas, six inches fell in Rawlins, Sherman and Wallace counties, seven inches in Thomas and Logan counties, eight inches in Sheridan county, ten inches in Decatur, Norton and Gove counties and eleven inches in Graham county.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Six to ten inches of snow was reported in Norton county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An intense low pressure system over Iowa resulted in a strong surface pressure gradient across the Tri-State region.  Northwest winds of 40 to 60 mph persisted for much of Christmas Day, creating areas of blowing snow and reduced visibility.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Peak wind gust of 61 mph occurred at 0008 CST on December 26th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large and intense area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and eventually up the east coast on December 18th and 19th. The initial precipitation began as a heavy wet snow on Friday afternoon December 18th. Accumulations around eastern Kentucky ranged between 1 and 4 inches. Ridgetop locations along the Virginia and west Virginia borders saw as much as 6 inches, with 13 inches reported on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County. This initial round of snow fell generally between 2 and 6 pm on the 18th. ||After several hours of nothing but rain, another round of widespread and intense snowfall began at around 10 pm. The Jackson weather office picked up 2.6 inches of snow between 10 pm and midnight on the 18th and there were 11 inches on the ground by early Saturday morning. By 7 am on Saturday December 19th 5 to 7 inches of snow blanketed the ground across much of southeast Kentucky. The highest snowfall totals for this event were 16 inches on Black Mountain, 13 inches on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County, and 11 inches at the Jackson weather office. Numerous trees and power lines were downed by the heavy wet snow with widespread and long lasting power outages reported across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Perry County fire dept reported trees down in the Vicco area. Power outages were reported in the Woodland section of Hazard.

After a period of heavy rain that left the ground saturated, strong winds developed behind a cold front during the late morning hours over the North Carolina mountains. The combination of very windy conditions and wet ground resulted in numerous fallen trees, which brought down power lines and damaged homes and cars.

A closed low pressure system tracking across the Great Basin brought heavy snow to portions of southwest Montana. Granite and Deerlodge Counties were most affected with snow amounts of six to seventeen inches reported in elevations above 6000 feet.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Barker Lakes SNOTEL reported seventeen inches of snow.  Peterson Meadows SNOTEL reported eleven inches of snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong arctic weather system brought heavy snow to portions of western Montana.  The Potomac/Seeley Lake region was particularly hard hit with six to eleven inches of new snow accumulations.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Stuart Mountain SNOTEL reported ten inches of snow.  North Fork Jocko SNOTEL reported eleven inches of snow.  Storm spotters in the lower elevations reported between three to eight inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper atmospheric area of low pressure and weak surface low moved across Vermont on the morning of December 28th. Periods of light snow occurred from daybreak through the late afternoon hours on December 28th which resulted in 2 to 4 inches of snow accumulation with localized higher amounts.||An arctic cold front and upper atmospheric disturbance moved across Vermont during the morning commute of December 29th with snow showers and localized snow squalls. Widespread snowfall accumulations of 1 to 3 inches occurred with localized amounts up to 4 inches.||Two-day storm totals were 4 to 12 inches across much of Vermont. Some specific higher snowfall totals included; 12 inches in Killington (Rutland county), 11 inches in Westfield (Orleans county) and North Underhill (Chittenden county), 10 inches in Lincoln (Addison county), 9 inches in Jay (Orleans county) and Richmond (Chittenden county), 7 inches in Sutton (Caledonia county), South Burlington (Chittenden county), Eden (Lamoille county), Rutland (Rutland county), Northfield (Washington county) and Sheldon Springs (Franklin county) with 6 inches in Stowe (Lamoille county), Newport (Orleans county), Waterbury (Washington county) and Bethel (Windsor county).||Rapidly falling temperatures to the single digits above zero degrees along with falling and blowing snow during the morning commute of December 29th accounted for roads to flash freeze that resulted in numerous vehicle accidents, especially along Interstate 89 between Montpelier and St. Albans.

A powerful low pressure system moved across Lower Michigan on the 9th.  Snow surged northward ahead of the low, with intense snowfall rates on the morning of the 9th.  By evening, snowfall totals of 6 to 12 inches were common across all of Northern Michigan.  Glennie, Rogers City, and Central Lake all had a foot of snow during the day, while Curtis picked up 16 inches.  The snow transitioned to lake effect snow that night, and lasted into the 11th in some of the snowbelts.  Localized 4 to 8 inch accumulations were common in a given 12 hour period.  There was a considerable amount of wind, and thus blowing and drifting snow, especially on the 9th.  Gaylord had its 2nd largest three-day snowfall since 1950, with 21.8 inches.  Almost all school districts were closed on the 9th, and some schools called off classes for three consecutive days.

Low pressure brought a period of moderate to heavy rain to the mountains of North Carolina Christmas eve and Christmas day. Around 3 inches of rain fell across much of the southern mountains of North Carolina which resulted in a few areas of flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: McMullen Creek exceeded its established flood stage and flooded portions of Addison Dr and Willhaven Rd.

Accumulations ranged from trace amounts over the lower elevations of the foothills, to localized 2-3 inch amounts over the mountains.  A few slick spots developed on mountain roads, resulting in quite a few accidents.

The remnants from Hurricane Ida which made landfall along the Florida panhandle combined with a powerful upper level storm system along the Carolina coast. The result was a powerful low pressure system which developed near Cape Fear and tracked to Cape Hatteras. Between 3 to 6 inches of rain fell across central North Carolina over a 3 day period. Gusty winds to 35 to 45 mph combined with saturated soil resulted in power outages and some property damage from falling trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hinson Street was closed due to high water.

A strong winter storm event struck the northwest quarter of Minnesota during the Christmas holiday, dropping heavy amounts of snow over an extended period of time. One to two feet of snow fell over portions of the northwest quarter of Minnesota, with the most snow falling over the central Red River Valley. The system was well forecast, which gave people ample time to adjust their Christmas plans. The actual track of the surface low was a bit of hybrid, tracking from Arkansas northward into Iowa, where it stayed nearly stationary for over a day. Conditions finally improved on the morning of the 26th, but it took a long time to dig out from all the snow.

An upper atmospheric area of low pressure and weak surface low moved across Vermont on the morning of December 28th. Periods of light snow occurred from daybreak through the late afternoon hours on December 28th which resulted in 2 to 4 inches of snow accumulation with localized higher amounts.||An arctic cold front and upper atmospheric disturbance moved across Vermont during the morning commute of December 29th with snow showers and localized snow squalls. Some specific higher snowfall totals included; 12 inches in Killington (Rutland county), 11 inches in Westfield (Orleans county) and North Underhill (Chittenden county), 10 inches in Lincoln (Addison county), 9 inches in Jay (Orleans county) and Richmond (Chittenden county), 7 inches in Sutton (Caledonia county), South Burlington (Chittenden county), Eden (Lamoille county), Rutland (Rutland county), Northfield (Washington county) and Sheldon Springs (Franklin county) with 6 inches in Stowe (Lamoille county), Newport (Orleans county), Waterbury (Washington county) and Bethel (Windsor county).||Rapidly falling temperatures to the single digits above zero degrees along with falling and blowing snow during the morning commute of December 29th accounted for roads to flash freeze that resulted in numerous vehicle accidents, especially along Interstate 89 between Montpelier and St. Albans.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A tight pressure gradient between high pressure off the southeast United States coast and Hurricane Ida over the northwestern Caribbean Sea and the southeast Gulf of Mexico produced strong winds over south Florida.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Sustained easterly winds of 25-30 mph persisted for over 2 days, with frequent gusts of 35-40 mph. Pompano Beach recorded a peak wind gust of 47 mph at 8 AM on November 9th. Other peak gusts include Virginia Key at 45 mph, Opa-Locka Airport at 40 mph and Palm Beach International Airport and Miami International Airport at 39 mph.||These winds produced power outages to approximately 3,000 customers across Miami-Dade, Broward and Palm Beach counties. Some trees were reported to have toppled and/or uprooted, with the only confirmed report being a snapped pine tree which fell onto a car in Dania Beach, producing damage. Moderate beach erosion was also reported along some southeast Florida beaches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As warm air headed north ahead of low pressure moving into the Ohio Valley freezing rain quickly developed across much of eastern Ohio, western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia, and Garrett county Maryland. Untreated roadways quickly accumulated up to one tenth of an inch of ice making travel nearly impossible between 6 AM and 10 AM. Major interstates in and around Pittsburgh, including the Pennsylvania Turnpike were closed for more than 2 hours until roads could be treated and surface temperatures warmed above freezing. 911 centers across the area received thousands of call due to minor accidents. 2 more serious accidents resulted in 2 deaths, one in Beaver county, PA and one in Westmoreland county, PA.

A strong center of low pressure tracked out of the plains states to the Great Lakes region. Ahead of this low in the Ohio Valley, southwest winds of 30 to 40 mph with gusts to 50 and 60 mph were common throughout the day. These strong winds peaked in the early afternoon with the passage of a cold front, and diminished later in the evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees were blown down in the Indian Hill area, closing a few streets. Utilities were damaged due to fallen trees on power lines. Another spotter estimated a 52 mph gust in Maderia at 12:05.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level storm moving across the Mississipi Valley brought a dry line and cold front into north Alabama during the afternoon and early evening hours.  Several classic supercell thunderstorms developed by early afternoon in northwest Alabama, sweeping across the remainder of north Alabama during mid to late afternoon hours.  Many of the storms produced very large hail, up to baseball and softball sized, producing significant damage, especially from Decatur through Madison and northwest Huntsville.   One of the supercells produced a long track tornado producing damage of up to EF-3 intensity which struck northeastern Marshall County, crossed Lake Guntersville, and moved into southern DeKalb County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Nickel size hail was reported along US Highway 43 south of Russellville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold Canadian system converged with a warm Pacific weather system to produced accumulating snow accross western Montana.  Snow amounts ranged from eight to eighteen inches of new snow.  In addition, as the strong cold front pushed through northwest Montana, northeast winds caused blowing and drifting snow and low visibilities.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A CoCoRaHS observer in Greenough reported 8 inches of snow.  An NWS employee reported 12 inches in Clinton.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Widespread heavy rainfall events on October 27th and again on the 29th and 30th sent the Green River above flood stage. Minor flooding began on the first of November and lasted a few days.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A storm system developed in the southern Plains around mid-month, then slowly lifted north through the Mississippi Valley toward the Great Lakes. The surface front meandered across the region from the 11th to the 18th. Heavy rainfall upriver caused the Mississippi River to exceed flood stage at Cape Girardeau.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Minor flooding of the Mississippi River occurred. At the Cape Girardeau river gage, the river crested at 34.21 feet on the 22nd. Flood stage is 32 feet. Some low-lying fields and bottomland river access roads were flooded.

A large and intense area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and eventually up the east coast on December 18th and 19th. The initial precipitation began as a heavy wet snow on Friday afternoon December 18th. Accumulations around eastern Kentucky ranged between 1 and 4 inches. Ridgetop locations along the Virginia and west Virginia borders saw as much as 6 inches, with 13 inches reported on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County. This initial round of snow fell generally between 2 and 6 pm on the 18th. ||After several hours of nothing but rain, another round of widespread and intense snowfall began at around 10 pm. The Jackson weather office picked up 2.6 inches of snow between 10 pm and midnight on the 18th and there were 11 inches on the ground by early Saturday morning. By 7 am on Saturday December 19th 5 to 7 inches of snow blanketed the ground across much of southeast Kentucky. The highest snowfall totals for this event were 16 inches on Black Mountain, 13 inches on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County, and 11 inches at the Jackson weather office. Numerous trees and power lines were downed by the heavy wet snow with widespread and long lasting power outages reported across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An inch of snow fell in Manchester.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow moving front stretched south of Long Island moved northward, combining with an upper level disturbance to produce showers and thunderstorms across southern New England. Plenty of moisture was in place across these areas, increasing the chance for heavy rain and flooding.

A persistent trof focused an extended interval of heavy snow across northern and portions of eastern Maine. Snow began during the afternoon of the 22nd and continued into the evening of the 23rd. The heaviest snow fell across northern and northwestern portions of Aroostook county where storm total snow accumulations of 10 to 15 inches were common...with 16 to 20 inches across the Saint John Valley where isolated totals exceeded 20 inches. A sharp gradient of diminishing snow totals occurred south of the trof.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm total snow accumulations generally ranged from 9 to 13 inches...with localized totals of up to 17 inches reported at Mount Chase.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong winds developed across eastern portions of Washington county in the wake of intensifying low pressure exiting through the maritimes and a strong cold front which had crossed the region. Wind gusts of around 60 mph were reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts of up to around 60 mph were reported.

A strong upper level storm moving across the Mississipi Valley brought a dry line and cold front into north Alabama during the afternoon and early evening hours.  Several classic supercell thunderstorms developed by early afternoon in northwest Alabama, sweeping across the remainder of north Alabama during mid to late afternoon hours.  Many of the storms produced very large hail, up to baseball and softball sized, producing significant damage, especially from Decatur through Madison and northwest Huntsville.   One of the supercells produced a long track tornado producing damage of up to EF-3 intensity which struck northeastern Marshall County, crossed Lake Guntersville, and moved into southern DeKalb County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail was reported in the Muscle Shoals community.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Winter storm conditions were reported. At Mountain High, 8 to 12 inches of snowfall was reported while Wrightwood reported 8 inches of snowfall. In addition to the snowfall, south winds gusting to 50 MPH were reported.

CZ_NAME: PT PIEDRAS BLANCAS TO PT ARGUELLO WWD 60NM
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong thunderstorm produced very strong winds across the coastal waters north of Point Arguello. The Point Arguello buoy reported wind gusts of 37 knots associated with the passage of a thunderstorm.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Point Arguello buoy reported a wind gust of 37 knots associated with the passage of a thunderstorm.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful winter storm brought heavy rain, flash flooding, gusty winds and severe thunderstorms to Central and Southern California. Rainfall amounts for this storm ranged from 1 to 3 inches over coastal areas to between 3 and 6 inches in the mountain and foothill areas. With such heavy rainfall, there were several reports of flash flooding along with mud and debris flows near the Station Fire burn area. In San Luis Obispo county, a severe thunderstorm producing very strong winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Near the Station Fire burn area, intense showers and thunderstorms producing flash flooding as well as mud and debris flows along the Angeles Crest Highway. Near mile marker 23, over 90 vehicles were stuck in mud and debris. First hand reports from other areas around the Station Fire reported water flowing in canyons like raging rivers.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong northwesterly wind event buffeted sections of Los Angeles and Ventura counties with strong winds. The strongest winds were reported in the mountains of Ventura and Los Angeles counties with wind gusts to 78 MPH recorded. However the strong and gusty winds did filter down into the Santa Clarita and San Fernando Valleys as well as the Antelope Valley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained weather spotter in Palmdale reported sustained northwest winds of 45 MPH.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front brought gusty winds to eastern California followed by a period of lake effect snow which brought several inches of snowfall to the south and southeast of Lake Tahoe.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A spotter just southwest of South Lake Tahoe reported 5 inches of snowfall. Four to five inches of snowfall was common to the south and east of Lake Tahoe (in the lake effect snow band), with up to 2 inches elsewhere around Lake Tahoe.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong storm in the Gulf of Alaska produced high wind around the northwest quadrant of the storm. Wind gust peaked at 98 mph in Dutch Harbor and were around 70 mph through the channeled terrain of the Alaska Peninsula.

A strong north Pacific storm moved across the Aleutians on the 18th and 19th producing strong wind in Shemya. The peak wind was 74 mph at Shemya.
A front moved across the Pribilof Islands on the 19th producing strong wind and snow that resulted in blizzard conditions.

The remnants from Hurricane Ida which made landfall along the Florida panhandle combined with a powerful upper level storm system along the Carolina coast. The result was a powerful low pressure system which developed near Cape Fear and tracked to Cape Hatteras. Between 3 to 6 inches of rain fell across central North Carolina over a 3 day period. Gusty winds to 35 to 45 mph combined with saturated soil resulted in power outages and some property damage from falling trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts of 40 to 45 mph along with heavy rain resulted in numerous trees falling and knocking down power lines. Several trees fell on three parked tractor trailers near Roanoke Rapids. One of the trucks was destroyed and the driver was trapped. There were no injuries.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large and intense area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and eventually up the east coast on December 18th and 19th. The initial precipitation began as a heavy wet snow on Friday afternoon December 18th. Accumulations around eastern Kentucky ranged between 1 and 4 inches. Ridgetop locations along the Virginia and west Virginia borders saw as much as 6 inches, with 13 inches reported on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County. This initial round of snow fell generally between 2 and 6 pm on the 18th. ||After several hours of nothing but rain, another round of widespread and intense snowfall began at around 10 pm. The Jackson weather office picked up 2.6 inches of snow between 10 pm and midnight on the 18th and there were 11 inches on the ground by early Saturday morning. By 7 am on Saturday December 19th 5 to 7 inches of snow blanketed the ground across much of southeast Kentucky. The highest snowfall totals for this event were 16 inches on Black Mountain, 13 inches on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County, and 11 inches at the Jackson weather office. Numerous trees and power lines were downed by the heavy wet snow with widespread and long lasting power outages reported across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An observer measure 6 inches of snow at 9 am in Alcorn.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low level pressure gradient over the Rocky Mountains was expected to produce strong winds over portions of southeast Wyoming. The strong winds were expected to produce low visibilities in areas of blowing snow due to recent snowfall in addition to dangerous wind chill values.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Winds varied through much of December 9th, with periods of high winds followed by periods of decreased winds. Three distinct periods of high winds were measured by Wyoming Department of Transportation sensor at Vedauwoo (KVDW). The sensor measured sustained winds in excess of 40 MPH on from 422 AM through 1227 PM, with a peak gust of 69 MPH around 1015 AM LST. Additionally, winds in excess of 40 MPH were measured from 327 PM through 522 PM and 9/1002 PM through 10/0202 AM LST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Arctic air plunged southeast across eastern Nebraska and southwest Iowa on January 14th and 15th.  Temperatures fell into the single digits above and below zero during the morning hours of 1/14, recovered a little in the afternoon and then fell to 5 below to 20 below, or a bit colder, by the morning of the 15th.  Northwest winds of 20 to 30 mph with higher gusts were observed into the afternoon of the 14th before subsiding in the afternoon and evening.  This produced wind chill values of 20 below to 30 below zero over much of the region.  By around midnight on the 15th most reporting sites observed winds dropped below 10 mph and remained that way through the morning of the 15th.  However, several locations, mainly south through southeast of Omaha, recorded wind speeds of 10 to 15 mph and wind chill values colder than 20 below through around 5am CST on the 15th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: As temperatures fell below zero across the county, northwest winds of 20 to 30 mph in the morning and early afternoon and 10 to 20 mph from late afternoon into late evening, produced wind chill values of 20 below to 30 below zero.  Winds dropped mostly below 10 mph by the early morning hours of 1/15 but air temperatures fell to 10 below to 20 below zero.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure developed over South Carolina during the early morning hours of Jan 20th 2009. The low pressure system tracked northeast and intensified offshore of the North Carolina coast during the rest of the day. Rain developed over eastern North Carolina after midnight on Jan 20th, and gradually changed to snow from west to east through the morning hours. Bands of snow dropped on average 3 to 6 inches across the northern counties with 1 to 3 inches south.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rain changed to snow around 10 am and continue into the evening hours. Snow accumulated 2 to 4 inches across the county.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts up to 37 knots were measured at Raccoon Point.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of low pressure tracked through the Tennessee Valley into the Ohio Valley on the 27th spreading precipitation across northern and central Virginia. Precipitation began as snow, but a change over to sleet, and eventually freezing rain occurred from south to north during the afternoon and evening of the 27th. Freezing rain finally changed to rain from south to north during the morning and afternoon hours of the 28th. Rain ended during the early evening hours of the 28th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ice accumulation around a quarter inch was reported across the county. Snow and sleet accumulation 1 inch was estimated across the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A complex of thunderstorms moved southeast out of Northwest Kansas into Central and South Central Kansas during the early morning hours of May 8th, 2009.  This complex of thunmderstorms would intensify over South Central Kansas during the morning and become a prolific damaging wind producer.  This swath of damaging winds, (measured at 80 to 100 mph) cut a path of destruction from just north of Wichita, Kansas to Parsons, Kansas. This storm system would continue on into Southern Missouri and eventually Southern Illinois producing widespread damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: At the El Dorado airport a small plane was flipped and a metal hanger collapsed.

Strong north to northwest winds, gusting to over 50 mph, combined with existing loose snow cover and 1 to 3 inches of new snow to produce blizzard conditions with widespread visibilities near zero over parts of southeast South Dakota during the day and early evening of January 12th. The very low visibilities were widespread where the greatest loose snow cover was located, and more localized in other areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: North to northwest winds sustained at 30 to 40 mph with gusts over 50 mph combined with several inches of loose snow cover, along with 1 to 3 inches of new snow, to produce widespread visibilities of a quarter mile or less in blowing snow. The low visibilities and drifting snow made travel impossible in many areas, and forced schools and businesses to close.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Arctic air plunged southeast across eastern Nebraska and southwest Iowa on January 14th and 15th.  Temperatures fell into the single digits above and below zero during the morning hours of 1/14, recovered a little in the afternoon and then fell to 5 below to 20 below, or a bit colder, by the morning of the 15th.  Northwest winds of 20 to 30 mph with higher gusts were observed into the afternoon of the 14th before subsiding in the afternoon and evening.  This produced wind chill values of 20 below to 30 below zero over much of the region.  By around midnight on the 15th most reporting sites observed winds dropped below 10 mph and remained that way through the morning of the 15th.  However, several locations, mainly south through southeast of Omaha, recorded wind speeds of 10 to 15 mph and wind chill values colder than 20 below through around 5am CST on the 15th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: As temperatures fell into the single digits across the county during the morning of 1/14 and then below zero by the evening of the 14th,  northwest winds of 20 to 30 mph in the morning and early afternoon and 10 to 20 mph from late afternoon into late evening, produced wind chill values of 20 below to 25 below zero.  Winds dropped mostly below 10 mph by the early morning hours of 1/15 but air temperatures fell to 10 below to 20 below zero.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Persistent northwest flow aloft ushered a series of weather disturbances across Wyoming bringing heavy snow to the mountains of northern Wyoming. Mountain snowfall of 12 to 18 inches was common. A prolonged period of light snow allowed accumulations to top-out between six and eight inches in Jackson Hole and the Star Valley.

Low pressure tracked through the Tennessee Valley and emerged off the Mid-Atlantic coast on the 5th. This system spread precipitation across Maryland. There was enough cold air drawn in from the north for precipitation to fall in the form of snow across most areas. Most of the snow fell during the morning and afternoon hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A total of 2.5 inches of snow fell near Bryans Road while 2.0 inches of snow fell in Waldorf.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong area of low pressure moved north across West Virginia to western Pennsylvania producing a heavy mix of precipitation. Snow accumulated 2 to 4 inches across northwest Pennsylvania on the night of the 27Th before changing to freezing rain the morning of the 28Th, then back to snow in the afternoon with another 1 to 2 inches. Ice accumulations in Pittsburgh and areas north were from a quarter to one half inch. For southeast Ohio, northern West Virgina, and Garrett county Maryland mixed precipitation changed to freezing rain during the evening of the 27Th with ice quickly accumulating to one half inch before changing to plain overnight. The rain changed back to snow during the afternoon of the 28Th with 1 to 2 inches of snow accumulating.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A Christmas tree in front of the Tuscaloosa County Courthouse was blown down.  Numerous trees were blown down near the Jim Walters Resources number 7 mine.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front pushing through the state brought thunderstorms with very heavy rain, causing a few areas to become flooded.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A portion of Cotton Hill Road, near the intersection with AL-30, became partially washed out due to water flowing over it.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level low pressure system moved from the Southern Rockies across the Southern Plains on the 24th. Widespread precipitation developed as this system approached. Arctic air gradually spread into the region behind a strong cold front changing the rain to sleet and then quickly to snow over much of northwestern Arkansas by the afternoon hours. Periods of snow, some falling heavily at times through the afternoon and evening hours, resulted in four to six inches of snow over far northwestern Arkansas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Four to six inches of snow fell across the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Arctic air following a frontal passage set off lake effect snows early on Friday 16th. Initially, the activity off Lake Erie focused on the Chautauqua ridge on a west wind, with several inches Friday morning, but winds backed slightly during the midday and afternoon, and a decent lake plume lifted well to the north into Buffalo's South Towns and even up into central Erie county. Lake Erie had a large amount of ice but the snow apparently formed off some open water north of Long Point. Over 6 fell in this narrow strip with plenty of blowing snow and near whiteout conditions just to the south of the city which snarled the evening rush hour. The activity weakened during the evening and lifted north across the Buffalo metro area and dropped a quick 1-3 inches early Saturday before dissipating. Reported snowfalls included: 12 inches at Perrsyburg; 10 inches at Elma, 9 inches in East Aurora; and 7 inches at Alden.|Off Lake Ontario, the activity was stronger as ice was not a factor. Bands developed early Friday over northern Cayuga and southwest Oswego counties and gradually meandered northward during Friday and Friday night, with several intense bands setting up across the area from Pulaski to Watertown. This continued through much of Saturday before weakening during the afternoon in the Watertown area, but not before nearly two feet fell. Snowfalls totals included: 29 inches at Pulaski; 21 inches at Watertown; and 12 inches in Carthage and Oswego.

Low pressure moved out of the southern Plains northeast across the Tennessee Valley reaching the southern New England Coast on the 28th.  The low brought an eight to twelve inch blanket of snow to the entire region by the evening of the 28th. Innumerable automobile accidents were reported throughout the region as the roads became hard to navigate in the heavy snow and reduced visibilities. Many schools cancelled classes across the region.

A small but potent winter storm moved from the plains across northern Illinois during the morning hours of January 14th.  Air temperatures were only 5 to 15 degrees above zero and snow/water ratios were very high, in some cases 40 to 1.  Snow begain falling just after midnight on January 14th and ended by early afternoon.  Stormtotal snowfall amounts included 7.2 inches in Morris, 7.0 inches in Dixon, 7.0 inches in Kankakee, 7.0 inches in Joliet, 6.5 inches in Peotone, 6.5 inches in Yorkville, 6.5 inches in Dwight, 6.0 inches in Oregon and 5.7 inches in Homewood.

A low pressure system developed over the lower Mississippi Valley during Tuesday January 27th. The low then strengthened, and tracked northeast from the lower Ohio Valley Wednesday morning on January 28th, into Pennsylvania during Wednesday afternoon, and into northern New England by Thursday morning January 29th. ||This storm spread a significant wintry mix of precipitation across western Massachusetts, beginning early Wednesday morning, and ending early Thursday morning.||Snow and sleet amounts ranged from 4 to 8 inches, with the greatest amounts occurring across higher elevations within northern Berkshire County. In addition, some freezing rain occurred, with ice accretion of generally under one tenth of an inch occurring.||The wintry mix led to either closures, or delayed openings of numerous schools and businesses both Wednesday and Thursday mornings. In addition, treacherous travel conditions existed during this period.

A strong but slow-moving low pressure system began its approach to Arkansas on the 23rd. Ahead of this low, unseasonably large amounts of moisture were drawn northward from the Gulf of Mexico. The approach of the low set off heavy rain and thunderstorms on the 23rd and 24th. Rainfall amounts of 3 to 6 inches were common for the two-day period. In a broad swath from southwest Arkansas through the central part of the state into northeast Arkansas, many places picked up 7 to 10 inches of rain. Flash flooding resulted initially, followed by areal flooding and river flooding. After the low passed by, colder air spilled into Arkansas. Light snow fell across parts of northern and western Arkansas from late on the 24th into the early morning hours of Christmas Day. Most snowfall amounts were in the 1/2 to 1 inch range, with spotty totals up to 2 inches. Though the amounts were rather small, hazardous driving conditions resulted.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Areas of generally light snow fell across portions of the Arkansas Ozarks and Ouachita Mountains of western Arkansas, causing area roads to become slick due to snow cover Christmas morning. Snowfall amounts of generally around one half to one inch were reported, with locally higher amounts of up to two inches of snowfall in the higher elevations.

Arctic air moved over the Upper Ohio Valley with a large dome of High pressure. Morning lows across eastern Ohio, western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia, and Garrett county Maryland. The lowest low temperatures ranged from 10 below zero at Pittsburgh to 22 below zero at Accident, Maryland. Low temperatures were generally 10 to 15 degrees below zero elsewhere.

A strong upper level storm system moved its way out of the southern Great Basin and into the Southern Plains during the afternoon hours of December 23rd. Strong southerly flow was found ahead of this storm system with dewpoint temperatures in the lower to middle 60s noted northward to the Interstate 20 corridor of northeast Texas and northern Louisiana. Impressive deep layer shear was noted in the warm sector across the region which was conducive for discrete storm cells during the afternoon and evening across northeast Texas. These storms spawned tornadoes and produced large hail across portions of northeast Texas. The storm system moved eastward during the predawn hours of December 24th with again, numerous storms producing tornadoes across southern Arkansas and northern Louisiana. In addition to all the storm damage...these storms were prolific rain makers with numerous reports of flash flooding across the region as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous roads were underwater across the county.

Freezing rain finally changed to rain during the afternoon of the 28th. Rain ended during the early evening hours of the 28th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deepening storm system, and the associated cold front that swept across Alabama, brought widespread showers and thunderstorms to the state.  Several storms produced heavy rain that caused flash flooding, along with damaging winds.  Even away from the thunderstorms, gusty gradient winds affected a large portion of Central Alabama.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees were blown down near exit 219 on Interstate 65, near Jemison, including some that were blown onto the highway.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong post-frontal gradient winds developed on December 9th, strongest during the late morning and afternoon as a deep area of low pressure tracked into northern Lower Michigan. Widespread wind gusts between 45 and 60 mph were common across much of northern Indiana.

There were reports of power lines and trees down across the region due to the strong winds, which resulted in isolated power outages.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong area of low pressure moved north across West Virginia to western Pennsylvania producing a heavy mix of precipitation. Snow accumulated 2 to 4 inches across northwest Pennsylvania on the night of the 27Th before changing to freezing rain the morning of the 28Th, then back to snow in the afternoon with another 1 to 2 inches. Ice accumulations in Pittsburgh and areas north were from a quarter to one half inch. For southeast Ohio, northern West Virgina, and Garrett county Maryland mixed precipitation changed to freezing rain during the evening of the 27Th with ice quickly accumulating to one half inch before changing to plain overnight. The rain changed back to snow during the afternoon of the 28Th with 1 to 2 inches of snow accumulating.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large and relatively slow moving storm brought a prolonged winter storm and even, for a time, blizzard conditions to eastern Nebraska and western Iowa from late on Dec. 7th through the early morning hours of Dec. 9th.  The storm was driven by an upper level disturbance that tracked from the west coast across the Rockies and deepened over the Mississippi River valley.  The heaviest snow fell in advance of when the stronger winds arrived, mainly during the morning and afternoon of Dec. 8th.  However, as the winds increased to 30 to 50 mph during the night of the 8th and early on the 9th, visibilities frequently dropped to near zero, especially in open areas.  Considerable drifting snow also occurred, in many cases closing roads back shut almost as fast as they could be opened.  This prompted many counties to pull snow plows off the roads for a while during the night of the 8th and 9th.  Many schools were closed for 3 days because of the storm, due the forecast of heavy snow to begin on the 7th, poor visibilities and roads drifted shut on the 8th and still some closed roads and bitter cold wind chills which followed the storm on the 9th.||Total snowfall from the storm was 6 to 15 inches over most of eastern Nebraska and western Iowa.  Higher amounts in eastern Nebraska included 15 inches in Union, 14 inches in Columbus, around 12 inches at the NWS in Valley, at Tekamah, Uehling, Steele City and Weeping Water.  In western Iowa heavier amounts included 12 inches in Clarinda and Hastings and around 11 inches in Harlan, Red Oak and Little Sioux.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 8 to 12 inches fell across much of the county from this storm with 10 inches measured in Shenandoah. The snow began during the late evening of 12/7 and continued into the early morning hours of 12/9.  Winds were not that strong when the snow started, but north winds increased during the afternoon of 12/8 and especially that evening into the next morning.  Frequent wind gusts of 40 mph or so were observed with a peak gust of 44 mph measured at Shenandoah.  The winds produced considerable blowing and drifting snow with blizzard conditions during the evening and early morning hours of the 8th and 9th, which closed many county roads.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong westerly flow aloft brought moisture in the form of heavy snow and rain to portions of western Montana. Liquid precipitation amounts ranged from 1 to 6 inches.  Snow fall amounts ranged between 3 and 13 inches, with the heavier amounts occuring over the higher terrain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Highway 12 going over Lolo Pass was closed due to the heavy snow and avalanche danger along the road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A small but potent winter storm moved from the plains across northern Illinois during the morning hours of January 14th.  Air temperatures were only 5 to 15 degrees above zero and snow/water ratios were very high, in some cases 40 to 1.  Snow begain falling just after midnight on January 14th and ended by early afternoon.  Stormtotal snowfall amounts included 7.2 inches in Morris, 7.0 inches in Dixon, 7.0 inches in Kankakee, 7.0 inches in Joliet, 6.5 inches in Peotone, 6.5 inches in Yorkville, 6.5 inches in Dwight, 6.0 inches in Oregon and 5.7 inches in Homewood.

A low northwest of the Aloha State produced surf of 10 to 15 feet along the north-facing shores of Niihau, Kauai, Oahu, Molokai, and Maui; and 8 to 12 feet along the west-facing shores of Niihau, Kauai, and Oahu.  No significant property damage or injuries were reported.

Low pressure tracked up through the Great Lakes. Plenty of moisture from the Atlantic Ocean and Gulf of Mexico was drawn into this system to produce widespread precipitation. There was enough cold air at the start of the storm for mixed precipitation, but warmer air did eventually work its way into the storm changing all mixed precipitation to rain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ice accumulation from freezing rain was estimated to be around one quarter of an inch, especially across the higher elevations.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong north to northwest winds, gusting to over 50 mph, combined with existing loose snow cover and 1 to 3 inches of new snow to produce blizzard conditions with widespread visibilities near zero over parts of northwest Iowa during the day and early evening of January 12th. The very low visibilities were widespread where the greatest loose snow cover was located, and more localized in other areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: North to northwest winds sustained at 30 to 40 mph with gusts around 50 mph combined with several inches of loose snow cover, along with 1 to 3 inches of new snow, to produce widespread visibilities of a quarter mile or less in blowing snow. The low visibilities and drifting snow made travel impossible in many areas, and forced schools and businesses to close.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: North to northwest winds gusting to around 50 mph, existing snow cover, and 1 to 3 inches of new snow produced areas of blowing snow with local visibilities below a quarter mile.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A clipper low pressure system strengthened as it approached Michigan from the northwest.  This storm produced two areas of heavy snow.  The main system snow fell in a wide band from Charlevoix and Bellaire, southeastward through Grayling and on to Standish and Tawas City.  Accumulations of 8 to 12 inches were common within this band.  A more localized band of lake enhanced snow affect part of the Lake Michigan coastline, near Manistee and Arcadia, as well as near Curtis and Gould City.  Snowfall amounts were around 10 inches, with locally near 15 inches in Curtis.

A low pressure system tracked east-northeast through the Ohio Valley late January 9th into January 10th. A narrow band of heavy snow fell on the northern fringe of this storm system across northern Indiana, with total snowfall amounts generally ranging between 5 and 10 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow affected the region January 9th into January 10th, with a brief lull in the snowfall during the afternoon and early evening hours of January 9th. Snowfall amounts across the county generally ranged 5 and 8 inches, with 6.0 inches of total snow accumulation reported near Lagrange. There were reports of a few accidents and slide-offs across the region.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An intensifying cyclone which moved from North Texas into Arkansas before easing northward through the Mississippi Valley, pushed a vigorous front through Deep South Texas during the pre-dawn hours of Christmas Eve, 2009.  As the cyclone deepened, a low level northwesterly jet developed around its southern and western flank, with wind speeds ranging from 50 to more than 60 knots just above the earth's surface, extending south through Deep South Texas.||Two wind peaks occurred in Deep South Texas:  First, along and just behind the early morning front, where northwest winds gusted between 40 and 50 mph, causing most of the damage reports.  During the afternoon, a second peak developed as a warming low level atmosphere mixed down some of the 50 to 60 mph winds associated with the developing jet.  Afternoon gusts reached 50 mph along the Laguna Madre in Kenedy County, and generally ranged from 35 to 45 mph elsewhere.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts, estimated between 44 and 48 mph based on observations at Harlingen/Valley International Airport earlier (353 AM, 48 mph) and Brownsville/South Padre Island Airport a bit later (431 to 438 AM, 44 mph), blew down a 50 foot section of aging fence along Alton Gloor Blvd. in the north side of the city at around 425 AM, and blew off shingles at an older apartment building near the intersection of Price Road and Old Port Isabel Highway several minutes later.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Arctic air moved over the Upper Ohio Valley with a large dome of High pressure. Morning lows across eastern Ohio, western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia, and Garrett county Maryland. The lowest low temperatures ranged from 10 below zero at Pittsburgh to 22 below zero at Accident, Maryland. Low temperatures were generally 10 to 15 degrees below zero elsewhere.
A strong winter storm produced heavy snow in the south Washington Cascades and Columbia River Gorge.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A winter storm produced heavy snow in the south Washington Cascades.  Some reports include 14 inches at June Lake and Sheep Canyon, 19 inches at Lone Pine.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong winter storm produced heavy snow in the south Washington Cascades and Columbia River Gorge.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A winter storm produced 6 inches of snow in the Columbia River Gorge.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level storm system moved its way out of the southern Great Basin and into the Southern Plains during the afternoon hours of December 23rd.  Strong southerly flow was found ahead of this storm system with dewpoint temperatures in the lower to middle 60s noted northward to the Interstate 20 corridor of northeast Texas and northern Louisiana.  Impressive deep layer shear was noted in the warm sector across the region which was conducive for discrete storm cells during the afternoon and evening across northeast Texas.  These storms spawned tornadoes and produced large hail across portions of northeast Texas.  The storm system moved eastward during the predawn hours of December 24th with again, numerous storms producing tornadoes across southern Arkansas and northern Louisiana.  In addition to all the storm damage...these storms were prolific rain makers with numerous reports of flash flooding across the region as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous parish roads were underwater and closed across the parish.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An already cold airmass was reinforced by even colder air behind a strong cold front. Low wind chills, freezing temperatures and frost affect most of east central Florida for three consecutive nights.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Sub-freezing temperatures occurred for three consecutive nights. Wind chill readings in the 20s also occurred during the morning of the 21st. The coldest morning at most locations was on the 22nd, when hard freeze conditions spread south across many locations of the interior peninsula to Lake Okeechobee. Official temperature sites reached the mid to upper 20s, with a NWS Cooperative sites at Scottsmoor in NW Brevard county reaching 22 and Plymouth in NW Orange county reaching 16. Sub-freezing minimum readings and widespread frost occurred on the 23rd. Only the barrier islands south of Cape Canaveral remained at or slightly above freezing throughout the event.
