EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Another month of below normal precipitation caused severe drought conditions (D2), that began in late September 2008, to persist across parts of north-central, central and northeast Wisconsin. The severe drought (D2) continued through February 2009.

Low pressure developed off the Mid-Atlantic coast causing precipitation to develop over Virginia. There was enough cold air in place for precipitation to start off as a wintry mix of sleet and freezing rain. Precipitation changed to all rain by late in the morning as warmer air was drawn into the system.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ice accumulation around one a trace was reported in Front Royal and Linden.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong pressure gradient developed between a 1058 mb high across northeast Alaska and low pressure in the Bering Sea.  The strong pressure gradient produced high winds and blizzard conditions along part of the Chukchi Sea coast during the afternoon and evening hours of the 21st.  White-out conditions in heavy blowing and drifting snow were observed at Point Hope during the afternoon, and the visibility remained one quarter mile or less at times into the evening. Both Point Hope and Kivalina observed wind gusts to 50 mph/58 kt.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The observer four miles northwest of Herman measured 10.5 inches of snow in 27 hours.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong post-frontal gradient winds developed on December 9th, strongest during the late morning and afternoon as a deep area of low pressure tracked into northern Lower Michigan. Widespread wind gusts between 45 and 60 mph were common across much of southwest Lower Michigan.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Very windy conditions were seen across the area on December 9th as a deep area of low pressure tracked into northern Lower Michigan.  Wind gusts between 45 and 60 mph were common during the late morning and afternoon hours.  There were reports of power lines and trees down across the region due to the strong winds, which resulted in isolated power outages.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A favorable southwest flow and surface pressure gradient generated high wind across portions of Fremont and Natrona counties. The wind was strongest during the morning and early afternoon. A peak gust of 66 mph was recorded at Hunt Field in Lander. Sustained winds of 40 mph with gusts near 60 mph were measured on Beaver Rim and at Hiland.

A tight surface pressure gradient generated high wind across western Natrona County. A peak gust to 78 mph was recorded at Fales Rock RAWS around 1000MST. Shortly afterward, sustained wind of 40 mph was measured near Hiland along U.S. Highway 20/26.

Cold air sweeping in behind a departing low pressure system produced lake effect snows beginning during the evening of the 7th. Off Lake Erie, over a foot of snow fell over the higher elevations during the morning and midday hours of the 8th. Specific snowfall reports included: Sinclairville 28 inches; Ellicottville 27 inches; Ashville 25 inches; Randolph 20 inches; Chafee 13 and Warsaw and Jamestown 8. The activity off Lake Ontario was much weaker and spread out. Wraparound snows Wednesday night (7th) evolved into west to northwest bands of lake effect Thursday and Thursday night. Off Lake Ontario, 11 inches fell in Volney, 10 inches at Highmarket and Hooker and 7 inches in Oswego.

Low pressure moved out of the southern Plains northeast across the Tennessee Valley reaching the southern New England Coast on the 28th.  The low brought an eight to twelve inch blanket of snow to the entire region by the evening of the 28th. Innumerable automobile accidents were reported throughout the region as the roads became hard to navigate in the heavy snow and reduced visibilities. Many schools cancelled classes across the region.

A large and relatively slow moving storm brought a prolonged winter storm and even, for a time, blizzard conditions to eastern Nebraska and western Iowa from late on Dec. 7th through the early morning hours of Dec. 9th.  The storm was driven by an upper level disturbance that tracked from the west coast across the Rockies and deepened over the Mississippi River valley.  The heaviest snow fell in advance of when the stronger winds arrived, mainly during the morning and afternoon of Dec. 8th.  However, as the winds increased to 30 to 50 mph during the night of the 8th and early on the 9th, visibilities frequently dropped to near zero, especially in open areas.  Considerable drifting snow also occurred, in many cases closing roads back shut almost as fast as they could be opened.  This prompted many counties to pull snow plows off the roads for a while during the night of the 8th and 9th.  Many schools were closed for 3 days because of the storm, due the forecast of heavy snow to begin on the 7th, poor visibilities and roads drifted shut on the 8th and still some closed roads and bitter cold wind chills which followed the storm on the 9th.||Total snowfall from the storm was 6 to 15 inches over most of eastern Nebraska and western Iowa.  Higher amounts in eastern Nebraska included 15 inches in Union, 14 inches in Columbus, around 12 inches at the NWS in Valley, at Tekamah, Uehling, Steele City and Weeping Water.  In western Iowa heavier amounts included 12 inches in Clarinda and Hastings and around 11 inches in Harlan, Red Oak and Little Sioux.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 8 to 12 inches fell across much of the county from this storm with 11.3 inches measured in Red Oak. The snow began during the late evening of 12/7 and continued into the early morning hours of 12/9.  Winds were not that strong when the snow started, but north winds increased during the afternoon of 12/8 and especially that evening into the next morning.  Frequent wind gusts of 35 to 40 mph were observed with a peak gust measured at 40 mph Red Oak.  The winds produced considerable blowing and drifting snow with blizzard conditions during the evening and early morning hours of the 8th and 9th, which closed many county roads.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Arctic air that spilled in behind an early December Winter Storm/Blizzard that hit eastern Nebraska combined with northwest winds of 15 to 25 mph and produced dangerously cold wind chill values.  Wind chill values of 20 below to 25 below zero were observed during the morning hours of December 9th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind chill Values of 20 below to 25 below zero were observed much of the morning hours of December 9th.  Temperatures warmed a little in the afternoon as winds subsided, this allowed wind chill values to moderate by afternoon.

A small but potent winter storm moved from the plains across northern Illinois during the morning hours of January 14th.  Air temperatures were only 5 to 15 degrees above zero and snow/water ratios were very high, in some cases 40 to 1.  Snow begain falling just after midnight on January 14th and ended by early afternoon.  Stormtotal snowfall amounts included 7.2 inches in Morris, 7.0 inches in Dixon, 7.0 inches in Kankakee, 7.0 inches in Joliet, 6.5 inches in Peotone, 6.5 inches in Yorkville, 6.5 inches in Dwight, 6.0 inches in Oregon and 5.7 inches in Homewood.

Strong westerly flow aloft brought moisture in the form of heavy snow and rain to portions of western Montana.  Liquid precipitation measured anywhere from 1 to 4 inches over a 48 hours period, with total snow accumulations ranging between 7 and 9 inches over some of the higher valley locations.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Idaho DOT closed Highway 12 going over Lolo Pass due to the heavy snow causing avalanche danger.  Additionally, storm spotters in Dixie reported new snow accumulations up to 9 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Another potent winter storm brought accumulating snow to portions of western Montana.  The hardest hit area was the Potomac/Seeley Lake Region, where snow amounts between 8 to 12 inches was reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Storm spotters between Seeley Lake and Swan Lake reported 8 to 12 inches of new snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Precipitation came in two waves.  The initial round of elevated convection was focused across portions of central and south central Missouri.   Rainfall amounts of one half to one and half inches fell with this initial rainfall.  A second more intense band of rainfall moved across the region Thursday evening as a cold front swept into the Ozarks.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Route BB between Pritchett Road and Brown School Road was closed due to flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong north to northwest winds, gusting to over 50 mph, combined with existing loose snow cover and 1 to 3 inches of new snow to produce blizzard conditions with widespread visibilities near zero over parts of northwest Iowa during the day and early evening of January 12th. The very low visibilities were widespread where the greatest loose snow cover was located, and more localized in other areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: North to northwest winds gusting to around 50 mph, existing snow cover, and 1 to 3 inches of new snow produced areas of blowing snow with local visibilities below a quarter mile.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Arctic air plunged southeast across eastern Nebraska and southwest Iowa on January 14th and 15th.  Temperatures in southwest Iowa fell into the single digits during the morning hours of 1/14, recovered a little in the afternoon and then fell to 5 below to 20 below, or a bit colder, by the morning of the 15th.  Northwest winds of 20 to 30 mph with higher gusts were observed into the afternoon of the 14th before subsiding in the afternoon and evening.  This produced wind chill values of 20 below to 30 below zero over much of the region.  Winds continued to decrease during the early morning hours of 1/15, and by 5am CST most recorded speeds were less than 10 mph.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: As temperatures fell to around zero during the morning of 1/14 and then below zero by the evening of the 14th, northwest winds of 20 to 30 mph in the morning and early afternoon and 10 to 20 mph from late afternoon into late evening, produced wind chill values of 20 below to 30 below zero.  Winds dropped mostly below 10 mph by the early morning hours of 1/15 but air temperatures fell to 10 below to 20 below zero.

An intensifying cyclone which moved from North Texas into Arkansas before easing northward through the Mississippi Valley, pushed a vigorous front through Deep South Texas during the pre-dawn hours of Christmas Eve, 2009.  As the cyclone deepened, a low level northwesterly jet developed around its southern and western flank, with wind speeds ranging from 50 to more than 60 knots just above the earth's surface, extending south through Deep South Texas.||Two wind peaks occurred in Deep South Texas:  First, along and just behind the early morning front, where northwest winds gusted between 40 and 50 mph, causing most of the damage reports.  During the afternoon, a second peak developed as a warming low level atmosphere mixed down some of the 50 to 60 mph winds associated with the developing jet.  Afternoon gusts reached 50 mph along the Laguna Madre in Kenedy County, and generally ranged from 35 to 45 mph elsewhere.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The second wave of gusty winds during the afternoon of Christmas Eve blew down a parking light pole onto several vehicles in McAllen, causing unknown damage to them, roughly around 3 PM CST.  Winds gusted between 30 and 40 mph in the area from noon until 4 PM, with the strongest recorded at McAllen's Miller Airport at 253 PM CST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Heavy lake effect snow occurred from the afternoon of the 28th to the morning hours of the 29th. Snowfall accumulations ranged from 6 to 10 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An average of 4 to 10 inches of snow fell across northern portions of the county. Cicero measured 10 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of strong to severe thunderstorms moved east across southeast Mississippi during the afternoon hours on Christmas Eve, producing localized downburst winds to near 60 mph.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Tree blown down blocking Highway 29 North at Prospect Road 6 miles north of Mahned in northwestern Perry County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A snowstorm caused multiple traffic accidents along Interstate 40 between Flagstaff and Williams.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A Pacific winter storm created hazardous driving conditions on I-40 between Flagstaff and Williams.  The freeway was closed while crews cleared a semi trailer that had rolled over.  Two other semis rolled over in the same area. There were a total of 10 collisions and 12 cars that slid off the road. Travel was also difficult on I-17, Highway 89, and Highway 180 around Flagstaff. There were 5 non-injury accidents and two injury accidents within the Flagstaff City limits.  There were 6 non-injury and 1 injury accidents reported by Coconino County law enforcement.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A front moved into the eastern Bering Sea producing strong northeast wind and snow across the Pribilof Islands that resulted in a blizzard.
An intense front moved through the western Aleutians the evening of February 7th. Hurricane force wind gusts were associated with this front as it moved through the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ship reports of sustained 60 KT were observed in the region. Estimate gusts over 70 KT with this front based upon the ship observations.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong front moved to the Pribilof Islands February 8th. Strong wind and snow with this front produced blizzard conditions in the Pribilof Islands.

Another month of below normal precipitation caused severe drought conditions (D2), that began in late September 2008, to persist across parts of north-central, central and northeast Wisconsin. The severe drought (D2) continued through February 2009.

Light precipitation developed ahead of an approaching warm front during Sunday evening, January 4th. With surface temperatures initially remaining below freezing, the precipitation began as a mix of sleet and freezing rain across the southern Adirondacks, western and central Mohawk Valley, and across the Lake George and Saratoga region. The precipitation then changed to plain rain and drizzle by early Monday morning on January 5th.||Ice accretion from freezing rain was generally one tenth of an inch or less. However, this light icing led to locally hazardous travel conditions late Sunday evening into early Monday morning.

A tight surface pressure gradient generated high wind across western Natrona County. A peak gust to 78 mph was recorded at Fales Rock RAWS around 1000MST. Shortly afterward, sustained wind of 40 mph was measured near Hiland along U.S. Highway 20/26.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A small but potent winter storm moved from the plains across northern Illinois during the morning hours of January 14th.  Air temperatures were only 5 to 15 degrees above zero and snow/water ratios were very high, in some cases 40 to 1.  Snow begain falling just after midnight on January 14th and ended by early afternoon.  Stormtotal snowfall amounts included 7.2 inches in Morris, 7.0 inches in Dixon, 7.0 inches in Kankakee, 7.0 inches in Joliet, 6.5 inches in Peotone, 6.5 inches in Yorkville, 6.5 inches in Dwight, 6.0 inches in Oregon and 5.7 inches in Homewood.

A potent Pacific storm system brought a mixture of snow and freezing rain, accompanied with strong winds to portions of western Montana.  Snow amounts of 7 to 18 inches fell in the valley locations, while 12 to 27 inches fell over the higher terrain.  In addition, sustained winds at 15 to 20 mph were not uncommon with gusts up to 30 mph, causing locally lowered visibility and severe driving conditions on area roads.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Spotters in the region reported snow amounts anywhere from 7 to 14 inches.  Winds gusted up to 30 mph creating blowing and drifting snow.  The Montana DOT reported severe driving conditions on area roads, including Interstate 90.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong north to northwest winds, gusting to over 50 mph, combined with existing loose snow cover and 1 to 3 inches of new snow to produce blizzard conditions with widespread visibilities near zero over much of southwest Minnesota during the day and early evening of January 12th. The very low visibilities were widespread where the greatest loose snow cover was located, and more localized in extreme southwest Minnesota.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: North to northwest winds sustained at 30 to 40 mph with gusts around 50 mph combined with several inches of loose snow cover, along with 1 to 3 inches of new snow, to produce widespread visibilities of a quarter mile or less in blowing snow. The low visibilities and drifting snow made travel impossible in many areas, and forced schools and businesses to close.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong but slow-moving low pressure system began its approach to Arkansas on the 23rd. Ahead of this low, unseasonably large amounts of moisture were drawn northward from the Gulf of Mexico. The approach of the low set off heavy rain and thunderstorms on the 23rd and 24th. Rainfall amounts of 3 to 6 inches were common for the two-day period. In a broad swath from southwest Arkansas through the central part of the state into northeast Arkansas, many places picked up 7 to 10 inches of rain. Flash flooding resulted initially, followed by areal flooding and river flooding. After the low passed by, colder air spilled into Arkansas. Light snow fell across parts of northern and western Arkansas from late on the 24th into the early morning hours of Christmas Day. Most snowfall amounts were in the 1/2 to 1 inch range, with spotty totals up to 2 inches. Though the amounts were rather small, hazardous driving conditions resulted.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rain that fell on December 24th assured that 2009 would be the wettest year ever recorded in Morrilton. Total rainfall for the year was 76.86 inches, breaking the record of 73.58 inches set in 1957.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow moving winter storm moved across northern Illinois on December 26th.  Snow began to fall during the early morning hours and continued through the late evening hours.  The snow was heavy at times in some areas and the snow to water ratio was quite large with the driest snow reported to be 40 to 1.  A foot of snow fell across the northwest suburbs of Chicago with a large area receiving six inches or more.  Snowfall totals included 12.1 inches in St. Charles; 12.0 inches in Elburn; 12.0 inches in North Aurora; 12.0 inches 1 mile north of Carol Stream; 11.9 inches 7 miles north northwest of St. Charles; 11.1 inches in Batavia; 10.6 inches in Streamwood; 10.3 inches in Elgin; 10.0 inches in Woodstock; 9.4 inches 4 miles north northwest of Rockford; 9.2 inches 3 miles southwest of Barrington; 8.9 inches in Mundelein; 7.5 inches in Island Lake; 6.7 inches in Downers Grove; 6.2 inches in Roscoe; 6.1 inches in Rockford and 6.0 inches at Chicago O'Hare Airport.

The combination of a weak high retreating over the northeast and deepening low pressure over the Great Lakes resulted in a significant accumulation of ice across portions of interior Northern New Jersey from the evening of January 6 into the afternoon of January 7. A warm front extending east from the developing low worked northward from the Mid Atlantic states with overrunning precipitation to its north.||Ice amounts averaged a little more than one-half inch across the western half of Passaic county, with the highest amount of 0.80 inches reported at Awosting.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level storm system moved its way out of the southern Great Basin and into the Southern Plains during the afternoon hours of December 23rd.  Strong southerly flow was found ahead of this storm system with dewpoint temperatures in the lower to middle 60s noted northward to the Interstate 20 corridor of northeast Texas and northern Louisiana.  Impressive deep layer shear was noted in the warm sector across the region which was conducive for discrete storm cells during the afternoon and evening across northeast Texas.  These storms spawned tornadoes and produced large hail across portions of northeast Texas.  The storm system moved eastward during the predawn hours of December 24th with again, numerous storms producing tornadoes across southern Arkansas and northern Louisiana.  In addition to all the storm damage...these storms were prolific rain makers with numerous reports of flash flooding across the region as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several pine trees were snapped along hwy. 175 north of the intersection of Hwy. 171 and 175.  The weak tornado tracked north along Hwy. 175 and uprooted several large trees on the east side of Hwy. 175 before lifting.  Maximum winds are estimated at 70-75 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure moved out of the southern Plains northeast across the Tennessee Valley reaching the southern New England Coast on the 28th.  The low brought an eight to twelve inch blanket of snow to the entire region by the evening of the 28th. Innumerable automobile accidents were reported throughout the region as the roads became hard to navigate in the heavy snow and reduced visibilities. Many schools cancelled classes across the region.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An already cold airmass was reinforced by even colder air behind a strong cold front. Low wind chills, freezing temperatures and frost affect most of east central Florida for three consecutive nights.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Sub-freezing temperatures occurred for three consecutive nights. Wind chill readings in the 20s also occurred during the morning of the 21st. The coldest morning at most locations was on the 22nd, when hard freeze conditions spread south across many locations of the interior peninsula to Lake Okeechobee. Official temperature sites reached the mid to upper 20s, with a NWS Cooperative sites at Scottsmoor in NW Brevard county reaching 22 and Plymouth in NW Orange county reaching 16. Sub-freezing minimum readings and widespread frost occurred on the 23rd. Only the barrier islands south of Cape Canaveral remained at or slightly above freezing throughout the event.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front moved from western Alaska to south central Alaska February 18th and 19th. Strong moist flow in advance of the front into the Susitna Valley produced 8 to 12 inches of snow in the Susitna Valley on the 19th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Spotters in the Susitna Valley reported 8 to 12 inches of snow and possibly more.

A strong north Pacific storm produced high wind over the central Aleutians on the 20th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Base on surface observations and the synoptic analysis wind is estimated to have reached 75 mph.

A very strong low level jet developed over eastern North Carolina ahead of a cold front. Bands of low topped convective showers helped mix these strong winds down to the ground producing numerous reports of damaging winds. One band of showers crossed during the late morning hours producing damage over mainly the northern parts of eastern North Carolina. Another band of showers crossed in the evening with damaging gusts over the entire region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Roof partially blown off a warehouse. Large tree blown down onto home damaging roof. Numerous trees and powerlines blown down.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure developed off the Mid-Atlantic coast causing precipitation to develop over Virginia. There was enough cold air in place for precipitation to start off as a wintry mix of sleet and freezing rain. Precipitation changed to all rain by late in the morning as warmer air was drawn into the system.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ice accumulation around one tenth of an inch was reported in Monterey.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Light precipitation developed ahead of an approaching warm front during Sunday evening, January 4th. With surface temperatures initially remaining below freezing, the precipitation began as a mix of sleet and freezing rain across the southern Adirondacks, western and central Mohawk Valley, and across the Lake George and Saratoga region. The precipitation then changed to plain rain and drizzle by early Monday morning on January 5th.||Ice accretion from freezing rain was generally one tenth of an inch or less. However, this light icing led to locally hazardous travel conditions late Sunday evening into early Monday morning.

Very cold temperatures and moderate northwest winds combined to lower wind chill readings to 35 to 45 below zero at times from the morning of January 14th to early morning on January 15th. The strongest winds were at the start of the event. While winds decreased slowly on the night of January 14th, actual temperatures also dropped, reaching 20 below to 30 below zero near daybreak on January 15th, about which time winds became light and no longer a major factor.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate to strong northwest winds and very cold air combined to lower wind chills to 35 to 45 below zero at times. The coldest winds chills were during the morning of January 14th with strong winds, and the night of January 14th to daybreak of January 15th when temperatures were falling and winds were slowly decreasing. The actual temperature dropped to 26 below zero at Pipestone on the morning of January 15th after the wind had subsided.

An area of low pressure passed through the Mid-Atlantic on the 10th into the early morning hours of the 11th. The track of the low was far enough north for warmer air to be drawn into the storm system above the surface. However, colder air remained trapped at the surface causing freezing rain to develop.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A light glaze of icing due to freezing rain was reported in Linden. Most of the icing occurred on trees.

Strong north to northwest winds, gusting to over 50 mph, combined with existing loose snow cover and 1 to 3 inches of new snow to produce blizzard conditions with widespread visibilities near zero over parts of southeast South Dakota during the day and early evening of January 12th. The very low visibilities were widespread where the greatest loose snow cover was located, and more localized in other areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: North to northwest winds sustained at 30 to 40 mph with gusts over 50 mph combined with several inches of loose snow cover, along with 1 to 3 inches of new snow, to produce widespread visibilities of a quarter mile or less in blowing snow. The low visibilities and drifting snow made travel impossible in many areas, and forced schools and businesses to close.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall totaled up to 1.5 inches in Charlottesville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Arctic air plunged southeast across eastern Nebraska and southwest Iowa on January 14th and 15th.  Temperatures fell into the single digits above and below zero during the morning hours of 1/14, recovered a little in the afternoon and then fell to 5 below to 20 below, or a bit colder, by the morning of the 15th.  Northwest winds of 20 to 30 mph with higher gusts were observed into the afternoon of the 14th before subsiding in the afternoon and evening.  This produced wind chill values of 20 below to 30 below zero over much of the region.  By around midnight on the 15th most reporting sites observed winds dropped below 10 mph and remained that way through the morning of the 15th.  However, several locations, mainly south through southeast of Omaha, recorded wind speeds of 10 to 15 mph and wind chill values colder than 20 below through around 5am CST on the 15th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: As temperatures fell below zero by the evening of the 14th, northwest winds of 10 to 20 mph produced wind chill values of 20 below to 25 below zero.  Winds dropped mostly below 10 mph by around 5am CST, but air temperatures by that time were around 8 below to 15 below zero.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system would strengthen as it crossed Southern Lower Michigan in the early morning hours of the 13th.  A widespread 2 to 4 inches of snow fell in most of Northern Michigan, with some blowing and drifting due to gusty and shifting winds.  However, cold air moving across Lake Michigan resulted in lake enhancement to the snow, and local areas of heavier snowfall.  Five to seven inches of snow fell in Leland, Suttons Bay, Lake Ann, Frankfort, and Arcadia.  Similar amounts fell near Ironton and Ellsworth.

A low pressure system tracked east-northeast through the Ohio Valley late January 9th into January 10th. A narrow band of heavy snow fell on the northern fringe of this storm system across southern Lower Michigan, with total snowfall amounts generally ranging between 8 and 13 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow developed early January 9th and continued into January 10th. There was a brief break in the snow Friday afternoon into early Friday evening, January 9th. Snowfall amounts of 8 to 13 inches were common across the county. An observer near Dowagiac reported a storm total snow accumulation of 12.3 inches. There were reports of accidents and slide-offs across the region.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous upper level disturbance crossing from Southwest Texas into the Big Bend Region helped intensify a Gulf Low, or Texas Nor'easter, just south of the mouth of the Rio Grande River late on December 15th and 16th.  Moderate to heavy rain developed across the region overnight on the 15th, and continued through the day and evening of the 16th as the system gradually tracked northward along the coast.||Event total rainfall in Hidalgo, Cameron, Willacy, and southern Kenedy County ranged from 3 to 4 1/2 inches, with peak values occurring in the more populated portions of the area including Pharr and McAllen in Hidalgo County, and Brownsville through Harlingen in Cameron County in particular.||The steady rains, falling on increasingly saturated soils, eventually produced pockets of nuisance flooding in typically poor drainage locations across the Lower and Middle Rio Grande Valley from mid morning through early evening on the 16th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rain, heavy at times during the daylight hours of the 16th, accumulated an estimated 1 1/2 to 2 inches between 6 AM and 6 PM in along the Highway 77 corridor of Willacy County.  High standing water occurred in these areas.  Event totals in Willacy County included 3.33 inches in Raymondville, and 2.92 inches in Port Mansfield.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An intensifying cyclone which moved from North Texas into Arkansas before easing northward through the Mississippi Valley, pushed a vigorous front through Deep South Texas during the pre-dawn hours of Christmas Eve, 2009.  As the cyclone deepened, a low level northwesterly jet developed around its southern and western flank, with wind speeds ranging from 50 to more than 60 knots just above the earth's surface, extending south through Deep South Texas.||Two wind peaks occurred in Deep South Texas:  First, along and just behind the early morning front, where northwest winds gusted between 40 and 50 mph, causing most of the damage reports.  During the afternoon, a second peak developed as a warming low level atmosphere mixed down some of the 50 to 60 mph winds associated with the developing jet.  Afternoon gusts reached 50 mph along the Laguna Madre in Kenedy County, and generally ranged from 35 to 45 mph elsewhere.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts, estimated between 45 and 50 mph based on a 323 AM peak gust observation at McAllen's Miller airport, helped to uproot a 40 foot tall live oak tree in Pharr.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong winter storm produced heavy snow in the north Oregon Cascades and Columbia River Gorge.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow fell in the north Oregon Cascades.  Some reports inlcude 20 inches at Mt Hood Meadows, 15 inches at Timberline and 14 inches at the Mt Hood Snotel site.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong winter storm produced heavy snow in the north Oregon Cascades and Columbia River Gorge.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A winter storm produced 4 to 6 inches of snow in the Columbia River Gorge.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Arctic air following another cold front produced lake effect snows off Lake Ontario during Saturday evening 24th. A southwest flow set up intense bands across Jefferson County which dropped close to a foot of snow by Sunday morning in the Watertown area. The bands settled south into southern Jefferson and northern Lewis counties for much of Sunday, with rates of 2-3 inches per hour from Adams to Barnes Corners and Hooker. A weak upper disturbance disrupted the bands Sunday night but they still dropped several inches down into the Oswego area overnight into Monday morning. The activity rejuvenated for awhile Monday and lifted north into Jefferson County before weakening Monday night. Reported snowfall totals included: 38 inches at Barnes Corners; 27 inches at Hooker, 24 inches at Adams, 12 to 16 inches in Watertown; and 11 inches in Oswego.

A large and relatively slow moving storm brought a prolonged winter storm and even, for a time, blizzard conditions to eastern Nebraska and western Iowa from late on Dec. 7th through the early morning hours of Dec. 9th.  The storm was driven by an upper level disturbance that tracked from the west coast across the Rockies and deepened over the Mississippi River valley.  The heaviest snow fell in advance of when the stronger winds arrived, mainly during the morning and afternoon of Dec. 8th.  However, as the winds increased to 30 to 50 mph during the night of the 8th and early on the 9th, visibilities frequently dropped to near zero, especially in open areas.  Considerable drifting snow also occurred, in many cases closing roads back shut almost as fast as they could be opened.  This prompted many counties to pull snow plows off the roads for a while during the night of the 8th and 9th.  Many schools were closed for 3 days because of the storm, due the forecast of heavy snow to begin on the 7th, poor visibilities and roads drifted shut on the 8th and still some closed roads and bitter cold wind chills which followed the storm on the 9th.||Total snowfall from the storm was 6 to 15 inches over most of eastern Nebraska and western Iowa.  Higher amounts in eastern Nebraska included 15 inches in Union, 14 inches in Columbus, around 12 inches at the NWS in Valley, at Tekamah, Uehling, Steele City and Weeping Water.  In western Iowa heavier amounts included 12 inches in Clarinda and Hastings and around 11 inches in Harlan, Red Oak and Little Sioux.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 8 to 12 inches fell across much of the county from this storm with 11 inches measured in Harlan. The snow began during the late evening of 12/7 and continued into the early morning hours of 12/9.  Winds were not that strong when the snow started, but north winds increased during the afternoon of 12/8 and especially that evening into the next morning.  Frequent wind gusts of 40 mph or more were observed with a peak gust of 48 mph measured in Harlan.  The winds produced considerable blowing and drifting snow with blizzard conditions during the evening and morning hours of the 8th and 9th, which closed many county roads.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cluster of thunderstorms moved out of the eastern CSRA and into the lower midland producing 3/4 inch hail and wind gusts to 50 mph.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Sheriff reported penny size hail in the Kline and Olar areas.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Lightning from a thunderstorm caused a house fire in McCormick County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Lightning struck a home in the Mt. Vintage subdivision in Merriwether causing major damage to a 2 story brick home.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An already cold airmass was reinforced by even colder air behind a strong cold front. Low wind chills, freezing temperatures and frost affect most of east central Florida for three consecutive nights.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Sub-freezing temperatures occurred for three consecutive nights. Wind chill readings in the 20s also occurred during the morning of the 21st. The coldest morning at most locations was on the 22nd, when hard freeze conditions spread south across many locations of the interior peninsula to Lake Okeechobee. Official temperature sites reached the mid to upper 20s, with a NWS Cooperative sites at Scottsmoor in NW Brevard county reaching 22 and Plymouth in NW Orange county reaching 16. Sub-freezing minimum readings and widespread frost occurred on the 23rd. Only the barrier islands south of Cape Canaveral remained at or slightly above freezing throughout the event.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Another month of below normal precipitation caused severe drought conditions (D2), that began in late September 2008, to persist across parts of north-central, central and northeast Wisconsin. The severe drought (D2) continued through February 2009.

Light precipitation developed ahead of an approaching warm front during Sunday evening, January 4th. With surface temperatures initially remaining below freezing, the precipitation began as a mix of sleet and freezing rain across the southern Adirondacks, western and central Mohawk Valley, and across the Lake George and Saratoga region. The precipitation then changed to plain rain and drizzle by early Monday morning on January 5th.||Ice accretion from freezing rain was generally one tenth of an inch or less. However, this light icing led to locally hazardous travel conditions late Sunday evening into early Monday morning.

Low pressure developed off the Mid-Atlantic coast causing precipitation to develop over Virginia. There was enough cold air in place for precipitation to start off as a wintry mix of sleet and freezing rain. Precipitation changed to all rain by late in the morning as warmer air was drawn into the system.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ice accumulation around one hundredth of an inch was reported across the county.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and wires were downed by snow and winds in Troy.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Very cold temperatures and moderate northwest winds combined to lower wind chill readings to 35 to 45 below zero at times from the morning of January 14th to early morning on January 15th. The strongest winds were at the start of the event. While winds decreased slowly on the night of January 14th, actual temperatures also dropped, reaching 20 below to 30 below zero near daybreak on January 15th, about which time winds became light and no longer a major factor.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate to strong northwest winds and very cold air combined to lower wind chills to 35 to 45 below zero at times. The coldest winds chills were during the morning of January 14th with strong winds, and the night of January 14th to daybreak of January 15th when temperatures were falling and winds were slowly decreasing. The actual temperature dropped to 24 below zero at Windom on the morning of January 15th after the wind had subsided.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An Arctic cold front that moved across the Omaha metro area during the early afternoon of January 3 caused a light drizzle that was falling across the area to freeze quickly.  Temperatures which were a few degrees above freezing before the front passed dropped into the 20s within an hour.  At Omaha-Eppley the temperature dropped from 34 at 104 pm to 28 at 123 pm.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Temperatures across the Omaha metro area were 34 or 35 degrees during the morning of January 3rd as a light drizzle developed.  An Arctic cold front that moved across the area during the early afternoon caused temperatures to fall into the upper 20s within a half hours time causing the drizzle to quickly freeze.  Many streets, parking lots and sidewalks became very slick and hazardous due to the sudden nature of the freeze even though precipitation amounts were only a trace or perhaps a hundredth of an inch or so.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered thunderstorms developed over the extreme southeastern Texas Panhandle and the northern South Plains during the afternoon hours of the 12th as a middle atmospheric storm system moved over the area. At least one thunderstorm became severe and produced hail up to the size of nickels northwest of Childress.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Local law enforcement officials reported nickel size hail along U.S. Highway 287 just northwest of Childress.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A significant severe weather episode impacted portions of southeastern New Mexico and the west Texas Permian Basin during the late afternoon and evening hours of the 11th. The storms developed east of a dryline and south of a warm front which advanced northward over the South Plains region. Thus cool stable air north of the frontal boundary precluded widespread severe weather over much of the South Plains, but a few thunderstorms, including a supercell storm, impacted the far southwestern portions of the South Plains region. While Doppler radar indicated the potential for a tornado with this storm over southern Yoakum County, no tornado was confirmed. Large hail and damaging thunderstorm winds, however, were observed.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A linear multicell thunderstorm complex impacted Yoakum County in the wake of an earlier supercell storm. This second round of thunderstorms produced a severe wind gust of 60 mph that was recorded by the Texas Tech University West Texas Mesonet west-northwest of Denver City. No damage was reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered thunderstorms impacted portions of the west Texas South Plains during the evening hours of the 28th and persisted into the very early morning hours of the 29th. A few storms became severe and produced hail up to the size of pennies.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The local broadcast media relayed a report of penny size in Lazbuddie shortly before 01:00 CST on the 29th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system moved through southern New England from the southwest spreading snow across the area.  This was followed by strong warm advection resulting in a precipitation change to freezing rain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Five and a half inches of snow fell across western Franklin county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system moved through southern New England from the southwest spreading snow across the area.  This was followed by strong warm advection resulting in a precipitation change to freezing rain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Four and a half inches of snow fell across western Middlesex county.  This was followed by freezing rain that left a glaze across much of the area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong north to northwest winds, gusting to over 50 mph, combined with existing loose snow cover and 1 to 3 inches of new snow to produce blizzard conditions with widespread visibilities near zero over parts of southeast South Dakota during the day and early evening of January 12th. The very low visibilities were widespread where the greatest loose snow cover was located, and more localized in other areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: North to northwest winds gusting to around 50 mph, existing snow cover, and 1 to 2 inches of new snow produced areas of blowing snow with local visibilities below a quarter mile.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A disturbance in the northern branch of the jet stream was able to phase with low pressure in the southern branch of the jet stream over the Southeast Coast on the night of the 18th. These two systems combined to develop a strong area of low pressure that slowly track up the Mid-Atlantic Coast during the 19th. The low was able to tap into moisture from the Gulf of Mexico and the Atlantic Ocean causing copious amounts of precipitation to develop. High pressure to the north kept plenty of cold air in place causing the precipitation to fall in the form of snow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts between 19 and 22 inches were reported across the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low far northwest of the isles generated surf of 10 to 20 feet along the north-facing shores, and 8 to 15 feet along west-facing shores, of Niihau, Kauai, Oahu, Molokai, and Maui.  There were no serious injuries or property damage.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure tracked through the Tennessee Valley and emerged off the Mid-Atlantic coast on the 5th. This system spread precipitation across eastern West Virginia. There was enough cold air drawn in from the north for precipitation to fall in the form of snow across most areas. Most of the snow fell during the morning and afternoon hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall was estimated to be over 5 inches across most of the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure tracked up through the Great Lakes. Plenty of moisture from the Atlantic Ocean and Gulf of Mexico was drawn into this system to produce widespread precipitation. There was enough cold air at the start of the storm for mixed precipitation, but warmer air did eventually work its way into the storm changing all mixed precipitation to rain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ice accumulation around one quarter of an inch was estimated across most of the county.

There was just enough cold air in place for precipitation to begin in the form of freezing rain across western Maryland. Warmer air eventually worked its way into the system causing precipitation to change to rain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trace of ice was reported at Eckhart Mines.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong north to northwest winds, gusting to over 50 mph, combined with existing loose snow cover and 1 to 3 inches of new snow to produce blizzard conditions with widespread visibilities near zero over much of southwest Minnesota during the day and early evening of January 12th. The very low visibilities were widespread where the greatest loose snow cover was located, and more localized in extreme southwest Minnesota.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: North to northwest winds sustained at 30 to 40 mph with gusts around 50 mph combined with several inches of loose snow cover, along with 1 to 3 inches of new snow, to produce widespread visibilities of a quarter mile or less in blowing snow. The low visibilities and drifting snow made travel impossible in many areas, and forced schools and businesses to close.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure passed through the Mid-Atlantic spreading precipitation over northern and central Virginia during the morning of the 31st. There was enough cold air for a period of snow and ice before drier air worked in during the afternoon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ice accumulation around one tenth of an inch was reported from near Reston and also near the intersection of Interstate 66 and 49.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong but slow-moving low pressure system began its approach to Arkansas on the 23rd. Ahead of this low, unseasonably large amounts of moisture were drawn northward from the Gulf of Mexico. The approach of the low set off heavy rain and thunderstorms on the 23rd and 24th. Rainfall amounts of 3 to 6 inches were common for the two-day period. In a broad swath from southwest Arkansas through the central part of the state into northeast Arkansas, many places picked up 7 to 10 inches of rain. Flash flooding resulted initially, followed by areal flooding and river flooding. After the low passed by, colder air spilled into Arkansas. Light snow fell across parts of northern and western Arkansas from late on the 24th into the early morning hours of Christmas Day. Most snowfall amounts were in the 1/2 to 1 inch range, with spotty totals up to 2 inches. Though the amounts were rather small, hazardous driving conditions resulted.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rain that fell on December 25th assured that 2009 would be the wettest year ever recorded in Warren. Total rainfall for the year was 87.47 inches, breaking the record of 81.87 inches set in 1905.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Freezing rain caused numerous traffic accidents throughout Elko county.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Law enforcement reported several traffic accidents due to ice covered roads from light freezing rain.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow moving winter storm moved across northern Illinois on December 26th.  Snow began to fall during the early morning hours and continued through the late evening hours.  The snow was heavy at times in some areas and the snow to water ratio was quite large with the driest snow reported to be 40 to 1.  A foot of snow fell across the northwest suburbs of Chicago with a large area receiving six inches or more.  Snowfall totals included 12.1 inches in St. Charles; 12.0 inches in Elburn; 12.0 inches in North Aurora; 12.0 inches 1 mile north of Carol Stream; 11.9 inches 7 miles north northwest of St. Charles; 11.1 inches in Batavia; 10.6 inches in Streamwood; 10.3 inches in Elgin; 10.0 inches in Woodstock; 9.4 inches 4 miles north northwest of Rockford; 9.2 inches 3 miles southwest of Barrington; 8.9 inches in Mundelein; 7.5 inches in Island Lake; 6.7 inches in Downers Grove; 6.2 inches in Roscoe; 6.1 inches in Rockford and 6.0 inches at Chicago O'Hare Airport.

Cold northwest winds off of Lake Michigan generated locally heavy lake effect snow in parts of Northwest Lower Michigan.  Mancelona and Twin Lakes picked up from 6 to 12 inches of snow on the 15th and early on the 16th.

Six to twelve inches of snow fell south of the I-96 corridor over south and southwest Michigan on the ninth and tenth.  The snow began during the morning of the ninth and continued through the early evening hours.  The mainly light snow combined with fog to produce visibilities between one quarter and one half of a mile along the I-94 corridor. ||Many locations saw a break in the falling snow during the late evening hours of the ninth, before a second period of heavier snow began during the early morning hours of the tenth.  Snow fell throughout the day on the tenth before tapering to flurries in the evening. ||The snowfall was associated with an area of low pressure initially over Nebraska during the morning of the ninth that moved east to southwest Indiana by the morning of the tenth.  The low continued to move east reaching the southern New England coast on the morning of the eleventh.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Six to ten inches of snow fell.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure moving northeast toward the Ohio valley produced a mix of snow and freezing rain across the region. Ice accumulations of one quarter inch or more fell across Garrett county Maryland, and parts of western Pennsylvania along and north of Interstate 80.

A strong storm system brought heavy snow to portions of western Pennsylvania and eastern Ohio with snow accumulations of 7 to 10 inches by late afternoon on January 10th. Mixed rain and snow fell across portions of southwest Pennsylvania, southeast Ohio, northern West Virginia and Garrett county Maryland with light snow accumulations.

Heavy lake effect snow occurred from the morning of the 16th to the early evening hours. Snowfall accumulations ranged around 1 foot.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy lake effect snow occurred from the morning of the 16th to the early evening hours. Snowfall accumulations ranged around 1 foot.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Heavy lake effect snow occurred from the afternoon of the 28th to the morning hours of the 29th. Snowfall accumulations ranged from 6 to 10 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An average of 5 to 8 inches of snow fell across northern portions of the county. Lakeport measured 7.4 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level storm system moved its way out of the southern Great Basin and into the Southern Plains during the afternoon hours of December 23rd.  Strong southerly flow was found ahead of this storm system with dewpoint temperatures in the lower to middle 60s noted northward to the Interstate 20 corridor of northeast Texas and northern Louisiana.  Impressive deep layer shear was noted in the warm sector across the region which was conducive for discrete storm cells during the afternoon and evening across northeast Texas.  These storms spawned tornadoes and produced large hail across portions of northeast Texas.  The storm system moved eastward during the predawn hours of December 24th with again, numerous storms producing tornadoes across southern Arkansas and northern Louisiana.  In addition to all the storm damage...these storms were prolific rain makers with numerous reports of flash flooding across the region as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous trees were downed, with trees damaging 3 homes on the northwest shore of Lake Darbonne. Several tin sheds were blown into the woods/lake, and a wooden shop was moved off of its foundation. Shingles were removed off of one home. The heaviest concentration of damage was found on Walnut Tree Road north of Highway 2. Per the local media/eye-witness reports, strong post-frontal gradient winds downed a couple of damaged trees along the tornados path, destroying a metal shed.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong post-frontal gradient winds developed on December 9th, strongest during the late morning and afternoon as a deep area of low pressure tracked into northern Lower Michigan. Widespread wind gusts between 45 and 60 mph were common across much of northern Indiana.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Very windy conditions were seen across the area on December 9th as a deep area of low pressure tracked into Michigan.  Wind gusts between 45 and 60 mph were common during the late morning and afternoon hours.  There were reports of power lines and trees down across the region due to the strong winds, which resulted in isolated power outages.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Arctic air following another cold front produced lake effect snows off Lake Ontario during Saturday evening 24th. A southwest flow set up intense bands across Jefferson County which dropped close to a foot of snow by Sunday morning in the Watertown area. The bands settled south into southern Jefferson and northern Lewis counties for much of Sunday, with rates of 2-3 inches per hour from Adams to Barnes Corners and Hooker. A weak upper disturbance disrupted the bands Sunday night but they still dropped several inches down into the Oswego area overnight into Monday morning. The activity rejuvenated for awhile Monday and lifted north into Jefferson County before weakening Monday night. Reported snowfall totals included: 38 inches at Barnes Corners; 27 inches at Hooker, 24 inches at Adams, 12 to 16 inches in Watertown; and 11 inches in Oswego.

Low pressure moved out of the southern Plains northeast across the Tennessee Valley reaching the southern New England Coast on the 28th.  The low brought an eight to twelve inch blanket of snow to the entire region by the evening of the 28th. Innumerable automobile accidents were reported throughout the region as the roads became hard to navigate in the heavy snow and reduced visibilities. Many schools cancelled classes across the region.

Low temperatures ranged from zero to 5 below zero on the morning of January 24th and January 25th.  A 74 year old man died in Chicago due to cold exposure.  In Johnsburg in McHenry County, a 17 year old male died from hypothermia after walking away from his car which had got stuck in a snow drift early in the morning of January 24th.

A squall line traveling along a cold front moved through the area late in the evening of January 19th into the early morning hours of January 20th. This fast moving line produced wind gusts of 45 to 55 mph and one tornadic storm that also produced large hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Golf ball size hail was reported in Lake Panasoffkee.

CZ_NAME: SAN BERNARDINO AND RIVERSIDE COUNTY VALLEYS - THE INLAND EMPIRE
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong, persistent 594 dm upper-level ridge over the West coast, combined with a 1045 mb surface high in the Great Basin and 30 to 40 kt 850 mb winds over Southern California led to strong Santa Ana winds on January 9th through the 13th. Wind gusts of up to 83 MPH were observed. The winds downed trees and power lines, overturned semi-trucks, and damaged roofs. ||Temperatures were well above normal during this period, with several days of record high maximum and minimum temperatures. On January 13th, the Santa Ana Fire Station recorded a minimum temperature of 73 degrees, the highest minimum temperature ever recorded for that station in the month of January, as well as the entire Winter season.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A peak gust of 60 MPH was measured at Palm Avenue Elementary school in San Bernardino at 1339 PST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper-level ridge of high pressure just off the West Coast and high surface pressure over the Great Basin brought locally strong, gusty offshore winds to the mountains and valleys of Southern California. The winds did cause some local damage to roofs, trees, power lines, freeway signs, and trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 59 MPH wind gust was measured by the Fremont Canyon RAWS at 0330 PST.

Other damage in the area included a large metal freeway sign that was blown down onto Westbound Highway 210 near State Street in San Bernardino around 0900 PST. Around 1250 PST there were reports of power lines down in Ontario.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure developed off the Mid-Atlantic coast causing precipitation to develop over Virginia. There was enough cold air in place for precipitation to start off as a wintry mix of sleet and freezing rain. Precipitation changed to all rain by late in the morning as warmer air was drawn into the system.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ice accumulation from freezing rain was less than one tenth of an inch across the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Light precipitation developed ahead of an approaching warm front during Sunday evening, January 4th. With surface temperatures initially remaining below freezing, the precipitation began as a mix of sleet and freezing rain across the southern Adirondacks, western and central Mohawk Valley, and across the Lake George and Saratoga region. The precipitation then changed to plain rain and drizzle by early Monday morning on January 5th.||Ice accretion from freezing rain was generally one tenth of an inch or less. However, this light icing led to locally hazardous travel conditions late Sunday evening into early Monday morning.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate to strong northwest winds and very cold air combined to lower wind chills to 35 to 45 below zero at times. The coldest winds chills were during the morning of January 14th with strong winds, and the night of January 14th to daybreak of January 15th when temperatures were falling and winds were slowly decreasing. The actual temperature dropped to 31 below zero at Brookings on the morning of January 15th after the wind had subsided.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Very cold temperatures and moderate northwest winds combined to lower wind chill readings to 35 to 45 below zero at times from the morning of January 14th to early morning on January 15th. The strongest winds were at the start of the event. While winds decreased slowly on the night of January 14th, actual temperatures also dropped, reaching 20 below to 30 below zero near daybreak on January 15th, about which time winds became light and no longer a major factor.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate northwest winds and very cold air combined to lower wind chills to 35 to 45 below zero at times. While winds were slowly decreasing during this time period, temperatures were steadily dropping.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong low pressure moved over the Cape Cod Canal and coupled with a strong low level jet to produce a burst of heavy snow over much of Southern New England during the morning commute.
Strong low pressure moved over the Cape Cod Canal and coupled with a strong low level jet to produce a burst of heavy snow over much of Southern New England during the morning commute.

A significant severe weather episode impacted portions of southeastern New Mexico and the west Texas Permian Basin during the late afternoon and evening hours of the 11th. The storms developed east of a dryline and south of a warm front which advanced northward over the South Plains region. Thus cool stable air north of the frontal boundary precluded widespread severe weather over much of the South Plains, but a few thunderstorms, including a supercell storm, impacted the far southwestern portions of the South Plains region. While Doppler radar indicated the potential for a tornado with this storm over southern Yoakum County, no tornado was confirmed. Large hail and damaging thunderstorm winds, however, were observed.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Penny size hail reportedly covered the ground at a cotton gin west of Denver City along Texas Highway 83 by 15:40 CST. At 15:45 CST, quarter size hail was reported west-northwest of Denver City.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong but slow-moving low pressure system began its approach to Arkansas on the 23rd. Ahead of this low, unseasonably large amounts of moisture were drawn northward from the Gulf of Mexico. The approach of the low set off heavy rain and thunderstorms on the 23rd and 24th. Rainfall amounts of 3 to 6 inches were common for the two-day period. In a broad swath from southwest Arkansas through the central part of the state into northeast Arkansas, many places picked up 7 to 10 inches of rain. Flash flooding resulted initially, followed by areal flooding and river flooding. After the low passed by, colder air spilled into Arkansas. Light snow fell across parts of northern and western Arkansas from late on the 24th into the early morning hours of Christmas Day. Most snowfall amounts were in the 1/2 to 1 inch range, with spotty totals up to 2 inches. Though the amounts were rather small, hazardous driving conditions resulted.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain on the 23rd led to a landslide on Petit Jean Mountain early on the morning of the 24th. Mud flowed down onto Arkansas Highway 154. About 200 truckloads of mud, topsoil, and fallen trees had to be removed.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered severe thunderstorms in advance of a cold front produced large hail, damaging winds, and one tornado across portions of central and eastern Virginia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: EF0 tornado tracked along a nearly 8 mile track from near Raynor east-northeast to approximately one mile northwest of Smithfield. Damage along the path was intermittent and primarily characterized by trees topped out or blown down. There was also minor damage to homes and sheds in the form of shingles off roofs and siding peeled away. In addition, a few metal roofs were damaged.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered severe thunderstorms in advance of a cold front produced large hail, damaging winds, and one tornado across portions of central and eastern Virginia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Scattered trees were downed and there was damage to sheds south of Moonlight. Damage was caused by straight line winds.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Funnel cloud was reported just to the northwest of the Middle Peninsula airport.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deepening area of low pressure tracked from Tennessee northeast into western Pennsylvania late January 27th into January 28th. A swath of heavy snow fell to the northwest of this track, which affected portions of northwest Ohio. Total snow accumulations ranged between 5 and 9 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow, moderate to heavy at times, developed during the afternoon hours on January 27th and continued through the morning hours of January 28th. Total snow accumulations of 6 to 9 inches were reported across the county, with a report of 7.8 inches at Van Wert. There were reports of slide-offs and accidents across the region. Most schools were closed on January 28th due to the heavy snowfall.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trained spotters in the Twin Falls area reported six inches of snow with blowing and drifting.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A complex of thunderstorms moved southeast out of Northwest Kansas into Central and South Central Kansas during the early morning hours of May 8th, 2009.  This complex of thunmderstorms would intensify over South Central Kansas during the morning and become a prolific damaging wind producer.  This swath of damaging winds, (measured at 80 to 100 mph) cut a path of destruction from just north of Wichita, Kansas to Parsons, Kansas. This storm system would continue on into Southern Missouri and eventually Southern Illinois producing widespread damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Estimated by local law enforcement.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Arctic air plunged southeast across eastern Nebraska and southwest Iowa on January 14th and 15th.  Temperatures fell into the single digits above and below zero during the morning hours of 1/14, recovered a little in the afternoon and then fell to 5 below to 20 below, or a bit colder, by the morning of the 15th.  Northwest winds of 20 to 30 mph with higher gusts were observed into the afternoon of the 14th before subsiding in the afternoon and evening.  This produced wind chill values of 20 below to 30 below zero over much of the region.  By around midnight on the 15th most reporting sites observed winds dropped below 10 mph and remained that way through the morning of the 15th.  However, several locations, mainly south through southeast of Omaha, recorded wind speeds of 10 to 15 mph and wind chill values colder than 20 below through around 5am CST on the 15th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: As temperatures fell into the single digits across the county during the morning of 1/14 and then below zero by the evening of the 14th,  northwest winds of 20 to 30 mph in the morning and early afternoon and 10 to 20 mph from late afternoon into late evening, produced wind chill values of 20 below to 25 below zero.  Winds dropped mostly below 10 mph by the early morning hours of 1/15 but air temperatures fell to 10 below to 20 below zero.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A disturbance in the northern branch of the jet stream was able to phase with low pressure in the southern branch of the jet stream over the Southeast Coast on the night of the 18th. These two systems combined to develop a strong area of low pressure that slowly track up the Mid-Atlantic Coast during the 19th. The low was able to tap into moisture from the Gulf of Mexico and the Atlantic Ocean causing copious amounts of precipitation to develop. High pressure to the north kept plenty of cold air in place causing the precipitation to fall in the form of snow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall was estimated between 20 and 25 inches across the county.

During January, drought conditions intensified across South Texas. By the end of January, extreme drought conditions existed across Bee, Goliad, Victoria, Refugio, and Aransas counties. Severe drought conditions existed across Calhoun, San Patricio, Live Oak, northern McMullen, and northern La Salle counties. Moderate drought existed across Nueces, Kleberg, Jim Wells, Duval, southern McMullen, southern La Salle, and northern Webb counties. Abnormally dry conditions were observed southern Webb county. (per the U.S. Drought Monitor: http://www.drought.unl.edu/dm/monitor.html) ||The primary impacts of the drought during January were agricultural and fire related. Forage was sparse and the supplemental feeding of hay to livestock continued.  Farmers were delaying the planting of some winter crops.  Moisture was badly needed for the upcoming planting of the Sorghum crop.  Periods of elevated to high fire danger occurred through the month with sporadic wildfires.  In addition, reservoir levels continued a gradual fall.  Choke Canyon Reservoir was near 80% capacity and Lake Corpus Christi near 64% capacity by the end of the month. Rivers and creeks in the rainfall deficit areas continued a slow fall, and were below baseflow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: During January, drought conditions intensified across South Texas. By the end of January, extreme drought conditions existed across Bee, Goliad, Victoria, Refugio, and Aransas counties. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Severe thunderstorms developed across portions of northwest and north Central Louisiana along and ahead of a cold front during the afternoon of January 3rd, 2009.  These thunderstorms developed in a marginally unstable airmass with lift produced along the frontal boundary itself. Hail was the man outcome with these severe thunderstorms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail was reported at the Hardtner Medical Center in Urbania, Louisiana.

Mixed rain and snow fell across portions of southwest Pennsylvania, southeast Ohio, northern West Virginia and Garrett county Maryland with light snow accumulations.

Heavy rainfall drenched the region to begin the new year.  The heavy rainfall combined with snowmelt runoff caused flooding along multiple rivers in northwest Oregon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain caused a landslide that closed the Columbia River historic highway between the Vista House and Multnomah Falls.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain caused the Necanicum River to overflow its banks and flood highway 101 near mile post 23. Approximately 10 inches of water was flowing across the highway.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain caused small creeks to overflow their banks resulting in one foot of water covering highway 101 near Gearhart.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful storm system brought very heavy rainfall to the region in early January. The heavy rainfall combined with snowmelt runoff caused flooding along multiple rivers in southwest Washington.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain caused several small stream  and creek flooding.  Damage included structures in the Plympton Creek and Fishhawk Falls area.  A landslide near Hamlet also closed highway 202.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large and relatively slow moving storm brought a prolonged winter storm and even, for a time, blizzard conditions to eastern Nebraska and western Iowa from late on Dec. 7th through the early morning hours of Dec. 9th.  The storm was driven by an upper level disturbance that tracked from the west coast across the Rockies and deepened over the Mississippi River valley.  The heaviest snow fell in advance of when the stronger winds arrived, mainly during the morning and afternoon of Dec. 8th.  However, as the winds increased to 30 to 50 mph during the night of the 8th and early on the 9th, visibilities frequently dropped to near zero, especially in open areas.  Considerable drifting snow also occurred, in many cases closing roads back shut almost as fast as they could be opened.  This prompted many counties to pull snow plows off the roads for a while during the night of the 8th and 9th.  Many schools were closed for 3 days because of the storm, due the forecast of heavy snow to begin on the 7th, poor visibilities and roads drifted shut on the 8th and still some closed roads and bitter cold wind chills which followed the storm on the 9th.||Total snowfall from the storm was 6 to 15 inches over most of eastern Nebraska and western Iowa.  Higher amounts in eastern Nebraska included 15 inches in Union, 14 inches in Columbus, around 12 inches at the NWS in Valley, at Tekamah, Uehling, Steele City and Weeping Water.  In western Iowa heavier amounts included 12 inches in Clarinda and Hastings and around 11 inches in Harlan, Red Oak and Little Sioux.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 8 to 12 inches fell across much of the county from this storm with 10.4 inches measured near Little Sioux and 8.5 inches measured at Logan.  The snow began during the late evening of 12/7 and continued into the early morning hours of 12/9.  Winds were not that strong when the snow started, but north winds increased during the afternoon of 12/8 and especially that evening into the next morning.  Frequent wind gusts of 40 mph or so were observed based on observations from surrounding sites.  The winds produced considerable blowing and drifting snow with blizzard conditions during the evening and early morning hours of the 8th and 9th, which closed many county roads.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Precipitation came in two waves.  The initial round of elevated convection was focused across portions of central and south central Missouri.   Rainfall amounts of one half to one and half inches fell with this initial rainfall.  A second more intense band of rainfall moved across the region Thursday evening as a cold front swept into the Ozarks.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A total rainfall amount of 3.20 inches was measured.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A low pressure system developed over the lower Mississippi Valley during Tuesday January 27th. The low then strengthened, and tracked northeast from the lower Ohio Valley Wednesday morning on January 28th, into Pennsylvania during Wednesday afternoon, and into northern New England by Thursday morning January 29th. ||This storm spread a significant wintry mix of precipitation across western Massachusetts, beginning early Wednesday morning, and ending early Thursday morning.||Snow and sleet amounts ranged from 4 to 8 inches, with the greatest amounts occurring across higher elevations within northern Berkshire County. In addition, some freezing rain occurred, with ice accretion of generally under one tenth of an inch occurring.||The wintry mix led to either closures, or delayed openings of numerous schools and businesses both Wednesday and Thursday mornings. In addition, treacherous travel conditions existed during this period.

Low pressure developed off the Mid-Atlantic coast causing precipitation to develop over Virginia. There was enough cold air in place for precipitation to start off as a wintry mix of sleet and freezing rain. Precipitation changed to all rain by late in the morning as warmer air was drawn into the system.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Very cold temperatures and moderate northwest winds combined to lower wind chill readings to 35 to 45 below zero at times from the morning of January 14th to early morning on January 15th. The strongest winds were at the start of the event. While winds decreased slowly on the night of January 14th, actual temperatures also dropped, reaching 20 below to 30 below zero near daybreak on January 15th, about which time winds became light and no longer a major factor.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate to strong northwest winds and very cold air combined to lower wind chills to 35 to 45 below zero at times. The coldest winds chills were during the morning of January 14th with strong winds, and the night of January 14th to daybreak of January 15th when temperatures were falling and winds were slowly decreasing. The actual temperature dropped to 26 below zero at Marshall on the morning of January 15th after the wind had subsided.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Snow accumulated 2 to 4 inches in southwest Minnesota, away from the far southwest corner of the state, during the evening of January 8th and the predawn hours of January 9th. The snow was accompanied by areas of freezing drizzle.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 2 to 4 inches was accompanied by periods of freezing drizzle. A report of 4 inches of snow was received from Ivanhoe.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Arctic air plunged southeast across eastern Nebraska and southwest Iowa on January 14th and 15th.  Temperatures in southwest Iowa fell into the single digits during the morning hours of 1/14, recovered a little in the afternoon and then fell to 5 below to 20 below, or a bit colder, by the morning of the 15th.  Northwest winds of 20 to 30 mph with higher gusts were observed into the afternoon of the 14th before subsiding in the afternoon and evening.  This produced wind chill values of 20 below to 30 below zero over much of the region.  Winds continued to decrease during the early morning hours of 1/15, and by 5am CST most recorded speeds were less than 10 mph.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: As temperatures fell below zero by the evening of the 14th, northwest winds of 10 to 20 mph produced wind chill values of 20 below to 25 below zero.  Winds dropped mostly below 10 mph during the early morning hours of 1/15 but air temperatures by that time were around 10 below zero.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong but slow-moving low pressure system began its approach to Arkansas on the 23rd. Ahead of this low, unseasonably large amounts of moisture were drawn northward from the Gulf of Mexico. The approach of the low set off heavy rain and thunderstorms on the 23rd and 24th. Rainfall amounts of 3 to 6 inches were common for the two-day period. In a broad swath from southwest Arkansas through the central part of the state into northeast Arkansas, many places picked up 7 to 10 inches of rain. Flash flooding resulted initially, followed by areal flooding and river flooding. After the low passed by, colder air spilled into Arkansas. Light snow fell across parts of northern and western Arkansas from late on the 24th into the early morning hours of Christmas Day. Most snowfall amounts were in the 1/2 to 1 inch range, with spotty totals up to 2 inches. Though the amounts were rather small, hazardous driving conditions resulted.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A small levee broke, allowing water to spill out of a private lake.  Lawson Road was flooded. The water cut through Ranch Road, cutting off access to three houses.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A clipper low pressure system strengthened as it approached Michigan from the northwest.  This storm produced two areas of heavy snow.  The main system snow fell in a wide band from Charlevoix and Bellaire, southeastward through Grayling and on to Standish and Tawas City.  Accumulations of 8 to 12 inches were common within this band.  A more localized band of lake enhanced snow affect part of the Lake Michigan coastline, near Manistee and Arcadia, as well as near Curtis and Gould City.  Snowfall amounts were around 10 inches, with locally near 15 inches in Curtis.

A deepening area of low pressure tracked from Tennessee northeast into western Pennsylvania late January 27th into January 28th. A swath of heavy snow fell to the northwest of this track, which affected portions of northwest Ohio. Total snow accumulations ranged between 5 and 9 inches.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow, moderate to heavy at times, developed during the afternoon hours on January 27th and continued through the morning hours of January 28th. Total snow accumulations of 6 to 9 inches were reported across the county, with a report of 6 inches at Columbus Grove. There were reports of slide-offs and accidents across the region. Most schools were closed on January 28th due to the heavy snowfall.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm front lifted through southeastern South Carolina during the afternoon which allowed warm and moist conditions to occur ahead of an approaching cold front. A strong upper level jet combined with a surface cold front aided in severe thunderstorm development overnight as the upper level forcing shifted towards the Atlantic Ocean.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter reported penny size hail on Owen Drive in West Ashley, South Carolina.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Intense low pressure moving through the Gulf of Maine coincided with the highest astronomical tides of the month to produce coastal flooding in areas along the Maine coast. Strong southeast winds produced a storm surge of 1.44 ft and near shore waves of 7 to 10 ft, bringing the Portland tide gage to 12.54 ft. Ocean water flooded Route 1 in Lincolnville and Frankfort. Water reached cars parked near Commercial Street in Portland. In Kennebunk powerful waves crashed in and around homes. At Popham Beach, trees were sucked into the ocean and severe beach erosion occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Intense low pressure and astronomically high tides produced coastal flooding in the Lincolville/Frankfort area on Route 1.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A complex of thunderstorms moved southeast out of Northwest Kansas into Central and South Central Kansas during the early morning hours of May 8th, 2009.  This complex of thunmderstorms would intensify over South Central Kansas during the morning and become a prolific damaging wind producer.  This swath of damaging winds, (measured at 80 to 100 mph) cut a path of destruction from just north of Wichita, Kansas to Parsons, Kansas. This storm system would continue on into Southern Missouri and eventually Southern Illinois producing widespread damage.

A low pressure system passing to the north, dragged a cold front across Northern Michigan on the 29th.  Lake effect snow occurred, both with the southwest winds ahead of the front, and with the northwest winds behind it.  This brought locally heavy snow to Honor/Lake Ann and nearby communities, Mancelona, and the East Jordan/Ironton/Charlevoix area.  Local snowfall amounts of 6 to 9 inches fell during the day and night of the 29th.
