EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow moving winter storm moved across northern Illinois on December 26th.  Snow began to fall during the early morning hours and continued through the late evening hours.  The snow was heavy at times in some areas and the snow to water ratio was quite large with the driest snow reported to be 40 to 1.  A foot of snow fell across the northwest suburbs of Chicago with a large area receiving six inches or more.  Snowfall totals included 12.1 inches in St. Charles; 12.0 inches in Elburn; 12.0 inches in North Aurora; 12.0 inches 1 mile north of Carol Stream; 11.9 inches 7 miles north northwest of St. Charles; 11.1 inches in Batavia; 10.6 inches in Streamwood; 10.3 inches in Elgin; 10.0 inches in Woodstock; 9.4 inches 4 miles north northwest of Rockford; 9.2 inches 3 miles southwest of Barrington; 8.9 inches in Mundelein; 7.5 inches in Island Lake; 6.7 inches in Downers Grove; 6.2 inches in Roscoe; 6.1 inches in Rockford and 6.0 inches at Chicago O'Hare Airport.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Severe thunderstorms developed across portions of northwest and north Central Louisiana along and ahead of a cold front during the afternoon of January 3rd, 2009.  These thunderstorms developed in a marginally unstable airmass with lift produced along the frontal boundary itself. Hail was the man outcome with these severe thunderstorms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A funnel cloud was sited along the Grant/La Salle parish line between Georgetown and Tullos, Louisiana.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level low pressure system moved from the Southern Rockies across the Southern Plains on the 24th. Widespread precipitation developed as this system approached. Arctic air gradually spread into the region behind a strong cold front changing the rain to sleet and then quickly to snow over much of northwestern Arkansas by the afternoon hours. Periods of snow, some falling heavily at times through the afternoon and evening hours, resulted in four to six inches of snow over far northwestern Arkansas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Four to six inches of snow fell across the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Arctic air following a frontal passage set off lake effect snows early on Friday 16th. Initially, the activity off Lake Erie focused on the Chautauqua ridge on a west wind, with several inches Friday morning, but winds backed slightly during the midday and afternoon, and a decent lake plume lifted well to the north into Buffalo's South Towns and even up into central Erie county. Lake Erie had a large amount of ice but the snow apparently formed off some open water north of Long Point. Over 6 fell in this narrow strip with plenty of blowing snow and near whiteout conditions just to the south of the city which snarled the evening rush hour. The activity weakened during the evening and lifted north across the Buffalo metro area and dropped a quick 1-3 inches early Saturday before dissipating. Reported snowfalls included: 12 inches at Perrsyburg; 10 inches at Elma, 9 inches in East Aurora; and 7 inches at Alden.|Off Lake Ontario, the activity was stronger as ice was not a factor. Bands developed early Friday over northern Cayuga and southwest Oswego counties and gradually meandered northward during Friday and Friday night, with several intense bands setting up across the area from Pulaski to Watertown. This continued through much of Saturday before weakening during the afternoon in the Watertown area, but not before nearly two feet fell. Snowfalls totals included: 29 inches at Pulaski; 21 inches at Watertown; and 12 inches in Carthage and Oswego.

Light precipitation developed ahead of an approaching warm front during Sunday evening, January 4th. With surface temperatures initially remaining below freezing, the precipitation began as a mix of sleet and freezing rain across the southern Adirondacks, western and central Mohawk Valley, and across the Lake George and Saratoga region. The precipitation then changed to plain rain and drizzle by early Monday morning on January 5th.||Ice accretion from freezing rain was generally one tenth of an inch or less. Strong north to northwest winds, gusting to over 50 mph, combined with existing loose snow cover and 1 to 3 inches of new snow to produce blizzard conditions with widespread visibilities near zero over parts of northwest Iowa during the day and early evening of January 12th. The very low visibilities were widespread where the greatest loose snow cover was located, and more localized in other areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: North to northwest winds gusting to around 50 mph, existing snow cover, and 1 to 3 inches of new snow produced areas of blowing snow with local visibilities below a quarter mile.

Arctic air plunged southeast across eastern Nebraska and southwest Iowa on January 14th and 15th.  Temperatures in southwest Iowa fell into the single digits during the morning hours of 1/14, recovered a little in the afternoon and then fell to 5 below to 20 below, or a bit colder, by the morning of the 15th.  Northwest winds of 20 to 30 mph with higher gusts were observed into the afternoon of the 14th before subsiding in the afternoon and evening.  This produced wind chill values of 20 below to 30 below zero over much of the region.  Winds continued to decrease during the early morning hours of 1/15, and by 5am CST most recorded speeds were less than 10 mph.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: As temperatures fell below zero by the evening of the 14th, northwest winds of 10 to 15 mph produced wind chill values of 20 below to 25 below zero.  Winds dropped mostly below 10 mph during the early morning hours of 1/15 but air temperatures by that time were around 10 below zero.

Local snowfall amounts of 6 to 9 inches fell during the day and night of the 29th.

A large and relatively slow moving storm brought a prolonged winter storm and even, for a time, blizzard conditions to eastern Nebraska and western Iowa from late on Dec. 7th through the early morning hours of Dec. 9th.  The storm was driven by an upper level disturbance that tracked from the west coast across the Rockies and deepened over the Mississippi River valley.  The heaviest snow fell in advance of when the stronger winds arrived, mainly during the morning and afternoon of Dec. 8th.  However, as the winds increased to 30 to 50 mph during the night of the 8th and early on the 9th, visibilities frequently dropped to near zero, especially in open areas.  Considerable drifting snow also occurred, in many cases closing roads back shut almost as fast as they could be opened.  This prompted many counties to pull snow plows off the roads for a while during the night of the 8th and 9th.  Many schools were closed for 3 days because of the storm, due the forecast of heavy snow to begin on the 7th, poor visibilities and roads drifted shut on the 8th and still some closed roads and bitter cold wind chills which followed the storm on the 9th.||Total snowfall from the storm was 6 to 15 inches over most of eastern Nebraska and western Iowa.  Higher amounts in eastern Nebraska included 15 inches in Union, 14 inches in Columbus, around 12 inches at the NWS in Valley, at Tekamah, Uehling, Steele City and Weeping Water.  In western Iowa heavier amounts included 12 inches in Clarinda and Hastings and around 11 inches in Harlan, Red Oak and Little Sioux.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 8 to 12 inches fell across much of the county from this storm with 12 inches measured in Clarinda and 10 inches measured in Shenandoah. The snow began during the late evening of 12/7 and continued into the early morning hours of 12/9.  Winds were not that strong when the snow started, but north winds increased during the afternoon of 12/8 and especially that evening into the next morning.  Frequent wind gusts of 40 mph or so were observed with a peak gust of 44 mph measured at Shenandoah and 40 mph at Clarinda.  The winds produced considerable blowing and drifting snow with visibilities frequently below 1/4 mile during the early morning hours of the 9th.  The blowing and drifting snow also closed many county roads.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very strong low level jet developed over eastern North Carolina ahead of a cold front. Bands of low topped convective showers helped mix these strong winds down to the ground producing numerous reports of damaging winds. One band of showers crossed during the late morning hours producing damage over mainly the northern parts of eastern North Carolina. Another band of showers crossed in the evening with damaging gusts over the entire region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees blown down on power lines with five thousand homes without electricity.

During January, drought conditions intensified across South Texas. By the end of January, extreme drought conditions existed across Bee, Goliad, Victoria, Refugio, and Aransas counties. Severe drought conditions existed across Calhoun, San Patricio, Live Oak, northern McMullen, and northern La Salle counties. Moderate drought existed across Nueces, Kleberg, Jim Wells, Duval, southern McMullen, southern La Salle, and northern Webb counties. Abnormally dry conditions were observed southern Webb county. (per the U.S. Drought Monitor: http://www.drought.unl.edu/dm/monitor.html) ||The primary impacts of the drought during January were agricultural and fire related. Forage was sparse and the supplemental feeding of hay to livestock continued.  Farmers were delaying the planting of some winter crops.  Moisture was badly needed for the upcoming planting of the Sorghum crop.  Periods of elevated to high fire danger occurred through the month with sporadic wildfires.  In addition, reservoir levels continued a gradual fall.  Choke Canyon Reservoir was near 80% capacity and Lake Corpus Christi near 64% capacity by the end of the month. Rivers and creeks in the rainfall deficit areas continued a slow fall, and were below baseflow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A complex of thunderstorms moved southeast out of Northwest Kansas into Central and South Central Kansas during the early morning hours of May 8th, 2009.  This complex of thunmderstorms would intensify over South Central Kansas during the morning and become a prolific damaging wind producer.  This swath of damaging winds, (measured at 80 to 100 mph) cut a path of destruction from just north of Wichita, Kansas to Parsons, Kansas. This storm system would continue on into Southern Missouri and eventually Southern Illinois producing widespread damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Water was over 14th avenue in multiple places.  County roads also flooded around Inman.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level storm system moved its way out of the southern Great Basin and into the Southern Plains during the afternoon hours of December 23rd.  Strong southerly flow was found ahead of this storm system with dewpoint temperatures in the lower to middle 60s noted northward to the Interstate 20 corridor of northeast Texas and northern Louisiana.  Impressive deep layer shear was noted in the warm sector across the region which was conducive for discrete storm cells during the afternoon and evening across northeast Texas.  These storms spawned tornadoes and produced large hail across portions of northeast Texas.  The storm system moved eastward during the predawn hours of December 24th with again, numerous storms producing tornadoes across southern Arkansas and northern Louisiana.  In addition to all the storm damage...these storms were prolific rain makers with numerous reports of flash flooding across the region as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A few trees large trees were downed along with large snapped limbs with the initial touchdown near SR 784 and Esperanza Road.  The storm then moved in a north northeast direction snapping tree tops on PR 207 before lifting just southeast of Martin, Louisiana. Maximum winds were estimated at 70-75 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Arctic air following a frontal passage set off lake effect snows early on Friday 16th. Initially, the activity off Lake Erie focused on the Chautauqua ridge on a west wind, with several inches Friday morning, but winds backed slightly during the midday and afternoon, and a decent lake plume lifted well to the north into Buffalo's South Towns and even up into central Erie county. Lake Erie had a large amount of ice but the snow apparently formed off some open water north of Long Point. Over 6 fell in this narrow strip with plenty of blowing snow and near whiteout conditions just to the south of the city which snarled the evening rush hour. The activity weakened during the evening and lifted north across the Buffalo metro area and dropped a quick 1-3 inches early Saturday before dissipating. Reported snowfalls included: 12 inches at Perrsyburg; 10 inches at Elma, 9 inches in East Aurora; and 7 inches at Alden.|Off Lake Ontario, the activity was stronger as ice was not a factor. Bands developed early Friday over northern Cayuga and southwest Oswego counties and gradually meandered northward during Friday and Friday night, with several intense bands setting up across the area from Pulaski to Watertown. This continued through much of Saturday before weakening during the afternoon in the Watertown area, but not before nearly two feet fell. Snowfalls totals included: 29 inches at Pulaski; 21 inches at Watertown; and 12 inches in Carthage and Oswego.

Many schools cancelled classes across the region.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong north to northwest winds, gusting to over 50 mph, combined with existing loose snow cover and 1 to 3 inches of new snow to produce blizzard conditions with widespread visibilities near zero over parts of northwest Iowa during the day and early evening of January 12th. The very low visibilities were widespread where the greatest loose snow cover was located, and more localized in other areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: North to northwest winds gusting to around 50 mph, existing snow cover, and 1 to 3 inches of new snow produced areas of blowing snow with local visibilities below a quarter mile.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong north to northwest winds, gusting to over 50 mph, combined with existing loose snow cover and 1 to 2 inches of new snow to produce blizzard conditions with widespread visibilities near zero over extreme northeast Nebraska during the day and early evening of January 12th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: North to northwest winds sustained at 30 to 40 mph with gusts around 50 mph combined with several inches of loose snow cover, along with 1 to 3 inches of new snow, to produce widespread visibilities of a quarter mile or less in blowing snow. The low visibilities and drifting snow made travel impossible in many areas, and forced schools and businesses to close.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Very cold temperatures and moderate northwest winds combined to lower wind chill readings to 35 to 45 below zero at times from the morning of January 14th to early morning on January 15th. The strongest winds were at the start of the event. While winds decreased slowly on the night of January 14th, actual temperatures also dropped, reaching 20 below to 30 below zero near daybreak on January 15th, about which time winds became light and no longer a major factor.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Moderate northwest winds and very cold air combined to lower wind chills to 35 to 45 below zero at times. While winds were slowly decreasing during this time period, temperatures were steadily dropping.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong low pressure moved over the Cape Cod Canal and coupled with a strong low level jet to produce a burst of heavy snow over much of Southern New England during the morning commute.

A strong but slow-moving low pressure system began its approach to Arkansas on the 23rd. Ahead of this low, unseasonably large amounts of moisture were drawn northward from the Gulf of Mexico. The approach of the low set off heavy rain and thunderstorms on the 23rd and 24th. Rainfall amounts of 3 to 6 inches were common for the two-day period. In a broad swath from southwest Arkansas through the central part of the state into northeast Arkansas, many places picked up 7 to 10 inches of rain. Flash flooding resulted initially, followed by areal flooding and river flooding. After the low passed by, colder air spilled into Arkansas. Light snow fell across parts of northern and western Arkansas from late on the 24th into the early morning hours of Christmas Day. Most snowfall amounts were in the 1/2 to 1 inch range, with spotty totals up to 2 inches. Though the amounts were rather small, hazardous driving conditions resulted.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Areas of generally light snow fell across portions of the Arkansas Ozarks and Ouachita Mountains of western Arkansas, causing area roads to become slick due to snow cover Christmas morning. Snowfall amounts of generally around one half to one inch were reported, with locally higher amounts of up to two inches of snowfall in the higher elevations.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow affected Henry county January 9th into January 10th, with a brief lull in the snow during the afternoon and early evening hours of January 9th. Snowfall totals generally ranged between 5 and 9 inches, with a report of 8 inches near Napoleon. There were a few reports of accidents and slide-offs across the region.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level storm system moved its way out of the southern Great Basin and into the Southern Plains during the afternoon hours of December 23rd.  Strong southerly flow was found ahead of this storm system with dewpoint temperatures in the lower to middle 60s noted northward to the Interstate 20 corridor of northeast Texas and northern Louisiana.  Impressive deep layer shear was noted in the warm sector across the region which was conducive for discrete storm cells during the afternoon and evening across northeast Texas.  These storms spawned tornadoes and produced large hail across portions of northeast Texas.  The storm system moved eastward during the predawn hours of December 24th with again, numerous storms producing tornadoes across southern Arkansas and northern Louisiana.  In addition to all the storm damage...these storms were prolific rain makers with numerous reports of flash flooding across the region as well.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous reports of roads underwater and closed across the parish.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A very strong low level jet developed over eastern North Carolina ahead of a cold front. Bands of low topped convective showers helped mix these strong winds down to the ground producing numerous reports of damaging winds. One band of showers crossed during the late morning hours producing damage over mainly the northern parts of eastern North Carolina. Another band of showers crossed in the evening with damaging gusts over the entire region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees blown down on power lines with five thousand homes without electricity.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Freezing rain mixed with sleet developed after midnight across the Middle Red River Valley of Northeast Texas...Southeast Oklahoma and Southwest Arkansas. Ice accumulations were mainly between one tenth and two|tenths of an inch with the primary accumulation areas being on area bridges and overpasses. The ice accumulations extended as far south as Tyler and Longview, Texas and as far north and east as McCurtain County, Oklahoma into Southwest Arkansas from Prescott and near Magnolia Arkansas towards portions of extreme northern Caddo and Bossier Parishes in Northwest Louisiana.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Freezing rain accumulation near one tenth of an inch resulted in most bridges and overpasses across the county becoming iced up.  There were a few vehicular accidents reported across the county.

A strong area of low pressure moved north across West Virginia to western Pennsylvania producing a heavy mix of precipitation. Snow accumulated 2 to 4 inches across northwest Pennsylvania on the night of the 27Th before changing to freezing rain the morning of the 28Th, then back to snow in the afternoon with another 1 to 2 inches. Ice accumulations in Pittsburgh and areas north were from a quarter to one half inch. For southeast Ohio, northern West Virgina, and Garrett county Maryland mixed precipitation changed to freezing rain during the evening of the 27Th with ice quickly accumulating to one half inch before changing to plain overnight. The rain changed back to snow during the afternoon of the 28Th with 1 to 2 inches of snow accumulating.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail was reported in the community of Georgetown, Louisiana.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Arctic air following a frontal passage set off lake effect snows early on Friday 16th. Initially, the activity off Lake Erie focused on the Chautauqua ridge on a west wind, with several inches Friday morning, but winds backed slightly during the midday and afternoon, and a decent lake plume lifted well to the north into Buffalo's South Towns and even up into central Erie county. Lake Erie had a large amount of ice but the snow apparently formed off some open water north of Long Point. Over 6 fell in this narrow strip with plenty of blowing snow and near whiteout conditions just to the south of the city which snarled the evening rush hour. The activity weakened during the evening and lifted north across the Buffalo metro area and dropped a quick 1-3 inches early Saturday before dissipating. Reported snowfalls included: 12 inches at Perrsyburg; 10 inches at Elma, 9 inches in East Aurora; and 7 inches at Alden.|Off Lake Ontario, the activity was stronger as ice was not a factor. Bands developed early Friday over northern Cayuga and southwest Oswego counties and gradually meandered northward during Friday and Friday night, with several intense bands setting up across the area from Pulaski to Watertown. This continued through much of Saturday before weakening during the afternoon in the Watertown area, but not before nearly two feet fell. Snowfalls totals included: 29 inches at Pulaski; 21 inches at Watertown; and 12 inches in Carthage and Oswego.

A large and relatively slow moving storm brought a prolonged winter storm and even, for a time, blizzard conditions to eastern Nebraska and western Iowa from late on Dec. 7th through the early morning hours of Dec. 9th.  The storm was driven by an upper level disturbance that tracked from the west coast across the Rockies and deepened over the Mississippi River valley.  The heaviest snow fell in advance of when the stronger winds arrived, mainly during the morning and afternoon of Dec. 8th.  However, as the winds increased to 30 to 50 mph during the night of the 8th and early on the 9th, visibilities frequently dropped to near zero, especially in open areas.  Considerable drifting snow also occurred, in many cases closing roads back shut almost as fast as they could be opened.  This prompted many counties to pull snow plows off the roads for a while during the night of the 8th and 9th.  Many schools were closed for 3 days because of the storm, due the forecast of heavy snow to begin on the 7th, poor visibilities and roads drifted shut on the 8th and still some closed roads and bitter cold wind chills which followed the storm on the 9th.||Total snowfall from the storm was 6 to 15 inches over most of eastern Nebraska and western Iowa.  Higher amounts in eastern Nebraska included 15 inches in Union, 14 inches in Columbus, around 12 inches at the NWS in Valley, at Tekamah, Uehling, Steele City and Weeping Water.  In western Iowa heavier amounts included 12 inches in Clarinda and Hastings and around 11 inches in Harlan, Red Oak and Little Sioux.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 8 to 12 inches fell across much of the county from this storm with 12 inches measured in Clarinda and 10 inches measured in Shenandoah. The snow began during the late evening of 12/7 and continued into the early morning hours of 12/9.  Winds were not that strong when the snow started, but north winds increased during the afternoon of 12/8 and especially that evening into the next morning.  Frequent wind gusts of 40 mph or so were observed with a peak gust of 44 mph measured at Shenandoah and 40 mph at Clarinda.  The winds produced considerable blowing and drifting snow with blizzard conditions during the evening and early morning hours of the 8th and 9th, which closed many county roads.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Precipitation came in two waves.  The initial round of elevated convection was focused across portions of central and south central Missouri.   Rainfall amounts of one half to one and half inches fell with this initial rainfall.  A second more intense band of rainfall moved across the region Thursday evening as a cold front swept into the Ozarks.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Homes were evacuated along Beaver Creek due to flooding.

A trade wind swell caused surf of 6 to 8 feet along the east-facing shores of Kauai, Oahu, Molokai, Maui, and the Big Island of Hawaii.  There were no reports of serious property damage or injuries.
Dry conditions continued to prevail over parts of Molokai, Maui, and the Big Island of Hawaii.  County officials kept water restrictions in place.

Low pressure passed through the Mid-Atlantic spreading precipitation over eastern West Virginia on the morning of the 31st. There was enough cold air for a period of snow before drier air worked in during the afternoon.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts around two to three inches were estimated across the western part of the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong low pressure moving through New York State coupled with a vigorous low level jet resulted in periods of damaging wind across Southern New England.  Rain and occasional thunder also occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Automated Surface Observing System at Windham Airport in Willimantic, CT (KIJD) recorded sustained wind speeds of 37 mph and gusts to 56 mph.  In addition, reports were received of large tree limbs blown down onto wires, bringing the wires down as well.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Arctic air plunged southeast across eastern Nebraska and southwest Iowa on January 14th and 15th.  Temperatures in southwest Iowa fell into the single digits during the morning hours of 1/14, recovered a little in the afternoon and then fell to 5 below to 20 below, or a bit colder, by the morning of the 15th.  Northwest winds of 20 to 30 mph with higher gusts were observed into the afternoon of the 14th before subsiding in the afternoon and evening.  This produced wind chill values of 20 below to 30 below zero over much of the region.  Winds continued to decrease during the early morning hours of 1/15, and by 5am CST most recorded speeds were less than 10 mph.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: As temperatures fell below zero by the evening of the 14th, northwest winds of 10 to 20 mph produced wind chill values of 20 below to 25 below zero.  Winds dropped mostly below 10 mph during the early morning hours of 1/15 but air temperatures by that time were around 10 below to 20 below zero.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A clipper low pressure system strengthened as it approached Michigan from the northwest.  This storm produced two areas of heavy snow.  The main system snow fell in a wide band from Charlevoix and Bellaire, southeastward through Grayling and on to Standish and Tawas City.  Accumulations of 8 to 12 inches were common within this band.  A more localized band of lake enhanced snow affect part of the Lake Michigan coastline, near Manistee and Arcadia, as well as near Curtis and Gould City.  Snowfall amounts were around 10 inches, with locally near 15 inches in Curtis.

Intense low pressure moving through the Gulf of Maine coincided with the highest astronomical tides of the month to produce coastal flooding in areas along the Maine coast. Strong southeast winds produced a storm surge of 1.44 ft and near shore waves of 7 to 10 ft, bringing the Portland tide gage to 12.54 ft. Ocean water flooded Route 1 in Lincolnville and Frankfort. Water reached cars parked near Commercial Street in Portland. In Kennebunk powerful waves crashed in and around homes. At Popham Beach, trees were sucked into the ocean and severe beach erosion occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Intense low pressure and astronomically high tides produced coastal flooding in Portland with water reaching cars parked on Commercial Street.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of low pressure developed off the Carolina coast on the morning of the 5th and moved northeast to south of Nova Scotia by the morning of the 6th.  The low brought 4 to 8 inches of snow to coastal and interior areas.  The foothills generally received from 2 to 6 inches with only an inch or two in the mountains.

A northwest flow behind a cold front triggered snow showers across eastern West Virginia along and west of the Allegheny front. Snow showers began on the afternoon of the 7th and lasted into the morning of the 9th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Bayard received 7.0 inches of snow and Mount Storm received 4.0 inches of snow. The snow began on the afternoon of the 7th and lasted into the morning of the 9th.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of low pressure passed through the Mid-Atlantic on the 10th into the early morning hours of the 11th. The track of the low was far enough north for warmer air to be drawn into the storm system above the surface. However, colder air remained trapped at the surface causing freezing rain to develop.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A light glaze of icing due to freezing rain was reported in Winchester and also across Cross Junction. Icy roads were also reported across the northern part of Frederick County.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure moved out of the southern Plains northeast across the Tennessee Valley reaching the southern New England Coast on the 28th.  The low brought an eight to twelve inch blanket of snow to the entire region by the evening of the 28th. Innumerable automobile accidents were reported throughout the region as the roads became hard to navigate in the heavy snow and reduced visibilities. Many schools cancelled classes across the region.
A cluster of thunderstorms produced large hail up to the size of baseballs during the late evening of June 18.
A cold upper low moved just south of Arizona November 29th into 30th. This resulted in significant snowfall in the higher elevations of Graham and Cochise Counties.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: About 20 inches of snow occurred at the top of Mt. Graham at an elevation above 10,000 feet.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A moist westerly flow brought moderate to heavy snow accumulations over the higher terrain of northwest Montana.  Total snow amounts ranged between five to eleven inches.  In addition to the snow, a strong jet stream caused gusty winds up to 45 mph, causing areas of blowing and drifting snow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: SNOTELs in the area reported between five to nine inches of snow above 4000 feet.  In addition gusty west winds up to 40 mph were reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Extreme (D3) drought conditions prevailed across portions of northwest Wisconsin in early November, mainly across Sawyer and Washburn counties.  This area was downgraded slightly to severe (D2) drought status by the middle and end of the month.  Severe drought conditions also covered much of Price, as well as southern Iron, Ashland, and Bayfield counties, and eastern Burnett county through the month of November.

Light freezing rain developed during the early morning hours across the foothills and southern mountains of North Carolina, producing light ice accretion on elevated surfaces. A few slick spots developed on bridges and overpasses before temperatures warmed above freezing later in the morning. The ice accretion did cause some isolated damage to trees and power lines.

The remnants from Hurricane Ida which made landfall along the Florida panhandle combined with a powerful upper level storm system along the Carolina coast. The result was a powerful low pressure system which developed near Cape Fear and tracked to Cape Hatteras. Between 3 to 6 inches of rain fell across central North Carolina over a 3 day period. Gusty winds to 35 to 45 mph combined with saturated soil resulted in power outages and some property damage from falling trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts of 40 to 45 mph along with heavy rain resulted in numerous trees falling and knocking down power lines.

CZ_NAME: TANGIER SOUND AND THE INLAND WATERS SURROUNDING BLOODSWORTH ISLAND
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front passed through the Tidal Potomac and Chesapeake Bay on the 24th of October. Despite limited instability, strong winds aloft were able to mix down to the surface in heavier showers. The gusty showers occurred during the afternoon and evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust in excess of 30 knots was reported at Bishops Head.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A complex of thunderstorms moved southward, out of the North Carolina mountains, and into Upstate South Carolina. The storms produced quite a bit of large hail and some wind damage as they moved southeast between the Greenville and Spartanburg metro areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Four to five inch diameter tree limbs were blown down between Tigerville and highway 11.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Golf ball size hail was reported in Inman Mills.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A few trees and power lines were blown down over the northwest side of the County. A tree fell on a shed in the Inman Mills community.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong pressure gradient behind a cold front produced damaging winds across all of western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia, eastern Ohio, and Garrett county Maryland. Sustained winds were from 30 to 40 MPH with gusts over 60 MPH. The strongest reported wind gusts were 68 MPH in Franklin, PA and 66 MPH in Eighty Four, PA. Trees and power lines were reported down across the region, with more than 50,000 homes without power late afternoon on the 9th at the peak of the winds.

A cold winter storm moved through Utah, bringing snow to much of the state. The heaviest snowfall occurred across southern and central Utah, with lighter amounts in the far northern parts of the state.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Orderville received 19 inches of snow for the storm, while Kodachrome Basin received 14 new inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold winter storm moved through Utah, bringing snow to much of the state. The heaviest snowfall occurred across southern and central Utah, with lighter amounts in the far northern parts of the state.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Tooele and West Jordan both received a storm total of 8 inches of snow. In addition, snow stuck very efficiently to the road surfaces, greatly impacting the morning commute.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A series of moist Pacific storm systems moved through Utah over a 3-day period. The storm brought wet, heavy snow to much of the state, with the heaviest snow across both the valleys and mountains of northern Utah.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Kolob SNOTEL received 3.30 inches liquid equivalent precipitation, or approximately 40 inches of new snow.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Providence received 10 inches of new snow.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Brigham City received 18 inches of new snow. Other totals included 12.5 inches at North Ogden and 10 inches in South Ogden.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful storm missed most of southwest Kansas (at least the heaviest).  There were still scattered reports of heavy snow in the northwest portion of the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow of six inches was measured at a location 18 miles northeast of Coolidge.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A swell generated by gale force winds northeast of the Aloha State produced surf of 10 to 25 feet along the north-facing shores of Niihau, Kauai, Oahu, Molokai, Maui, and the Big Island of Hawaii.  The swell also caused surf of 8 to 20 feet along the east-facing shores of all the same isles plus Lanai.  There were no reports of serious property damage or injuries.

A light mix of sleet and snow developed over the mountains and foothills of western North Carolina during the evening, and continued for much of the overnight. Accumulations ranged from trace amounts over the lower elevations of the foothills, to localized 2-3 inch amounts over the mountains.  A few slick spots developed on mountain roads, resulting in quite a few accidents.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Cold west to southwest winds blowing across Lake Michigan produced locally heavy lake effect snow in far Northern Lower Michigan, and a small part of far Eastern Upper Michigan.  Ellsworth and Charlevoix picked up 6 to 8 inches of snow in the early morning hours of the 4th.  The snow shifted north to Emmet County later that day, with 6 inches in Brutus by mid evening, and near 10 inches just north of Pellston by morning on the 5th.  That snow band continued on to De Tour Village in Chippewa County, with 6 to 7 inches of snow there.

Arctic air plunged southeast across eastern Nebraska and southwest Iowa on January 14th and 15th.  Temperatures fell into the single digits above and below zero during the morning hours of 1/14, recovered a little in the afternoon and then fell to 5 below to 20 below, or a bit colder, by the morning of the 15th.  Northwest winds of 20 to 30 mph with higher gusts were observed into the afternoon of the 14th before subsiding in the afternoon and evening.  This produced wind chill values of 20 below to 30 below zero over much of the region.  By around midnight on the 15th most reporting sites observed winds dropped below 10 mph and remained that way through the morning of the 15th.  However, several locations, mainly south through southeast of Omaha, recorded wind speeds of 10 to 15 mph and wind chill values colder than 20 below through around 5am CST on the 15th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: As temperatures fell below zero across the county, northwest winds of 20 to 30 mph in the morning and early afternoon and 10 to 20 mph from late afternoon into late evening, produced wind chill values of 20 below to 25 below zero.  Winds dropped mostly below 10 mph by the early morning hours of 1/15 but air temperatures fell to 10 below to 20 below zero.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong coastal low pressure sytem tracking from the Gulf of Mexico northeast along the Carolina coast collided with cold air resulting in a a major winter storm. The heavierst snow fell across the northwest piedmont, foothills and mountains of North Carolina where up to seven inches of snow in the Triad with over two feet of snow in portions the mountains. Numerous motorists were stranded on highways and interstates west and north of Wintson Salem. Hundreds of automobile accidents were reported in the northwest piedmont.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Between 1 to 3 inches of snow fell across Durham county. In the city of Durham an inch of snow accumulated on roads before snow changed over the rain. Further north over the northern portions of the county snow fell for a longer period of time resulting in around 3 inches of snow. Law enforecement responded to a number of accidents the evening of the snowfall.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A disturbance in the northern branch of the jet stream was able to phase with low pressure in the southern branch of the jet stream over the Southeast Coast on the night of the 18th. These two systems combined to develop a strong area of low pressure that slowly track up the Mid-Atlantic Coast during the 19th. The low was able to tap into moisture from the Gulf of Mexico and the Atlantic Ocean causing copious amounts of precipitation to develop. High pressure to the north kept plenty of cold air in place causing the precipitation to fall in the form of snow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts were reported between 18 and 22 inches across the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deepening storm system, and the associated cold front that swept across Alabama, brought widespread showers and thunderstorms to the state.  Several storms produced heavy rain that caused flash flooding, along with damaging winds.  Even away from the thunderstorms, gusty gradient winds affected a large portion of Central Alabama.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two trees were blown down on Bachelors Chapel Road, in the Hokes Bluff area.

Wind gusts between 45 and 60 mph were common during the late morning and afternoon hours.  There were reports of power lines and trees down across the region due to the strong winds, which resulted in isolated power outages.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Light freezing rain developed during the early morning hours across the foothills and southern mountains of North Carolina, producing light ice accretion on elevated surfaces. A few slick spots developed on bridges and overpasses before temperatures warmed above freezing later in the morning. The ice accretion did cause some isolated damage to trees and power lines.

A large and intense area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and eventually up the east coast on December 18th and 19th. The initial precipitation began as a heavy wet snow on Friday afternoon December 18th. Accumulations around eastern Kentucky ranged between 1 and 4 inches. Ridgetop locations along the Virginia and west Virginia borders saw as much as 6 inches, with 13 inches reported on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County. This initial round of snow fell generally between 2 and 6 pm on the 18th. ||After several hours of nothing but rain, another round of widespread and intense snowfall began at around 10 pm. The Jackson weather office picked up 2.6 inches of snow between 10 pm and midnight on the 18th and there were 11 inches on the ground by early Saturday morning. By 7 am on Saturday December 19th 5 to 7 inches of snow blanketed the ground across much of southeast Kentucky. The highest snowfall totals for this event were 16 inches on Black Mountain, 13 inches on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County, and 11 inches at the Jackson weather office. Numerous trees and power lines were downed by the heavy wet snow with widespread and long lasting power outages reported across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous noninjury accidents were reported along KY 632 on Phelps Mountain, US 23 on Dorton Mountain, and US 460 on Card Mountain near Pikeville.

CZ_NAME: TIDAL POTOMAC COBB IS MD TO SMITH PT VA
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front passed through the Tidal Potomac and Chesapeake Bay on the 24th of October. Despite limited instability, strong winds aloft were able to mix down to the surface in heavier showers. The gusty showers occurred during the afternoon and evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust in excess of 30 knots was reported at Lewisetta.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A brush fire was started along Highway 76 near Verdugo Canyon Road when a tractor crashed into a power pole around 1130 PST on November 16th. The fire burned about 145 acres before being contained on the evening of the 17th. Four firefighters sustained injuries fighting the blaze, and no damage was reported.

A large, long period west swell reached the beaches of Southern California early on the 28th. Waves of 7 to 9 feet with some sets as high as 12 feet were reported. The swell and surf quickly subsided overnight. Two boats were capsized in the high surf, trapping 6 people. Only minor injuries were reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 25 foot fishing boat capsized around 0800 PST when returning to the San Diego Bay. Six people were on board and became trapped in the cabin. They managed to open the door and escape from the boat and were promptly rescued by the lifeguards. All six were admitted to the hospital, five of which were treated and released. The sixth person was kept and monitored overnight. A lifeguard boat flipped two hours later when trying to upright the overturned fishing boat. The two lifeguards on board were not injured.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Offshore winds quickly developed on the evening of the 23rd.The strong gusty Northeast winds mainly impacted the Inland Empire below the Cajon Pass and the Santa Ana Mountains. There was one report of a car being blown off the road and one tree down. The winds diminished overnight.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High winds began at the Fremont Canyon RAWS around 2130 PST and ended between 0130 PST and 0230 PST on the 24th. A peak wind gust of 74 MPH was measured between 2231 and 2330 PST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong pressure gradient behind a cold front produced damaging winds across all of western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia, eastern Ohio, and Garrett county Maryland. Sustained winds were from 30 to 40 MPH with gusts over 60 MPH. The strongest reported wind gusts were 68 MPH in Franklin, PA and 66 MPH in Eighty Four, PA. Trees and power lines were reported down across the region, with more than 50,000 homes without power late afternoon on the 9th at the peak of the winds.

The final winter storm of the month brought light to moderate rain and gusty winds to the region on December 22nd and 23rd. Strong onshore flow associated with the storm produced strong gusty winds to the mountains and deserts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: High winds were measured by the Julian CWOP between 0806 and 1107 PST. Between 0835 and 0848 PST multiple gusts of 65 MPH were measured.

CZ_NAME: WATERS FROM BAFFIN BAY TO PT MANSFIELD TX EXT FROM 20 TO 60NM
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous cold front moved through Deep South Texas and the adjacent Gulf of Mexico coastal waters toward the end of October, producing a line of strong to severe thunderstorms which began in western Kenedy County then migrated south southeast through Willacy and Cameron County, as well as the adjacent coastal waters.||Wind gusts between 55 and 65 mph were common as the storms intensified; interestingly, persistent winds within the microburst core maintained these gusts for 15 minutes or more in some areas, with up to an hour of sustained winds above Gale Force. Post-frontal winds behind the line continued with near Gale Force gusts for several hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A line of strong to severe thunderstorms preceded a cold front into the Lower Texas Gulf waters, producing at least 15 minutes of gale force sustained winds with gusts to storm force.  The peak gust of 53 knots (61 mph) occurred at 214 PM CST, with sustained winds of 43 knots (49 mph) lasting for at least 10 minutes beginning at 210 PM CST.

CZ_NAME: LAGUNA MADRE FROM PORT OF BROWNSVILLE TO ARROYO COLORADO
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous cold front moved through Deep South Texas and the adjacent Gulf of Mexico coastal waters toward the end of October, producing a line of strong to severe thunderstorms which began in western Kenedy County then migrated south southeast through Willacy and Cameron County, as well as the adjacent coastal waters.||Wind gusts between 55 and 65 mph were common as the storms intensified; interestingly, persistent winds within the microburst core maintained these gusts for 15 minutes or more in some areas, with up to an hour of sustained winds above Gale Force. Post-frontal winds behind the line continued with near Gale Force gusts for several hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A line of strong to severe thunderstorms produced a long duration microburst as it swept across the Laguna Madre and into the Lower Texas Gulf coast.  At 154 PM CST, a 57 mph wind gust was recorded at the Realitos Peninsula Texas Coastal Ocean Observation Network.  Gusts of 50 mph or greater occurred until 324 PM before the sensor temporarily became non operational.  Times are accurate within 6 minutes.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A swell generated by gale force winds northeast of the Aloha State produced surf of 10 to 25 feet along the north-facing shores of Niihau, Kauai, Oahu, Molokai, Maui, and the Big Island of Hawaii.  The swell also caused surf of 8 to 20 feet along the east-facing shores of all the same isles plus Lanai.  There were no reports of serious property damage or injuries.

A few slick spots developed on mountain roads, resulting in quite a few accidents.

The remnants from Hurricane Ida which made landfall along the Florida panhandle combined with a powerful upper level storm system along the Carolina coast. The result was a powerful low pressure system which developed near Cape Fear and tracked to Cape Hatteras. Between 3 to 6 inches of rain fell across central North Carolina over a 3 day period. Gusty winds to 35 to 45 mph combined with saturated soil resulted in power outages and some property damage from falling trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts of 40 to 45 mph along with heavy rain resulted in numerous trees falling and knocking down power lines. Several trees fell on homes, apartment buildings and vehicles.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Scattered showers brought light amounts of rain on the 6th and 12th. The first real rain of the season occurred on the 28th and 29th. Several mountain locations received over an inch of rain, and higher elevations received six to twelve inches of snow. Rainfall amounts in the valley ranged anywhere from one-tenth of an inch to over one inch.||The State of Emergency for the State of California, as well as the Secretarial Disaster Declaration, remained in place. Some mandatory and voluntary water restrictions remained in place as well. Beginning November 1st, San Diego residents have been restricted to running sprinklers for only seven minutes a day before 10 am and after 4 pm. The Weekly U.S. Drought Monitor had all areas except for the deserts classified as D2 (severe drought), while the deserts remained at D1 (moderate drought).

A powerful low pressure system moved across Lower Michigan on the 9th.  Snow surged northward ahead of the low, with intense snowfall rates on the morning of the 9th.  By evening, snowfall totals of 6 to 12 inches were common across all of Northern Michigan.  Glennie, Rogers City, and Central Lake all had a foot of snow during the day, while Curtis picked up 16 inches.  The snow transitioned to lake effect snow that night, and lasted into the 11th in some of the snowbelts.  Localized 4 to 8 inch accumulations were common in a given 12 hour period.  There was a considerable amount of wind, and thus blowing and drifting snow, especially on the 9th.  Gaylord had its 2nd largest three-day snowfall since 1950, with 21.8 inches.  Almost all school districts were closed on the 9th, and some schools called off classes for three consecutive days.

A strong pressure gradient behind a cold front produced damaging winds across all of western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia, eastern Ohio, and Garrett county Maryland. Sustained winds were from 30 to 40 MPH with gusts over 60 MPH. The strongest reported wind gusts were 68 MPH in Franklin, PA and 66 MPH in Eighty Four, PA. Trees and power lines were reported down across the region, with more than 50,000 homes without power late afternoon on the 9th at the peak of the winds.

A strong coastal low pressure sytem tracking from the Gulf of Mexico northeast along the Carolina coast collided with cold air resulting in a a major winter storm. The heavierst snow fell across the northwest piedmont, foothills and mountains of North Carolina where up to seven inches of snow in the Triad with over two feet of snow in portions the mountains. Numerous motorists were stranded on highways and interstates west and north of Wintson Salem. Hundreds of automobile accidents were reported in the northwest piedmont.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Between 4 to 8 inches of snow fell across Forsyth county and Winston-Salem. Many primary roads including Highway 52, Highway 421 and portions Interstate 40 became impassible during the evening. Law enforecement responded to hundreds of automobile accidents.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Precipitation was above normal for the first time in all of central and southern Indiana since July. Towards the end of December, river flooding developed for the first time in more than five months. Northern Indiana received significant snow and ice on the 18th and 19th. Rainfall returned on the 23rd as freezing rain. Rainfall of 1 to 3 inches fell on the 23rd and 24th in much of central and southern Indiana. This caused rivers to rise to bankfull levels in areas south of I-70. Precipitation in northern Indiana was once again a winter mix and did not have a large effect on streams. Near record temperatures later on the 26th and 27th ended the ice problems, but contributed to the developing river flooding by allowing additional precipitation to fall as rain. Rainfall generally ranged from 1/2 to 2 inches. This resulted in widespread lowland flooding in western and southern Indiana. No snow remained on the ground at the end of the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rainfall and warm temperatures that occurred on and off during the second half of December led to considerable lowland flooding along the Wabash River during late December and very early January, affecting Sullivan County at and near Riverton. This flood event is a continuation from December.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A disturbance in the northern branch of the jet stream was able to phase with low pressure in the southern branch of the jet stream over the Southeast Coast on the night of the 18th. These two systems combined to develop a strong area of low pressure that slowly track up the Mid-Atlantic Coast during the 19th. The low was able to tap into moisture from the Gulf of Mexico and the Atlantic Ocean causing copious amounts of precipitation to develop. High pressure to the north kept plenty of cold air in place causing the precipitation to fall in the form of snow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A report of 17.5 inches of snow was received fro near Toms Brook.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A two pronged winter storm moved across the region during the period of December 6th through December the 8th, 2009.  The initial system on December 6th spread a thin layer of freezing drizzle across portions of Central Kansas, which produced numerous automobile accidents with one leading to a death.  A more potent low pressure area tracked along the Kansas/Oklahoma border on December 7th and 8th, 2009.  This system led to a band of heavy snow across Central Kansas with a band of 6 to 12 inches along a line from Great Bend, Kansas to Salina, Kansas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Three to eight inches of snow fell across the county, with the heaviest amounts near Bushton, Kansas and Frederick, Kansas in the northern portion of the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Bitter cold arctic air poured into South-central and Southeast Wisconsin on January 13th in the wake of an Alberta Clipper low pressure. At sunrise air temperatures ranged from -3 to +5, however, by late morning air temperatures ranged from -2 to +7 across southern Wisconsin.  Northwest winds of 13 to 22 knots (15 to 25 mph) with gusts to 30 knots (35 mph) generated wind chill values of -20 to -30.  Several public schools delayed the start of classes by 2 hours.

A couple bands of lake-effect snow developed over southern Lake Michigan in association with a meso-low pressure, and then moved inland to affect the counties of Racine and Kenosha.  In the city of Racine (Racine Co.), 8 inches was measured, while 5 inches fell in the city of Kenosha (Kenosha Co.).  The axis of the greatest snow accumulations extended from the city of Racine southwest to near Paddock Lake (Kenosha Co.) where roughly 6 inches fell.  An estimated 2 to 4 inches accumulated over extreme southeast Milwaukee County.  At the Racine Airport, north-northwest winds gusted to 29 knots (33 mph) during the heavy lake-effect snow squalls which lowered visibilities at that location to around 1/4 mile at times.

Strong post-frontal gradient winds developed on December 9th, strongest during the late morning and afternoon as a deep area of low pressure tracked into northern Lower Michigan. Widespread wind gusts between 45 and 60 mph were common across much of northern Indiana.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Very windy conditions were seen across the area on December 9th as a deep area of low pressure tracked into Michigan.  Wind gusts between 45 and 60 mph were common during the late morning and afternoon hours.  There were reports of power lines and trees down across the region due to the strong winds, which resulted in isolated power outages.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong area of low pressure moved north across West Virginia to western Pennsylvania producing a heavy mix of precipitation. Snow accumulated 2 to 4 inches across northwest Pennsylvania on the night of the 27Th before changing to freezing rain the morning of the 28Th, then back to snow in the afternoon with another 1 to 2 inches. Ice accumulations in Pittsburgh and areas north were from a quarter to one half inch. For southeast Ohio, northern West Virgina, and Garrett county Maryland mixed precipitation changed to freezing rain during the evening of the 27Th with ice quickly accumulating to one half inch before changing to plain overnight. The rain changed back to snow during the afternoon of the 28Th with 1 to 2 inches of snow accumulating.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was reported down on Lake Shore Drive at mile marker eight.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A few strong to severe thunderstorms moved across parts of northern Illinois during the afternoon hours of June 8th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Nickel to quarter size hail was reported on Route 59.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain fell across parts of west central Will County during the afternoon and early evening of June 16th.  Storms developed over the same areas as they slowly moved northeast, producing torrential rains over a relatively small area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain fell across parts west central Will County causing flash flooding.  Numerous roads were flooded and closed.  In Joliet, Hammas was closed between Jefferson and Onedia; Midhurst Lane at Midhurst Court was flooded with water two feet deep; Edgerton was flooded between Midhurst Lane and Westfield and also north of Harrogate Avenue.  In Crest Hill, Route 30 at Larkin was flooded with stalled vehicles in the intersection and the intersection of Arduagh and Noonan Drive was flooded.  In Romeoville, ten inches of flowing was reported along Weber Road near Interstate 55 and Romeo Road was heavily flooded.  Basement flooding was also reported.  Storm total rainfall amounts included 4.09 inches just southwest of Larkin and Theodore in Joliet; 3.95 inches just northwest of Gaylord and Theodore in Joliet; 3.05 inches at the National Weather Service office in Romeoville; 2.50 inches near Bruce and Lawrence Avenue in Lockport; 2.28 inches was reported in Homer Glen; 2.27 inches at the Joliet Lock & Dam; 1.74 inches in Plainfield and 1.70 inches in Shorewood.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong to severe thunderstorms moved across northwest Indiana during the early morning hours of June 19th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts were estimated to 60 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large and intense area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and eventually up the east coast on December 18th and 19th. The initial precipitation began as a heavy wet snow on Friday afternoon December 18th. Accumulations around eastern Kentucky ranged between 1 and 4 inches. Ridgetop locations along the Virginia and west Virginia borders saw as much as 6 inches, with 13 inches reported on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County. This initial round of snow fell generally between 2 and 6 pm on the 18th. ||After several hours of nothing but rain, another round of widespread and intense snowfall began at around 10 pm. The Jackson weather office picked up 2.6 inches of snow between 10 pm and midnight on the 18th and there were 11 inches on the ground by early Saturday morning. By 7 am on Saturday December 19th 5 to 7 inches of snow blanketed the ground across much of southeast Kentucky. The highest snowfall totals for this event were 16 inches on Black Mountain, 13 inches on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County, and 11 inches at the Jackson weather office. Numerous trees and power lines were downed by the heavy wet snow with widespread and long lasting power outages reported across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: McCreary county emergency management reported that Highway 92 was closed at the intersection with 1470 due to slick roads. Approximately 20 other accidents had also been reported around the county. Two to 3 inches of snow were estimated to be on the ground.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A moist westerly flow brought moderate to heavy snow accumulations over the higher terrain of northwest Montana.  Total snow amounts ranged between five to eleven inches.  In addition to the snow, a strong jet stream caused gusty winds up to 45 mph, causing areas of blowing and drifting snow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: SNOTELs in the area reported five to nine inches of new snow.  In addition, wind gusts up to 90 mph were reported over Logan Pass.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: SNOTELs in the area reported between five to eleven inches of new snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An approaching upper level trough and associated jet brought accumulating snow to portions of north central Idaho.  The heaviest snow amounts were over the Camas Prairie where three to seven inches of new snow was reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A spotter six miles southeast of Grangeville reported eight inches of snow, with the DOT reporting up to six inches of snow on area roads.  Power went out locally to a few customers in Grangeville due to snowload related problems.  In addition, a few car accidents were reported on area roads.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Winds were expected to increase ahead of an approaching cold front moving across southeast Wyoming.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wyoming Depart of Transportation sensor at Arlington (KARL) measured at peak gust of 64 MPH at 10 AM LST. Winds were sustained in excess of 40 MPH between 5 AM and 5 PM LST.

CZ_NAME: CENTRAL LARAMIE RANGE AND SOUTHWEST PLATTE COUNTY
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Winds were expected to increase ahead of an approaching cold front moving across southeast Wyoming.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wyoming Department of Transportation sensor at Bordeaux (KBDX) measured peak gust of 63 MPH at 8 AM LST with sustained winds in excess of 40 MPH from 6 AM through 9 AM LST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low level pressure gradient over the Rocky Mountains was expected to produce strong winds over portions of southeast Wyoming. The strong winds were expected to produce low visibilities in areas of blowing snow due to recent snowfall in addition to dangerous wind chill values.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wyoming Department of Highways sensor at Arlington (KARL) measured sustained winds of 40 to 45 MPH with gusts 60 to 65 MPH from 9/546 AM through 10/241 PM LST. Peak gusts of 68 MPH occurred around 10/1230 AM.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The final winter storm of the month brought light to moderate rain and gusty winds to the region on December 22nd and 23rd. Strong onshore flow associated with the storm produced strong gusty winds to the mountains and deserts.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts in excess of 58 MPH were measured by the Whitewater RAWS between 1250 and 1650 PST. Multiple wind gusts of 66 MPH were measured during this period. At 1801 PST, the Palm Springs Airport ASOS measured a peak wind gust of 63 MPH. Blowing dust and downed palm fronds were also reported during this time.

The Weekly U.S. Drought Monitor improved much of the region to D1 (moderate drought), while southwest San Bernardino and portions of central Riverside and extreme northeast Orange counties remained in a D2 (severe drought) classification.

A powerful winter storm brought heavy rain, flash flooding, gusty winds and severe thunderstorms to Central and Southern California. Rainfall amounts for this storm ranged from 1 to 3 inches over coastal areas to between 3 and 6 inches in the mountain and foothill areas. With such heavy rainfall, there were several reports of flash flooding along with mud and debris flows near the Station Fire burn area. In San Luis Obispo county, a severe thunderstorm producing very strong winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong and gusty southwest winds were reported in the foothills of the Antelope Valley. The Lake Palmdale RAWS sensor reported wind gusts as high as 63 MPH while the sensor at Valyermo reported wind gusts to 58 MPH.

CZ_NAME: WATERS FROM PT MANSFIELD TO RIO GRANDE TX EXT FROM 20 TO 60NM
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous cold front moved through Deep South Texas and the adjacent Gulf of Mexico coastal waters toward the end of October, producing a line of strong to severe thunderstorms which began in western Kenedy County then migrated south southeast through Willacy and Cameron County, as well as the adjacent coastal waters.||Wind gusts between 55 and 65 mph were common as the storms intensified; interestingly, persistent winds within the microburst core maintained these gusts for 15 minutes or more in some areas, with up to an hour of sustained winds above Gale Force. Post-frontal winds behind the line continued with near Gale Force gusts for several hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A line of strong thunderstorms, enhanced by the strong cold front catching up to it, produced wind gusts nearing 70 mph as recorded by a Texas A&M University Automated Buoy System observation east of South Padre Island, beginning at 330 PM CST.  The microburst following the front maintained storm force gusts through at least 4 PM CST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong pressure gradient behind a cold front produced damaging winds across all of western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia, eastern Ohio, and Garrett county Maryland. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Precipitation was above normal for the first time in all of central and southern Indiana since July. Towards the end of December, river flooding developed for the first time in more than five months. Northern Indiana received significant snow and ice on the 18th and 19th. Rainfall returned on the 23rd as freezing rain. Rainfall of 1 to 3 inches fell on the 23rd and 24th in much of central and southern Indiana. This caused rivers to rise to bankfull levels in areas south of I-70. Precipitation in northern Indiana was once again a winter mix and did not have a large effect on streams. Near record temperatures later on the 26th and 27th ended the ice problems, but contributed to the developing river flooding by allowing additional precipitation to fall as rain. Rainfall generally ranged from 1/2 to 2 inches. This resulted in widespread lowland flooding in western and southern Indiana. No snow remained on the ground at the end of the month.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rainfall and warm temperatures that occurred on and off during the second half of December led to lowland flooding along the Wabash River during late December and very early January, affecting Knox County at and near Vincennes during the first week of January. The river crested at 18.8 feet on the 5th at the Red Skelton Bridge river gage.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Above normal temperatures through January 4th, melting snow and ice, along with rainfall that fell in late December rose the level of the White River at and near Muncie to less than one foot above flood stage briefly on January 6th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rainfall and warm temperatures that occurred on and off during the second half of December and above normal temperatures through January 4th led to slightly greater than bank full conditions on the White River, affecting Delaware County at and near Muncie. This event was very short lived.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A two pronged winter storm moved across the region during the period of December 6th through December the 8th, 2009.  The initial system on December 6th spread a thin layer of freezing drizzle across portions of Central Kansas, which produced numerous automobile accidents with one leading to a death.  A more potent low pressure area tracked along the Kansas/Oklahoma border on December 7th and 8th, 2009.  This system led to a band of heavy snow across Central Kansas with a band of 6 to 12 inches along a line from Great Bend, Kansas to Salina, Kansas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of one to two inches produced some auto accidents across the county.  Four accidents were caused by the slick roadways, but none were serious.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A complex of thunderstorms moved southeast out of Northwest Kansas into Central and South Central Kansas during the early morning hours of May 8th, 2009.  This complex of thunmderstorms would intensify over South Central Kansas during the morning and become a prolific damaging wind producer.  This swath of damaging winds, (measured at 80 to 100 mph) cut a path of destruction from just north of Wichita, Kansas to Parsons, Kansas. This storm system would continue on into Southern Missouri and eventually Southern Illinois producing widespread damage.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong north to northwest winds, gusting to over 50 mph, combined with existing loose snow cover and 1 to 3 inches of new snow to produce blizzard conditions with widespread visibilities near zero over parts of southeast South Dakota during the day and early evening of January 12th. The very low visibilities were widespread where the greatest loose snow cover was located, and more localized in other areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: North to northwest winds sustained at 30 to 40 mph with gusts over 50 mph combined with several inches of loose snow cover, along with 1 to 3 inches of new snow, to produce widespread visibilities of a quarter mile or less in blowing snow. The low visibilities and drifting snow made travel impossible in many areas, and forced schools and businesses to close.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong, moist westerly flow off the Pacific Ocean provided a prolonged period of snowfall across northwest and far west Wyoming. EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong area of low pressure moved north across West Virginia to western Pennsylvania producing a heavy mix of precipitation. Ice accumulations in Pittsburgh and areas north were from a quarter to one half inch. For southeast Ohio, northern West Virgina, and Garrett county Maryland mixed precipitation changed to freezing rain during the evening of the 27Th with ice quickly accumulating to one half inch before changing to plain overnight. The rain changed back to snow during the afternoon of the 28Th with 1 to 2 inches of snow accumulating.

Precipitation began as snow, but a change over to sleet, and eventually freezing rain occurred from south to north during the afternoon and evening of the 27th. Freezing rain finally changed to rain from south to north during the morning and afternoon hours of the 28th. Rain ended during the early evening hours of the 28th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ice accumulation of one tenth of an inch was reported throughout the county. Snow and sleet accumulation up to one inch was also reported throughout the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: During January, drought conditions intensified across South Texas. By the end of January, extreme drought conditions existed across Bee, Goliad, Victoria, Refugio, and Aransas counties. Severe drought conditions existed across Calhoun, San Patricio, Live Oak, northern McMullen, and northern La Salle counties. Moderate drought existed across Nueces, Kleberg, Jim Wells, Duval, southern McMullen, southern La Salle, and northern Webb counties. Abnormally dry conditions were observed southern Webb county. (per the U.S. Drought Monitor: http://www.drought.unl.edu/dm/monitor.html) ||The primary impacts of the drought during January were agricultural and fire related. Forage was sparse and the supplemental feeding of hay to livestock continued.  Farmers were delaying the planting of some winter crops.  Moisture was badly needed for the upcoming planting of the Sorghum crop.  Periods of elevated to high fire danger occurred through the month with sporadic wildfires.  In addition, reservoir levels continued a gradual fall.  Choke Canyon Reservoir was near 80% capacity and Lake Corpus Christi near 64% capacity by the end of the month. Rivers and creeks in the rainfall deficit areas continued a slow fall, and were below baseflow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A disturbance in the northern branch of the jet stream was able to phase with low pressure in the southern branch of the jet stream over the Southeast Coast on the night of the 18th. These two systems combined to develop a strong area of low pressure that slowly track up the Mid-Atlantic Coast during the 19th. The low was able to tap into moisture from the Gulf of Mexico and the Atlantic Ocean causing copious amounts of precipitation to develop. High pressure to the north kept plenty of cold air in place causing the precipitation to fall in the form of snow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall totaled up to 20.0 inches at Shenandoah Junction.

A powerful winter storm brought heavy rain, flash flooding, gusty winds and severe thunderstorms to Central and Southern California. Rainfall amounts for this storm ranged from 1 to 3 inches over coastal areas to between 3 and 6 inches in the mountain and foothill areas. With such heavy rainfall, there were several reports of flash flooding along with mud and debris flows near the Station Fire burn area. In San Luis Obispo county, a severe thunderstorm producing very strong winds.

Near the community of La Canada-Flintridge, numerous streets were closed due to mud and debris flows including Rockcastle Drive, Earnslow Drive and Canyonside Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large and intense area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and eventually up the east coast on December 18th and 19th. The initial precipitation began as a heavy wet snow on Friday afternoon December 18th. Accumulations around eastern Kentucky ranged between 1 and 4 inches. Ridgetop locations along the Virginia and west Virginia borders saw as much as 6 inches, with 13 inches reported on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County. This initial round of snow fell generally between 2 and 6 pm on the 18th. ||After several hours of nothing but rain, another round of widespread and intense snowfall began at around 10 pm. The Jackson weather office picked up 2.6 inches of snow between 10 pm and midnight on the 18th and there were 11 inches on the ground by early Saturday morning. By 7 am on Saturday December 19th 5 to 7 inches of snow blanketed the ground across much of southeast Kentucky. The highest snowfall totals for this event were 16 inches on Black Mountain, 13 inches on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County, and 11 inches at the Jackson weather office. Numerous trees and power lines were downed by the heavy wet snow with widespread and long lasting power outages reported across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: One and a half inches of snow fell in Mount Carmel.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A lightning bolt hit the ground near three people that had stopped riding their motorcycles because of the heavy rain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Four motorcyclist stopped on the shoulder of a roadway because of the heavy rain.  One of them hid in a near by culvert.  While stopped,  lightning hit the ground near the three cyclists knocking them on the ground.  All three were air lifted to hospitals.  The woman had badly burned feet.  One man was very disoriented.  The third man was unconscious.  The current had entered his feet and exited his head in three places.  He died two days later in the hospital.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A complex of thunderstorms moved southeast out of Northwest Kansas into Central and South Central Kansas during the early morning hours of May 8th, 2009.  This complex of thunmderstorms would intensify over South Central Kansas during the morning and become a prolific damaging wind producer.  This swath of damaging winds, (measured at 80 to 100 mph) cut a path of destruction from just north of Wichita, Kansas to Parsons, Kansas. This storm system would continue on into Southern Missouri and eventually Southern Illinois producing widespread damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The wind was measured at the KSN TV mesonet.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Arctic air plunged southeast across eastern Nebraska and southwest Iowa on January 14th and 15th.  Temperatures fell into the single digits above and below zero during the morning hours of 1/14, recovered a little in the afternoon and then fell to 5 below to 20 below, or a bit colder, by the morning of the 15th.  Northwest winds of 20 to 30 mph with higher gusts were observed into the afternoon of the 14th before subsiding in the afternoon and evening.  This produced wind chill values of 20 below to 30 below zero over much of the region.  By around midnight on the 15th most reporting sites observed winds dropped below 10 mph and remained that way through the morning of the 15th.  However, several locations, mainly south through southeast of Omaha, recorded wind speeds of 10 to 15 mph and wind chill values colder than 20 below through around 5am CST on the 15th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: As temperatures fell into the single digits across the county during the morning of 1/14 and then below zero by the evening of the 14th,  northwest winds of 20 to 30 mph in the morning and early afternoon and 10 to 20 mph from late afternoon into late evening, produced wind chill values of 20 below to 25 below zero.  Winds dropped mostly below 10 mph by the early morning hours of 1/15 but air temperatures fell to 10 below to 20 below zero.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A disturbance in the northern branch of the jet stream was able to phase with low pressure in the southern branch of the jet stream over the Southeast Coast on the night of the 18th. These two systems combined to develop a strong area of low pressure that slowly track up the Mid-Atlantic Coast during the 19th. The low was able to tap into moisture from the Gulf of Mexico and the Atlantic Ocean causing copious amounts of precipitation to develop. High pressure to the north kept plenty of cold air in place causing the precipitation to fall in the form of snow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts between 20 and 22 inches across the county.

Precipitation began as snow, but a change over to sleet, and eventually freezing rain occurred during the afternoon and evening of the 27th. Freezing rain finally changed to rain during the afternoon of the 28th. Rain ended during the early evening hours of the 28th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ice accumulation from freezing averaged around a quarter of an inch across eastern County. Snow and sleet accumulations around 2.0 inches were also reported.
