EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong but slow-moving low pressure system began its approach to Arkansas on the 23rd. Ahead of this low, unseasonably large amounts of moisture were drawn northward from the Gulf of Mexico. The approach of the low set off heavy rain and thunderstorms on the 23rd and 24th. Rainfall amounts of 3 to 6 inches were common for the two-day period. In a broad swath from southwest Arkansas through the central part of the state into northeast Arkansas, many places picked up 7 to 10 inches of rain. Flash flooding resulted initially, followed by areal flooding and river flooding. After the low passed by, colder air spilled into Arkansas. Light snow fell across parts of northern and western Arkansas from late on the 24th into the early morning hours of Christmas Day. Most snowfall amounts were in the 1/2 to 1 inch range, with spotty totals up to 2 inches. Though the amounts were rather small, hazardous driving conditions resulted.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Jacks Creek flooded U.S. Highway 67/167 outside of Jacksonville.  A considerable traffic back-up occurred, exacerbated by the large number of people traveling for the Christmas holidays.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A warm and moist overrunning set up provided ample lift and moisture for a strong Pacific storm that hit much of Western Idaho and Eastern Oregon with heavy snow and gusty winds during the overnight hours between the fourth and fifth of January.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Baker County Sheriff's office, Oregon Deparment of Transportation and trained spotters reported from five to ten inches of snow closing Interstate 84 and many local roads as well as schools and businesses.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A complex of thunderstorms moved southeast out of Northwest Kansas into Central and South Central Kansas during the early morning hours of May 8th, 2009.  This complex of thunmderstorms would intensify over South Central Kansas during the morning and become a prolific damaging wind producer.  This swath of damaging winds, (measured at 80 to 100 mph) cut a path of destruction from just north of Wichita, Kansas to Parsons, Kansas. This storm system would continue on into Southern Missouri and eventually Southern Illinois producing widespread damage.

A persistent upper low triggered thunderstorms over the North Carolina mountains and foothills during the early morning hours of the 9th. A few of the storms produced large hail. Thunderstorms redeveloped in this same area early in the afternoon and more severe weather was reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong pressure gradient behind a cold front produced damaging winds across all of western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia, eastern Ohio, and Garrett county Maryland. Sustained winds were from 30 to 40 MPH with gusts over 60 MPH. The strongest reported wind gusts were 68 MPH in Franklin, PA and 66 MPH in Eighty Four, PA. Trees and power lines were reported down across the region, with more than 50,000 homes without power late afternoon on the 9th at the peak of the winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A moist and unstable airmass existed over the area with a broad scale upper level trough over the region. Convection developed along the sea breezes and outflows.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Palm Coast CERT members estimated wind gusts to 60 mph in West-Central Palm Coast.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large scale upper level trough continued over the eastern half of the country with a moist and unstable airmass over the local region. Mid level winds were around 30 to 40 knots with lifted indices near -8 deg C. Storms developed along the sea breezes.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Lightning struck homes in Palm Coast and Flagler Beach. Brush fires were also reported. The cost of damage was estimated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An unstable and moist airmass under prevailing southwest flow steered convection inland from the Gulf of Mexico throughout the day.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A funnel cloud was sighted and persisted for about 1 minute.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A swell generated by gale force winds northeast of the Aloha State produced surf of 10 to 25 feet along the north-facing shores of Niihau, Kauai, Oahu, Molokai, Maui, and the Big Island of Hawaii.  The swell also caused surf of 8 to 20 feet along the east-facing shores of all the same isles plus Lanai.  There were no reports of serious property damage or injuries.

Just enough instability was present in the vicinity of an upper level low pressure system in place over Eastern Kentucky with aid from a weak surface trough for the generation of isolated severe convection across Northeast Tennessee.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: One tree was reported down on Horton Highway near Jearoldstown.

The remnants from Hurricane Ida which made landfall along the Florida panhandle combined with a powerful upper level storm system along the Carolina coast. The result was a powerful low pressure system which developed near Cape Fear and tracked to Cape Hatteras. Between 3 to 6 inches of rain fell across central North Carolina over a 3 day period. Gusty winds to 35 to 45 mph combined with saturated soil resulted in power outages and some property damage from falling trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts of 40 to 45 mph along with heavy rain resulted in numerous trees falling and knocking down power lines.

CZ_NAME: SAN BERNARDINO AND RIVERSIDE COUNTY VALLEYS - THE INLAND EMPIRE
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Offshore winds quickly developed on the evening of the 23rd.The strong gusty Northeast winds mainly impacted the Inland Empire below the Cajon Pass and the Santa Ana Mountains. There was one report of a car being blown off the road and one tree down. The winds diminished overnight.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A peak wind gust of 66.4 MPH was measured by the Palm Avenue Elementary School mesonet at 0123 PST. High winds occurred between approximately 0015 PST and 0200 PST.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Lightning ignited a fire that caused damage at a home on Doolie Rd.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Lightning ignited a fire that caused damage at a home on Doolie Rd.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Cold west to southwest winds blowing across Lake Michigan produced locally heavy lake effect snow in far Northern Lower Michigan, and a small part of far Eastern Upper Michigan.  Ellsworth and Charlevoix picked up 6 to 8 inches of snow in the early morning hours of the 4th.  The snow shifted north to Emmet County later that day, with 6 inches in Brutus by mid evening, and near 10 inches just north of Pellston by morning on the 5th.  That snow band continued on to De Tour Village in Chippewa County, with 6 to 7 inches of snow there.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong center of low pressure tracked out of the plains states to the Great Lakes region. Ahead of this low in the Ohio Valley, southwest winds of 30 to 40 mph with gusts to 50 and 60 mph were common throughout the day. These strong winds peaked in the early afternoon with the passage of a cold front, and diminished later in the evening.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A few trees were blown down in various parts of the county.

The swell also caused surf of 8 to 20 feet along the east-facing shores of all the same isles plus Lanai.  There were no reports of serious property damage or injuries.

A powerful low pressure area from the Pacific and strong upper level winds brought damaging downslope winds to the southern Grande Ronde Valley and the Joseph area. Wind gusts included 88 mph 3 miles north of Joseph, which caused long term power outages and 60 mph in the North Powder area which brought down tree limbs.   Sustained winds at least 40 mph occured 5 miles west northwest of Union (44 mph) and in the North Powder area (51 mph).

Swells from powerful lows far northwest of the islands caused surf of 20 to 45 feet on north-facing shores of Niihau, Kauai, Oahu, Molokai, and Maui; 10 to 25 feet along the west-facing shores of Niihau, Kauai, Oahu, and Molokai; and 8 to 14 feet along the west-facing shores of the Big Island of Hawaii. The wrap-around effect was also in evidence as surf rose to 6 to 10 feet along the east-facing shores of Kauai, Oahu, and the Big Island. A professional surfer was injured at Waimea Beach Park on Oahu on December 7th because of the conditions. There were no reports of serious property damage, though the surf did deposit sand and other debris on coastal roads and property near the shore in several locales.

Strong post-frontal gradient winds developed on December 9th, strongest during the late morning and afternoon as a deep area of low pressure tracked into northern Lower Michigan. Widespread wind gusts between 45 and 60 mph were common across much of northern Indiana.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Very windy conditions were seen across the area on December 9th as a deep area of low pressure tracked into Michigan.  Wind gusts between 45 and 60 mph were common during the late morning and afternoon hours.  There were reports of power lines and trees down across the region due to the strong winds, which resulted in isolated power outages.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold airmass encompassed southeast New Mexico and west Texas on 12/03/09.  A shortwave trough translated eastward over the region on the night of the 3rd and resulted in 1 to 3 inches of snow across the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: One to one and a half inches of snow fell 8 miles south of Kent on 12/04/09.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level low pressure system moved slowly through the Mid-South during the time period of September 17th-September 18th, 2009. Deep moisture associated with the upper low produced several rounds of heavy rain causing flash flooding over much of the Mid-South.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain produced flash flooding around Memphis. Portions of Airways Road was flooded between Holmes and Stateline Roads. Poplar Avenue between Ridgeway and Kirby was flooded as well. The ramp at Interstate 40 and Danny Thomas Boulevard was closed due to flood water as well as many other streets in the city. As much as 3 feet of water stalled vehicles at the intersection of Avalon and Overton. A daycare center had to be evacuated due to flood water at Millbranch and East Shelby Drive.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper level low pressure system moved slowly through the Mid-South during the time period of September 17th-September 18th, 2009. Deep moisture associated with the upper low produced several rounds of heavy rain causing flash flooding over much of the Mid-South.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain flooded creeks along Bible Hill Road. The road was closed due to flood waters as a result.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain produced extensive flooding at the undepass of Shiloh Road. Numerous other roads were closed in Corinth as well.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong area of low pressure moved north across West Virginia to western Pennsylvania producing a heavy mix of precipitation. Snow accumulated 2 to 4 inches across northwest Pennsylvania on the night of the 27Th before changing to freezing rain the morning of the 28Th, then back to snow in the afternoon with another 1 to 2 inches. Ice accumulations in Pittsburgh and areas north were from a quarter to one half inch. For southeast Ohio, northern West Virgina, and Garrett county Maryland mixed precipitation changed to freezing rain during the evening of the 27Th with ice quickly accumulating to one half inch before changing to plain overnight. The rain changed back to snow during the afternoon of the 28Th with 1 to 2 inches of snow accumulating.
Scattered severe thunderstorms in advance of a cold front produced large hail, damaging winds, and one tornado across portions of central and eastern Virginia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter size hail was reported on Cumberland Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong coastal low pressure sytem tracking from the Gulf of Mexico northeast along the Carolina coast collided with cold air resulting in a a major winter storm. The heavierst snow fell across the northwest piedmont, foothills and mountains of North Carolina where up to seven inches of snow in the Triad with over two feet of snow in portions the mountains. Numerous motorists were stranded on highways and interstates west and north of Wintson Salem. Hundreds of automobile accidents were reported in the northwest piedmont.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Between 1 to 4 inches of snow fell across Orange county accumulating on all major highways from Hillsborough north. Locations around Chapel Hill received around an inch of snow while Hillsborough received 3 inches and locations north of Hillsborough received up to 4 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A disturbance in the northern branch of the jet stream was able to phase with low pressure in the southern branch of the jet stream over the Southeast Coast on the night of the 18th. These two systems combined to develop a strong area of low pressure that slowly track up the Mid-Atlantic Coast during the 19th. The low was able to tap into moisture from the Gulf of Mexico and the Atlantic Ocean causing copious amounts of precipitation to develop. High pressure to the north kept plenty of cold air in place causing the precipitation to fall in the form of snow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts between 18 and 19 inches were reported across the county.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: The observer eight miles southwest of Ontonagon measured 13 inches of snow in 24 hours.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An EF-1 tornado with winds estimated at 104 mph cut a 1.6 mile path across southeastern Washington County. The tornado went through the Ciba plant in McIntosh causing damage to the plants roofs and vehicles. No injuries were reported with this tornado.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An EF-1 tonado developed near the intersection of Topton Road and U.S. Highway 43. The tornado traveled northeast for about 1.6 miles and ended near the Ciba industrial plant. Numerous pine trees were snapped at their bases along the entire path and extensive roof damage was observed to single family residence homes. The Ciba plant experienced damage to several of its building's roofs. The high winds also blew through the glass door entry-ways of several buildings. High winds also blew out the rear windshields of an entire row of pickup trucks. One truck in the parking lot was flipped upside down and extensive tree damage occurred near the entrance to the plant.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The dry weather continued into the third week of January. Breezy conditions and low humidities contributed to an increasing number of wildfires, but few of these fires consumed more than 100 acres.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wildfire 3 miles southeast of Newport consumed only about 15 acres, but the fire spread into a mobile home park. Two vacant mobile homes were destroyed, as were a bobtail truck, a dump truck, a speedboat, and a large equipment shed containing a considerable amount of equipment.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deepening storm system, and the associated cold front that swept across Alabama, brought widespread showers and thunderstorms to the state.  Several storms produced heavy rain that caused flash flooding, along with damaging winds.  Even away from the thunderstorms, gusty gradient winds affected a large portion of Central Alabama.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A few trees were blown down in and around the city of Berry.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous county, state, and US highways became flooded across Marion County, including CR-61, US-43, CR-11, US-78, and CR-52. Taylor Road in the city of Guin, and Providence Street in the city of Winfield, were also flooded.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong post-frontal gradient winds developed on December 9th, strongest during the late morning and afternoon as a deep area of low pressure tracked into northern Lower Michigan. Widespread wind gusts between 45 and 60 mph were common across much of northern Indiana.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Very windy conditions were seen across the area on December 9th as a deep area of low pressure tracked into Michigan.  Wind gusts between 45 and 60 mph were common during the late morning and afternoon hours.  There were reports of power lines and trees down across the region due to the strong winds, which resulted in isolated power outages.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A complex of thunderstorms moved southeast out of Northwest Kansas into Central and South Central Kansas during the early morning hours of May 8th, 2009.  This complex of thunmderstorms would intensify over South Central Kansas during the morning and become a prolific damaging wind producer.  This swath of damaging winds, (measured at 80 to 100 mph) cut a path of destruction from just north of Wichita, Kansas to Parsons, Kansas. This storm system would continue on into Southern Missouri and eventually Southern Illinois producing widespread damage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two to four inches of rainfall fell in less than 30 minutes to produce lots of street flooding across Coffeyville.  5 to 10 motorists were stranded when their cars stalled in the high water.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong pressure gradient behind a cold front produced damaging winds across all of western Pennsylvania, northern West Virginia, eastern Ohio, and Garrett county Maryland. Sustained winds were from 30 to 40 MPH with gusts over 60 MPH. The strongest reported wind gusts were 68 MPH in Franklin, PA and 66 MPH in Eighty Four, PA. Trees and power lines were reported down across the region, with more than 50,000 homes without power late afternoon on the 9th at the peak of the winds.

CZ_NAME: LAGUNA MADRE FROM 5NM N OF PT MANSFIELD TO BAFFIN BAY TX
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous cold front moved through Deep South Texas and the adjacent Gulf of Mexico coastal waters toward the end of October, producing a line of strong to severe thunderstorms which began in western Kenedy County then migrated south southeast through Willacy and Cameron County, as well as the adjacent coastal waters.||Wind gusts between 55 and 65 mph were common as the storms intensified; interestingly, persistent winds within the microburst core maintained these gusts for 15 minutes or more in some areas, with up to an hour of sustained winds above Gale Force. Post-frontal winds behind the line continued with near Gale Force gusts for several hours.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A thunderstorm wind gust to 65.5 mph was recorded at the Texas Coastal Ocean Observing Network buoy near Rincon del San Jose, beginning at 1:06 PM CST and continuing until at least 1:15 PM CST until the sensor briefly went offline.

Location of marine report is approximate and is a practical eastward extension of the land report, which is less than a mile from the Laguna Madre waters.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A large and intense area of low pressure moved across the Tennessee valley and eventually up the east coast on December 18th and 19th. The initial precipitation began as a heavy wet snow on Friday afternoon December 18th. Accumulations around eastern Kentucky ranged between 1 and 4 inches. Ridgetop locations along the Virginia and west Virginia borders saw as much as 6 inches, with 13 inches reported on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County. This initial round of snow fell generally between 2 and 6 pm on the 18th. ||After several hours of nothing but rain, another round of widespread and intense snowfall began at around 10 pm. The Jackson weather office picked up 2.6 inches of snow between 10 pm and midnight on the 18th and there were 11 inches on the ground by early Saturday morning. By 7 am on Saturday December 19th 5 to 7 inches of snow blanketed the ground across much of southeast Kentucky. The highest snowfall totals for this event were 16 inches on Black Mountain, 13 inches on Flatwood Mountain in Pike County, and 11 inches at the Jackson weather office. Numerous trees and power lines were downed by the heavy wet snow with widespread and long lasting power outages reported across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Three inches of snow was measured on the ground on Card Mountain along Highway 460 in southern Pike county near Dorton. The snow began falling around 330 pm.

CZ_NAME: LAGUNA MADRE FROM PORT OF BROWNSVILLE TO ARROYO COLORADO
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous cold front moved through Deep South Texas and the adjacent Gulf of Mexico coastal waters toward the end of October, producing a line of strong to severe thunderstorms which began in western Kenedy County then migrated south southeast through Willacy and Cameron County, as well as the adjacent coastal waters.||Wind gusts between 55 and 65 mph were common as the storms intensified; interestingly, persistent winds within the microburst core maintained these gusts for 15 minutes or more in some areas, with up to an hour of sustained winds above Gale Force. EVENT_NARRATIVE: Wind gusts associated with a line of strong thunderstorms preceding a cold front increased to just over 37 knots at the Port Isabel C-MAN station, located a mile from the southmost portion of the Laguna Madre.  Gusts at or above gale force (34 knots) continued for 18 minutes, and returned an hour later as the frontal gradient moved across the area.

CZ_NAME: LAGUNA MADRE FROM PORT OF BROWNSVILLE TO ARROYO COLORADO
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A few clusters of thunderstorms developed in the Laguna Madre, initially between South Padre Island and Port Isabel, but moved north to the Cameron/Willacy County line before moving into the Gulf waters and weakening rapidly, during the late afternoon of October 25th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Texas Coastal Ocean Observing Network location at the Realitos Peninsula recorded a wind gust just above 34 knots from a pulse thunderstorm.

CZ_NAME: LAGUNA MADRE FROM PORT OF BROWNSVILLE TO ARROYO COLORADO
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A few clusters of thunderstorms developed in the Laguna Madre, initially between South Padre Island and Port Isabel, but moved north to the Cameron/Willacy County line before moving into the Gulf waters and weakening rapidly, during the late afternoon of October 25th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A quick moving pulse thunderstorm that raced northward across the Laguna Madre produced a quick moving microburst that produced gale force gusts earlier between Port Isabel and South Padre Island also produced a brief gale force gust along the Realitos Peninsula, as recorded by the Texas Coastal Ocean Observation Network.

CZ_NAME: LAGUNA MADRE FROM PORT OF BROWNSVILLE TO ARROYO COLORADO

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A developing small cluster of pulse thunderstorms moved through the south end of the Laguna Madre during the late afternoon October 25th, producing a brief downburst of gale force gusts as recorded by the Port Isabel C-MAN site.  Gusts lasted for at least six minutes.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful low pressure area from the Pacific and strong upper level winds brought damaging downslope winds to the southern Grande Ronde Valley and the Joseph area. Wind gusts included 88 mph 3 miles north of Joseph, which caused long term power outages and 60 mph in the North Powder area which brought down tree limbs.   Sustained winds at least 40 mph occured 5 miles west northwest of Union (44 mph) and in the North Powder area (51 mph).

A deep low pressure system tracking across the Cascade Mountains and lower Columbia Basin produced a tight pressure gradient and strong downslope winds.  Wind gusts in mph were Hot Lake (63) and 5 miles west northwest of Union (59).  Trees were knocked down blocking the road in Wasco County 5 miles west of Pine Grove and 15 miles west of Pine Grove.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A light mix of sleet and snow developed over the mountains and foothills of western North Carolina during the evening, and continued for much of the overnight. Affected roads included Airport Rd, King St, Grove St, and Fruitland Rd.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong area of low pressure moved north across West Virginia to western Pennsylvania producing a heavy mix of precipitation. Snow accumulated 2 to 4 inches across northwest Pennsylvania on the night of the 27Th before changing to freezing rain the morning of the 28Th, then back to snow in the afternoon with another 1 to 2 inches. Ice accumulations in Pittsburgh and areas north were from a quarter to one half inch. For southeast Ohio, northern West Virgina, and Garrett county Maryland mixed precipitation changed to freezing rain during the evening of the 27Th with ice quickly accumulating to one half inch before changing to plain overnight. The rain changed back to snow during the afternoon of the 28Th with 1 to 2 inches of snow accumulating.

An area of low pressure tracked through the Tennessee Valley into the Ohio Valley on the 27th spreading precipitation across northern and central Virginia. Precipitation began as snow, but a change over to sleet, and eventually freezing rain occurred from south to north during the afternoon and evening of the 27th. Freezing rain finally changed to rain from south to north during the morning and afternoon hours of the 28th. Rain ended during the early evening hours of the 28th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Ice accumulation around a quarter inch was reported across the county. Snow and sleet accumulation 1 inch was estimated across the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong coastal low pressure sytem tracking from the Gulf of Mexico northeast along the Carolina coast collided with cold air resulting in a a major winter storm. The heavierst snow fell across the northwest piedmont, foothills and mountains of North Carolina where up to seven inches of snow in the Triad with over two feet of snow in portions the mountains. Numerous motorists were stranded on highways and interstates west and north of Wintson Salem. Hundreds of automobile accidents were reported in the northwest piedmont.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Between one to two inches of snow fell across the county. Several automobile accidents were reported the evening of December 18th.  Precipitation changed over to rain by the morning of December 19th. Northern sections of Franklin county experienced around 2 inches of snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow moving cold front tracked across the Mid-South on October 9th. Numerous showers and thunderstorms ahead of the front produced some flash flooding in portions of northeast Arkansas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A bridge off Millcreek Road had water covering it. Over three inches of rain fell in the area over several hours.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A roof was blown off of a shed. Several power lines were blown down on Billhill Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A two pronged winter storm moved across the region during the period of December 6th through December the 8th, 2009.  The initial system on December 6th spread a thin layer of freezing drizzle across portions of Central Kansas, which produced numerous automobile accidents with one leading to a death.  A more potent low pressure area tracked along the Kansas/Oklahoma border on December 7th and 8th, 2009.  This system led to a band of heavy snow across Central Kansas with a band of 6 to 12 inches along a line from Great Bend, Kansas to Salina, Kansas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall amounts of 2 to 4 inches produced 18 accidents across the county.  One such accident occurred along Interstate 135 when a vehicle slid into a semi tractor trailer.  The driver of the car was seriously injured and taken to the hospital.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A mixture of freezing drizzle, sleet and light snow made driving conditions treacherous across the county.  A combination of rollovers, slide-offs and spin arounds led to 133 accidents during the morning rush hour.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure tracked east across the Carolinas, then pushed offshore, dumping two to four inches of snow across much of the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow began falling the morning of January 20th, and spotters in Tar Heel and White Lake reported four inches of accumulation by midday, with two and a half inches reported in Elizabethtown. Many businesses were closed, and all schools were closed. No weather related traffic accidents were relayed to the National Weather Service.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow moving storm along the California coast brought strong winds to the Central High Plains on the 3rd, while snow fell over much of the west and north on the 4th into the 5th.
A slow moving storm along the California coast brought strong winds to the Central High Plains on the 3rd, while snow fell over much of the west and north on the 4th into the 5th.
Five mornings of temperatures in the single digits to the teens resulted in one death due to exposure on New Years Day.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 42 year old male was found dead in his truck, apparently as a result of continued exposure to the cold.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front brought heavy showers to the islands toward the end of January.  The boundary caused small stream and drainage ditch flooding, and ponding of roadways.  No serious property damage or injuries were reported.

A cold front brought heavy showers to the islands toward the end of January.  The boundary caused small stream and drainage ditch flooding, and ponding of roadways.  No serious property damage or injuries were reported.

Strong north to northwest winds, gusting to over 50 mph, combined with existing loose snow cover and 1 to 3 inches of new snow to produce blizzard conditions with widespread visibilities near zero over parts of southeast South Dakota during the day and early evening of January 12th. The very low visibilities were widespread where the greatest loose snow cover was located, and more localized in other areas.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: North to northwest winds sustained at 30 to 40 mph with gusts over 50 mph combined with several inches of loose snow cover, along with 1 to 3 inches of new snow, to produce widespread visibilities of a quarter mile or less in blowing snow. The low visibilities and drifting snow made travel impossible in many areas, and forced schools and businesses to close.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong post-frontal gradient winds developed on December 9th, strongest during the late morning and afternoon as a deep area of low pressure tracked into northern Lower Michigan. Widespread wind gusts between 45 and 60 mph were common across much of northern Indiana.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Very windy conditions were seen across the area on December 9th as a deep area of low pressure tracked into Michigan.  Wind gusts between 45 and 60 mph were common during the late morning and afternoon hours.  There were reports of power lines and trees down across the region due to the strong winds, which resulted in isolated power outages.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A fast moving trough resulted in strong winds across Southeast Arizona with blowing dust on December 22nd along with heavy snow in the higher elevations of Northern Greenlee County.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong winds caused damage to power lines at the intersection of Irvington Road and 12th Avenue in south Tucson.  The winds resulted in low hanging power lines which created a traffic hazard.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The second powerful winter storm in a week raced through the region on December 12th and 13th. The storm brought high winds, heavy rain, and caused minor to moderate damage. Wind gusts in the high desert reached an impressive 100 MPH! The wind and heavy rain contributed to many downed trees, power outages, minor roadway flooding, and a flash flood. Parts of Highway 18 in the San Bernardino Mountains were closed due to large rocks on the roadway. In Perris, two people had to be rescued from a vehicle that had become trapped in a flooded intersection.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two 4 foot by 8 foot signs fell over on cars in Wrightwood due to strong winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The second powerful winter storm in a week raced through the region on December 12th and 13th. The storm brought high winds, heavy rain, and caused minor to moderate damage. Wind gusts in the high desert reached an impressive 100 MPH! The wind and heavy rain contributed to many downed trees, power outages, minor roadway flooding, and a flash flood. Parts of Highway 18 in the San Bernardino Mountains were closed due to large rocks on the roadway. In Perris, two people had to be rescued from a vehicle that had become trapped in a flooded intersection.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Excessive runoff from the heavy rain in the San Bernardino Mountains produced strong currents in the Whitewater River wash, which caused an earthen berm at a percolation basin in Palm Springs to collapse. The water then continued to flow through the wash and across several streets, bringing large amounts of mud and debris with it. Indian Canyon Road, Gene Autry Road, and Vista Chino road, all of which lie across the wash's natural path, were closed due to flooding. Three cars were swept off the road during the flood - two on Indian Canyon Drive and one on Vista Chino. One of the percolation ponds also sustained damage.

Widespread dense fog developed across most of western Kentucky except the Henderson and Owensboro areas. Visibility was below one-quarter mile. There was a report of visibility only near 25 feet at Hopkinsville. Since temperatures were below freezing, light icing occurred in the thick fog. A light south wind flow of milder air over the snow and ice-covered ground set the stage for dense fog.

Low pressure tracked from the Oklahoma panhandle into the Ohio Valley from February 13th through the 14th.  This system brought heavy snow to around a 50 mile wide swath across eastern Nebraska and western Iowa generally along and north of Interstate 80 in eastern Nebraska and along and south of the interstate in western Iowa.  The heaviest snow stretched from Columbus and David City Nebraska east through Omaha and then to Underwood and Oakland Iowa.  On the southern end the snowfall tapered down to several inches from southeast Nebraska into far southwest Iowa.  Meanwhile, the snow ended rather abruptly on the northern end with little or no snow measured along and north of a line from Norfolk Nebraska to Little Sioux Iowa.  Heavier snow totals in Nebraska included 7.5 inches in David City and 6 to 8 inches across much of the Omaha metro area including 6.8 inches at the NWS office near Valley and 5.5 inches at Omaha Eppley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow fell over all of Sarpy county with 7 inches reported by cooperative observers in Gretna and Bellevue and 6.5 inches by the coop observer in Papillion.

An area of low pressure over the southeastern states on the morning of the 1st moved northeast along the coast to just east of the Delmarva Peninsula by the morning of the 2nd and then into the Canadian Maritimes by the morning of the 3rd.  The storm brought heavy snow to most of western Maine, except in the mountains where lighter amounts fell.  Snowfall amounts ranged from 2 to 4 inches in the western Maine mountains to 6 to 10 inches along the coast and interior.

An area of low pressure over the mid Mississippi Valley on the morning of the 8th moved to the mid Atlantic States by the morning of the 9th and then well out to sea by the morning of the 10th.  The low brought heavy snow to southern sections of interior Rockingham County where amounts ranged from 5 to 9 inches.  Generally, 4 to 6 inches of snow fell across Merrimack, Sullivan, Belknap, Strafford, and southern Carroll and southern Grafton Counties.  Lesser amounts fell to the north.

A weather disturbance extending from the Gulf Coast States to Kentucky brought a widespread snowfall to Eastern Kentucky beginning late in the afternoon of March 12th, lasting into the early morning hours of March 13th. Sleet was reported in many locations, along with some freezing rain. In general, one to four inches of snow fell across the area, with locally higher amounts where the heavier snow and sleet persisted.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An inch of snow fell in North Corbin.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of thunderstorms tracked across extreme southeast Kansas and southern Missouri from west to east.  Several observations of wind damage occurred along the line, along with a few observations of marginally severe hail.  One tornado touched down on the northern edge of Nixa, which damaged more than a dozen homes.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A National Weather Service storm survey revealed that an EF-0 tornado touched down along the northwestern edge of Nixa and tracked to near Highway 160 between Tracker Road and Highway CC.  Wind speeds were estimated at 80 mph which damaged more than a dozen homes.

The storms evolved into a quasi-linear convective system (QLCS) with embedded mesocyclones, one of which became tornadic.  There were also a few reports of large hail and damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter-sized hail was reported to the media by the public.  The hail lasted 3 to 5 minutes.

A strong upper level low pressure system moved through Arkansas during the night of February 28th, 2009. The upper level low produced bands of snow across North Mississippi during the evening hours which continued into the early morning hours of March 1st, 2009. Total snow accumulations ranged from an inch to as much as 5 inches. The hardest hit area was along the Tennessee Border from Southaven in DeSoto County to Corinth in Alcorn County. Roads were hazardous as a result of the snow and many accidents occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An additional 1-3 inches of snow fell across Benton County during the early morning hours of March 1st. Total snow accumulations during the February 28th-March 1st, 2009 snow storm was around 5 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deepening low pressure center tracked north-northeast from northeast Texas to eastern Missouri. A strong southerly wind flow brought abundant moisture northward across the Lower Ohio Valley and southeast Missouri. Widespread rainfall amounts from two to four inches occurred, with up to six inches in the hilly terrain north and west of Poplar Bluff.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A few state roads were closed due to flooding. State Route K was closed just north of Route B. State Route M was closed seven miles north of U.S. Highway 60. State Route Z was closed two miles south of Route 103.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A few state roads were closed due to flooding, including sections of Routes D and E.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An well-defined upper level disturbance moved east into the southern plains during the late afternoon and early evening hours. Thunderstorms developed over the panhandles and southwest Kansas and congealed into a complex as it moved into western Oklahoma. Thunderstorms were able to sustain themselves as the low-level jet developed by mid evening. Thunderstorms earlier in the day stabilized the atmosphere, with cut down on storm intensity during the late evening. However, strong winds were reported over several locations as the thunderstorms moved into eastern Oklahoma by the late night hours. The strongest winds were reported in Kiowa county, where a gust of 68 was measured. No damage was reported with the thunderstorms.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Rain changed to snow during the early evening across portions of the foothills and the western Piedmont of North Carolina. Snow became heavy at times throughout the evening, and up to 4 inches had accumulated across the area by 10 pm. Snow, heavy at times and accompanied by occasional lightning, continued into the late evening and early overnight hours. By the time the snow tapered off, accumulations of 3-6 inches were common across the area. However, localized amounts of up to 9 inches were reported, especially along a corridor extending from Shelby to Hickory. The heavy wet snow caused quite a few trees and power lines to fall, resulting in numerous power outages. Some structures received minor to moderate roof damage due to the weight of the snow. Some customers were without power for several days. A tree fell on the library in Belmont, NC, causing damage to the roof. Numerous traffic accidents also occurred.

Rain changed to snow across the southwest foothills of North Carolina  during the late afternoon. The snow became heavy at times, particularly along the I-85 corridor. By mid-evening, 1-4 inches of accumulation was reported across much of the area. Snow, heavy at times, and accompanied by occasional lightning, continued into the evening hours. By the time the snow tapered off, accumulations of 3-6 inches were common across the area. However, localized amounts of up to 8 inches were reported along the I-85 corridor.  The heavy wet snow, combined with gusty winds, caused quite a few trees and power lines to fall, resulting in numerous power outages. Some customers were without power for several days. One tree fell on and damaged a home in Gaffney. In addition, there were numerous traffic accidents.

Mainly non-thunderstorm winds occurred during the afternoon and evening hours of February 11th. A High Wind Warning was in effect for the day as well as portions of the days on either side. A strong low pressure system moved across Illinois and northern Indiana with a trailing cold front that passed through Indiana. An intense pressure gradient ahead of the front and strong pressure rises behind the front caused very strong winds to blow. A saturated ground from recent snow melt and new rainfall may have contributed to the reports of downed trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was blown onto a mobile home. Wind gusts were estimated between 50 and 60 MPH.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front moved through the region triggering showers and thunderstorms. Damaging winds, large hail and tornadoes were reported with the storms.
A strong cold front moved through the region triggering showers and thunderstorms. Damaging winds, large hail and tornadoes were reported with the storms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tornado touched down about a quarter of a mile north of Rosedale.  The roof of a machine shed was lifted off and tossed 50 to 75 yards to the north northeast.  The tornado then skipped along and north of Fieldon Rosedale Road.  There was mainly large limb and isolated tree damage along this path.  One area of large tree damage was located southwest of the intersection of Fieldon Rosedale Road and Otter Creek Road.  A water pump house was nearly destroyed at this location before the tornado lifted and dissipated.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed over West Tennessee during the late evening hours of February 17th, 2009. The thunderstorms developed out ahead of a developing low pressure system located over the Central Plains. Some of the thunderstorms became severe producing large hail.

A weak cold front moved through the region during the overnight hours of March 24th and had stalled across southeast Texas into southwest and south central Louisiana.  During the afternoon and overnight hours of March 25th...a strong upper level disturbance moved across the Texas Hill Country and into the region from the west.  The result was widespread shower and thunderstorm activity...some of which produced large hail...damaging thunderstorm wind gusts...as well as isolated tornadoes across portions of the region.  The atmosphere ahead of the storm system was moderately unstable but dynamics aloft were primed for the formation of strong to severe convection.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees were down near the town of Haughton, Louisiana.

Widespread dense fog developed across most of western Kentucky except the Henderson and Owensboro areas. Visibility was below one-quarter mile. There was a report of visibility only near 25 feet at Hopkinsville. Since temperatures were below freezing, light icing occurred in the thick fog. A light south wind flow of milder air over the snow and ice-covered ground set the stage for dense fog.

The combination of a stalled out warm front through the area and the approach of a strong cold front, resulted in numerous strong to severe thunderstorms across southern South Carolina and southeast Georgia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Law Enforcement reported an awning torn down at Liberty Tire and Brake off of Highway 84. Power lines were also reported down on Gausett Pafford Road in Hinesville, Georgia.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An approaching storm system ushered in the warmest air of the month on the 7th. The warm front associated with this system stalled across northern Illinois and Indiana. As a wave passed along this front, rain of 2 to 4 inches fell in the Tippecanoe River Basin from the afternoon of the 7th through the late morning hour of the 8th.||This rain had an immediate impact on the Tippecanoe River. By the evening of the 8th, extensive flooding quickly developed. The warm front remained over northern Illinois and Indiana and after about 24|hours another wave brought 2 to 4 inches of rain to the Tippecanoe River Basin from the evening of the 9th through the morning of the 11th.||With extensive flooding already in progress and saturated ground conditions, major flooding quickly developed along the Tippecanoe River by the morning of the 11th. Flood crests were similar to those|of February 2008.||Many local river residents listened to the Carroll County EMA director about the potential for serious flooding and voluntarily left their homes on the 9th and 10th. A few chose to ride out the flood. Some of these people needed rescued.||Because the heaviest rain was confined to northern Indiana, only the Wabash River in western Indiana and eastern Illinois flooded. This was the 3rd time since late December that extensive lowland flooding occurred along the Wabash. The March flood exceeded the previous two floods from Lafayette to just downstream of Terre Haute on the Wabash River.||The biggest problem caused by the flood along the Wabash was the inconvenience to local traffic that normally used State Road 43, State Road 225 and local roads in the Grandville Bridge area. The flood also caused disruption to the construction of a natural gas pipeline going from the Rocky Mountains to the east coast. This was third delay in three months to construction of the pipeline underneath the Wabash in the Montezuma area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Extensive flooding occurred along the Wabash River in and near Covington, IN. The river crested 9.69 feet above flood stage at the Covington river gauge on March 13th, a reading of 25.69 feet.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The second day in a row of widespread severe weather affected southwest Louisiana, with numerous reports of large hail and damaging winds.  The damage in St. Mary Parish from these severe thunderstorms was considered worse than the damage from Hurricane Gustav in September 2008.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure center lifted northeast from the southern Plains into the Great Lakes.  A tight pressure gradient resulted in strong southerly winds ahead of an associated dry line and pressure trough which pushed eastward through the Tennessee Valley.  A broken line of showers and isolated thunderstorms developed along the dry line during the late morning hours, and swept rapidly east across the Tennessee Valley during the early afternoon hours.  Although a couple of reports of wind damage occurred with the showers and thunderstorms, the more prominent impact was due to damaging non-thunderstorm winds ahead of and immediately behind the dry line passage.  Numerous trees were blown down resulting in sporadic power outages.  There were also a few reports of minor roof damage and a couple of car accidents due to the high winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorm winds damaged trees along Zierdt Road in Triana.

One tornado touched down on the northern edge of Nixa, which damaged more than a dozen homes.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level low pressure system moved through Arkansas during the night of February 28th, 2009. The upper level low produced bands of snow across East Arkansas during the evening hours which continued into the early morning hours of March 1st, 2009. Total snow accumulations ranged from 2 inches to as much as 12 inches. The hardest hit area was portions of Mississippi County from Blytheville to Wilson, where up to a foot of snow fell. Roads were hazardous as a result of the snow and many accidents occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Around two inches of snow fell across Phillips County during the early morning hours of March 1st. Total snow accumulation during the February 28th-March 1st, 2009 snow storm was around 2 inches.

A stationary frontal boundary was located east to west near the Interstate 20 corridor of northern Louisiana. Low level moisture was rapidly returning to the region with the aid of a low level jet which overran the surface boundary during the late evening hours of March 27th. This coupled with a strong upper level atmospheric trough which was moving south and east out of the Oklahoma and Texas Panhandle region. The upper level storm system provided the lift needed for strong to severe thunderstorms to form across the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Police department reported several trees downed in and around Jonesboro, Louisiana.

Thunderstorms developed during heating of the afternoon over parts of Southern Oklahoma. Temperatures reached into the 90s, making temperature-dew point spreads on the order of 30-40 degrees. Instability was minimal, but a few thunderstorms were able to produce very strong winds, causing some minor damage in Stephens county. |At the same time, numerous thunderstorms developed ahead of a cold front that moved into northwest Oklahoma during the afternoon hours of the 26th. These thunderstorms developed through the evening hours, with the aid of convergence along the front, and lift associated with an upper level storm system moving through the central plains. The thunderstorms formed into several complexes due to the presence of numerous outflow boundaries. Surface moisture and instability along and just behind the front were sufficient for the thunderstorms to become severe. The thunderstorms moved off to the east with strong winds and large hail reported. A landspout developed over southwest Kingfisher county, remaining nearly stationary for over 10 minutes. No damage was reported with the landspout.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Quarter to golf ball-size hail was reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Despite significant snowfall during the first week of month, followed by warm temperatures that melted all the snow cover, flooding was not a problem until the 11th.  Rain of 1/2 to 3 1/2 inches fell in east central Illinois and much of Indiana on this day. The rain caused the most extensive flooding seen since June 2008. Because snow cover had previously melted and ground previously greatly thawed, significant flooding only occurred in portions of west central Indiana. Significant flooding lasted less than a day in most areas. River flooding lasted from a few days to two weeks. Uneventful and generally dry weather prevailed  after this episode through the 26th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flooding occurred along the Wabash River in Sullivan County, including in and near Riverton, due to heavy rain.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front moved through the region triggering showers and thunderstorms. Damaging winds, large hail and tornadoes were reported with the storms.

In general, one to four inches of snow fell across the area, with locally higher amounts where the heavier snow and sleet persisted.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak cold front moved through the region during the overnight hours of March 24th and had stalled across southeast Texas into southwest and south central Louisiana.  During the afternoon and overnight hours of March 25th...a strong upper level disturbance moved across the Texas Hill Country and into the region from the west.  The result was widespread shower and thunderstorm activity...some of which produced large hail...damaging thunderstorm wind gusts...as well as isolated tornadoes across portions of the region.  The atmosphere ahead of the storm system was moderately unstable but dynamics aloft were primed for the formation of strong to severe convection.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A large tree fell across Pock Street blocking the street in Mansfield, Louisiana.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Soaking rains over a four-day period beginning on the 7th provided the region with nearly all of the months precipitationbetween 2 and 3 inches. The rain combined with the melting winter snowpack and frozen ground to result in widespread flooding on area rivers and creeks. There were numerous reports of road closures along those rivers and creeks. This was the third winter flood event this seasona rare occurrence in western New York. |Specific river/creek crest information follows:  Cazenovia Creek at Ebenezer (flood stage 10 feet) crested at 11.51 feet at 3AM on the 8th. Cayuga Creek at Lancaster (flood stage 8 feet) crested at 9.31 feet at 5AM on the 8th. Buffalo Creek at Gardenville (flood stage 7 feet) crested at 7.71 feet at 4AM on the 8th. Ellicott Creek at Williamsville (flood stage 8 feet) crested at 8.04 feet at 2AM on the 9th. Black Creek at Churchville (flood stage 6 feet) crested at 6.48 feet at 5PM on the 9th. Oatka Creek at Garbutt (flood stage 6 feet) crested at 6.70 feet at 2PM on the 9th. Allegheny River at Olean (flood stage 10 feet) crested at 10.34 feet at 11AM on the 11th. Tonawanda Creek at Batavia (flood stage 9 feet) crested at 10.57 feet at 11PM on the 8th; and at Rapids (flood stage 12 feet) crested at 13.68 feet at 6AM on the 11th.

A strong low pressure center moved northeast from Oklahoma into south central Missouri by late afternoon, with a warm front extending east from the low across western Kentucky. The warm front served as a focusing mechanism for some of the ingredients needed for tornadogenesis.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A semi truck was overturned on Interstate 24 near mile marker 88.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure center moved northeast from Oklahoma into south central Missouri by late afternoon, with a warm front extending east from the low across western Kentucky. The warm front served as a focusing mechanism for some of the ingredients needed for tornadogenesis. While most of the severe weather occurred in western Kentucky, a supercell produced a funnel cloud over the Evansville area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The supercell thunderstorm that produced a strong tornado over Henderson County, Kentucky crossed the Ohio River. A rotating funnel cloud was reported at the intersection of the Lloyd Expressway and Interstate 164 in Evansville.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of thunderstorms impacted portions of the Missouri Ozarks during the morning of 24 March.  A few of these storms became marginally severe producing large hail and damaging winds.  Heavy rain caused flash flooding to occur in several areas.

A slow moving cold front approached eastern North Carolina from the northwest during the afternoon of March 27th 2009. Weak instability developed ahead of the front and isolated thunderstorms developed during the early evening hours as an upper level disturbance crossed the region. Two tornadoes developed with the isolated thunderstorms over the inland sections of eastern North Carolina.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: NWS Survey revealed an EF-1 tornado with winds estimated between 105 to 110 miles an hours touched down just west of Hookerton. The tornado produced minor to moderate damage to several homes and snapped several trees off. The tornado had a path length of nearly one mile and was about 100 yards wide.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A slow moving cold front approached eastern North Carolina from the northwest during the afternoon of March 27th 2009. Weak instability developed ahead of the front and isolated thunderstorms developed during the early evening hours as an upper level disturbance crossed the region. Two tornadoes developed with the isolated thunderstorms over the inland sections of eastern North Carolina.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: NWS survey revealed an EF-1 tornado with winds estimated between 85 and 90 mph touched down just southeast of Greenville. The tornado was on the ground a little over one half mile and was about one hundred yards wide. The tornado did minor damage to about forty homes off Ashcroft Drive resulting in about two hundred thousand dollars in damage.

Snowfall amounts ranged from 2 to 4 inches in the western Maine mountains to 6 to 10 inches along the coast and interior.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A major winter storm affected the region from January 27th through the 28th, producing snow, sleet, freezing rain, and plain rain across Eastern Kentucky. This occurred as a low pressure system moved northeast from the Gulf Coast states on the 27th, reaching Eastern Kentucky on the 28th. Runoff from the precipitation led to flooding of streams, creeks, and rivers, across portions of Eastern Kentucky. The flooding lingered in some areas through January 30th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous roads were flooded due to the ice and debris in the Red River causing it to overflow its banks. Roads closures included Pompeii, Adams Ridge, Rosslyn, Bowen and Maple Street. These roads were all in the Clay City and Stanton areas.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure center lifted northeast from the southern Plains into the Great Lakes.  A tight pressure gradient resulted in strong southerly winds ahead of an associated dry line and pressure trough which pushed eastward through the Tennessee Valley.  A broken line of showers and isolated thunderstorms developed along the dry line during the late morning hours, and swept rapidly east across the Tennessee Valley during the early afternoon hours.  Although a couple of reports of wind damage occurred with the showers and thunderstorms, the more prominent impact was due to damaging non-thunderstorm winds ahead of and immediately behind the dry line passage.  Numerous trees were blown down resulting in sporadic power outages.  There were also a few reports of minor roof damage and a couple of car accidents due to the high winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorm winds produced power outages in the Sherwood Park area of Huntsville, near Alabama A & M University, in Hazel Green, Toney and New Market.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low-topped supercell thunderstorms developed along a powerful cold front during the late afternoon of the 28th.  The storms evolved into a quasi-linear convective system (QLCS) with embedded mesocyclones, one of which became tornadic.  There were also a few reports of large hail and damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tornado snapped numerous trees and uprooted several cedar tree trunks along a 1.5 mile path north of U.S. highway 64 between Huntland and Maxwell.  Shingles and roof panels of a home and a barn were peeled back along Stratton Road and Pleasant Ridge Road near Branchville.

A strong upper level low pressure system moved through Arkansas during the night of February 28th, 2009. The upper level low produced bands of snow across East Arkansas during the evening hours which continued into the early morning hours of March 1st, 2009. Total snow accumulations ranged from 2 inches to as much as 12 inches. The hardest hit area was portions of Mississippi County from Blytheville to Wilson, where up to a foot of snow fell. Roads were hazardous as a result of the snow and many accidents occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An additional inch or less of snow fell across Poinsett County during the early morning hours of March 1st. Total snow accumulation during the February 28th-March 1st, 2009 snow storm was around 2-3 inches.

Widespread dense fog developed across most of western Kentucky except the Henderson and Owensboro areas. Visibility was below one-quarter mile. There was a report of visibility only near 25 feet at Hopkinsville. Since temperatures were below freezing, light icing occurred in the thick fog. A light south wind flow of milder air over the snow and ice-covered ground set the stage for dense fog.

A stationary frontal boundary was located east to west near the Interstate 20 corridor of northern Louisiana. Low level moisture was rapidly returning to the region with the aid of a low level jet which overran the surface boundary during the late evening hours of March 27th. This coupled with a strong upper level atmospheric trough which was moving south and east out of the Oklahoma and Texas Panhandle region. The upper level storm system provided the lift needed for strong to severe thunderstorms to form across the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several trees were snapped along Interstate 20 about 2 miles west of Well Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Rain changed to snow during the early evening across portions of the foothills and the western Piedmont of North Carolina. Snow became heavy at times throughout the evening, and up to 4 inches had accumulated across the area by 10 pm. Snow, heavy at times and accompanied by occasional lightning, continued into the late evening and early overnight hours. By the time the snow tapered off, accumulations of 3-6 inches were common across the area. However, localized amounts of up to 9 inches were reported, especially along a corridor extending from Shelby to Hickory. The heavy wet snow caused quite a few trees and power lines to fall, resulting in numerous power outages. Some structures received minor to moderate roof damage due to the weight of the snow. Some customers were without power for several days. A tree fell on the library in Belmont, NC, causing damage to the roof. Numerous traffic accidents also occurred.

Mainly non-thunderstorm winds occurred during the afternoon and evening hours of February 11th. A High Wind Warning was in effect for the day as well as portions of the days on either side. A strong low pressure system moved across Illinois and northern Indiana with a trailing cold front that passed through Indiana. An intense pressure gradient ahead of the front and strong pressure rises behind the front caused very strong winds to blow. A saturated ground from recent snow melt and new rainfall may have contributed to the reports of downed trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Indiana Department of Environmental Management equipment recorded the gust to 65 MPH.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An approaching storm system ushered in the warmest air of the month on the 7th. The warm front associated with this system stalled across northern Illinois and Indiana. As a wave passed along this front, rain of 2 to 4 inches fell in the Tippecanoe River Basin from the afternoon of the 7th through the late morning hour of the 8th.||This rain had an immediate impact on the Tippecanoe River. By the evening of the 8th, extensive flooding quickly developed. The warm front remained over northern Illinois and Indiana and after about 24|hours another wave brought 2 to 4 inches of rain to the Tippecanoe River Basin from the evening of the 9th through the morning of the 11th.||With extensive flooding already in progress and saturated ground conditions, major flooding quickly developed along the Tippecanoe River by the morning of the 11th. Flood crests were similar to those|of February 2008.||Many local river residents listened to the Carroll County EMA director about the potential for serious flooding and voluntarily left their homes on the 9th and 10th. A few chose to ride out the flood. Some of these people needed rescued.||Because the heaviest rain was confined to northern Indiana, only the Wabash River in western Indiana and eastern Illinois flooded. This was the 3rd time since late December that extensive lowland flooding occurred along the Wabash. The March flood exceeded the previous two floods from Lafayette to just downstream of Terre Haute on the Wabash River.||The biggest problem caused by the flood along the Wabash was the inconvenience to local traffic that normally used State Road 43, State Road 225 and local roads in the Grandville Bridge area. The flood also caused disruption to the construction of a natural gas pipeline going from the Rocky Mountains to the east coast. This was third delay in three months to construction of the pipeline underneath the Wabash in the Montezuma area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Extensive flooding of agricultural land occurred along the Wabash River near Lyford, IN, and across the river from Clinton. The river crested 6.1 feet above flood stage at the Clinton river gauge on March 14th with a reading of 24.1 feet. Data is estimated due to missing data.

By the time the snow tapered off, accumulations of 3-6 were common across the area. However, localized amounts of up to 8 inches were reported along the I-85 corridor.  The heavy wet snow, combined with gusty winds, caused quite a few trees and power lines to fall, resulting in numerous power outages. Some customers were without power for several days. One tree fell on and damaged a home in Gaffney. In addition, there were numerous traffic accidents.

Rain of 1/2 to 3 1/2 inches fell in east central Illinois and much of Indiana on this day. The rain caused the most extensive flooding seen since June 2008. Because snow cover had previously melted and ground previously greatly thawed, significant flooding only occurred in portions of west central Indiana. Significant flooding lasted less than a day in most areas. River flooding lasted from a few days to two weeks. Uneventful and generally dry weather prevailed  after this episode through the 26th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Extensive lowland flooding occurred along the Wabash River in Knox County, including near Mount Carmel, Illinois, due to heavy rain.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weather disturbance extending from the Gulf Coast States to Kentucky brought a widespread snowfall to Eastern Kentucky beginning late in the afternoon of March 12th, lasting into the early morning hours of March 13th. Sleet was reported in many locations, along with some freezing rain. In general, one to four inches of snow fell across the area, with locally higher amounts where the heavier snow and sleet persisted.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Five and a half inches of snow fell in Tuttle.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: South winds developed over the Tehachapi Mountains on March 27th, and downsloped into the south end of the San Joaquin Valley. Temperatures warmed to well above normal, with Bakersfield reaching a high of 85 degrees. The low at Meadows Field on the 27th was 56 degrees, which was just 1 degree from the record high minimum temperature for the date (57 degrees in 1978). The winds subsided during the night as an upper-level ridge of high pressure moved over the San Joaquin Valley. This ridge brought continued well-above-normal temperatures to the Valley on March 28th. Fresno had a high of 81 degrees, the first 80-degree day since November 18th, 2008. Bakersfield warmed to 87 degrees, just missing a 106-year-old record high of 88, set in 1893. The 87 degrees at Meadows Field was the warmest day in March for Bakersfield. Likewise, Fresnos 81 degrees was its warmest day for the month.|An upper-level disturbance tracked across the Pacific Northwest during the night of March 28th-29th, then dropped into the Great Basin. Although this disturbance did not bring any precipitation to the region, it did bring gusty winds to the Kern County|mountains and deserts on the 29th, and even some locally gusty winds to the San Joaquin Valley during the afternoon and evening. Gusts to around 40 mph were widespread across the San Joaquin Valley floor, and gusts in the mountains and deserts were between 45 and 50 mph.|March ended with a dry upper-level disturbance moving into the Pacific Northwest and California. This disturbance brought another round of gusty west winds to the Kern County mountains and deserts during the evening of the 31st, with winds gusting between 40 and 50 mph.

A cold front moving through the state generated heavy showers from Kauai to Maui.  The system caused ponding of roadways, and small stream and drainage ditch flooding.  However, no significant property damage or injuries were reported.

Soaking rains over a four-day period beginning on the 7th provided the region with nearly all of the months precipitationbetween 2 and 3 inches. The rain combined with the melting winter snowpack and frozen ground to result in widespread flooding on area rivers and creeks. There were numerous reports of road closures along those rivers and creeks. This was the third winter flood event this seasona rare occurrence in western New York. |Specific river/creek crest information follows:  Cazenovia Creek at Ebenezer (flood stage 10 feet) crested at 11.51 feet at 3AM on the 8th. Cayuga Creek at Lancaster (flood stage 8 feet) crested at 9.31 feet at 5AM on the 8th. Buffalo Creek at Gardenville (flood stage 7 feet) crested at 7.71 feet at 4AM on the 8th. Ellicott Creek at Williamsville (flood stage 8 feet) crested at 8.04 feet at 2AM on the 9th. Black Creek at Churchville (flood stage 6 feet) crested at 6.48 feet at 5PM on the 9th. Oatka Creek at Garbutt (flood stage 6 feet) crested at 6.70 feet at 2PM on the 9th. Allegheny River at Olean (flood stage 10 feet) crested at 10.34 feet at 11AM on the 11th. Tonawanda Creek at Batavia (flood stage 9 feet) crested at 10.57 feet at 11PM on the 8th; and at Rapids (flood stage 12 feet) crested at 13.68 feet at 6AM on the 11th.

A cold and unstable upper level trough impacted western Montana with moderate to heavy snow fall. In addition, a surge of arctic air was pulled into northwest Montana. This front acted as a focusing mechanism for increased snow production.  Total snow amounts ranged from three to six inches.| |Increased north to east winds produced dangerous winds chills colder than twenty below zero across the northern Flathead valley and Glacier National Park. The combination of winds and snow led to reduced visibility across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The combination or snow, blowing snow, lowered visibility, and extreme wind chills lead to the declarations of severe driving conditions from Kalispell to Columbia Falls to Coram.  Wind chills dropped down to twenty three below for several hours.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous upper level trough of low pressure moved south out of British Columbia and into the northern Rockies, producing heavy mountain snow. Light to moderate snow accumulations occurred in some valley locations.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trained spotters in Essex reported a storm total snowfall of twelve inches. A spotter in West Glacier measured a total snowfall of eight inches.  On Marias Pass over Highway 2, snow fall amounts ranged between ten to twelve inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The Lazy J Wildfire began around 1542 CST approximately eleven miles east southeast of Stinnett near the Canadian River north of Farm to Market Road 280 in southeast Hutchinson County. The wildfire burned an estimated eighteen hundred acres...however no structures were threatened or damaged. There were no injuries reported. The wildfire was caused by transmission lines and was contained as of 1500 CST on 3/10/09. A total of six fire departments responded to the wildfire.

The Beck Ranch Wildfire began around 1816 CST approximately twelve miles north northwest of Middle Water in northwest Hartley County northwest of U.S. Highway 54. The wildfire burned an estimated three hundred acres...although no structures were threatened or damaged. There were no injuries reported. A total of three fire departments responded to the wildfire which was caused by lightning. The wildfire was contained between 1900 and 1930 hours CST.

The storm brought heavy snow to most of western Maine, except in the mountains where lighter amounts fell.  Snowfall amounts ranged from 2 to 4 inches in the western Maine mountains to 6 to 10 inches along the coast and interior.

A strong upper level low pressure system moved through Arkansas during the night of February 28th, 2009. The upper level low produced bands of snow across East Arkansas during the evening hours which continued into the early morning hours of March 1st, 2009. Total snow accumulations ranged from 2 inches to as much as 12 inches. The hardest hit area was portions of Mississippi County from Blytheville to Wilson, where up to a foot of snow fell. Roads were hazardous as a result of the snow and many accidents occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An additional 2-3 inches of snow fell across Mississippi County during the early morning hours of March 1st. Total snow accumulations for the February 28th-March 1st, 2009 event was between 7-12 inches.

A weak cold front moved through the region during the overnight hours of March 24th and had stalled across southeast Texas into southwest and south central Louisiana. During the afternoon and overnight hours of March 25th...a strong upper level disturbance moved across the Texas Hill Country and into the region from the west. The result was widespread shower and thunderstorm activity...some of which produced large hail...damaging thunderstorm wind gusts...as well as isolated tornadoes across portions of the region. The atmosphere ahead of the storm system was moderately unstable but dynamics aloft were primed for the formation of strong to severe convection.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Four trees were downed across Hwy. 7.  The road was closed until 10 pm.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A stationary frontal boundary was located east to west near the Interstate 20 corridor of northern Louisiana. Low level moisture was rapidly returning to the region with the aid of a low level jet which overran the surface boundary during the late evening hours of March 27th. This coupled with a strong upper level atmospheric trough which was moving south and east out of the Oklahoma and Texas Panhandle region. The upper level storm system provided the lift needed for strong to severe thunderstorms to form across the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail was reported in the Dodson, Louisiana community.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Widespread dense fog developed across most of western Kentucky except the Henderson and Owensboro areas. Visibility was below one-quarter mile. There was a report of visibility only near 25 feet at Hopkinsville. Since temperatures were below freezing, light icing occurred in the thick fog. A light south wind flow of milder air over the snow and ice-covered ground set the stage for dense fog.

High winds developed in and near the foothills of Boulder, Jefferson and Larimer Counties.  Peak wind gusts included:  101 mph at Eldora Ski Resort, 100 mph, 6 miles northwest of Boulder; 84 mph at the NCAR Mesa Lab, 82 mph at Pinewood Lake, 79 mph; 5 miles northwest of Boulder, and 75 mph at the National Wind Technology Center.  In Nederland, a wind turbine recently installed was damaged by the high wind.

A stationary frontal boundary across the region triggered numerous showers and embedded thunderstorms.  The storms dumped anywhere from 2 to 4 inches of rain over southern Missouri and southern Illinois causing some isolated flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Between 2 and 4 inches of rain fell in a short amount of time on frozen ground, causing flash flooding.  Several roads were flooded including Highway B near Highway 32 in Ste. Genevieve county.  Also, several streets in downtown Ste. Genevieve were covered with several inches of water.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Rain changed to snow during the early evening across portions of the foothills and the western Piedmont of North Carolina. Snow became heavy at times throughout the evening, and up to 4 inches had accumulated across the area by 10 pm. Snow, heavy at times and accompanied by occasional lightning, continued into the late evening and early overnight hours. By the time the snow tapered off, accumulations of 3-6 inches were common across the area. However, localized amounts of up to 9 inches were reported, especially along a corridor extending from Shelby to Hickory. The heavy wet snow caused quite a few trees and power lines to fall, resulting in numerous power outages. Some structures received minor to moderate roof damage due to the weight of the snow. Some customers were without power for several days. A tree fell on the library in Belmont, NC, causing damage to the roof. Numerous traffic accidents also occurred.

A powerful low pressure system tracked across eastern Colorado and Nebraska and produced strong winds and snow across southeast Wyoming.  Blizzard conditions occurred over some areas with many roads closed due to blowing and drifting snow and extremmely low visibilities along with numerous accidents.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong winds with gusts in excess of 50 mph and snowfall from 7 to 12 inches caused blizzard conditions with drifts over 4 feet.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Mainly non-thunderstorm winds occurred during the afternoon and evening hours of February 11th. A High Wind Warning was in effect for the day as well as portions of the days on either side. A strong low pressure system moved across Illinois and northern Indiana with a trailing cold front that passed through Indiana. An intense pressure gradient ahead of the front and strong pressure rises behind the front caused very strong winds to blow. A saturated ground from recent snow melt and new rainfall may have contributed to the reports of downed trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were reported to have been blown down in Sullivan and Dugger, Indiana.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow accompanied by winds gusting to over 40 mph produced blizzard conditions over southeast South Dakota away from the eastern border of the state. The blizzard began on the evening of March 30th and continued through the daytime hours of March 31st. Travel was brought to a standstill, with numerous roads closed, including Interstate 90 from Mitchell west. The greatest reported snow accumulation was 16.5 inches near Corsica.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 6 to 10 inches, accompanied by northerly winds gusting over 45 mph, produced blizzard conditions that brought travel and commerce to a standstill. Numerous businesses, schools, and roads were closed; and many roads not officially closed were impassable. The city of Huron received 9.5 inches of snow, with a peak wind gust of 46 mph from the north.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An approaching storm system ushered in the warmest air of the month on the 7th. The warm front associated with this system stalled across northern Illinois and Indiana. As a wave passed along this front, rain of 2 to 4 inches fell in the Tippecanoe River Basin from the afternoon of the 7th through the late morning hour of the 8th.||This rain had an immediate impact on the Tippecanoe River. By the evening of the 8th, extensive flooding quickly developed. The warm front remained over northern Illinois and Indiana and after about 24|hours another wave brought 2 to 4 inches of rain to the Tippecanoe River Basin from the evening of the 9th through the morning of the 11th.||With extensive flooding already in progress and saturated ground conditions, major flooding quickly developed along the Tippecanoe River by the morning of the 11th. Flood crests were similar to those|of February 2008.||Many local river residents listened to the Carroll County EMA director about the potential for serious flooding and voluntarily left their homes on the 9th and 10th. A few chose to ride out the flood. Some of these people needed rescued.||Because the heaviest rain was confined to northern Indiana, only the Wabash River in western Indiana and eastern Illinois flooded. This was the 3rd time since late December that extensive lowland flooding occurred along the Wabash. The March flood exceeded the previous two floods from Lafayette to just downstream of Terre Haute on the Wabash River.||The biggest problem caused by the flood along the Wabash was the inconvenience to local traffic that normally used State Road 43, State Road 225 and local roads in the Grandville Bridge area. The flood also caused disruption to the construction of a natural gas pipeline going from the Rocky Mountains to the east coast. This was third delay in three months to construction of the pipeline underneath the Wabash in the Montezuma area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Flooding occurred along the Wabash River in Sullivan County across from Hutsonville, IL. The river crested 6.6 feet above flood stage at the Hutsonville river gauge on March 17th with a reading of 22.6 feet. Floods in this area of Sullivan County affect agricultural/hunting land and county roads almost exclusively.
