An upper trough near the islands caused southwest to west winds to exceed 50 knots over the summits of Mauna Kea and Mauna Loa on the Big Island of Hawaii.  There were no reports of significant injuries or property damage.
Dry conditions persisted over parts of the Big Island of Hawaii.  Water restrictions continued.

A vigorous upper level trough of low pressure moved south out of British Columbia and into the northern Rockies, producing heavy mountain snow. Light to moderate snow accumulations occurred in some valley locations.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trained spotters in Lindbergh Lake reported eleven inches of snow, while spotters in Condon reported seven inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A vigorous upper level trough of low pressure moved south out of British Columbia and into the northern Rockies, producing heavy mountain snow. Light to moderate snow accumulations occurred in some valley locations.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter in Elk City measured twenty four inches of new snow from the event.  A trained spotter in Dixie measured eight inches of new snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong Pacific low pressure system moved into the northern Rockies with abundant moisture.  This system was accompanied by a strong cold front, which pushed through the area over the weekend.  Initially lower elevations started out with a rain snow mix, then transitioned to snow as the the front moved through the area. Snow fall totals in the valley locations ranged between four and eight inches, while the higher terrain received up to a foot of new snow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A trained spotter in Deerlodge reported nine inches of new snow accumulations.  Philipsburg reported a foot of new snow accumulations.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deep low pressure system moved south out of Canada and into the Western Dakotas. Northwest winds behind the low produced strong upslope flow over the Big Horn Mountains and portions of Sheridan County resulting in accumulating snowfall.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Dayton and Story received 7 to 8 inches of snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A series of weather systems moved across Southern Canada resulting in high winds across the Upper Yellowstone and Upper Stillwater valleys.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Sustained winds of 40 mph occurred in Harlowton.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A series of weather systems moved across Southern Canada resulting in high winds across the Upper Yellowstone and Upper Stillwater valleys.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Sustained winds of 50 mph with gusts to 86 mph were reported at the Livingston Airport.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A series of weather systems moved across Southern Canada resulting in high winds across the Upper Yellowstone and Upper Stillwater valleys.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Sustained winds of 50 mph with gusts to 82 mph were recorded at the Stillwater Mine.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold Pacific storm system brought high winds and locally heavy snow to the Mojave Desert and southern Great Basin.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: This gust occurred 1 mile ESE of Red Rock Canyon.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold Pacific storm system brought high winds and locally heavy snow to the Mojave Desert and southern Great Basin.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: This gust occurred 6 miles SSE of Hayford Peak.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold Pacific storm system brought high winds and locally heavy snow to the Mojave Desert and southern Great Basin.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: This gust occurred at the North Las Vegas Airport (KVGT).  In addition, gusts estimated at 55 mph knocked down two power poles in North Las Vegas.  One pole fell onto and damaged a vehicle.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front brought locally high winds to southern Nevada and northwest Arizona.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong winds blew down a 20-foot tall, 18-inch diameter tree near Exit 66 on Interstate 40 (13 miles E of Kingman).

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front brought locally high winds to southern Nevada and northwest Arizona.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: This gust occurred 6 miles SSE of Hayford Peak.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorms developed over West Tennessee during the late evening hours of February 17th, 2009. The thunderstorms developed out ahead of a developing low pressure system located over the Central Plains. Some of the thunderstorms became severe producing large hail.
A cold front moved through the North Mississippi during the day on February 27th, 2009. Heavy rain associated with the front produced flash flooding over portions of the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy rain produced flash flooding outside of Pittsboro. Water covered Highway 9 between Pittsboro and Calhoun City as a result.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong winds between 20 to 30 mph affected West Tennessee during the afternoon of February 3, 2009. An 18-wheeler was overturned in Jackson as a result of the strong winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An 18-wheeler overturned in Jackson.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of severe thunderstorms on the 31st produced large hail, a brief weak tornado, and flash flooding in portions of southwest Georgia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tornado briefly touched down in an open field.  No damage was reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A line of severe thunderstorms on the 31st produced large hail, a brief weak tornado, and flash flooding in portions of southwest Georgia.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Repeated torrential rains from thunderstorms produced flash flooding throughout much of the county.  Several roads were under water.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure tracked from the Oklahoma panhandle into the Ohio Valley from February 13th through the 14th.  This system brought heavy snow to around a 50 mile wide swath across eastern Nebraska and western Iowa generally along and north of Interstate 80 in eastern Nebraska and along and south of the interstate in western Iowa.  The heaviest snow stretched from Columbus and David City Nebraska east through Omaha and then to Underwood and Oakland Iowa.  On the southern end the snowfall tapered down to several inches from southeast Nebraska into far southwest Iowa.  Meanwhile, the snow ended rather abruptly on the northern end with little or no snow measured along and north of a line from Norfolk Nebraska to Little Sioux Iowa.  Heavier snow totals in Nebraska included 7.5 inches in David City and 6 to 8 inches across much of the Omaha metro area including 6.8 inches at the NWS office near Valley and 5.5 inches at Omaha Eppley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow fell over the southern half of Platte county, with around 6 inches reported by the coop observer in Columbus.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weather disturbance extending from the Gulf Coast States to Kentucky brought a widespread snowfall to Eastern Kentucky beginning late in the afternoon of March 12th, lasting into the early morning hours of March 13th. Sleet was reported in many locations, along with some freezing rain. In general, one to four inches of snow fell across the area, with locally higher amounts where the heavier snow and sleet persisted.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Four and one tenth of an inch of snow fell at the Jackson weather office.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A broad area of low pressure was over north central Georgia and extended through Southeast Alabama through the western panhandle of Florida. A warm front extended through east-central Georgia, which placed the local forecast area in the warm sector of the storm system. Pre-frontal convection developed across the forecast area which resulted in scattered wind damage from storms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were blown down across State Road 90 north of Willacoochee.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A severe thunderstorm impacted Baker County on 3/1/2009.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Small branches were blown down and a metal bracket holding rain gage was damaged due to thunderstorm wind gusts.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An extended dry spell led to drought conditions and several wildfires across north Florida.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Florida State Watch Office reported that the County Road 1474 wildfire near Hawthorne was about 300 acres and was 40 percent contained as of this morning. The fire started yesterday 3/18/09 at 546 p.m. local time in Beckhamtown, Florida. Three outbuildings were damaged by the fire.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level low pressure system moved through Arkansas during the night of February 28th, 2009. The upper level low produced bands of snow across East Arkansas during the evening hours which continued into the early morning hours of March 1st, 2009. Total snow accumulations ranged from 2 inches to as much as 12 inches. The hardest hit area was portions of Mississippi County from Blytheville to Wilson, where up to a foot of snow fell. Roads were hazardous as a result of the snow and many accidents occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An additional inch or less of snow fell across Randolph County during the early morning hours of March 1st. Total snow accumulations for the February 28th-March 1st, 2009 event was between 4-7 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak cold front moved through the region during the overnight hours of March 24th and had stalled across southeast Texas into southwest and south central Louisiana.  During the afternoon and overnight hours of March 25th...a strong upper level disturbance moved across the Texas Hill Country and into the region from the west.  The result was widespread shower and thunderstorm activity...some of which produced large hail...damaging thunderstorm wind gusts...as well as isolated tornadoes across portions of the region.  The atmosphere ahead of the storm system was moderately unstable but dynamics aloft were primed for the formation of strong to severe convection.

Rain changed to snow during the early evening across portions of the foothills and the western Piedmont of North Carolina. Snow became heavy at times throughout the evening, and up to 4 inches had accumulated across the area by 10 pm. Snow, heavy at times and accompanied by occasional lightning, continued into the late evening and early overnight hours. By the time the snow tapered off, accumulations of 3-6 inches were common across the area. However, localized amounts of up to 9 inches were reported, especially along a corridor extending from Shelby to Hickory. The heavy wet snow caused quite a few trees and power lines to fall, resulting in numerous power outages. Some structures received minor to moderate roof damage due to the weight of the snow. Some customers were without power for several days. A tree fell on the library in Belmont, NC, causing damage to the roof. Numerous traffic accidents also occurred.

A stationary frontal boundary across the region triggered numerous showers and embedded thunderstorms.  The storms dumped anywhere from 2 to 4 inches of rain over southern Missouri and southern Illinois causing some isolated flash flooding.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Between 2 and 4 inches of rain fell in a short amount of time onto frozen ground causing flash flooding.  Several roads were flooded including Highway O about 8 miles southwest of Fredericktown and Highway V, about 8 miles southeast of Fredericktown.  Also, North Main Street in Fredericktown was closed due to flooding.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Isolated thunderstorms developed over the region producing some small hail. Some one inch hail was reported with the stronger storms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Brief period of quarter sized hail with intermixed smaller hail fell at Meramec State Park.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Mainly non-thunderstorm winds occurred during the afternoon and evening hours of February 11th. A High Wind Warning was in effect for the day as well as portions of the days on either side. A strong low pressure system moved across Illinois and northern Indiana with a trailing cold front that passed through Indiana. An intense pressure gradient ahead of the front and strong pressure rises behind the front caused very strong winds to blow. A saturated ground from recent snow melt and new rainfall may have contributed to the reports of downed trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Automated equipment recorded a wind gust of 58 mph at the Indianapolis International Airport.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A powerful low pressure system tracked across eastern Colorado and Nebraska and produced strong winds and snow across southeast Wyoming.  Blizzard conditions occurred over some areas with many roads closed due to blowing and drifting snow and extremmely low visibilities along with numerous accidents.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall was estimated to be from 6 to 10 inches along with gusty winds which created considerable blowing and drifting snow.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An approaching storm system ushered in the warmest air of the month on the 7th. The warm front associated with this system stalled across northern Illinois and Indiana. As a wave passed along this front, rain of 2 to 4 inches fell in the Tippecanoe River Basin from the afternoon of the 7th through the late morning hour of the 8th.||This rain had an immediate impact on the Tippecanoe River. By the evening of the 8th, extensive flooding quickly developed. The warm front remained over northern Illinois and Indiana and after about 24|hours another wave brought 2 to 4 inches of rain to the Tippecanoe River Basin from the evening of the 9th through the morning of the 11th.||With extensive flooding already in progress and saturated ground conditions, major flooding quickly developed along the Tippecanoe River by the morning of the 11th. Flood crests were similar to those|of February 2008.||Many local river residents listened to the Carroll County EMA director about the potential for serious flooding and voluntarily left their homes on the 9th and 10th. A few chose to ride out the flood. Some of these people needed rescued.||Because the heaviest rain was confined to northern Indiana, only the Wabash River in western Indiana and eastern Illinois flooded. This was the 3rd time since late December that extensive lowland flooding occurred along the Wabash. The March flood exceeded the previous two floods from Lafayette to just downstream of Terre Haute on the Wabash River.||The biggest problem caused by the flood along the Wabash was the inconvenience to local traffic that normally used State Road 43, State Road 225 and local roads in the Grandville Bridge area. The flood also caused disruption to the construction of a natural gas pipeline going from the Rocky Mountains to the east coast. This was third delay in three months to construction of the pipeline underneath the Wabash in the Montezuma area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Extensive flooding of agricultural land occurred along the Wabash River in and near Clinton, IN. The river crested 6.1 feet above flood stage at the Clinton river gauge on March 14th with a reading of 24.1 feet. Data is estimated due to missing data.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong mid-level jet max associated with a mid to upper level trough combined with a deep surface low resulted in high winds across a small portion of the plains of southeast New Mexico.

Westerly winds increased over the higher terrain of the mountains of west texas as an upper level trough approached the region.  Strong mid level flow mixed down towards the surface, resulting in very high wind gusts near Guadalupe, TX.

A passing mid-level low north of the region resulted in a 70 kt mid-level speed max working its way over the area during the early morning hours.  Deep dry adiabatic layers resulted in maximum mixing potential, which allowed the stronger winds to mix down to the surface.  The 700 hPa gradient over the area on this day suggested the potential for high winds was high, especially over the higher terrain of west Texas.

Light winds, clear skies, and ample moisture near the ground resulted in areas of dense fog. Visibility fell to one-quarter mile or less at many locations.

Yet another winter storm moved in on this date.  Warnings were in effect above 3500 feet.  Rainfall and temperature reports from below the snow level along with temperature readings above indicated that snowfall meeting Heavy Snow Warning criteria did occur.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Rainfall and temperature reports from below the snow level along with temperature readings above indicated that snowfall meeting Heavy Snow Warning criteria did occur in this zone during this interval.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Several episodes of widespread severe weather and heavy rainfall occurred from March 26th through the 28th as a series of strong upper air disturbances impacted the central gulf region as a meandering and nearly stationary frontal boundary drifted back and forth across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A National Weather Service storm survey indicated that a tornado traveled along a 7 mile long path in Hancock County. The tornado caused substantial damage to the roof of a church on Highway 603 and to a large outbuilding south of Necaise. The debris from large trees blocked Highway 603, Highway 43, and Highway 53.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees were knocked down in eastern Orleans parish along Highway 11 in Irish Bayou.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: March began with an upper-level low off the California coast. Strong warming in the south end of the San Joaquin Valley gave Bakersfield a record high of 86 degrees, which almost was the warmest day of the month at Meadows Field. The low drew subtropical moisture into interior central California from the southwest, bringing rain and high-elevation snow to the region. In Yosemite National Park, a foot of new snow fell at Tuolumne Meadows during the night of March 2nd-3rd.|Colder air moved into the region during the 3rd as a slow moving cold front dropped south. The high at Fresno dropped from 67 on the 3rd to only 59 on the 4th, and Bakersfields high fell 13 degreesfrom 74 on the 3rd to only 61 the next day. More snow fell over the Southern Sierra Nevada beginning the night of March 3rd and continuing through the 4th. Estimated snowfalls at SNOTEL sites ranged from 15 inches to around 2 feet. With a cold, unstable airmass over the San Joaquin Valley, conditions were right for thunderstorms to form over the west side of the San Joaquin Valley during the afternoon and evening of March 4th.|The trough pulled east of California during the morning of March 7th. This system brought the bulk of Marchs precipitation to central California, with Fresno having a storm total of 0.18 inch, and Bakersfield receiving 0.20 inch. With the moist lower levels of the airmass over the San Joaquin Valley, patchy fog developed during the morning hours of the 7th.

A squall line impacted portions of extreme southeast Kansas and the Missouri Ozarks during the evening and overnight period of 9 April, 2009.  A barn was destroyed south of Columbus while other observations of small hail occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Severe thunderstorm wind gusts destroyed a barn.

Mountain snowfall of one to two feet was common. A relatively rare storm total snow accumulation of 11 inches was recorded in Dubois.

A severe thunderstorm traveled along Interstate 80 for about 40 miles through eastern Sweetwater County. The storm produced large hail, damaging wind, and a funnel cloud. Damage was most intense around Wamsutter where the combination of wind and hail obliterated vinyl siding and broke windows at numerous homes and businesses.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A remote weather station near Continental Divide on Interstate 80 at mile marker 184 recorded wind gusts of 65 to 68 mph for ten minutes.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front moved through the region triggering showers and thunderstorms. Damaging winds, large hail and tornadoes were reported with the storms.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorm winds blew down numerous trees and power lines along Pike County Road 202 next to the Mississippi River.  Twenty homes sustained minor to major damage.  One home was knocked off of its pilings and into a nearby tree.  Another home had the entire roof and porch torn off and thrown into the Mississippi River.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level low pressure system moved through Arkansas during the night of February 28th, 2009. The upper level low produced bands of snow across West Tennessee during the evening hours which continued into the early morning hours of March 1st, 2009. Total snow accumulations ranged from a half of an inch to as much as 16 inches. The hardest hit area occurred in Lauderdale, Tipton, Haywood, Madison, Crockett and Fayette Counties where over a foot of snow fell. Roads were hazardous as a result of the snow and many accidents occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Up to a half of an inch of snow fell across Weakley County during the early morning hours of March 1st. Total snow accumulations for the snowstorm February 28th-March 1st were around 2-3 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level low pressure system moved through Arkansas during the night of February 28th, 2009. The upper level low produced bands of snow across East Arkansas during the evening hours which continued into the early morning hours of March 1st, 2009. Total snow accumulations ranged from 2 inches to as much as 12 inches. The hardest hit area was portions of Mississippi County from Blytheville to Wilson, where up to a foot of snow fell. Roads were hazardous as a result of the snow and many accidents occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An additional 1-2 inches of snow fell across Craighead County during the early morning hours of March 1st. Total snow accumulations for the February 28th-March 1st, 2009 event was between 2-8 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak cold front moved through the region during the overnight hours of March 24th and had stalled across southeast Texas into southwest and south central Louisiana.  During the afternoon and overnight hours of March 25th...a strong upper level disturbance moved across the Texas Hill Country and into the region from the west.  The result was widespread shower and thunderstorm activity...some of which produced large hail...damaging thunderstorm wind gusts...as well as isolated tornadoes across portions of the region.  The atmosphere ahead of the storm system was moderately unstable but dynamics aloft were primed for the formation of strong to severe convection.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A large tree was down near town.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure center moved northeast from Oklahoma into south central Missouri by late afternoon, with a warm front extending east from the low across western Kentucky. The warm front served as a focusing mechanism for some of the ingredients needed for tornadogenesis. While most of the severe weather occurred in western Kentucky, a supercell produced a funnel cloud over the Evansville area.

A strong cold front moved across southeast Georgia and north Florida accompanied by unseasonably cold temperatures.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snow flurries were reported by Jeff Davis 911 dispatch in the City of Hazlehurst.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure center lifted northeast from the southern Plains into the Great Lakes.  A tight pressure gradient resulted in strong southerly winds ahead of an associated dry line and pressure trough which pushed eastward through the Tennessee Valley.  A broken line of showers and isolated thunderstorms developed along the dry line during the late morning hours, and swept rapidly east across the Tennessee Valley during the early afternoon hours.  Although a couple of reports of wind damage occurred with the showers and thunderstorms, the more prominent impact was due to damaging non-thunderstorm winds ahead of and immediately behind the dry line passage.  Numerous trees were blown down resulting in sporadic power outages.  There were also a few reports of minor roof damage and a couple of car accidents due to the high winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Thunderstorm winds damaged several roofs and knocked trees onto power lines in and around Cherokee.  Residents and businesses on the following streets were affected:  Herbert Street, Virginia Street, Pine Street, Second Street, Pike Road, Main Street, U.S. Highway 72, Chickasaw Drive, Lair Lane, and Forrest Road.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low-topped supercell thunderstorms developed along a powerful cold front during the late afternoon of the 28th.  The storms evolved into a quasi-linear convective system (QLCS) with embedded mesocyclones, one of which became tornadic.  There were also a few reports of large hail and damaging winds.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Nickel sized hail was reported along state highway 121, about 4 miles north of the Tennessee-Alabama state line.

CZ_NAME: JEFFERSON & W DOUGLAS COUNTIES ABOVE 6000 FEET / GILPIN / CLEAR CREEK / NE PARK COUNTIES BELOW 9000 FEET
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A fast moving storm system brought heavy snow to the the foothills of Boulder and Jefferson Counties as well as the western and southern suburbs of the metropolitan Denver.  The storm resulted in multiple accidents along the Urban Corridor.  In the foothills storm totals included:  9 inches at Genesee and 5 miles west of Rollinsville, 7 inches, 8 miles north of Blackhawk, Eldorado Springs, and Ken Caryl; with 6 inches near Evergreen.  In the suburbs of Denver, storm totals included:  8 inches at Lakewood, 6.5 inches in Arvada, 5.5 inches at Boulder and Westminster, 5 inches at Greenwood Village and Littleton, with 4.5 inches at Centenniel.

Mainly non-thunderstorm winds occurred during the afternoon and evening hours of February 11th. A High Wind Warning was in effect for the day as well as portions of the days on either side. A strong low pressure system moved across Illinois and northern Indiana with a trailing cold front that passed through Indiana. An intense pressure gradient ahead of the front and strong pressure rises behind the front caused very strong winds to blow. A saturated ground from recent snow melt and new rainfall may have contributed to the reports of downed trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Power outages were reported on the east side of Terre Haute.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure tracked from the Oklahoma panhandle into the Ohio Valley from February 13th through the 14th.  This system brought heavy snow to around a 50 mile wide swath across eastern Nebraska and western Iowa generally along and north of Interstate 80 in eastern Nebraska and along and south of the interstate in western Iowa.  The heaviest snow stretched from Columbus and David City Nebraska east through Omaha and then to Underwood and Oakland Iowa.  On the southern end the snowfall tapered down to several inches from southeast Nebraska into far southwest Iowa.  Meanwhile, the snow ended rather abruptly on the northern end with little or no snow measured along and north of a line from Norfolk Nebraska to Little Sioux Iowa.  Heavier totals in western Iowa included around 8 inches in Council Bluffs, 7.3 inches at Underwood and 6.8 inches in Oakland.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow was reported over most of Pottawattamie county with this storm.  The cooperative observer in Underwood measured 7.3 inches while the observer in Oakland reported 6.8 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low-level jet ahead of an upper level disturbance brought elevated instability to eastern Nebraska during the morning hours of February 26th.  Despite surface temperatures in the 30s, the elevated instability helped spawn a few severe thunderstorms over eastern Nebraska and western Iowa.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail up to 3/4 inches in diameter was reported on the west side of Onawa.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: An 82 mph wind gust was reported by a jack-up barge located near an oil rig platform in Vermilion Block 31.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Several severe thunderstorms developed across southwest Louisiana during the afternoon hours, causing a few reports of large hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The public reported nickel size hail covering the entire ground at the intersection of Highway 14 and Smith Road in Lake Charles.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Several episodes of widespread severe weather and heavy rainfall occurred from March 26th through the 28th as a series of strong upper air disturbances impacted the central gulf region as a meandering and nearly stationary frontal boundary drifted back and forth across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A weak tornado briefly touched down causing damage around Tucker Street and 8th Street and on Taylor Street. Pacagoula High School experienced light damage when the scoreboard on the football field was blown down and numerous sections of fence were knocked down with debris littering the field. Traffic lights around the area were knocked down and several trees were blown down. Maximum winds associated with this tornado were estimated around 75 mph with a path length around 250 yards and a maximum width of 50 yards.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An upper-level trough coupled with a 125 MPH jet max and strong onshore pressure gradients brought light rain and strong winds to Southern California on March 22nd. Gusty winds knocked down trees, freeway signs, and power lines in the mountains and deserts. Two fires were reported during this time, both of which caused damage to structures and trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A vegetation fire fueled by gusty winds spread to a single family home near La Quinta and partially destroyed the roof.

A dry system moved through California on March 8th and 9th, bringing only some high clouds and locally gusty winds to the Kern County mountains and deserts. Winds gusted in excess of 45 mph at both Mojave and Ridgecrest during the afternoon and early evening of the 9th.|In the wake of this storm, a cold airmass lingered over the San Joaquin Valley. Temperatures plummeted into the mid 20s in the coldest Valley locations during the morning of March 10th. Naval Air Station Lemoore had a low of only 24 degrees, while the airports at Merced and Porterville dropped to 27 degrees.

CZ_NAME: W END OF THE 7 MILE BRIDGE TO KEY W OUT 20NM
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Towering cumulus cloud lines and rain showers along the Lower Florida Keys gradually built further up the island chain by afternoon. A few waterspouts of brief duration were reported.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A waterspout was observed by the captain of a recreational vessel approximately four miles south of the Bahia Honda Bridge.  The waterspout moved toward the west-northwest and had a visible spray ring while the condensation funnel only extended about half-way between the cumulus cloud base and the water surface.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong upper level low pressure system moved through Arkansas during the night of February 28th, 2009. The upper level low produced bands of snow across North Mississippi during the evening hours which continued into the early morning hours of March 1st, 2009. Total snow accumulations ranged from an inch to as much as 5 inches. The hardest hit area was along the Tennessee Border from Southaven in DeSoto County to Corinth in Alcorn County. Roads were hazardous as a result of the snow and many accidents occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Around 1-2 inches of snow fell across Coahoma County during the early morning hours of March 1st. Total snow accumulations during the February 28th-March 1st, 2009 snow storm was around 1-2 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dense fog around during the morning gave way to a very unstable atmosphere across northwest and north central Louisiana.  A stalled frontal boundary was located across deep east Texas into central Louisiana. An upper level storm system moved quickly eastward across central Texas into west central Louisiana and as a result, strong to severe thunderstorms developed.  These storms produced mainly large hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Penny to nickel sized hail was reported.

A weather disturbance extending from the Gulf Coast States to Kentucky brought a widespread snowfall to Eastern Kentucky beginning late in the afternoon of March 12th, lasting into the early morning hours of March 13th. Sleet was reported in many locations, along with some freezing rain. In general, one to four inches of snow fell across the area, with locally higher amounts where the heavier snow and sleet persisted.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two and two tenths of an inch of snow fell in Emma.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weak cold front moved through the region during the overnight hours of March 24th and had stalled across southeast Texas into southwest and south central Louisiana.  During the afternoon and overnight hours of March 25th...a strong upper level disturbance moved across the Texas Hill Country and into the region from the west.  The result was widespread shower and thunderstorm activity...some of which produced large hail...damaging thunderstorm wind gusts...as well as isolated tornadoes across portions of the region.  The atmosphere ahead of the storm system was moderately unstable but dynamics aloft were primed for the formation of strong to severe convection.

Rain changed to snow during the early evening across portions of the foothills and the western Piedmont of North Carolina. Snow became heavy at times throughout the evening, and up to 4 inches had accumulated across the area by 10 pm. Snow, heavy at times and accompanied by occasional lightning, continued into the late evening and early overnight hours. By the time the snow tapered off, accumulations of 3-6 inches were common across the area. However, localized amounts of up to 9 inches were reported, especially along a corridor extending from Shelby to Hickory. The heavy wet snow caused quite a few trees and power lines to fall, resulting in numerous power outages. Some structures received minor to moderate roof damage due to the weight of the snow. Some customers were without power for several days. A tree fell on the library in Belmont, NC, causing damage to the roof. Numerous traffic accidents also occurred.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong northwest winds gusting to 58 mph occurred over northern Lincoln County.  The combination of strong winds and very dry conditions caused areas of blowing dust and dirt to create brownout conditions.  As a result, visibilities were restricted to near zero along sections of Interstate 70.  Along the interstate near Genoa, eight passenger cars and six tractor-trailer trucks were involved in a collision.  Two people were killed and at least 6 others were injured, one seriously.  The multi-vehicle collison forced the closure of the interstate for several hours.

Mainly non-thunderstorm winds occurred during the afternoon and evening hours of February 11th. A High Wind Warning was in effect for the day as well as portions of the days on either side. A strong low pressure system moved across Illinois and northern Indiana with a trailing cold front that passed through Indiana. An intense pressure gradient ahead of the front and strong pressure rises behind the front caused very strong winds to blow. A saturated ground from recent snow melt and new rainfall may have contributed to the reports of downed trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An EF1 tornado very briefly occurred near near South County Road 300 East and East County Road 550 South. The tornado dislodged a barn roof and damaged the roof of a single family home across the street.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The combination of clear skies and light winds allowed temperatures to fall to near or just below freezing across portions of the Schoharie Valley, the Lake George region, and north central Taconics early Thursday morning. The growing season already started in this region after a prolonged period of abnormally warm temperatures.

An approaching storm system ushered in the warmest air of the month on the 7th. The warm front associated with this system stalled across northern Illinois and Indiana. As a wave passed along this front, rain of 2 to 4 inches fell in the Tippecanoe River Basin from the afternoon of the 7th through the late morning hour of the 8th.||This rain had an immediate impact on the Tippecanoe River. By the evening of the 8th, extensive flooding quickly developed. The warm front remained over northern Illinois and Indiana and after about 24|hours another wave brought 2 to 4 inches of rain to the Tippecanoe River Basin from the evening of the 9th through the morning of the 11th.||With extensive flooding already in progress and saturated ground conditions, major flooding quickly developed along the Tippecanoe River by the morning of the 11th. Flood crests were similar to those|of February 2008.||Many local river residents listened to the Carroll County EMA director about the potential for serious flooding and voluntarily left their homes on the 9th and 10th. A few chose to ride out the flood. Some of these people needed rescued.||Because the heaviest rain was confined to northern Indiana, only the Wabash River in western Indiana and eastern Illinois flooded. This was the 3rd time since late December that extensive lowland flooding occurred along the Wabash. The March flood exceeded the previous two floods from Lafayette to just downstream of Terre Haute on the Wabash River.||The biggest problem caused by the flood along the Wabash was the inconvenience to local traffic that normally used State Road 43, State Road 225 and local roads in the Grandville Bridge area. The flood also caused disruption to the construction of a natural gas pipeline going from the Rocky Mountains to the east coast. This was third delay in three months to construction of the pipeline underneath the Wabash in the Montezuma area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Extensive flooding of agricultural land occurred along the Wabash River in Parke County in and near Montezuma, IN. The river crested 10.69 feet above flood stage at the Montezuma river gauge on March 14th, a reading of 24.69 feet. The flooding also affected some roads and possibly flooded basements.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 40 mph wind gust was reported by the Devall tow boat near the Ellander Bridge.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low-level jet ahead of an upper level disturbance brought elevated instability to eastern Nebraska during the morning hours of February 26th.  Despite surface temperatures in the 30s, the elevated instability helped spawn a few severe thunderstorms over eastern Nebraska and western Iowa.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Hail up to penny size was reported.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Some snow-melt combined with a little rain and warming temperatures helped create an ice jam on the Elkhorn River which caused flooding around and downstream of West Point.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: An ice jam downstream of West Point caused flooding along the Elkhorn River near and downstream of West Point.  The flooding caused the closure of Highway 275 from the Jct of Highway 91 to the Dodge county line. The flooding also crossed a county road near Scribner and flooded a few farm fields around Crowell.  Damage was minimal.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A compact upper level system that tracked from the northern Rockies across central Nebraska and into eastern Kansas brought a 12 to 18 hour period of snow to eastern Nebraska and southwest Iowa.  Although the snow was briefly heavy, water equivalent was generally fairly low and most accumulations over the region were less than 6 inches.  However, isolated locations received 6 or more inches, especially across Pierce county where 6 to 9 inches fell over much of the county.  Even though north winds occasionally gusted over 20 mph, blowing and drifting snow was not a major issue with this storm.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Snowfall of 5 to 8 inches was reported over much of Cedar county.  Randolph picked up 8 inches for the highest amount reported in the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deepening low pressure center tracked north-northeast from northeast Texas to eastern Missouri. A strong southerly wind flow brought abundant moisture northward across the Lower Ohio Valley and southeast Missouri. Widespread rainfall amounts from two to four inches occurred, with up to six inches in the hilly terrain north and west of Poplar Bluff.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Several state roads were closed due to flooding, including sections of Routes C, E, FF, KK, and M. Most of these closures were off Route 34 in the northern part of the county.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Dense fog around during the morning gave way to a very unstable atmosphere across northwest and north central Louisiana. A stalled frontal boundary was located across deep east Texas into central Louisiana. An upper level storm system moved quickly eastward across central Texas into west central Louisiana and as a result, strong to severe thunderstorms developed. These storms produced mainly large hail.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A couple of trees were downed west of Athens along Hwy. 84.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Rain changed to snow across the southwest foothills of North Carolina  during the late afternoon. The snow became heavy at times, particularly along the I-85 corridor. By mid-evening, 1-4 inches of accumulation was reported across much of the area. Snow, heavy at times, and accompanied by occasional lightning, continued into the evening hours. By the time the snow tapered off, accumulations of 3-6 inches were common across the area. However, localized amounts of up to 8 inches were reported along the I-85 corridor.  The heavy wet snow, combined with gusty winds, caused quite a few trees and power lines to fall, resulting in numerous power outages. Some customers were without power for several days. One tree fell on and damaged a home in Gaffney. In addition, there were numerous traffic accidents.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Despite significant snowfall during the first week of month, followed by warm temperatures that melted all the snow cover, flooding was not a problem until the 11th.  Rain of 1/2 to 3 1/2 inches fell in east central Illinois and much of Indiana on this day. The rain caused the most extensive flooding seen since June 2008. Because snow cover had previously melted and ground previously greatly thawed, significant flooding only occurred in portions of west central Indiana. Significant flooding lasted less than a day in most areas. River flooding lasted from a few days to two weeks. Uneventful and generally dry weather prevailed  after this episode through the 26th.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Minor flooding occurred along the White River in Madison County, including in and near Anderson, due to heavy rain. It affected local parks and low lying farmland.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Soaking rains over a four-day period beginning on the 7th provided the region with nearly all of the months precipitationbetween 2 and 3 inches. The rain combined with the melting winter snowpack and frozen ground to result in widespread flooding on area rivers and creeks. There were numerous reports of road closures along those rivers and creeks. This was the third winter flood event this seasona rare occurrence in western New York. |Specific river/creek crest information follows:  Cazenovia Creek at Ebenezer (flood stage 10 feet) crested at 11.51 feet at 3AM on the 8th. Cayuga Creek at Lancaster (flood stage 8 feet) crested at 9.31 feet at 5AM on the 8th. Buffalo Creek at Gardenville (flood stage 7 feet) crested at 7.71 feet at 4AM on the 8th. Ellicott Creek at Williamsville (flood stage 8 feet) crested at 8.04 feet at 2AM on the 9th. Black Creek at Churchville (flood stage 6 feet) crested at 6.48 feet at 5PM on the 9th. Oatka Creek at Garbutt (flood stage 6 feet) crested at 6.70 feet at 2PM on the 9th. Allegheny River at Olean (flood stage 10 feet) crested at 10.34 feet at 11AM on the 11th. Tonawanda Creek at Batavia (flood stage 9 feet) crested at 10.57 feet at 11PM on the 8th; and at Rapids (flood stage 12 feet) crested at 13.68 feet at 6AM on the 11th.

This was the third winter flood event this seasona rare occurrence in western New York. |Specific river/creek crest information follows:  Cazenovia Creek at Ebenezer (flood stage 10 feet) crested at 11.51 feet at 3AM on the 8th. Cayuga Creek at Lancaster (flood stage 8 feet) crested at 9.31 feet at 5AM on the 8th. Buffalo Creek at Gardenville (flood stage 7 feet) crested at 7.71 feet at 4AM on the 8th. Ellicott Creek at Williamsville (flood stage 8 feet) crested at 8.04 feet at 2AM on the 9th. Black Creek at Churchville (flood stage 6 feet) crested at 6.48 feet at 5PM on the 9th. Oatka Creek at Garbutt (flood stage 6 feet) crested at 6.70 feet at 2PM on the 9th. Allegheny River at Olean (flood stage 10 feet) crested at 10.34 feet at 11AM on the 11th. Tonawanda Creek at Batavia (flood stage 9 feet) crested at 10.57 feet at 11PM on the 8th; and at Rapids (flood stage 12 feet) crested at 13.68 feet at 6AM on the 11th.

Spotty freezing rain fell in the morning hours of January 10th due to an approaching cold front. Cold air was also in place in the early morning, before warm air overspread the region and changed the precipitation to all rain.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A thin glaze of ice had accumulated in Relief.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A weather disturbance, combined with northwest winds flowing over the higher terrain of Eastern Kentucky, resulted in a widespread snowfall across the area on January 18th through the 19th. Most areas saw 1 to 2 inches of snow.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Eight tenths of an inch of snow fell on top of ice covered roadways, creating treacherous driving conditions 3 miles northwest of Blackey.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A cold front brought locally high winds to southern Nevada and northwest Arizona.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong winds snapped a cable on a window-washing platform on a high-rise hotel in Las Vegas, slamming the platform into the side of the hotel at the 15th floor.  Several windows were broken, and two workers suffered minor injuries.

In the Northeast Plains storm totals included:  10.5 inches, 6 miles south of New Raymer; 10 inches at Hugo, 8 inches, 6 miles north-northeast of Woodrow; 7.5 inches, 10 miles northwest of Yuma, 7 inches, 4 miles east of Akron and at Karval; and 6 inches at Fort Morgan.  Storm totals elsewhere ranged from 3 to 5 inches.  In addition, the wind produced snow drifts ranging from 2 to 4 feet in some areas.
High winds developed over portions of the Northeast Plains.  Peak wind gust reports included 60 mph at Keenesburg, and 58 mph at Akron.

A strengthening low pressure system tracked northeast from the southern Plains on Thursday April 2nd, to the upper Ohio Valley by Friday morning April 3rd, and into southern Quebec by Saturday morning April 4th.||The tightening pressure gradient around this low pressure system led to strong gusty winds across portions of eastern New York and western New England during Saturday. Peak wind gusts of 35 to 45 MPH were measured across the region.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was reported down at the intersection of Moe Road and Englemore Road in Clifton Park.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Cold and moist west to northwest winds blowing across the nearby Great Lakes, in the wake of a strong low pressure system led to the development snow showers and embedded heavier squalls across portions of northern Herkimer County, beginning Tuesday afternoon, and ending Wednesday morning.||Snowfall amounts of 3 to 6 inches were reported, mainly for areas near and north of Route 28, with 6 inches reported at Old Forge.

The combination of clear skies and light winds allowed temperatures to fall to near or just below freezing across much of Bennington County in Vermont early Thursday morning. The growing season already started in this region after a prolonged period of abnormally warm temperatures.

Mainly non-thunderstorm winds occurred during the afternoon and evening hours of February 11th. A High Wind Warning was in effect for the day as well as portions of the days on either side. A strong low pressure system moved across Illinois and northern Indiana with a trailing cold front that passed through Indiana. An intense pressure gradient ahead of the front and strong pressure rises behind the front caused very strong winds to blow. A saturated ground from recent snow melt and new rainfall may have contributed to the reports of downed trees.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The Jackson County REMC reported that 2400 customers were without power as a result of downed lines and/or utility poles.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure tracked from the Oklahoma panhandle into the Ohio Valley from February 13th through the 14th.  This system brought heavy snow to around a 50 mile wide swath across eastern Nebraska and western Iowa generally along and north of Interstate 80 in eastern Nebraska and along and south of the interstate in western Iowa.  The heaviest snow stretched from Columbus and David City Nebraska east through Omaha and then to Underwood and Oakland Iowa.  On the southern end the snowfall tapered down to several inches from southeast Nebraska into far southwest Iowa.  Meanwhile, the snow ended rather abruptly on the northern end with little or no snow measured along and north of a line from Norfolk Nebraska to Little Sioux Iowa.  Heavier snow totals in Nebraska included 7.5 inches in David City and 6 to 8 inches across much of the Omaha metro area including 6.8 inches at the NWS office near Valley and 5.5 inches at Omaha Eppley.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Heavy snow fell over all of Douglas county with 6.8 inches measured at the NWS office near Valley and 5.5 inches at Omaha Eppley.  Other reports of 6 to 8 inches were received from various sources throughout the county.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 44 mph wind gust was reported by a SAWRS site in South Marsh Island Block 268.

CZ_NAME: COASTAL WATERS FROM INTRACOASTAL CITY TO CAMERON LA OUT 20 NM
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The second day in a row of widespread severe weather affected the northwestern Gulf of Mexico, with numerous reports of severe winds from offshore oil rigs.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A 41 mph wind gust was reported by an oil rig platform in Vermilion Block 24.  Observer reported some blockage to the wind gauge, and winds were probably higher.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Several episodes of widespread severe weather and heavy rainfall occurred from March 26th through the 28th as a series of strong upper air disturbances impacted the central gulf region as a meandering and nearly stationary frontal boundary drifted back and forth across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous power poles were knocked down with multiple electrical transformers blown off poles. Also, scattered trees were knocked down and a roof was ripped off of a house along Antonio Road near Highway 1.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Several episodes of widespread severe weather and heavy rainfall occurred from March 26th through the 28th as a series of strong upper air disturbances impacted the central gulf region as a meandering and nearly stationary frontal boundary drifted back and forth across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A very weak tornado briefly touched down in the Springhill subdivision. The tornado was only about 25 yards wide with a path length of approximately 250 yards. The tornado resulted in minor tree damage and caused yard items to be blown around. The estimated wind speed associated with this tornado was around 65 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Several episodes of widespread severe weather and heavy rainfall occurred from March 26th through the 28th as a series of strong upper air disturbances impacted the central gulf region as a meandering and nearly stationary frontal boundary drifted back and forth across the area.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous trees were blown down and there were power outages along Highway 24 near Woodville.

A tight pressure gradient between low pressure over the Plains and high pressure over Hudson Bay caused strong southeast wind gusts over portions of the Keweenaw Peninsula from the 23rd into the 24th. Freezing rain also developed over portions of northwest Upper Michigan during this same time.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: The observer in Mohawk measured one-quarter inch of freezing rain. The combination of the ice and southeast winds gusting near 40 mph toppled numerous trees on US-41 and M-26 between the towns of Phoenix, Central and Copper Harbor. Most of the trees were between 6 and 18 inches in diameter.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: March began with an upper-level low off the California coast. Strong warming in the south end of the San Joaquin Valley gave Bakersfield a record high of 86 degrees, which almost was the warmest day of the month at Meadows Field. The low drew subtropical moisture into interior central California from the southwest, bringing rain and high-elevation snow to the region. In Yosemite National Park, a foot of new snow fell at Tuolumne Meadows during the night of March 2nd-3rd.|Colder air moved into the region during the 3rd as a slow moving cold front dropped south. The high at Fresno dropped from 67 on the 3rd to only 59 on the 4th, and Bakersfields high fell 13 degreesfrom 74 on the 3rd to only 61 the next day. More snow fell over the Southern Sierra Nevada beginning the night of March 3rd and continuing through the 4th. Estimated snowfalls at SNOTEL sites ranged from 15 inches to around 2 feet. With a cold, unstable airmass over the San Joaquin Valley, conditions were right for thunderstorms to form over the west side of the San Joaquin Valley during the afternoon and evening of March 4th.|The trough pulled east of California during the morning of March 7th. This system brought the bulk of Marchs precipitation to central California, with Fresno having a storm total of 0.18 inch, and Bakersfield receiving 0.20 inch. With the moist lower levels of the airmass over the San Joaquin Valley, patchy fog developed during the morning hours of the 7th.

A line of thunderstorms tracked across extreme southeast Kansas and southern Missouri from west to east.  Several observations of wind damage occurred along the line, along with a few observations of marginally severe hail.  One tornado touched down on the northern edge of Nixa, which damaged more than a dozen homes.

A strong upper level low pressure system moved through Arkansas during the night of February 28th, 2009. The upper level low produced bands of snow across North Mississippi during the evening hours which continued into the early morning hours of March 1st, 2009. Total snow accumulations ranged from an inch to as much as 5 inches. The hardest hit area was along the Tennessee Border from Southaven in DeSoto County to Corinth in Alcorn County. Roads were hazardous as a result of the snow and many accidents occurred.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Around 3 inches of snow fell across Calhoun County during the early morning hours of March 1st. Total snow accumulations during the February 28th-March 1st, 2009 snow storm was around 3 inches.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deepening low pressure center tracked north-northeast from northeast Texas to eastern Missouri. A strong southerly wind flow brought abundant moisture northward across the Lower Ohio Valley and southeast Missouri. Widespread rainfall amounts from two to four inches occurred, with up to six inches in the hilly terrain north and west of Poplar Bluff.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: A few state roads were closed due to flooding, including sections of Routes EE, H, and PP.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As a deep 500 mb trough developed over the Plains, warmer and more moist air streamed across the Mississippi Valley. This fetch of moisture produced a large area of showers. Storm total rainfall amounts were between 3 and 5 inches over southeast Missouri and southern Illinois from the 23rd to the 25th. As a result, a number of rivers rose above flood stage.
EVENT_NARRATIVE: Minor flooding of the Mississippi River occurred. At the Cape Girardeau gage, the river crested at 32.38 feet on the 29th. Flood stage there is 32 feet. Minor flooding of low-lying fields occurred.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deepening low pressure system lifted northeast across northern Illinois into Lower Michigan. On the back side of the low, strong west winds gusted to around 45 mph.

A passing mid-level low north of the region resulted in a 70 kt mid-level speed max working its way over the area during the early morning hours.  Deep dry adiabatic layers resulted in maximum mixing potential, which allowed the stronger winds to mix down to the surface.  The 700 hPa gradient over the area on this day suggested the potential for high winds was high, especially over the higher terrain of west Texas.

A mid to upper level low moved across the Texas Panhandle on Sunday, April 12, 2009.  The mid level speed max near the base of the trough axis, combined with strong mixing, resulted in high winds across the Guadalupe and Davis Mountains of west Texas during the afternoon hours.  Although the surface winds were also strong across the plains due to a tight pressure gradient from a lee low, they did not reach high wind criteria.
